<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIFT EVENING UNRAVELS, AS FRANCO PULLS THE STRING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is like this for the New York Mets. They will
tease you with dramatic finishes against all odds and make you feel
as if nothing is out of their reach, not the National League wild
card, not even the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And then the dispirited Florida Marlins roll into town. For some
reason, the meek make the Mets lose the kind of focus and edge that
allow them to beat the elite teams in the league. It happened to
them against Friday night at Shea Stadium, when the Mets lost a
golden opportunity to pull even with the Chicago Cubs in the
wild-card race by losing to the Marlins, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   A collapse seemed unlikely. The Mets had a 6-4 lead heading into
the ninth inning when their closer, John Franco, fell apart, giving
up a two-run single with the bases loaded. That was followed by a
sacrifice fly by Edgar Renteria that gave the Marlins a lead that
the Mets could not overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who made late-inning heroics a habit in Houston, had
nothing left to pull out of its bag. The 34,862 fans at Shea
grasped the importance of the game, and they were merciless in
their booing of Franco as he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets understood the gravity of Friday night's game, too.
They spent Friday afternoon with one eye on the row of television
sets that hang from the clubhouse ceiling. Instead of the normal
echo from dueling talk shows, all channels were tuned to the Cubs'
game against the Reds at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every play elicited a reaction from a passing Met,
including a moan by Franco on an error by Reds second baseman Bret
Boone in the early innings. By the time the Mets had finished their
pre-game warmup, their groans had been replaced by grins because
they knew exactly where they stood in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had lost. All the Mets had to do was finish off the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed like a simple feat, considering the Marlins had won
just 50 games and lost 103 before Friday night. But their record
against the Mets was much better _ 4-5 coming in _ and this night
would not end without angst for New York. Rick Reed, an All-Star
pitcher who baffled hitters in the first half of the season,
continued to display an unnerving knack for serving up a home run
ball as a chaser to otherwise fine pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had given up six home runs in his two previous starts, a
pattern that continued when Kevin Orie blasted a 1-0 pitch in the
second inning, and Cliff Floyd followed by hitting a homer off a
2-2 pitch in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   As they grabbed hold of Reed's mistakes, the depleted Marlins
were making the game uncomfortable for the Mets. Although the Mets
were making headway against the Marlins' starter, Livan Hernandez,
using a wild pitch to score a run in the first and getting a home
run by John Olerud in the third, the score was tied, 3-3, in the
bottom of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Mike Piazza slipped into his cape once again,
delivering a two-run double down the third-base line with two outs
to provide a 5-3 lead. Trouble still lurked, though.
</P>
<P>
   Reed left a mess when he departed in the seventh inning with
Marlins on first and third and no outs. Reliever Dennis Cook came
jogging out of the bullpen and ran right over the Marlins, striking
out the side.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Cook had the crowd on its feet. Shea, though far
from packed, was lively and loud. The Mets, often uninspired when
facing sinking teams, were hoping to look into the seats for the
kind of edge that has sustained the Sammy Sosa-powered Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sammy has provided the Cubs with something we've been
without,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said before the game.
``When we got Mike Piazza here, I thought we'd have more of a 10th
man. And we did that first homestand. But that turned around on us
over the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Insults were hurled at Piazza as he struggled to find his groove
with the Mets after he arrived from the Dodgers. But slowly, with
every game-winning hit, Piazza has discovered the kinder side to
the New York fan. Even so, the empty seats at Shea have revealed
the difference in the kind of support the Cubs have thrived on as
Sosa matches Mark McGwire home run for home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sammy, you see the support building,'' Valentine said.
``Fans are cheering, even in the opposing ballparks. And that's a
bonus when you're looking for any edge you can get. We haven't had
that at home. We haven't had that home-field advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   That only partly explains why the Mets , who have been
adrenaline junkies getting their fix by facing daunting challenges
and impossible circumstances, have been surge-less when facing meek
teams like the Florida Marlins
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell's man of steel performance out of the bullpen of
late, which included consecutive saves on back-to-back days this
week, has surprised everyone but him. In the first game against
Houston, he pitched two shutout innings. In the second, he went one
and two-thirds, and then threw two shutout innings in the third
game for a save. He still had enough left to throw one shutout
inning in the fourth game for another save. The more innings he
pitches, the better Wendell believes his stuff gets. ``If you feel
too strong, you might tend to overthrow,'' Wendell said. ``You try
to do too much. Sometimes if you're a little under the weather, or
fatigued, you're better off.'' ... In order to accommodate Fox
Sports' national broadcast of the Mets game against the Braves on
Sept. 26, the game time has been switched from 7:10 p.m. to 1:15
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
