<HEADLINE>
STUCK ON THEMSELVES: FAST-MOVING CRAZE COMES FROM JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA HELSER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nikki Martin and Sheree Bennett are stuck on their own sweet
faces.
</P>
<P>
   Or more precisely, their faces are now stuck on them.
</P>
<P>
   Through the magic of a photo-sticker machine they discovered in
a Tempe mall on a recent Saturday afternoon, they can emblazon
their faces on stickers while joining a fast-moving craze imported
from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never done this before,'' said Sheree, standing
shoulder-to-shoulder with her friend as they fed three $1 bills
into the glorified voting booth, one of six or seven such machines
in metropolitan Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Following instructions from the singsong voice coming from
within, they selected an appropriate frame for their faces and then
struck a pose.
</P>
<P>
   Voila!
</P>
<P>
   Within 60 seconds they were oohing and ahhing over the results _
a sheet of 16 tiny, (one-half by three-quarters of an inch)
individual photos of themselves, complete with superimposed kitty
ears, noses and whiskers, suitable for power sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sheree could utter the words, ``Way cool!'' she had
planted one of the stickers squarely on her cheekbone as Nikki
positioned another one on her lime-green pager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give them to our friends, too,'' said Nikki, an
eighth-grader from Chandler, ``and I'll put them on my notebook.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a socially acceptable spinoff of graffiti or just
another way to be noticed in an otherwise anonymous world,
``putting your face all over the place'' with the help of a sticker
machine has become one of the Valley's hottest new trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very, very popular,'' said Cookie Lee, manager of
Sanrio, a children's shop at Arizona Mills in Tempe, full of
merchandise featuring cartoon characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mall is busy, there's a waiting line at the machine
and what amazes me is, after they do one, they get in line to do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanrio's machine, in place since the franchised shop opened at
the end of May, features frames of Sanrio's cartoon characters such
as Pretty Kitty.
</P>
<P>
   But other Sticker Stations, such as the one located near the
IMAX Theatre at the Grand Canyon provide a variety of superimposed
artwork that serves as accompanying adornment for those posing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real hot one now is the one with Al Gore and Bill Clinton,''
said Darrel Jackson, who maintains the premises. ``It looks like
you're standing between them.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's first photo-sticker machine clicked its first
pictures in Japan three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Intended to lure customers into stores, it was particularly
well-received by girls 10 to 14 years old. But it proved to be
attractive to a broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my sister was teaching school over in Japan, she'd always
send her letters with these stickers on them,'' said 27-year-old
Elise French of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   French finally was in a position to retaliate recently when she
and her husband, Troy, stumbled upon the Sanrio store sticker
machine.
</P>
<P>
   French is destined to see many more if APBI and another
distributor, Atlus Dream Entertainment Company, have their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of 1999, APBI will have over 2,000 across the
nation,'' said Liz Wellford, public relations spokeswoman for APBI.
She said there are about 1,600 in the country now.
</P>
<P>
   As for Arizona, Wellford said there are plans for at least four
more of the company's Sticker Stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the month or early next there'll be one at The
Limited Too in Scottsdale Fashion Square, one at the Arizona
Factory Shops and another in one of the Old Navy Stores,'' she
said. ``We just don't know which one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more individuals are buying the machines and their
stickers. Attilio Leonardi, who purchased his 300-pound machine for
$8,000 and normally keeps it busy in Tucson's Foothills Mall, rents
it out for family reunions, bar mitzvahs and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real popular at special functions,'' he said. ``I charge
$200 to get it there and then $2 for the 16 photos.''
</P>
<P>
   A line of accessories, specifically made to show off the sticky
photos, also is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's pendants, key chains, bracelets,'' said Leonardi,
``and these things like rolls of film that you stick them on.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Linda Helser can be reached at 444-8243 or at linda.helser &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
