<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SETS TENTATIVE TRIAL DATE FOR FIVE POLICEMEN IN LOUIMA
BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge on Friday tentatively set a trial
date of March 22 for four New York City police officers charged
with brutalizing a Haitian immigrant, Abner Louima, in Brooklyn
last year and for a sergeant accused of trying to cover up part of
the assault.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Eugene Nickerson of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn
also indicated that there was a good chance the trial would not
start by then. Instead, he characterized the date as ``something to
work for.''
</P>
<P>
   The case has already been delayed for months, first by a switch
from state to federal prosecution and more recently by a dispute
over legal representation for two of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that Louima was beaten by the four officers in a
police car after he was arrested in a street brawl on Aug. 9, 1997,
and that two officers later tortured him in a bathroom of the 70th
Precinct station house.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers and the sergeant insist the charges against
them are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the police officers said outside Nickerson's
courtroom Friday that among the major pretrial issues they will ask
the judge to decide will be whether there should be one trial for
all the defendants or whether any of the officers should be tried
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Each lawyer said he would seek a severance for his client from
one or more of the other defendants because of conflicting defense
moves.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also said they might be restricted in their defense
strategy if the officers were tried together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have antagonistic defenses,'' said Marvyn Kornberg, the
lawyer for Justin Volpe, who is accused of torturing Louima in the
station house bathroom by ramming a stick into his rectum and then
his mouth, causing severe internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A second officer, Charles Schwarz, is accused of helping Volpe
by holding Louima down.
</P>
<P>
   Those officers and Officers Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese are
accused of beating Louima in the patrol car on the way to the
station house. All four are charged with violating Louima's civil
rights. The sergeant, Michael Bellomo, is accused of trying to
cover up the police car beating.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kornberg told Nickerson that he would submit a motion that his
client's trial should be moved elsewhere, saying the intensive
pretrial publicity would prevent Volpe from obtaining a fair trial
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for Bruder and Wiese, Stuart London and Joseph
Tacopina, respectively, also said they would ask for a change of
venue.
</P>
<P>
   Later, another judge in the same court, Sterling Johnson, ruled
that a civil suit that Louima has filed against the city, the
indicted officers and other parties would be held in abeyance until
the criminal prosecution was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The same ruling applies to a similar suit filed by another
Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine, who prosecutors say was beaten
by Volpe after the brawl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
