<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BEAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW COUNTING ON BEAN TO DETHRONE HOLYFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (js) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The opponent weighed in at a less-than-svelte 231 on
Thursday, 19 more pounds than he weighed for his last unsuccessful
title shot. If Vaughn Bean were a puncher, this would be good. But
his best attribute is said to be his lateral movement.
</P>
<P>
   As Evander Holyfield prepares to get back in the ring for the
first time in 10 months, and it is hard to know whom to feel more
sorry for: Bean, the No. 1 contender whom most fans do not expect
to leave the ring standing, or the legions of fight fans yawning
for the heavyweight division to percolate again.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, home is apparently no place to lose your World
Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation titles. A
Georgia Dome crowd that promoters are hoping will swell above
30,000 will back Holyfield, who will be host to a homecoming party
afterward. Between 50 million and 60 million homes will have access
to the fight on Showtime's free-preview weekend
</P>
<P>
   Still, with more pertinent boxing matters going on in Las Vegas
this weekend _ Oscar de la Hoya trying to send Julio Cesar Chavez
into retirement and Mike Tyson attempting to get his boxing license
renewed _ Holyfield-Bean is not exactly boffo box office.
</P>
<P>
   Asked earlier this week when he would try to unify the title
with the World Boxing Federation champion Lennox Lewis, Holyfield
curtly replied, ``Some time next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Bean will have to do. He has the right to be here
because he is the mandatory IBF challenger, meaning Holyfield
(35-3, 25 knockouts) would be stripped of his belt if he did not
fight Bean (31-1, 25 knockouts).
</P>
<P>
   But other than Michael Moorer, who defeated Bean by majority
decision in March 1997, they have no common opponents. Most of
Bean's record was built from a litany of journeyman fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Louisiana and grew up in Chicago. Testament to
how unknown he is, two of Bean's four trainers _ Joe Frazier and
Michael Spinks _ have signed more autographs than he has this week.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 11 inches, he is 3 inches shorter than Holyfield. Bean
moves and jabs well, but may have trouble catching up to the
sculpted Holyfield, who weighed in at a lithe 217 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he came in so heavy, Bean replied, ``I'm still
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight is Holyfield's first in his hometown since he knocked
out Bert Cooper in 1991. He has not fought since last November, an
eighth-round technical knockout of Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he was prepared to defend both titles, on June 6
at Madison Square Garden, doctors determined that the No. 1 WBA
contender, Henry Akinwande, had Hepatitis B. The fight was
postponed It may come off in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares for his 17th title bout, about the only thing
Holyfield does not have going for him is his age. At 35, he is 10
years older than Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's waist, however, is 4 inches smaller than the
challenger's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
