A3975 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     09-19 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRACING FOR MORTGAGE LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors are still reeling from the news that
trading losses, mostly in emerging markets, will erase a lot of
earnings from the books of leading financial services companies in
the United States this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch said it lost $135 million trading bonds in July
and August, cutting earnings to one-fourth their level during those
months in 1997. Citicorp's losses will slice $200 million from
third-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks have been trounced on the news. Bankers Trust
has fallen to $63.75 from an April high of $136.4375. Lehman
Brothers is down 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Time to bargain-hunt? Or is there another wave of losses out
there?
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is, surf's up. Falling interest rates mean fresh
problems at banks and brokerage firms in their mortgage lending
businesses or trading of mortgage-backed securities.
</P>
<P>
   As rates fall, homeowners refinance mortgages. What's good for
consumers _ their borrowing costs shrink _ is bad for the
institutions that made the higher-rate loans or serviced them.
That's because the income and servicing fees on these loans vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Even though mortgage rates have yet to decline sharply, the
number of consumers refinancing their mortgages is way up. The
Mortgage Bankers Association refinancing index is at double the
level seen in May. And the index will skyrocket in coming weeks
when mortgage rates really plummet.
</P>
<P>
   How gnarly will the refinancing wave be? Nobody knows.
``Mortgage rates have declined to levels not seen in the history of
the modern mortgage market,'' said Bob Kulason, director of the
mortgage strategy group at Salomon Smith Barney. Thus, predicting
future prepayments is much tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Prepayments are important because finance companies make
assumptions about the profitability of a loan based on how long it
is likely to stay on the books. If loans get paid down faster than
anticipated, the assumptions are wrong and earnings need to be
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders in Green Tree Financial learned this the hard way
last fall. The company, which makes loans to buyers of manufactured
housing, found prepayments on its loans coming in faster than
expected. It took a $150 million pretax charge to earnings, and the
stock fell 20 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street firms that trade mortgage-backed securities are also
vulnerable to lower rates; those with big mortgage holdings are
already behind the eight ball this year. The return on the Lehman
Brothers government bond index is 7.89 percent while that of a
mortgage-backed securities index is only 5.21 percent. Mortgages
typically beat Treasuries' returns by 1 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, many trading houses and hedge funds bought
mortgages and hedged the positions by selling Treasuries. As
Treasuries rose and mortgages lagged, these investors took a double
hit.
</P>
<P>
   And those traders holding interest-only strips, a derivative
security that pays out only the interest generated by a pool of
mortgages and is not backed by the loan's principal, will find
themselves with nothing when homeowners pay off their loans.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a trader want such a security? If rates stayed where
they were or rose, the strips would continue to produce income. And
since few Wall Street traders believed rates could drop to their
current levels _ 5.15 percent on the 30-year bond _ interest-only
strips were the thing to own.
</P>
<P>
   When will mortgage problems surface? Not until October or
November at the earliest, says Charles Peabody, bank analyst at
Mitchell Securities in New York. ``The first losses are likely to
be housed in hedging strategies,'' Peabody said. ``Arbitrage losses
first, absolute dollar losses later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
