<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIARY-BUSINESS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES FOR RATE CUTS ARE RAISED, THEN DASHED  
 SO LONG, EBULLIENCE, HELLO, CUTBACKS  
 TURNING TIDES SINK A BIG TECHNOLOGY DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The week began with President Clinton hoping to strike up the
Group of Seven band of major economic powers in a rousing chorus of
coordinated interest rate cuts, to relieve the pressure on
embattled Latin American countries like Brazil that are struggling
to contain currency and debt crises. World financial markets took
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But by midweek all was disharmony, thanks to political paralysis
in Japan, election distractions in Germany and muddy political and
economic waters in the United States. The chief soloist, Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, made it clear that no
sweet music would be forthcoming _ and the markets, disappointed,
sank once more.
</P>
<P>
   The week closed to the clangor of printing presses, as Russia's
central bank, against all advice, tried papering over economic
chasms with freshly minted rubles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Long, Ebullience, Hello, Cutbacks
</P>
<P>
   Telltale droplets of blood began appearing on the forehead of
corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Venator, nee Woolworth, which only recently finished scrapping
its 5-and-dimes to concentrate on specialty retailing, said it
would shutter 570 Kinney and Footquarters shoe stores and take a
$173 million charge. Toys ``R'' Us said it would close 90 stores,
shed up to 3,000 jobs, take a $495 million charge and revamp its
remaining outlets to combat stiffening competition from discount
stores. CBS and NBC each announced layoffs in the hundreds, while
ABC said it would make nonpersonnel cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reader's Digest said it would slash its dividend, sell much of
its art collection and let some workers go because of sagging
performance. Citicorp and Travelers Group confirmed that their
pending merger would spell the end of several thousand jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Turning Tides Sink a Big Technology Deal
</P>
<P>
   Tellabs called off its planned $7.1 billion acquisition of
Ciena, the top maker of equipment for building the capacity of
phone networks, because shareholder approval was unlikely, thanks
mainly to a near free fall in Ciena's business outlook after the
deal was announced on June 3. Since then, Ciena has warned that its
third-quarter profit would be less than half of what analysts
expected, said it had failed to land two important contracts, and
seen its stock tumble 81 percent _ abetted by the general
late-summer slide in the markets, of course _ while Tellabs fell 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other deals came undone, too: Coca-Cola's plan to buy the
Orangina soft drink business from Pernod-Ricard for $840 million
was blocked by French regulators, who agreed with Pepsico's
complaint that it would stifle competition. And privately held
Quark abandoned its icily greeted offer to acquire Adobe Systems,
Quark's main rival in desktop-publishing software.
</P>
<P>
   But Allied Signal's hostile bid for AMP, the leading maker of
electronic connectors, gained momentum when shareholders
controlling 72 percent of AMP voted to go along. That allowed
Allied to trim back its tender offer to apply to only 18 percent of
AMP shares, fewer than needed to trip an AMP anti-takeover
provision. AMP's board responded by lowering the threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Takes
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices rose two-tenths of 1 percent in August, the same
as in July. ... Fewer foreign cars and cheaper oil meant that the
nation's imports fell in July. But exports fell faster, reflecting
soft demand in troubled Asian countries. So the trade deficit
widened to $13.92 billion. ... Sluggish sales in Asia hammered
Nike, whose profits fell 35 percent in the latest quarter. ...
Three former executives of Archer Daniels Midland, including the
chairman's son, were found guilty of conspiring to fix prices of
lysine, the animal feed additive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
