<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HIRE GEIVETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kevin Malone completed his first week as Dodgers
general manager Friday by making his first hire. Tampa Bay Devil
Rays assistant GM Bill Geivett, who has known Malone since both
joined the Angels in 1985, assumes a similar position with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Geivett, 35, worked the past two seasons under Devil Rays GM
Chuck LaMar, developing the expansion team's international scouting
programs that included Latin America, the Far East and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been part of every facet of a baseball operation and
has special skills, talents and abilities that will help the
Dodgers in the years to come,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Under former general manager Fred Claire, the assistant GM
duties included clerical work and some contract negotiations. Those
responsibilities will remain with Robert Schweppe, son of former
farm director Bill Schweppe, and general counsel Sam Fernandez, who
was chief negotiator in contract talks last spring with catcher
Mike Piazza. Geivett will play a scouting role with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Schweppe and Sam Fernandez are highly valued
specialists and they will remain specialists,'' Malone said. ``Bill
will work more in player evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Devil Rays, Geivett worked under Malone in
Montreal as director of player development. Geivett, one of the few
people in baseball of Philippine descent, also has college
assistant coaching jobs at Loyola Marymount and Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some challenges, but there's also a lot of tradition
and history with very high standards,'' Geivett said. ``To be
chosen as the one of the caretakers of that, that's something I'd
like to be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Mum on manager: Although Malone has been candid about people
he'd like to hire (Geivett, former Baltimore boss Pat Gillick), he
refused to speculate about the manager's position. He is expected
to offer Glenn Hoffman a prominent role in the farm system but for
now says Hoffman is his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not fair to speculate,'' Malone said. ``As far as I'm
concerned, Glenn Hoffman is the manager of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
My focus right now is stabilizing the organization and finding
people who can take us forward. There are other areas I need to
address before the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds honored: Before the game, Giants left fielder Barry Bonds
was honored for becoming the first player to reach 400 homers and
400 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds has reached 30 homers and 30 steals five times. With a
week to go, he might come up short, but it won't be from lack of
effort. He has 34 homers and stole his 25th base in the fourth
inning Friday. Last week, he raised eyebrows by attempting to steal
with the Giants trailing 14-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
