<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS NOT WORRIED ABOUT FINLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Angels manager Terry Collins insists he isn't
concerned about Chuck Finley, even though the ace of the Anaheim
staff has made it into the seventh inning only twice in his past
five starts and won only three of his past 15 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Finley pitched eight shutout innings against Kansas City on
Sept. 6 but allowed five runs in 41/3 innings against Cleveland
(Sept. 1), eight runs in 51/3 against Baltimore (Sept. 11) and five
runs in 62/3 vs. Texas on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't pitched good, that's not a secret,'' said Collins.
``But in my mind there's no doubt he'll go out the next time and
keep us in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big-game guy. There's no doubt he's the guy I want out
there and so does the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins did say he might move Steve Sparks up a day (to Monday)
and push Finley back to Tuesday since Sparks lasted only 12/3
innings against Texas on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not ready: Barring a special situation, Darin Erstad (strained
left hamstring) won't play again until Monday, when the Rangers and
Angels begin a three-game series at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't run him in there where he has to beat something out,''
Collins explained. ``It depends on the situation, maybe two outs
and we need a hit or with a runner at third and we need a fly
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said after watching his first baseman try to run on
Thursday night, he had little choice but to pull him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him run and said, `This is not going to go,''' he said.
``If he had stayed in and tried to play base-to-base, there is a
good chance he would have blown it out. You know how he is, he
would have got caught up in the emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins did have some good news to report on Erstad. Trainer Ned
Bergert told him that Erstad said his leg felt better Friday than
it did on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No vindication: Cecil Fielder made it clear he was unhappy when
the Angels released him on Aug. 5, hinting that Anaheim's move was
prompted by the team's unwillingness to pay some performance
bonuses. But Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said he doesn't
feel vindicated by Cleveland's decision to release the power hitter
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't matter to me,'' he said. ``We make our moves
for our own reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, however, made it clear he didn't appreciate some of
Fielder's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't begrudge Cecil for being upset, but to say that it had
anything to do with with anything other than our roster or ability
is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mad over what he said, but he was wrong, just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielder was hitting .143 with no home runs and no RBI for the
Indians. He struck out 13 times in 35 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher corps: With catcher Phil Nevin on crutches the day after
spraining his left ankle in Texas, the Angels acquired catcher Chad
Kreuter from the Chicago White Sox for cash considerations. Kreuter
will be available for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   Kreuter, 34, hit .253 with two home runs and 33 RBI in 93 games
for Chicago this year. To make room for Kreuter on the 40-man
roster, Charlie O'Brien (broken finger) was placed on the 60-day
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   This Kreuter's second stint with the Angels. He hit .234 in 70
games last season before signing a free-agent contract with the
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin, who said he needs ``a few days to let the swelling go
down,'' was obviously upset about being injured at this point of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kills me, it's not supposed to happen,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
