<SLUG> BC-NY-SEN-D'AMATO-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: D'AMATO PAINTS A `LIBERAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with ny-senaterace) 
(bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 30-second commercial that the re-election campaign
of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., began broadcasting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Jamestown Associates Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The advertisement opens with an ominous view of
the Brooklyn Bridge and the skyline of lower Manhattan in
foreboding dark blue tones. ``Chuck Schumer'' appears in black
letters at the top right of the screen. The word ``liberal''
scrolls across the bottom in huge capital letters as a stern
picture of Rep. Charles Schumer appears at left. As the voice-over
begins, ``Three Largest Tax Increases'' appears in jagged white
type, and a stack of dollar bills grows on screen. An image of a
hammer lying unused appears as the narrator criticizes Schumer on
the issue of welfare, followed by the image of a jail cell door
swinging open as Schumer is criticized on crime. Finally, the word
``wrong'' flashes repeatedly in bright red letters, as the narrator
again declares Schumer wrong on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``Chuck Schumer's a New York City liberal, and he
proves it every day. Chuck Schumer voted for the three largest tax
increases in American history. Chuck Schumer voted for more welfare
and against workfare. And Chuck Schumer voted for less jail time
for violent criminals. Liberal Chuck Schumer. Wrong on taxes. Wrong
on welfare. Wrong on crime. Wrong for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Measuring the largest tax increase in history is a
game that campaign strategists love to play. Depending on who is
counting, either President Clinton's 1993 budget or a 1982 bill
signed by President Reagan could be described as the largest tax
increase ever. Schumer did support both of these bills, but the
advertisement fails to mention that Sen. Alfonse D'Amato also voted
for the 1982 bill.
</P>
<P>
   The ad accurately notes Schumer's vote against President
Reagan's 1984 anticrime bill, which contained tougher drug and bail
laws. D'Amato supported the bill and it became law. A decade later,
Schumer sponsored the tough 1994 crime bill, which extended prison
spending and the federal death penalty and it also became law.
D'Amato voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The ad seeks to drive home what has quickly become
the D'Amato campaign's central message: that Schumer is a
``liberal'' who is ``wrong for us.'' But it does little more than
demonstrate how hard it will be for D'Amato and Schumer, both
18-year veterans of Congress, to contrast their voting records in
ways that are clear to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Schumer about crime is likely to fall flat in
light of the 1994 crime bill, his recent support of the death
penalty and his well-known work on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Branding Schumer ``a New York City liberal'' plays to the
historic resentment of the city among voters upstate, but risks
alienating voters in New York City, the majority of whom are
registered Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
