<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SEN-SCHUMER-ADS-NY     09-19 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEN-SCHUMER-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: SCHUMER SEES `TOO MANY LIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with NY-SENATERACE)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are two 15-second commercials that the campaign of Charles
Schumer, the Democratic nominee for U.S. senator in New York, began
broadcasting Thursday night and Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Morris, Carrick &AMP; Guma
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The first advertisement opens with ``D'Amato's
lying about Chuck Schumer on taxes'' in white type on a black
screen with ``lying'' underlined in red, then flashes to a white
screen with ``The Truth'' in large black letters. It cuts to a
scene of Schumer speaking with constituents. ``Schumer voted to cut
taxes,'' appears on the screen. Then, a cut-out picture of D'Amato
appears next to a red arrow pointing up to indicate increased
taxes. Finally the words ``D'Amato: too many lies for too long''
appear next to his picture.
</P>
<P>
   The second ad opens the same way and cuts to a similar scene of
Schumer with constituents. ``Chuck Schumer: tough on crime''
appears on-screen as the narrator speaks about the 1994 crime bill.
It then shows two police officers and ``Chuck Schumer: put new
police on the street'' and ``Chuck Schumer: banned assault
weapons'' appear on-screen. The ad ends with the same picture of
D'Amato and the words ``D'Amato voted no'' followed by ``D'Amato:
too many lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``D'Amato's lying about Chuck Schumer on taxes. The
truth: Schumer voted to cut taxes for 2 million New York families.
Since 1981, D'Amato voted for $300 billion in tax increases.
D'Amato's been raising taxes for three decades. D'Amato: too many
lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``D'Amato's lying about Chuck Schumer on crime. The truth: Chuck
Schumer's the tough-on-crime Democrat who wrote the law that put
thousands of new police on the street and banned assault weapons.
D'Amato voted no. D'Amato: too many lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The first ad asserts that D'Amato voted for $300
billion in tax increases since 1981, based on budget bills in 1982,
1984 and 1995. In fact, he voted for only two of those bills. Both
candidates voted in favor of the 1982 bill and both supported early
versions of the 1984 bill but ultimately voted against it. In any
event, using the Schumer campaign's accounting, both men have voted
for more than $264 billion in taxes since 1981. The main purpose of
the third bill, the 1995 Republican budget package supported by
D'Amato and opposed by Schumer, was a $245 billion tax cut. So
while the bill included about $30 billion in tax increases, it
hardly indicated support of higher taxes by D'Amato. As for the
second ad, D'Amato did vote against the 1994 crime bill, saying it
contained too much ``pork.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: These ads are intended as a counterattack to the
D'Amato ad calling Schumer ``wrong'' on taxes, welfare and crime.
They seek to convey a hard-and-fast message: the D'Amato ads are
untrue and the senator is untrustworthy. Accusing D'Amato of
``lying'' and of ``too many lies for too long'' may strike voters
as too vicious so early in the campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
