r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN     09-19 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OSCAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ HITS, THEN QUITS AGAINST DE LA HOYA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As unbelievable as it sounds, Julio Cesar Chavez had
Oscar De La Hoya right where he wanted him Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In an unforgettable eighth round, the two traded punches with no
regard for defense _ drawing a screaming, pro-Chavez crowd of
17,715 at Thomas &AMP; Mack Center to its feet _ and it was the aging
former champion who seemed to be in better condition when it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if a remarkable eight rounds meant absolutely
nothing, Chavez quit.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sport's great champions, his head bowed, blood
dripping from a cut inside his mouth and his opponent in apparent
trouble, in effect borrowed an infamous phrase from Roberto Duran
as he sat on his stool: No mas .
</P>
<P>
   It was an inglorious finish to an otherwise glorious effort.
</P>
<P>
   As for De La Hoya, he got the job done: He retained his WBC
welterweight title and remained undefeated (29-0, with 24
knockouts). However, he didn't dominate his 36-year-old opponent
(101-3-2, 84 KOs) as he had hoped and many expected. He fought
Chavez's fight much of the time, engaging in many toe-to-toe
exchanges in an apparent effort to get that knockout he so wanted
and didn't fare nearly as well as expected.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was ahead on all three cards, but it wasn't
one-sided: 79-63, 78-75, 78-75.
</P>
<P>
   And he never came close to that knockout, the knockout that
would force Chavez to give him the credit he refused to give him
after their first bout was stopped with Chavez cut in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, De La Hoya landed plenty of power punches and Chavez felt
them. However, he was never hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Chavez yelled, ``You did it, you did it'' and later
added, ``He's a great fighter,'' but it had to be half-hearted: Had
he not given up, it seemed, it could've been Chavez who did it.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's inexplicable explanation? ``We had a bad game
plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya controlled the fight when he stayed on the outside.
However, he refused to stay there: And, while De La Hoya also never
was hurt, he almost paid a very expensive price.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of so many, Chavez, who suffered inconsequential
cuts over both eyes, looked much like the Chavez of old and proved
that he has plenty left. De La Hoya's co-trainer, Gil Clancy, said,
``We beat the Chavez of old. Chavez was the best we've seen in five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges were both as thrilling and shocking as any seen in
this town in some time. And it all culminated in that unforgettable
eighth, when De La Hoya in effect said, ``What the heck? It's me or
him,'' and the two wailed away. A buzzing crowd couldn't wait for
the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was no next round. When the fight was stopped, De La
Hoya leaped in the air to indicate his joy, but he also had to be
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   At the post-fight press conference, Chavez said, ``I want to
make one thing clear: My corner stopped the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   However, replays of Chavez sitting on his stool appeared to show
him shaking his head as he was asked whether he wanted to continue.
Either way, it was fortunate for De La Hoya that Chavez didn't get
up.
</P>
<P>
   The champion will next face Ike Quartey, the former WBA
welterweight champion who many believed would be his first
legitimate challenger. Instead, Chavez was that legitimate
challenger, at least until he decided he couldn't take it any more
and spoiled what could've been one of the sport's great
performances.
</P>
<P>
   In other fights, Yory Boy Campas (72-2, 62 KOs) retained his IBF
junior middleweight championship when his one-sided fight with
Larry Barnes (44-3, 17 KOs) was stopped after three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mia St. John (8-0, 5 KOs) of Calabasas remained undefeated,
narrowly outpointing B.J. Felter (0-3) in a four-round
featherweight women's bout.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Diaz (23-2, 18 KOs) of Coachella stopped Hector Quiroz
(25-3-1, 21 KOs) at 1:05 of the 12th and final round of a junior
lightweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   And Eric ``Butterbean'' Esch (39-1-1, 29 KOs) knocked out Troy
Roberts (14-7, 13 KOs) 41 seconds into the third round of a
scheduled four-round heavyweight bout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
