<HEADLINE>
BURKETT COMES UP ACES FOR RANGERS IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander John Burkett presented his most
compelling argument to remain a member of the Texas Rangers'
rotation through the season's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The honorable Johnny Oates, who also serves as the Rangers'
manager, remains noncommittal toward his verdict despite powerful,
11th-hour evidence presented by Burkett during Friday night's 3-1
victory against the Oakland Athletics at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett surrendered only one run on four hits through eight
innings, and home runs from third baseman Todd Zeile and first
baseman Lee Stevens during the middle innings helped the Rangers
keep their 11/2-game lead ahead of the Anaheim Angels in the
American League West, pending the result of the Angels game later
Friday night against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone way past thinking about myself,'' said Burkett, who
will be the odd-man out should Oates decide in favor of a four-man
rotation before Wednesday. ``A lot of managers wouldn't have stayed
with me this long, and I appreciate that. I'll understand whatever
he decides.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett's understanding of the situation stems from his
performance this season. Friday night's 89-pitch appearance was the
33-year-old veteran's best since his July 9 start against the
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Burkett's first since Aug. 6, and his earned-run
average slipped under the 6.00 threshold. However, his next
scheduled start would be Wednesday against the Angels at Edison
International Field of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I want to pitch again? Yes,'' said Burkett, who gained that
elusive eighth victory in his 21st decision. ``I feel like I can
rise to the occasion even though it's hard to have confidence in
someone who is 8-13 with a 6-point ERA, but I think I can do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett presented his case.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Burkett, who pitched on nine days rest after muscle
spasms in his neck prevented him making his scheduled start
Tuesday, pitched ahead in the count throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about how important it was to pitch aggressively and
get ahead,'' catcher Ivan Rodriguez said. ``He came ready to pitch
and demonstrated that.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B: Right-handers Rick Helling (19-7) and Aaron Sele
(18-10) crossed the 200-inning barrier this season, and ``neither
one of them is feeling 100 percent right now,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager also indicated that he would prefer to stay with a
five-man rotation and not start ``four guys in a role they're not
accustomed to'' with only three days rest.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit C: Burkett owns a 3-1 record and 3.16 ERA in his four
previous starts against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit D: Burkett's Sept. 21, 1996, victory against the Angels
in Anaheim snapped the Rangers' five-game losing streak, and that
7-1 victory helped propel the organization toward its first and
only AL West title.
</P>
<P>
   Two arguments also can be made against Burkett starting
Wednesday against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander remains the rotation's most unreliable member,
as his record and ERA suggest.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' 5-1 victory June 12 at The Ballpark in Arlington
occurred with Burkett on the mound. Burkett surrendered home runs
to center fielder Jim Edmonds, right fielder Garret Anderson and
designated hitter Tim Salmon during that eight-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Oates acknowledged this week his thoughts of going to a four-man
rotation, which would mean that Burkett will not start another game
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never said he wouldn't,'' Oates said. ``I'll let you
know. I've said the rotation is going to be flexible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
