<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OATES HAS EARNED THE RIGHT FOR JOB SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ John Burkett helped general manager Doug
Melvin dodge potentially embarrassing questions about how his team
could be in the position of being caught short of pitching in
September on Friday night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Rangers' critical 3-1 victory against
Oakland behind Burkett's surprisingly strong eight innings _ he
hadn't won since Aug. 6 _ continued the momentum built by their
two-game sweep of the archrival Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, dangerously short in the bullpen despite a 14-man
pitching staff and the ability to add even more, might have been in
trouble if Burkett had been knocked out early. But the veteran
right-hander pitched like he did during the stretch run in 1996,
when he won two key games in the final week of the season to help
the Rangers secure their first division championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's a news bulletin that will raise few eyebrows:
Throughout it all, manager Johnny Oates remained calm, cool and
collected.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he did scratch his nose at one point in the fifth inning,
causing a ripple of excitement through the Metroplex, but it was
just a small itch.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the TV cameras showed the Rangers' manager back to his
normal statue-like self, arms folded across his chest, eyelids
drooping, gaze fixed hypnotically on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had a camera inside my stomach,'' Oates said, ``they
might see something different.''
</P>
<P>
   That know-nothing talk show critics and callers occasionally
criticize Oates for his seemingly passive disposition is of no
consequence. Only if new owner Tom Hicks is listening _ and you're
free to wonder if that's the case _ is there reason to be
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, without question, hesitation or preamble, should be told
that he will be back as the Rangers' manager in 1999, something
that hasn't been done yet.
</P>
<P>
   No waiting to see whether the Rangers will win the West. No
nothing. Just do it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Oates already has another year on his contract. That's your
basic severance package and he knows it. That does not mean he'll
be back.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Tom Schieffer says he expects no major changes
and Melvin maintains that he's happy with the job Oates and his
staff have done.
</P>
<P>
   But the official company line is that all evaluations, as usual,
will come following the season.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine if Hicks is on board, something that has yet to be
determined. The Rangers' new owner wasn't at The Ballpark for
Thursday night's critical showdown against the Angels _ he was the
honoree at a charity roast at The Dallas Press Club _ or for Friday
night's almost equally important victory against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The critics claim that not only is Oates too easy-going but that
he has surrounded himself with coaches who reflect the same
personality. Quiet. Unassertive. Boring.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   First, baseball's long and demanding 162-game, six-month
schedule requires an even keel. It has too many peaks and valleys
to accommodate those whose emotions ratchet up and down like a
fairgrounds roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   Even more importantly, what you see on TV or read about in your
daily newspaper does not always reflect what's going on behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't normally know, for instance, that Oates and hitting
coach Rudy Jaramillo aired each other out in the dugout during a
game in this homestand; or that Tom Goodwin and Rusty Greer heard
in no uncertain terms about their base running blunders after
Thursday night's game; or that a coach and a player wrestled in the
tunnel leading to the clubhouse the last time the Rangers played in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of slightly stained laundry that every team has
but that Oates normally chooses not to air in public.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is pleased with the job his coaches have done and he has
told Melvin that. It is Oates who will pay the highest price if
he's wrong about them.
</P>
<P>
   That includes pitching coach Dick Bosman, who has come under
fire because the Rangers' team earned-run average has rested near
or at the bottom of the league most of the season. He has done what
he could with what he's had.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosman's defense, remember that Rick Helling (19-7), who'd
never won more than five games in a season before this year, will
very likely become just the third 20-game winner in franchise
history, that Aaron Sele (18-10) has resurrected his career after
being given up for dead by the Red Sox and that the bullpen has
overachieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have had managers who ripped the players after every
loss (remember Kevin Kennedy?) and who screamed and kicked trash
cans over in the dugout during games (say hello, Doug Rader) and
those tactics failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Oates delivered this franchise its first and only
division title and he's on the verge of doing so for the second
time in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't buy a little job security, somebody's definitely
listening to the wrong people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
