</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FOYT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOYT'S CAREER MAKES HIM A CERTIFIED LEGEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To ascend from superstar status to become a legend, you must do
something that makes people say, ``only old so-and-so could do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The defining moment for Nolan Ryan came when a young third
baseman named Robin Ventura charged the mound after being hit by a
pitch. The old man grabbed the rushing Ventura, swiftly landed a
series of blows to his noggin and, in a few frenzied seconds,
gained larger-than-life status.
</P>
<P>
   The defining moment for A.J. Foyt came during the inaugural Indy
Racing League event at Texas Motor Speedway last year. The car
owner was celebrating a victory by his driver Billy Boat, when Arie
Luyendyk charged into victory circle, claiming he had won the race.
Foyt wasn't in the mood for debate. He slapped the driver from
behind, knocking him to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the funniest thing,'' IRL driver Greg Ray said. ``He's
the only person who could get away with it. Nobody really holds it
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRL returns to Fort Worth for the running of Lone Star 500K
Sunday at TMS. The series features up-and-coming drivers such as
Tony Stewart, Kenny Brack, Boat and Ray, and established veterans
such as Indianapolis 500 champions Luyendyk and Eddie Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   But its dominant personality is a certified legend and Texas
hero named Anthony Joseph Foyt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody may say legend,'' Foyt said Friday, after Boat drove
a Foyt Racing car to the pole for Sunday's Lone Star 500K. ``But my
name is just good old A.J.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know him say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he didn't exist, you'd have to invent him,'' Cheever said.
``Foyt's a legend. He is hard-headed, he is arrogant, he is very
opinionated, but I love him. I think he's a great guy. He was one
hell of a racer. He's one of the cornerposts to the IRL.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt was born in Houston in 1935, the son of a man who owned a
garage that specialized in race cars. By the time he was 5, he knew
he wanted to be a driver. When he was 18, he was a regular on the
midget-racing circuit in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   He worked his way up the Indy-car ranks and became the most
dominant driver in that series.
</P>
<P>
   He first won the prestigious Indy 500 in 1961 and went on to
become the first four-time winner of the ``greatest spectacle in
racing.'' He is the all-time Indy-car leader with 67 victories and
won the points title seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt also ran a part-time NASCAR schedule and won seven races in
the stock-car ranks, including the 1972 Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   He dabbled in endurance racing and won the 24 hours of LeMans in
1967 and the Daytona 24-hour race in 1983. He has won 12 driving
championships in various categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my fair share of glory through the years,'' Foyt said.
``I couldn't have had a better career, I don't think. I wouldn't
change anything I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt inspired boys who dreamed of racing the cars he drove to
glory, including Ray who, like Foyt, grew up in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember reading a biography about A.J. when I was in fifth
grade,'' Ray said. ``I remember the story of him driving go-karts
and quarter midgets, and taking the cars out when his dad wasn't
there and getting grounded, and being ornery just like he is now. I
actually did a skit in an English class of the life of A.J. Foyt,
being a four-time Indianapolis 500 champion.''
</P>
<P>
   With Foyt, it's my way or no raceway. When you have a resume
such as his, you tend to believe that your way must be the best
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who works for him is in for a very demanding
relationship,'' said Cheever, who drove for Foyt in the
Championship Auto Racing Teams ranks in 1994 and '95. ``I don't
think he could ever be a diplomat. Everybody would be at war in
about 20 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray experienced what it's like to work for Foyt when he joined
the team for two races this summer while Boat recovered from
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have three things to get along with A.J. Foyt as a
driver,'' Ray said. ``If you're a strong personality guy, if you
can _ for lack of a better word _ drive the crap out of the race
car, and if you can tell him what it's doing articulately and in
very few words, then you're A.J.'s kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt's gruff, terse manner can cause people to underestimate
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J. is not exactly polished around the corners, but he is a
very, very smart man,'' Ray said. ``He is also very passionate
about racing, and that is why he's been so good at it. A lot of
people worry about what people think of them. A lot of people worry
about how much money they're going to make. At the end of the day,
A.J. is one of those kind of guys who's always stuck to his guns
and did what he believed in, and everything worked out because he
did the right things for the right reasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
