<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARCA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIMMEL WINS POLE, THEN RUNS INTO WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In the space of a scant few seconds Friday,
Frank Kimmel experienced the full Wide World of Sports treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One moment, Kimmel tasted the thrill of victory. He roared past
the start/finish line at Texas Motor Speedway after a hot lap at
173.393 mph to take the pole for the ARCA Z-MAX 250 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The next, he experienced the agony of defeat. He hit the wall in
Turn 2 in his No. 46 Advance Auto Parts-Visionaire Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tore up the car pretty good, but it's fixable, so I think
we'll be OK,'' said Kimmel, the points leader in the ARCA
Bondo/Mar-Hyde Series who is after his 10th victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Kimmel didn't know he had tasted the thrill of
victory. If he had, he likely wouldn't have hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ciochetti, the 12th car out, set the pace with a lap of
31.182 seconds at 173.176 mph. It was the fastest circuit since the
ARCA cars arrived at the track Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had the pole there for a little bit, but I knew
it was going to be close,'' said Ciochetti, driver of the No. 17
Hughes Supply Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ciochetti realized the driver most likely to bump him was
Kimmel, who had run speeds close to that in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it held up until Kimmel topped it with the first of
his two laps.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, Kimmel didn't know he was the new pole sitter.
He was told via the radio that a stopwatch clocked him at 31.14,
but he didn't know if he could trust it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went ahead and started to run the second lap as hard as I
could to make up a little more and got a little off line coming off
\RTurn\S 2,'' Kimmel said. ``I got up in some loose stuff and
wasn't smart enough to back out of it, and I smacked the wall
pretty hard. We ran a .14 the first lap. If I had known that going
into the second lap, we never would have wrecked. But hindsight is
always better.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wreck, Kimmel will get to start from the pole
because his car was repairable. If he had gone to a backup car, he
would have had to start at the rear of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Ciochetti's speed held up for the outside of the front row.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the fastest car, but we've got the fastest car
with all four wheels still on it,'' he said. ``That's almost as
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Norris, who entered his first ARCA race to shoot race
footage for Walker, Texas Ranger _ the show starring his dad, Chuck
Norris _ qualified third at 172.062 mph.
</P>
<P>
   That was a surprise, but not because Norris is competing in an
ARCA event for the first time. He is an experienced racer who is
running the complete NASCAR Winston West series this season. The
surprise came because the No. 14 Prolong Super Lubricants Ford had
precious little practice time Thursday because of a master cylinder
problem, locked up brakes and an oil-line leak during practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy with it,'' Norris said. ``The car ran great.
After all that trouble \RThursday\S, I'm real happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he didn't take his second pole of the season,
Ciochetti also is happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to be on the front row,'' he said. ``You're
away from the trouble if it starts, unless you're the trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The fast drivers are concerned that there could be trouble
Saturday because of the disparity of the speeds in qualifying _ the
slowest car ran a not-so-hot lap of 145.231 mph, almost 30 mph
slower than Kimmel _ because of the length of the race and because
of tires that aren't gripping the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting a lot of attrition, but I'm hoping that doesn't
happen,'' Ciochetti said. ``Everybody doesn't have a handle on this
place.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pole went to the fastest. The race won't necessary come down
to the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to have to be a smart race,'' Kimmel said.
``Whoever is the smartest will win this thing. And I've already
done my stupid thing for the week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
