<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT SEIZES LONE STAR POLE IN RECORD FASHION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Billy Boat captured the pole for the Lone
Star 500K Sunday with a backup engine he did not know about, and
with innuendo he has come to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the most recent Pep Boys Indy Racing League event at
Texas Motor Speedway in June, Boat added the track qualifying
record to his resume with a hot lap of 225.979 mph. Boat's one-lap
wonder _ the gearbox in his car broke on his second allowable lap _
erased the mark of 224.448 mph set by Tony Stewart for the True
Value 500K on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Boat earned the sixth PPG Pole of his career and fifth of the
season, an IRL record. The pole was Boat's third consecutive _
another IRL record. The speed was also the fastest by a new formula
IRL car, which debuted in the series in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Good stuff from a guy who was admittedly lost after the first
day of practice, when he posted a top speed of 216.381 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out to lunch this morning,'' said Boat, driver of the
No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora owned by four-time Indianapolis 500
champion A.J. Foyt of Houston. ``We went back and changed almost
everything. We changed springs, (ride) heights _ there wasn't
anything we didn't change. We went out and two changes later we ran
a lap at 226. I'm constantly amazed at the wealth of his (Foyt's)
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat was also amazed to learn during the post-qualifying news
conference that he had set the record with a backup motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy had a race motor in today, our backup race motor,
because we broke his qualifying motor on the dyno,'' said Foyt,
whose specially prepared qualifying Oldsmobile Aurora V-8s are the
envy and bane of his competitors. ``This was actually a very good
backup race motor. That's why we put it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, meanwhile, salvaged some pride and managed to raise
temperatures inside Foyt's pits when he pulled out a lap at 224.869
mph on the final attempt of the afternoon. That allowed Stewart,
the reigning series champion, to secure the No. 2 qualifying
position.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before qualifying, Firestone engineers reported the air
temperature at 93 degrees and track temperature at 127 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, whose No. 1 Glidden-Menards Special Dallara/Aurora was
uncharacteristically down on horsepower in the most recent race at
Atlanta Motor Speedway, fired the last shot at Boat after his team
changed engines. At 5:19 p.m., Stewart took the car out for a
``leak check'' of the engine but did not take the green flag to
start his qualifying run. He returned at 5:37 p.m. but fell short
of knocking Boat off the pole.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was running a qualifying motor, Stewart said: ``I
think we're running anything that we have that's in one piece. I
don't even know how many motors we have. Anything that's in one
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Team Menard have been publicly at odds with the Foyt
camp since the race at New Hampshire International Speedway in
June, when team-owner John Menard suggested that Foyt's qualifying
engines were not totally legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on that,'' Stewart said tersely.
``The guy's a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the charges of cheating are a backhanded compliment,
Foyt said, ``Usually the ones that call you cheaters _ that's who
you need to look it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat's three consecutive poles are the perfect complement to
teammate Kenny Brack, who has won a record three consecutive IRL
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good young crew working very hard,'' said Foyt,
explaining the hot streaks. ``They realized what a win means to
them. Like I've always said, when you start tasting those wins you
just go crazy for it. It's like giving a kid candy. They're just
working that much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack, driving a car Foyt said was identical to Boat's except
for the engine, wound up 10th with a hot lap at 222.186 mph in the
No. 14 Power Team Dallara/Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Racing teammates Scott Sharp, who formerly drove for
Foyt, and Mark Dismore make up the second row after posting
respective speeds of 224.551 mph and 224.299 mph in their
Dallara/Auroras. Sharp was among nine drivers who took the No. 2
spot in the order before Stewart settled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the bad thing about going out first,'' said Boat, who
actually went out second to Roberto Guerrero. ``We were sitting
there, it seemed like, forever. There was a lot of fast guys there
at the end and we knew it was cooling off so they were going to
pick up a little speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of agonizing down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
