<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HIT AGAIN BY INJURY BUG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys' banged-up defensive line
took another hit Friday. Lineman Antonio Anderson will miss three
to four weeks because of torn cartilage in his knee, coach Chan
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is expected to have surgery this morning. He injured
his knee in practice Thursday. A magnetic resonance imaging exam
performed Friday revealed torn cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   With tackles Leon Lett (knee) Chad Hennings (knee, ankle, wrist)
hobbling, the Cowboys' front four will be challenged to hold up
against a Giants offensive line that averages 315 pounds per
player.
</P>
<P>
   Lett and Hennings returned to practice Friday for the first time
this week. Gailey said both will probably start against the Giants,
although Lett might be limited to 25 to 30 plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like Chad and Leon did OK,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lett played about 15 snaps against Denver last week, but Gailey
said he expects Lett to play more against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to limit him,'' he said. ``He's looking better
than he was last week, so I'm hoping he will play more snaps than
he played last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had played mostly behind defensive end Greg Ellis,
registering one tackle in two games. Gailey said the club is
considering whether to add a defensive lineman to replace Anderson.
But the Cowboys will go into the Giants game with a seven-man
rotation on the line, instead of the normal eight-man rotation,
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurvin McCormack is expected to get most of the defensive snaps
in Anderson's place, Gailey said. WARREN NEARS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Running back Chris Warren, who has surprised team trainer Jim
Maurer with his fast recovery from an injured groin muscle, said he
needs one week before he will be ready to play. He said he expects
to be placed on the inactive list for the Giants game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
