<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Dodgers could have gone quietly, the way
they had all season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the night they were eliminated from the National League
wild-card race, the Dodgers decided to play it tough Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Not until a Barry Bonds homer off Scott Radinsky to lead off the
bottom of the eighth was the Dodgers' season mathmatically ended
with a 4-3 loss to the San Francisco Giants at 3Com Park in front
of 31,452.
</P>
<P>
   For Bonds, honored before the game as baseball's first player to
reach 400 home runs and 400 stolen bases, it was his 35th homer of
the year and 409th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, it was the same old sad refrain.
</P>
<P>
   They took the lead, lost an important player _ in this case,
Dave Mlicki to injury _ then watched the game slip away.
</P>
<P>
   The game had none of the classic overtures of this storied
rivalry _ no pennant race on the line, no fights in the stands. But
in a season of unfamiliar faces, the Dodgers were hoping to see
more of Mlicki, who left the game with one out in the sixth with
lower back pain.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Mlicki departed that the Giants tied the game at
three with a seventh-inning pinch single by Marvin Bernard off
Radinsky that scored Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants entered the game five back in the wild-card race with
10 games to play. The Chicago Cubs and New York Mets already had
lost Friday.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered to Mlicki, already under contract ($2.25
million) for 1999, but already is best known as the pitcher stolen
in the Hideo Nomo deal, Fred Claire's last trade as general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki has been solid, 8-3 in 19 starts since he came to the
Dodgers from the New York Mets along with right-handed reliever
Greg McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   After Claire was fired, interim GM Tom Lasorda sent McMichael
back to the Mets for left-hander Brian Bohanon. Mlicki and Bohanon
have re-established careers with the Dodgers that were floundering
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants, Mlicki made few mistakes. The first was a
fourth-inning double by Jeff Kent that scored Bonds with the Giants
first run.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had taken a 1-0 lead in the top of the fourth
against Giants starter Mark Gardner, who last won Sept. 6 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi opened with a single, stole second and took third
on a throwing error by Giants catcher Brent Mayne. He scored on an
infield out by Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added two runs in the fifth when Gardner was undone
by his control. After allowing a double to Roger Cedeno, Gardner
retired Jim Eisenreich, but walked Eric Karros and Bobby Bonilla to
load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   With Mondesi at the plate, Gardner threw a wild pitch to score
Cedeno and put Karros at third. Karros scored on an infield out by
Mondesi to give the Dodgers a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki first strained is back swinging the bat in the sixth
inning when he flied to the right-field warning track. He struck
out Burks to open the Giants sixth, but then gave up a double to
Bonds off the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi made it a close play when his strong throw just missed
getting Bonds and punched the air in disgust. So did Dodgers
manager Glenn Hoffman when Kent followed with his second RBI double
to cut the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki clutched his lower back as pitching coach Charlie Hough
came to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers turned to rookie left-hander Jeff Kubenka, who won
his first major league game Sept. 8 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants pinch hit Joe Carter for J.T. Snow and Carter flied
to medium center. Cedeno made the catch and Kent made an
ill-advised attempt to take third. Cedeno threw him out easily to
end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were back at in the seventh when Kubenka walked
Charlie Hayes to open the inning. Hayes was sacrificed to second
and went to third on Rich Aurelia's ground single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Kubenka came back to strike out pinch hitter Chris Jones before
giving way to the veteran Radinsky, who gave up the game tying
single to pinch hitter Bernard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
