<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN HAS NO DEFENSE FOR WINLESS START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After waiting 40 years for the school's second national
championship in football, Michigan fans are now waiting for some
good news. They had better be patient.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines' first 0-2 start in a decade was darkened
considerably this week by the news that senior safety Marcus Ray,
considered the best player on a veteran defense, has been suspended
while an investigation is conducted into his alleged dealings with
an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The litany of problems is long: no running game, a porous
defense, inconsistent special teams. Also, there's a quarterback
controversy brewing; freshman Drew Henson continues to impress in
relief of starter Tom Brady.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, a school icon is missing. The ``Go Blue''
banner that hangs in the tunnel at Michigan Stadium was stolen last
week. Since 1962, the players have jumped and touched the banner as
they ran on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me what's going on, what's happening, I'm still
surprised with it,'' Michigan offensive tackle Jon Jansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Michigan led the nation in total defense. After two
games, Michigan ranks 84th in total defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected us to be a much better defensive football team than
we are,'' coach Lloyd Carr said. With nine starters returning, that
was a reasonable expectation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Wolverines allowed 9.5 points and 89 yards rushing
per game. In losing its first two, Michigan is allowing 37 points
and 235 yards rushing a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any questions of whether or not this is the same team as last
year, or whether we're going to be stellar on defense, they've been
answered: We're not there yet,'' nose tackle Rob Renes said. `We
have a lot of improvement to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Michigan faces Eastern Michigan, which makes the
eight-mile trip from Ypsilanti to Ann Arbor with a 1-1 record. In
two weeks, the Wolverines face Michigan State, which dominated a
Notre Dame team that mauled Michigan in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines are 0-0 in the Big Ten. And there's always the
(annual) dream of ruining Ohio State's year in the season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two weeks to get ready for the Big Ten season, and
we each have to take a look at where we are and what we're doing,''
Carr said. ``It's going to be a lonely time now. We understand
that. But we have to dig ourselves out of this hole.''
CHAMPIONSHIP FALLS
</P>
<P>
   In the 62 years of The Associated Press rankings, 11 teams that
finished No. 1 failed to finish in the top 10 the next season.
Michigan, last season's AP champion, is 0-2 and unranked. The 11
teams that had the biggest falls after a championship season: Team,
title year Next season W-L, rank Alabama, 1992 9-3-1, 14th
Colorado, 1990 8-3-1, 20th Penn State, 1986 8-4-01, UR BYU, 1984
11-3-0, 16th Miami (Fla.), 1983 8-5-0, 18th Penn State, 1982 8-4-1,
UR USC, 1962 7-3-0, UR Syracuse, 1959 7-2-0, 19th Notre Dame, 1949
4-4-1, UR Ohio State, 1942 3-5-0, UR Minnesota, 1941 5-4-0, UR TCU,
1938 3-7-0, UR
</P>
<P>
   Notes: UR means team was not ranked in final poll; Alabama's
record in 1993 was changed to 1-12 because of NCAA-mandated
forfeits; In 1962, the AP poll ranked 10 teams.
BCS SETS RATINGS DATES
</P>
<P>
   It's complicated. It's maligned. And it's not going to make its
debut until mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series' ratings, which will decide what
teams play in the national championship game, will debut Nov. 17.
The news media and coaches polls are a Monday morning staple, but
the championship ratings take more time to figure because of all
the factors. The ratings combine the two polls, three computer
ratings, strength of schedule and won-loss record.
</P>
<P>
   The series ratings will be released four times. The final time
will be Dec. 6, the day after the major conference title games. The
teams that finish first and second will be matched in the Fiesta
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was not to do it too early because we wanted to get
enough games to gauge the teams' strengths,'' said BCS spokesman
Charles Bloom of the Southeastern Conference, which is charged with
figuring and distributing the ratings. ``Also, we didn't want to
have the poll come out that many times. The only one that makes a
difference is the last one.''
JOE (GRAND) PA
</P>
<P>
   Joe Paterno kept saying that reaching a coaching milestone was
no big deal. But after he recorded the 300th victory of his career
Saturday against Bowling Green, Paterno was surprised that his
emotions betrayed him.
</P>
<P>
   After the Nittany Lions' 48-3 victory, his players carried him
to the middle of the field for a postgame ceremony. He told the
sellout crowd of 96,291 spectators that he was ``overwhelmed'' and
``filled up with memories'' of his 48 years at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' he said later. ``You think you know yourself.
I didn't realize I'd get that choked up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room with his players, he started crying. The
tears flowed again when Matthew Gigerich, his 16-month-old
grandson, toddled up and presented gramps with the game ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in tears a little bit when he started crying,''
linebacker LaVar Arrington said. ``It was an emotional thing. It
meant a lot to me. We made history today and I was proud to be a
part of it.''
LIGHTENING UP
</P>
<P>
   Before his team's game with Iowa last week, Iowa State coach Dan
McCarney told defensive backs Jeff Waters and Jamarcus Powers he
would change his hair color if the Cyclones won.
</P>
<P>
   Final score: Iowa State 27, Iowa 9. McCarney hair color: blond
from brunette.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks horrible,'' McCarney said. ``It's taking homeliness
and ugliness to a new level.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarney won't have to put up with his new look for long. The
color can be shampooed out.
IN QUOTES
</P>
<P>
   Purdue coach Joe Tiller believes that the Boilermakers' attitude
after a 21-19 defeat of Rice on Saturday is a sign of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come a long way in a short period of time at Purdue
when we come off the field and we're disappointed with a win,''
Tiller said.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee wide receiver Peerless Price on life without
quarterback Peyton Manning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, when you have one guy who gets all that
attention, you sometimes kind of sit back and wait for him to make
something happen. And the thing with Peyton is that he almost
always made a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden on 26-year-old sophomore Chris
Weinke after his six interceptions in an upset loss to North
Carolina State:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you none of them have lost any confidence in
him. You know why? Because there's not a one of them who can look
at him and say, `Hey, I did good. You did bad.' It was a total team
loss.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Voters in The Associated Press poll were not impressed by
Kansas State's 73-7 victory against Northern Illinois. The Wildcats
dropped from fourth to fifth and were passed by UCLA. Jeff
Sagarin's computer rankings list Michigan (0-2) No. 15 and Kansas
State (2-0) No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   _ Figure today's Florida-Tennessee game to be decided early. The
Gators have won the past five in the series and have outscored the
Volunteers 52-13 in the first quarter. In four of the five losses,
Tennessee was scoreless in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clemson, coming off a 37-0 loss to Virginia Tech, opens
Atlantic Coast Conference play at No. 10 Virginia. The Tigers have
lost five of their past six ACC openers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Under coach Butch Davis, Miami is 3-7 against ranked
opponents. The 2-0 Hurricanes face four ranked foes in the next
five games _ Virginia Tech today, UCLA, Rutgers, Florida State and
West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oregon State (2-0) is at Southern California today. The
Beavers have not won their first two games since 1985. The last
time they were 3-0 was 1967, which is also the last season they
defeated USC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
