</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATERACE (New York) _ The Senate race in New York state
turned nasty almost immediately after the primaries ended. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The arguments have not changed,
nor have the graphic charts, the anecdotal stories, or the votes.
The Senate, for the second time in two years, voted on Friday day
to uphold Clinton's veto of a ban on a late-term abortion procedure
that opponents call partial birth. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
votes to release the videotape of President Clinton's grand jury
testimony and an additional 2,800 pages of material from Kenneth
Starr's investigation. By Alison Mitchell. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GINGRICH (Washington) _ In the starkest display of
contrasting Republican approaches to capitalizing on the White
House scandal, several speakers at the Christian Coalition's
convention here on Friday expressed outrage at President Clinton
while others said only that he deserved their prayers. By Richard
L. Berke. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ President Clinton on Friday focused
his attention on an area where he has displayed comfort, as well as
intellectual and political surefootedness: race. On a day when the
appearance of normality was a precious commodity at the White
House, Clinton's only public act was to officially receive the
report of the Advisory Board to the President's Initiative on Race.
By Steven A. Holmes. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BLACKS (Atlanta) _ In dozens of interviews this week,
black Americans ranging from the NAACP's chairman, Julian Bond, to
the comedian Chris Rock cited everything from Clinton's choice of
friends to his choice of woodwinds in explaining why he has
connected with minorities unlike any previous president, viscerally
as well as politically. And while blacks, like most Americans, are
deeply disturbed by Clinton's infidelity, recklessness and
dishonesty, they are not willing to jettison what they see as a
unique relationship in exchange for an uncertain and potentially
threatening future. By Kevin Sack. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LABOR-LEADER (New York) _ The politically influential leader
of the local representing New York City's school cafeteria aides
and crossing guards has been expelled from his union for improper
financial dealings. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERCARE-FIASCO (Chicago) _ It sounds like a typical child
welfare dispute: The foster parents who have reared a 2{-year-old
boy almost since birth want to adopt him. The boy's mother, who
lost him because of addiction but has since stopped using drugs,
wants him back. But when the foster parents are powerful city
alderman and a prominent judge, accusations of political favoritism
are bound to bubble up. And because the couple are white and the
child is black, the case has also brought a small petition drive
and a protest vigil led by a black minister. By Pam Belluck. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-MEXICO-DRUGS (Mexico City) _ After a nearly three-year
inquiry into drug corruption in Mexico, Swiss police investigators
have concluded that a brother of former President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari played a central role in Mexico's cocaine trade, raking in
huge bribes to protect the flow of drugs into the United States. By
Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CASTE-VIOLENCE (Meerut, India) _ When Srichand, among the
least touchable of untouchables, was killed Sept. 2, he was doing
the humiliating work of his subcaste, the balmikis, going from
house to house with a broom, a scoop and a bowl, carrying away the
``night soil'' from the dry toilets in people's houses. While the
spark for the murder was a disputed romance, the kindling lay in
the caste-based tensions of India, where a half-century of
well-intended efforts to erase the lines of prejudice have in some
ways made caste more important than ever. By Barry Bearak. (With
photos and map.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COMMUNE (Xiaogang, China) _ In late 1978, starving and
desperate, the 20 families in this village of Anhui Province in
eastern China took matters into their own hands, and secretly
divided up the communal farm, risking the wrath of the party.
Within a few years, as the country learned of the remarkable gains
in Xiaogang and a few other pioneering places, the hated communal
farms broke apart all over China _ the single greatest step toward
the country's vibrant, market-oriented economy of the 1990s. By
Erik Eckholm. (With photo and map.)
</P>
