</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENES PITCHES ANOTHER GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Facing the Diamondbacks on Friday night obviously was
not on Atlanta star right-hander Greg Maddux's list of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   After his previous start on Sunday, when he came out of the game
against Florida after six innings with tightness in his triceps,
Maddux said, ``I'll be able to start against the Arizona _ what are
they called? _ The Diamondbacks?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he will remember who they are after they defeated him
and the Braves, 5-0, in front of 46,434 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason that Arizona was able to raise its record to
62-93 was not so much getting to Maddux, but the fact that the
Braves couldn't get to Diamondbacks right-hander Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of a near no-hitter against the Reds in Cincinnati
on Sunday, Benes came through to shut down Atlanta on three hits
through eight innings to increase his scoreless inning streak to
20, one-third of an inning shy of right-hander Willie Banks' club
record. Over his past five starts, Benes is 3-1 with an ERA of
0.69.
</P>
<P>
   He also was able to raise his record to 14-13, the first time he
has gone beyond the .500 level this season. The 14 victories equal
the 14 of Tampa Bay's Rolando Arrojo for the most wins by an
expansion pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Alan Embree, who came to Arizona from the Braves on
June 23 in a trade for right-hander Russ Springer, began the ninth
but got in trouble. He walked leadoff man Gerald Williams, but
Williams was doubled off first when Chipper Jones lined out to Matt
Williams at third and Matt Williams threw to Travis Lee at first.
</P>
<P>
   Embree gave up a single to Ryan Klesko and a double to Andruw
Jones before Arizona Manager Buck Showalter brought in veteran
right-handed closer Gregg Olson, who got pinch-hitter Andres
Galarraga on a game-ending grounder to Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored single runs in the third and sixth, then
broke it open with three in the seventh off Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Benes started the rally with a single to right field, then later
scored on a fielder's choice grounder by Matt Williams. Travis Lee
followed with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got a case of ``wildness'' as Benes led off the top of
the third. One pitch was extremely tight and the other amazingly
went behind the big fellow.
</P>
<P>
   If one were a conspiracy buff, one might think the pitches were
retaliatory in nature after a game in Atlanta on April 22 in which
Benes plunked the Braves Andruw Jones with a pitch after John
Smoltz had hit Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Though Smoltz called Williams immediately after that game to say
it wasn't intentional, Benes didn't apologize in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that we're not here to make friends,'' Benes
said.
</P>
<P>
   So since Smoltz wasn't scheduled to pitch and make a possible
response, it was Maddux's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux walked Benes and attempted to pick him off first, but the
throw went past first baseman Ryan Klesko and Benes took off for
second. He probably should have stopped there, but he lumbered for
third like a big truck that had lost its brakes. He lunged
head-first in the dirt, but the throw to third baseman Chipper
Jones was there in plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Fox then singled to left-center, stole second and scored
the first Arizona run on a single to left by Jay Bell. It was the
1,500th hit of Bell's career.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux then bore down to strike out six of the next nine
batters. His strikeout of Fox for the second out of the fifth
inning was his 200th of the season, the first time he has reached
that mark in his career.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the sixth, the Diamondbacks got consecutive
singles from Lee, Tony Batista and David Dellucci to produce a run
for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux then ran out of gas in the seventh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
