<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-CHAVEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESPECT, TITLE FOR OSCAR  
 CHAMPION STOPS CHAVEZ AFTER 8 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ For weeks, respect was just a word. Friday night, it
finally meant something.
</P>
<P>
   It could be measured.
</P>
<P>
   Seen.
</P>
<P>
   And spilled.
</P>
<P>
   Only Julio Cesar Chavez tasted it.
</P>
<P>
   For Chavez, a mouthful of blood was the bitter residue of defeat
at the fast and wicked hands of angry Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya had been promising to make his boyhood idol submit.
He promised punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he delivered. There was no knockout. Chavez was
never off his feet. But the fight ended after eight rounds with
Chavez seated on his stool and blood filling his mouth from a cut
on his lower right lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got what I wanted: I made him quit,'' De La Hoya (29-0, 24
knockouts) said after he retained the World Boxing Council's
welterweight title in front of a Thomas &AMP; Mack Center crowd of
17,125.
</P>
<P>
   There could be no bigger insult hurled at a proud fighter who is
so worshiped in his native Mexico. It hurt more than any punch
thrown by De La Hoya, who was badly bruised beneath his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   Bruises vanish. Cuts leave only scars. But humiliation is a
savage cut. It always stings.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez (101-3-2, 84 KOs) raged at suggestions that he is a
quitter. He spit out a couple of expletives in English.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed his cornermen for the stoppage. But he never said why
he didn't argue the decision, and De La Hoya expressed skepticism
about who was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't quit,'' an interpreter said as he translated
Chavez's Spanish. ``He's a man. He has heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But by boxing standards, he's a very old man. More than 100
bouts has turned the 36-year-old warrior into a relic. An irony is
that the bout ended after one of his most spirited rounds in years.
</P>
<P>
   With blood trickling down his face from a slight cut above his
left eye, Chavez tested De La Hoya as severely as anyone has.
</P>
<P>
   There were moments when De La Hoya's eyes seemed to fill with
uncertainty as Chavez shook off a couple of early combinations and
went straight at him again and again.
</P>
<P>
   In the round's final seconds, the crowd went wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico, Mexico,'' Chavez partisans chanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar, Oscar,'' countered De La Hoya fans.
</P>
<P>
   The echoes still reverberated through the arena when, suddenly,
it was over. The end was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya had to be the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Judges John Keane, David Van De Wide and Anek Hongtongtain
thought so. De La Hoya led on all three cards. Computerized
punching statistics also favored De La Hoya, who earned $9 million
and a percentage of pay-per-view TV sales. He connected on 49
percent of his blows compared to Chavez's 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After the fight, Chavez said he will retire after a bout with
International Boxing Federation junior welterweight Vince Phllips.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seemed certain:
</P>
<P>
   There will not be a third De La Hoya-Chavez match. De La Hoya
faces other, perhaps more difficult challenges. On Nov. 21 at Las
Vegas, he has a date with former World Boxing Association
welterweight champ Ike Quartey, who was at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat me; I don't want no more,'' Chavez finally said.
</P>
<P>
   From him, it was a mouthful.
</P>
<P>
   Of respect. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
