A4017 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-NTEXAS-ADV-AZ     09-19 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-NTEXAS-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS: BIG PAYDAY ASU: MAKE THEM-PAY DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Arizona State's practice field has resembled a
holding cell of sorts this week, with coaches taking a tough love
approach to workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Has ASU been scared straight? The answer comes tonight when
North Texas, which became a Division I-A program three years ago,
visits Sun Devil Stadium. Kickoff is 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking them very seriously, obviously,'' ASU
quarterback Ryan Kealy said. ``We're 0-2, so if we don't, there's
something really wrong with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sun Devils are 36{-point favorites, they might as
well be underdogs. The slap of reality provided by losses to
Washington and Brigham Young has made this team take nothing for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Everything on paper suggests this game will be a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who also call themselves the Mean Green, are still
finding their way under first-year Coach Darrell Dickey. They've
managed a combined nine points in losses to Oklahoma and Texas
Tech. Dickey plans to use quarterbacks Jason Attaway and LaDarrin
McLane against the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas has acknowledged that scheduling this game has much
to do with money. The Eagles will make $370,000 from this contest
and $1.28 million this season, the most in the country.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas' schedule is rated the 52nd toughest in the nation
by ``USA'' ``Today's'' Jeff Sagarin, which is tougher than powers
Nebraska (92nd) and Florida (133rd).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on the win-loss record, but it helps our athletic
department a lot,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tough on the ego, too. The Sun Devils are bitter about
their start and the prevailing theme among players seems to be:
Take out frustrations on North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like them to play angry every week,'' ASU Coach Bruce
Snyder said. ``Smart angry, not dumb angry. I hope none of these
guys have to go to war, but the game of football is as close to war
as you're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said, ``(The Sun Devils) are probably disappointed in the
way they've played. They may be a little better equipped than us to
handle that from a mental standpoint. That's what their intentions
will be on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our intentions will be to hang together, work through
our mistakes and keep getting better as a football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting jobs could be won or lost in this game for ASU. Snyder
will be taking a close look at junior college transfers Junior
Ioane and Erik Flowers, who will be starting at defensive tackle
and end, respectively, tonight for the first time. Eric Fields
starts for Stephen Trejo at linebacker, and free safety Phillip
Brown replaces Mitchell Freedman, who is sidelined because of a
thigh strain.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Peters steps in at left guard for Randy Leaphart, who is
out indefinitely because of a knee injury, and punter Stephen Baker
also will kick field goals after Mike Gauthier struggled in ASU's
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Snyder isn't buying this mismatch pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a real spirited group,'' he said. ``This is a real
compliment to Coach Dickey. In terms of schematics, they are smart,
they are not dumb. They play very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like the Sun Devils, who hope they have completed their
work-release program. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
