<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR     09-19 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER MUST PLAY HERO'S PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - A huge scab simmers below his elbow, an angry
wound that hasn't healed and probably won't until the season is
over. An early barrage of turf bruises are both self-inflicted and
inescapable, gifts of his inexperience and the men paid to protect
his backside.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing hurts like his bruised ego. And nothing has lingered
like the taste of failure.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer returns to the cozy cocoon Sunday, the place where
his legend was born. A place where he received a standing ovation
after debuting with a three-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are not as hard on me as, say, I was in New York and
threw a couple of picks,'' Plummer said. ``If I would've played
like I did last week and played in New York, they'd probably have a
guy starting for me this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Plummer, this is not the East Coast. But for the
first time, he returns in the form of a question mark. And for the
first time, he may be a quarterback on a short leash. &QL; 
Risking a riot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he orchestrates a victory, the whole tone of the season
changes, and everything's fine in the desert. But if Plummer
struggles again in a must-win venture against the Eagles, Vince
Tobin may have no choice but to turn to Dave Brown. Even if it
means risking a riot at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good week of practice, we have a good game plan, and
we should do a lot better,'' Plummer said. ``I think the guys take
it personally when a team gets seven sacks on them. Whether 2 or 3
of them were my fault, they still took it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   They should, because it's two weeks into the season, and Plummer
has been sacked nine times. In 26 possessions, the offense has
produced 24 points, 14 punts and five turnovers. They have yet to
score in the first half, turning each contest into a futile game of
catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   And so should Plummer, who has looked nothing like a budding
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   There are many theories surrounding the slow start. After a
nine-game audition last season, defenses have recognized Plummer as
a legitimate weapon. Opposing coaches have heeded the words of Bill
Walsh, who considers him the next Joe Montana and an MVP candidate
for this season. Together, they have done everything possible to
make his life miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be the fishbowl of structure. Last season, Plummer's
brilliance was mostly improvisational, a guy who made plays while
running for his life. This year, he is asked to read defenses, pick
the right receivers, succeed under a well-defined system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every quarterback is facing stuff like this, whether it's a
first-year guy or Warren Moon,'' Plummer said. ``They probably do
it more to myself to test me, see how far I've come, see how much
I've learned. And also to test the offensive line. We've been
tested, and we haven't stepped up.'' &QL; 
Downward trend &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Cardinals tried simplifying the game plan. This
week, they'll concentrate on keeping guys at home to help with
protection. The trend is ominous, an offense that is reacting to
what the defense is doing rather than the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that changes this week, a week in which the entire offense
started watching film together, stressing accountability. Plummer
cringed at his mistakes. Offensive lineman owned up to missed
assignments. Together, they vowed to get it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations are put on me, and they think the stadium will be
built if I have success,'' Plummer said. ``But you can't attribute
that (pressure) to my two bone-headed interceptions last week.
Nothing is like the expectations I put on myself as a quarterback
maturing and learning the system. I want to get better. And when we
get this offense all timed out and get everything going, I feel
more comfortable that we'll start moving the ball better.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, because somehow the Cardinals must discover the end zone.
And when the final gun sounds on Sunday, they better have found the
win column.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all starts with the guy taking snaps from center.
The hometown hero who has to start acting the part. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
