<HEADLINE>
TRAILING, 5-1, THUNDER MAN AGES TO PULL OUT A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ZUCKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For 45 minutes Friday night, the Arizona Thunder could
not figure out how to penetrate a stifling Sacramento Knights
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, it was the Sacramento defense that could
not figure out how to stop the Thunder offense.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 5-1, with seconds to go in the third quarter, the Thunder
stormed back to score six unanswered goals and held on to defeat
the Knights, 7-6, at Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually made a great game out of a lazy game,'' said an
exasperated Thunder Coach Petar Baralic after the victory. ``I
really don't like to win games like this. It may be good for the
spectators, but not for the teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Muth scored the first hat trick in the Thunder's brief
history, putting Arizona ahead for good in the fourth quarter with
his third goal. Trailing, 5-3, with just over six minutes to play,
the Thunder fired off four goals in 2:15 minutes to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indoor soccer is such a high-scoring game,'' Muth said. ``If
you can keep it relatively close, anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything almost did happen. Despite three agonizing quarters in
which the Thunder had plenty of scoring opportunities but could not
break through, Arizona continued to put pressure on Knights
goalkeeper Blair Quinn, finally hitting paydirt.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Soderman scored twice in the fourth quarter, while Jason
Vanacour and Kenny Wright each added a goal. Vanacour triggered the
four-goal flurry on a deflection of a hard shot by Mark Kerlin, who
had two assists, with 6:02 to go. Wright then tied the game at 5
with a beautiful one-on-one move around a defender and a pinpoint
shot past Quinn's left arm.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights (4-3) nearly came back in the game's waning minutes
after a goal by Danny Barber made it 7-6. They pulled Quinn in
favor of a sixth attacker but could not get a shot past Thunder
goalkeeper Chris Sagar.
</P>
<P>
   Sagar, making his first start after Scott Hileman signed with
the Florida Thunder Cats of the National Professional Soccer
League, made 13 saves to earn the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``For playing for the first time for the whole game, (Sagar) did
very well,'' Baralic said.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams will meet again tonight in Sacramento. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
