<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL FINDS A HOME AT 2ND BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Normally when a veteran player is asked to switch
positions in the 10th year of his major league career, it's almost
considered an act of heresy.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when that player is asked to move from shortstop,
where he had played 1,497 games at perhaps the most demanding
position on the field, to second base.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; Jay Bell is handling it well enough that second base may
become his permanent home in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay has taken to it well,'' said Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck
Showalter, &UR; who moved Bell to second and inserted  &UR; Tony Batista at
shortstop eight games ago in Cincinnati as part of a season-ending
experiment. ``I think it has inspired him, and I think he looks at
it as a challenge. I'll be very surprised if he can't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing about Jay is he'll do anything if he thinks it
can help the ball team. I know it sounds like a cliche, but in his
case, I really mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since making the switch, Bell has played errorless ball after
committing 18 errors in 135 games at shortstop, and the only miscue
Batista has made came in the second game after the move when he
dropped Bell's feed on a potential double play.
</P>
<P>
   What's more Bell, who collected his 1,500th career hit with an
RBI single in the third Friday night against  &UR; Greg Maddux, and
Batista have hit six of the team's last seven homers and have
formed one of the National League's most potent double-play
combinations at the plate with a combined 37 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things that Buck and I were talking about
for about three months, and it finally came about,'' Bell said. ``I
certainly appreciate that Buck came to me and asked me about it
first. I told him whatever helps the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a piece of the puzzle that will enable us to have
success in the future, I'm certainly willing to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, 32, broke into the majors with Cleveland by playing two
games at second in 1986, then moved to short in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is challenging is I don't have a rote memory of
going to places like I do at short,'' he said. ``At second base, I
have to think about where to go on certain situations. On the other
hand, the throw is nice and easy and you don't have to rush
yourself.'' &QL; 
Future 'Backs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rod Barajas, who catches for the Diamondbacks Class A High
Desert team, spent a day this week with the parent team before
joining the Instructional League in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   He said the heralded pitching trio of right-hander  &UR; Brad Penny
and southpaws
 &UR; John Patterson and  &UR; Nick Bierbrodt, just babes at 20, are all they
are said to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patterson has clocked 99 miles per hour and throws 95 to 94
consistently,'' Barajas said. ``Penny is probably the furthest
along and throws around 93 to 94. Their fastballs don't have a lot
of movement, but both have good command of their pitches and know
when to move the ball in and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bierbrodt improved a lot, too. We were in the pennant race at
the end of the season _ before he kind of had a
it's-just-another-game approach _ but he started battling every
game and got really mad if he didn't pitch well. It's funny, all
three really try to outdo each other.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
