<HEADLINE>
LANGKOW, WAITE READY FOR BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle of the backups will begin tonight at the Arrowhead
Pond of Anaheim, and  &UR; Jimmy Waite and  &UR; Scott Langkow say they are
ready.
</P>
<P>
   The two goalies will split time in the nets when the Coyotes
play the Mighty Ducks to open their eight-game preseason schedule.
Waite, the odds-on favorite to win the No. 2 job behind  &UR; Nikolai
Khabibulin, will get the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday night) Jimmy Waite was our best goaltender,''
Coyotes Coach
 &UR; Jim Schoenfeld said a day after Waite shined during the team's
annual Black and White scrimmage. ``Maybe it's a battle for No. 3.
We need Nik to play better, too. We need everyone pushing
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Langkow, the goalie of the year and a first-team All-Star last
season in the American Hockey League, won't concede anything, even
though most people probably aren't giving him a chance to beat out
the veteran Waite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just motivates me more than anything,'' he said. ``I've got
to make a strong showing, and that starts (tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update &QL; 
Veterans not expected to make the trip include  &UR; Jeremy Roenick,
Rick Tocchet, &UR; Teppo Numminen and  &UR; Jyrki Lumme.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Michel Petit suffered a concussion during Thursday's
scrimmage after a hard check by  &UR; Louie DeBrusk. He will be
sidelined indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing  &UR; Dallas Drake is back on the ice after missing two
days with back spasms. Center  &UR; Cliff Ronning said he will play
Sunday against the Vancouver Canucks after missing two days with
pulled abdominal muscles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
