<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-IOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMEY WARY OF IOWA  
 UA OFFENSE THRIVES WITH PAIR OF QBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Arizona has won its first two football games easily,
climbed to No. 16 in the rankings and appears ready to be a factor
in the Pac-10 race.
</P>
<P>
   However, Coach Dick Tomey isn't giddy about his Wildcats just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   He's pleased with their efforts in wins over Hawaii and
Stanford, but he knows his team has yet to be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   It's questionable if that challenge will come tonight, when
Arizona will open its home schedule against Iowa (1-1) at 7 p.m. in
Wildcat Stadium. The Hawkeyes lost last week to Iowa State, 27-9,
for the first time in 16 years. But, as Tomey is quick to point
out, the last time Iowa lost to the Cyclones, it beat Arizona the
next week.
</P>
<P>
   So Tomey is wary, and he hopes his team is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are a better team than they showed last week,''
Tomey said. ``They have the best skill people we have played
against, and it is not even close. They have more skill people than
(Hawaii and Stanford) put together.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona has more offensive threats than in any of Tomey's
previous 11 seasons in Tucson, beginning with its two quarterbacks,
sophomore Ortege Jenkins and junior Keith Smith. Each has started a
game this season, with Smith earning the nod last week at Stanford.
And each has come off the bench to spark the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey won't say which player will start tonight, but both will
play. That's as definitive as he gets about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, both players seem to be handling the
job-sharing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we keep winning, I don't see it changing,'' Jenkins
said. ``I'll get my two quarters, and Keith will get his two.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Arizona's biggest questions entering this season was its
defense, but the Wildcats have been dominant in the first two games
and held Stanford to 60 net rushing yards last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've played an offensive team yet that could
present the challenges that many teams in our conference will,''
Tomey said. ``We've got a lot of growing to do, but so far, we're
reasonably pleased with what we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear that Iowa will present that kind of challenge,
either. The Hawkeyes are averaging just 58 yards rushing this
season after leading the Big Ten a year ago with 217 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   This year's rushing average has been hurt by the team's
inability to protect the quarterback. The Hawkeyes have given up 12
sacks for 105 yards of losses, which in college football is
deducted from the rushing total.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Coach Hayden Fry, 69, is in his 37th year as a head coach,
and he's not panicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying hard to keep my head screwed on straight,'' he said
on the Big Ten's weekly conference call. ``I've been coaching so
long that I know the worst thing you can do with a young team is be
inconsistent.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 0222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
