<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL DIRECTOR ANGERED BY MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   J &UR; ohn Junker, &UR; executive director of the Fiesta Bowl, is a little
peeved at ``Sports Illustrated'' these days. And not because
representatives keep calling him during dinner trying to extend his
subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ``SI'' ran an item in its Scorecard section, pointing
out that the Fiesta Bowl is not assured of hosting a national
championship game, as ABC and Tostitos, the bowl's sponsor, are
implying in promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine correctly noted that a split vote for the national
championship could give a non-Fiesta Bowl team at least a share of
the national title. It's not likely to happen, but it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   So Junker decided to do a little writing himself and e-mailed a
challenge to the magazine last week. Junker offered to donate
$1,000 of his money to Arizona Special Olympics if the Fiesta Bowl
doesn't crown a national champion. If it does, then the magazine
would donate $1,000 to the charity.
</P>
<P>
   To punctuate his seriousness, Junker has sent the magazine a
personal check for $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you willing to put your money where your mouth is?''
Junker asked in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ``Sports Illustrated'' hasn't replied. But then, neither
has Junker's wife,  &UR; Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't told her about it yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Junker thinks his money is safe because the chance of another
bowl producing a national champion is remote, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a college football coach out there who is saying,
`We want to go to the Orange Bowl because maybe we can win a
national championship there,' '' he said. &QL; 
Tossin' it around &QL; 
Southern California Coach  &UR; Paul Hackett has returned to the college
game after spending the past five seasons coaching in the NFL, and
he's noticed a few changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more wide open right now,'' said Hackett, the
former coach at Pittsburgh. ``These people are all over the joint.
It's trick plays, screens to receivers underneath, all the skill
players. . . . It's far different than what I remember. It drives
coaches crazy, but it's great for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in Hackett's impression might have more to do
with geography than X's and O's. The Pac-10 has been known for its
wide-open style for years, while schools in the East usually have
been far more conservative. &QL; 
No wonder &QL; 
It's no wonder Arizona State's defense has struggled in the first
two games. The players are either too inexperienced to play at a
high level now, or they just aren't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this group with 1996. Seven players from that team made
NFL rosters this year, including linebacker  &UR; Derek Smith, a starter
for the Redskins; defensive end  &UR; Derrick Rodgers, a starter for the
Dolphins; linebacker  &UR; Pat
 &UR; Tillman, who is starting for the Cardinals; cornerback  &UR; Jason
Simmons, Pittsburgh; safety  &UR; Damien Richardson, Carolina; defensive
lineman  &UR; Shawn
 &UR; Swayda, Atlanta; and defensive lineman  &UR; Vince Amey, who is on the
Raiders' practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   The other starters were safety  &UR; Mitchell Freedman, a senior this
year; defensive end  &UR; Brent Burnstein, who was cut by the Cardinals
in camp this year; linebacker  &UR; Scott Van der Ahe, who was cut by
the Colts this year, and cornerback  &UR; Marcus Soward, now a teacher.
Defensive lineman  &UR; Jeremy Staat, now with the Steelers, was a
backup.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tillman, Simmons, Amey and Richardson did not
redshirt. If they had, they would be fifth-year seniors this year.
ASU's program has not developed to the point where players of that
quality are easily replaced. &QL; 
Hissing match &QL; 
Kansas Coach  &UR; Terry Allen and Missouri Coach  &UR; Larry Smith
acknowledged they have been reprimanded by the Big 12 for their
comments regarding the officiating in last week's game between the
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Allen was angry because officials didn't call pass interference
when the Tigers intercepted a pass at the Missouri goal line in
Missouri's 41-23 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about 10 different (camera) angles,'' Allen said.
``The defensive back pushes our receiver down and makes the
interception. It was right in front of the official.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that there were three clips on their punt return for
a touchdown,'' he said. ``That's why coaches don't officiate.
That's all part of the game. I've been hurt and helped both
ways.'' &QL; 
Perhaps they'll listen now &QL; 
Before his team's first game, Northwestern's  &UR; Gary Barnett preached
to his team about how dangerous Nevada-Las Vegas was. Northwestern
proceeded to win, 41-7.
</P>
<P>
   So when Barnett preached the same sermon last week for the Duke
game, his players apparently tuned him out. Lowly Duke whipped
Northwestern, 44-10. &QL; 
No circus acts &QL; 
 &UR; Phil Fulmer has a 55-11 record at Tennessee but is 1-5 against
Florida, which has won five straight over the Vols. Despite those
failures, Fulmer didn't use any special motivational ploys this
week as his sixth-ranked Volunteers prepared for today's game
against the second-ranked Gators in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to stand on my head and eat bugs and shave my
hair or anything like that,'' said Fulmer, the spoilsport.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, the Gators have enjoyed needling
Tennessee. Coach
 &UR; Steve Spurrier has joked about the Volunteers' annual drive for a
Citrus Bowl bid, a jibe at Tennessee's failure to make it to the
Sugar Bowl as the SEC champion.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida has toned down the act this season. It was the
Gators, not the Volunteers, who played in the Citrus Bowl last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to the Big House,'' Spurrier said of today's game
in Neyland Stadium. ``And we expect to be treated with a lot more
respect this year because we are now the defending Citrus Bowl
champions.'' &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL; 
 &UR; Kevin Gilbride Jr., the son of the San Diego Chargers coach, is a
freshman quarterback at Brigham Young. Gilbride, who played at a
Jacksonville, Fla., high school, was one of the top-rated prep
quarterbacks in the country last year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State Coach  &UR; Bobby Bowden blamed himself for quarterback
 &UR; Chris Weinke's poor performance in a loss to North Carolina State
last week. Weinke, a 26-year-old sophomore, was 9 for 32 and threw
five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've loaded him down like he's a senior, and he's not, which
he showed,'' Bowden said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
