<HEADLINE>
USC'S SOWARD KNOWS WAY TO THE END ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pac-10 has its share of show stoppers. In  &UR; Paul Hackett's
mind, no one is better than Southern California's  &UR; R. Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most exciting player in college football,'' the
Trojans coach said. ``We're only one game into our season. Just
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   What separates Soward is his propensity to get into the end
zone. He scores once every 5{ times he touches the ball. In the
22nd game of his career Saturday, against San Diego State, he
scored three touchdowns and rolled up 256 yards on nine plays. The
scores came on receptions of 8 and 53 yards and a 74-yard punt
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not enough,'' the junior said. ``My mind-set is that I
should score every time I touch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference has an array of exciting players, including ASU's
 &UR; J.R.
 &UR; Redmond and Arizona's  &UR; Dennis Northcutt, who can rack up yards. One
of the most interesting individual races in the league will be that
for leader in all-purpose yards.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska Coach  &UR; Frank Solich didn't win any friends in Berkeley
with his decision to kick a meaningless field goal with 19 seconds
remaining last weekend. The Cornhuskers were up, 21-3, at that
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was chicken (bleep),'' Bears safety  &UR; Marquis Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Solich said afterward he wouldn't do it again if put in the same
situation. &QL; 
On the rise &QL; 
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   By closing the 1997 season with four straight wins, the Wildcats
sent a message. Opening 1998 with two more was significant.
</P>
<P>
   The roughest part of their schedule will come in early October
with games against UCLA and Washington. &QL; 
On the decline &QL; 
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook isn't good for the Cardinal, which lost its opener
to San Jose State, 35-23, and fell to Arizona, 31-14.
</P>
<P>
   Five of its next seven games could be against ranked teams. &QL; 
Quote of the week &QL; 
``They did to ASU what we wanted to do to them defensively but
couldn't get done,'' Washington linebacker  &UR; Todd Johnson said about
Brigham Young, which will visit the Huskies today. &QL; 
Parting shots &QL; 
Linebacker  &UR; Anthony Kelly, one of the top recruits in Washington's
1998 class, has been granted a waiver by the NCAA and may practice
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   California has decided to redshirt wide receiver  &UR; Michael
 &UR; Ainsworth, who has been slowed by a deep thigh bruise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
