<HEADLINE>
NAU FACES CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ A major test awaits Northern Arizona's
football team tonight as it attempts to win its third straight game
under new Coach Jerome Souers.
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't so much whether the Lumberjacks (2-0) can
beat California State-Northridge (0-1) in a Big Sky Conference
opener at 6:05 p.m. at Walkup Skydome. The bigger picture focuses
on how the Lumberjacks will respond without quarterback Travis
Brown. He dislocated his left (non-throwing) elbow last week
against Southwest Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Brown, who entered the game in the fourth quarter, was 5
for 7 for 115 yards, including a 50-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Brown, a junior who crossed the 7,000-yard mark in
passing last week, will be assessed a week at time, Souers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a stabilizing factor on offense,'' Souers said.
``We were just starting to jell. But we've got to channel our
energy to do the same with Clay. We're banking on him.''
</P>
<P>
   If the new quarterback can get the ball into the hands of
receivers Francis St. Paul and Dion Black, he should put up some
big numbers. St. Paul is coming off national and conference honors
for his three-touchdown, 204-yard performance. It was Black's
circus catch that got the NAU offense into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks are ranked No. 13 in the Sports Network poll and
tied for No. 13 with Montana in the ESPN/USA Today poll. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
