<HEADLINE>
SPINKS PUTS `JINXS' ON TUCSON'S SUAZO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The son has all his front teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, there's not much that separates  &UR; Cory Spinks
from his dad,
 &UR; Leon, best-known for a famous upset of  &UR; Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   There's the fluid ring style with occasional power from wild
hooks that seem to circle the building before they land. And
there's the nickname:
</P>
<P>
   The Jinxs.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Spinks spells it with an `S' on the back of his robe.
Presumably, he wants everybody to know he's capable of casting more
than one bad spell.
</P>
<P>
   One was enough for Tucson junior welterweight  &UR; Lupe Suazo on
Friday during a non-televised bout before  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya's
victory over  &UR; Julio Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo (4-2, 4 knockouts) got the jinx. Spinks (11-0, 3 KOs) got
the win. The decision got the boos.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges scored against Suazo, who won the national
amateur championship in 1993 at Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Suazo was the aggressor throughout, but he was bloodied and
bruised near the left eye by Spinks' hooks. &QL; 
The populist's price &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is called the people's champ. His managers invested
$100,000 of his $6 million purse on tickets for fans and friends.
Lots of fans. Lots of friends. The people's champ knows how to keep
his corner populated. &QL; 
In your ear &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Tyson was in town. He will appear today at a Nevada
Athletic Commission hearing on reinstatement of his license. But he
wasn't at ringside Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody invited me,'' Tyson said at a World Boxing Council
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   (Insert your own ear joke here.) &QL; 
On the undercard &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Antonio Diaz (23-2, 18 KOs) of Coachella, Calif., kept the
International Boxing Association title he took from Phoenix super
lightweight  &UR; Ahmed Santos with a 12th-round technical knockout of
Mexican Hector Quiroz (25-3-1, 21 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   True colors &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. sportswriters often are accused of hiding a bias. Mexican
sportswriters wear one. Some wore red headbands, Chavez's
trademark, in the press room. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
