<SLUG> BC-CAR-SPRINT-BIRMINGHAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING BACK ON TRACK  
 RACER RECOVERS FROM ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This is what David Birmingham Jr. remembers of May 27,
1995:
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, next to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember leading most of the trophy dash and finishing
second,'' Birmingham said. ``I remember being mad about that. The
next thing I remember is being at the hospital on a Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash, however, occurred 72 hours earlier, on a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was a horrible accident.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing leader Dan Fredenburg in a midget heat race at
Manzanita Speedway, Birmingham was attempting to make a pass for
the lead. But Birmingham misjudged the distance separating the two
vehicles and struck Fredenburg's right rear tire with his car's
left front tire.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Birmingham's racer was sent into an uncontrollable
series of violent flips, six in all. When the machine landed
upright with a devastating thump after the final flip, Birmingham
was slumped over the steering wheel and unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was out 10 to 15 minutes,'' said Birmingham, who,
despite wearing a helmet, suffered a laceration near the top of his
head that required two large staples to close. ``But I don't
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Birmingham was released from the hospital within six
days, it could have been worse. In addition to the head injury,
which was serious enough to warrant an induced coma, Birmingham
suffered a badly broken left arm and a dislocated left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, now 31, wasn't issued a physician's release to
resume racing for almost a year after the crash. Then it was
another year before he finally climbed behind the steering wheel
again.
</P>
<P>
   But since returning to the Arizona Midget Racing Association
circuit in April 1997, Birmingham has been on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham notched career midget win No. 1 last August in Show
Low and finished third in the final driver standings, despite
missing several races.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham has added two more wins this season and likely will
finish runner-up in the championship standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started racing midgets in about 1989 or so, but before the
accident, I'd never won a race or finished way up in the
standings,'' Birmingham said. ``I really think I've become a better
racer since the crash because I'm smarter now. I'm more patient,
more willing to wait for my opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   And more determined than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were at the hospital and we knew after a couple of
days that he (David) would be all right, my friends would say to
me, `You can't let him race again. Make him not want to start back
up,' '' said Dayna Birmingham, who married her husband only six
weeks before the accident. ``I said, `If I do that, we'll have to
get him a blood transfusion, because racing's in his blood.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that when I married him. His dad raced and owned race
cars, and it's all David has done.''
</P>
<P>
   David Birmingham Sr., David's father, owned midget race cars
that drivers such as Jerry McClung and the late Bobby Ball drove.
The elder Birmingham, who, like Dayna, was at the race in which his
son was injured, said the crash reminded him of a wreck nearly
three decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``(McClung) was my driver, and we were at (Corona, Calif. in
1971),'' Birmingham Sr. said. ``There was an accident and Danny
Caruthers died. When I saw David's crash, it scared me. They were
so similar.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver Mark Passerrelli was the first to arrive at Birmingham's
wrecked car and immediately took control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was starting to turn blue,'' Passerrelli said. ``I told
(the paramedics) we need to get a helicopter out here now. When we
got him out of the car and on the stretcher, he woke up. He doesn't
remember this, but he started kicking and screaming. He didn't want
to go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham eventually went to the front of the midget class.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's a good racer,'' said Passerrelli, a multiple midget
champion. ``I think before the accident, he was intimidated by
drivers like myself. He's not that way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I'm beside another driver or someone's coming up right
behind me, no matter how good they are, to me they're just another
driver,'' Birmingham said. ``I used to think I had to try and
impress other racers. I think that's what happened the night I
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember feeling like I should have won that trophy dash,
and then when it came to the heat race, I think I was trying to
prove something to people. It forced me to make a misjudgement, and
look what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was bad. But at least Birmingham doesn't
remember. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
