<HEADLINE>
TIRE AGENTS STILL AROUSE SUSPICIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A powerful motor and an aerodynamically sleek chassis would be
useless if fitted with slippery tires.
</P>
<P>
   It would be like  &UR; Mark McGwire or  &UR; Sammy Sosa whaling away at a
 &UR; Randy
 &UR; Johnson fastball with an extra-long summer sausage.
</P>
<P>
   This simple fact prompted drag racer  &UR; Tom Vosnick to invent a
chemical solution 20 years ago that, when applied to fresh rubber,
made tires more sticky than they were already.
</P>
<P>
   Vosnick called it ``Formula V Traction Treatment,'' and he still
sells it today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tire softeners have been in the news lately, but I call my
product a tire freshener,'' said Vosnick, whose Advanced Automotive
Inc. is based in McKeesport, Pa. ``My product enhances the rubber
and makes it fresher and stickier. It took me four years to develop
it, but it's amazing what it can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What it can do is help give drivers an edge on the track, which
is what NASCAR Winston Cup car owner  &UR; Jack Roush claimed may have
been what helped rival driver  &UR; Jeff Gordon fend off the field over
the final 50 laps of a recent race when he took on only two tires
during a final pit stop when almost everyone else slapped on four.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing theory is that tire softeners or fresheners
lose their advantage after a few laps, which is why former racer
 &UR; Dean Borchert of Chandler used such products only during
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put it on sometimes when I was qualifying'' for a NASCAR
Southwest Tour race, Borchert said. ``When you first come out on
the racetrack on cold tires, it takes several laps to bring them up
to temperature. By using this stuff, it bridged that gap. It gives
you a good jump on the competition because it's giving you the
adhesion immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gordon's tires were impounded by NASCAR officials and
sent to an unknown chemical laboratory, where tests results showed
no illegal substances or wrongdoing, Borchert said it doesn't prove
anything.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are ``useless unless you know what you're looking
for,'' Borchert said. ``It's a hard thing to detect.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosnick doesn't claim his product is undetectable when placed
under a microscope. But he knows of several lab tests performed on
tires laced with his product that were returned negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sense there's something there, but they can't prove it,''
Vosnick said. ``I do know that practically every (short-track)
record in North Carolina was set with my product.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosnick's product sells for $24.95 a gallon, and when applied
correctly, there is enough to treat about eight tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally recommend putting on three to four coats a day for
three days in a row, then letting them sit for two to four days,''
Vosnick said. ``Most tire softeners will (lose their effectiveness)
within 10 laps or so, but I know some (Winston Cup) teams tested my
product at Martinsville (Speedway in North Carolina) and went 120
laps.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the controversy, NASCAR recently changed its
policy of releasing race-day tires on the morning of a race. Now
teams receive the tires about an hour before the green flag. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Crew chief  &UR; Larry McReynolds will remain at Richard Childress
Racing for at least one more season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Carl Trimmer of Tucson finished fourth in the NASCAR Winston
Racing Series Sunbelt Region, posting eight wins in 19 starts and
an astonishing 18 top-five and 19 top-10 finishes. Other Tucson
drivers to finish among the top 50 were  &UR; Jeff Huebner (15th),  &UR; Paul
Banghart (21st),  &UR; John
 &UR; Sweeney III (33rd) and  &UR; Charles Wares (47th).
</P>
<P>
   Mark Armijo can be reached at 602-444-8323 or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
