r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-19 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR'S NIGHT ANYTHING BUT EASY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As expected, Oscar De La Hoya methodically beat up
Julio Cesar Chavez Friday night, bruising his face, slicing his
left eye, and cutting his lip so badly that the blood flowing out
of Chavez's mouth forced him into a reluctant surrender after the
eighth round.
</P>
<P>
   But what was not expected was what Julio Cesar Chavez did inside
that boxing ring for 24 frantic minutes against De La Hoya before
his injuries put an end to a most gallant performance.
</P>
<P>
   What was not expected was that Chavez, supposedly too old,
supposedly too soft, supposedly in it for the $6 million payday,
would wind up posing a most serious challenge to De La Hoya before
17,125 thrilled spectators at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center.
</P>
<P>
   What was not expected was that 36-year-old Julio Cesar Chavez
would reach back into his legendary past and somehow extricate long
missing skills to give Oscar De La Hoya the most exhaustive and
perilous fight of his dazzling young career.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, Oscar De La Hoya is still the Golden Boy, still the WBC
welterweight champion, still his sport's greatest gate attraction
until Mike Tyson returns.
</P>
<P>
   But on this memorable evening in Las Vegas, in a fight that was
expected to be a breeze for him, De La Hoya found himself in a
fearsome debate from the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   This time he wasn't exchanging punches with a Patrick
Charpentier, or a Macho Camacho, or a Wilfredo Rivera or any of the
other bums that his promoter, Bob Arum, has been lining up for him
in the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   This time he actually found himself in a legitimate fight
against a motivated opponent determined to prove that he still had
some magic left in his vast repertoire of tricks and punches.
</P>
<P>
   And Julio Cesar Chavez unleashed all of them against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   He charged De La Hoya relentlessly throughout the match, and hit
him with savage body shots, including a low blow in the third round
that drew a stern warning from the referee, Dick Steele, and a
vehement protest from De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   He fired one right hand after another at De La Hoya, and had the
audience in a constant uproar with his valiant resolve.
</P>
<P>
   He turned the eighth round into the most memorable seen in this
building since that epic 10th round of the first Evander
Holyfield-Riddick Bowe fight, standing there with his younger,
bigger, stronger but not more courageous rival and attempting to
answer De La Hoya's wicked combinations with those of his own.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were standing and cheering wildly because Julio Cesar
Chavez was performing like the fighter who had once been such a
dominant figure in his mean occupation.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a reflection of Oscar De La Hoya's emerging greatness
that he still was able to handle everything that Chavez threw at
him and Chavez threw 346 punches at him and connected on 162 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya still was able to catch Chavez with an assortment of
jabs, uppercuts, left hooks and straight right hands that, at the
finish, left Chavez a battered heap unable to answer the call for
the ninth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got what I wanted ... I made Chavez quit,'' said De La Hoya,
and Chavez indeed did quit after that torrid eighth round in which
the two fellows threw a remarkable 173 punches at each other.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Julio Cesar Chavez quit with honor.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was no reason for him to continue, inasmuch as
De La Hoya's stinging punches had ripped open those cuts on his
swollen face and inasmuch as he faced only certain doom in the
remaining rounds.
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt in the closing moments that Oscar De La Hoya
was getting stronger, and Julio Cesar Chavez was getting weaker.
</P>
<P>
   There was no need for Chavez to be humiliated on a night in
which he conducted himself with such fistic dignity.
</P>
<P>
   I had him winning only one round in the fight I thought the
opening round was even and had De La Hoya ahead by a 79-73 count
when Chavez called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my corner that stopped it,'' said Chavez afterward.
``De La Hoya beat me this time. But he's not a knockout puncher.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya might not be a knockout puncher against Chavez,
but I doubt if anyone in the welterweight division would be able to
knock out the granite-jawed Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it took Chavez to bring out the best in De La Hoya,
and the 25-year-old 1992 Olympic gold medal winner from East L.A.
certainly rose to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he rose too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he was too hyper, too energetic for his own good
against Chavez in the early rounds, choosing to brawl with him
instead of moving and bobbing and taking advantage of his far
superior jabs and quickness.
</P>
<P>
   But once he settled down, De La Hoya took total command, even
though Chavez never stopped coming forward and never stopped
throwing punches.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya would throw more he wound up throwing 517
punches and connecting on 254 and would wind up proving that he
reacts quite nobly in adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought just the opposite of how I should have fought at
least at the beginning,'' said De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   He did, but it made no difference.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya is a terrific fighter who probably will beat
Ike Quartey when they meet in November, and will probably beat all
the other heralded welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   It took a terrific fighter to beat an inspired Julio Cesar
Chavez Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
