<HEADER>
A4040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     09-19 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' HOPES OFFICIALLY END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Dodgers could have gone quietly, the way
they had all season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the night they were eliminated from the National League
wild-card race, the Dodgers finally decided to play it tough
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Barry Bonds homered to open the eighth inning
off Scott Radinsky that the Dodgers' season mathematically ended
with a 4-3 loss to the San Francisco Giants in front of 31,452 at
3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing that the wild-card race is over for
us,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``But I will never fault the
effort of this team. Barry Bonds has beaten a few teams like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bonds, honored before the game as baseball's first player to
reach 400 home runs and 400 stolen bases, it was his 35th homer of
the year and 409th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, it was the same sad refrain. They took the
lead, lost an important player _ in this case, starter Dave Mlicki
to injury _ then watched the game slip away.
</P>
<P>
   This one had none of the classic overtures of this storied
rivalry, no fights in the stands, no pennant races to decide. But
in a season of unfamiliar faces, the Dodgers were hoping to see
more of Mlicki, who left the game in the sixth with lower back
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki first experienced discomfort in his lower back during his
previous start in San Diego, an 8-7 loss last Saturday. He tweaked
it batting in the top of the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not serious, but I just couldn't go on,'' Mlicki said.
``I first felt it in the third. I have one more start and I'm going
to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Mlicki left that the Giants tied the game at 3-3
with a seventh-inning pinch single by Marvin Bernard off Radinsky
(6-6) that scored Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   With Bonds' homer, the Giants now are four games behind the
wild-card leading Chicago Cubs and three back of the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave the victory to Julian Tavares (5-3), who pitched a
scoreless eighth. Robb Nen pitched a scoreless for his 38th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was appropriate that Barry has such a big night on his
night,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``He started some
rallies, he completed some rallies, and that big home run against a
tough lefty was primo.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered to Mlicki, who hopes to make his next
start Thursday against the Milwaukee Brewers. Mlicki is already
under contract ($2.25 million) for 1999, but already is best known
as the pitcher stolen in the Hideo Nomo deal, Fred Claire's last
trade as general manager.
</P>
<P>
   After Claire was fired, interim GM Tom Lasorda sent Greg
McMichael back to the Mets for left-hander Brian Bohanon. Mlicki
and Bohanon have re-established careers with the Dodgers that were
floundering in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a great addition for this team,'' Hoffman said. ``It
would have been great to see him continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki first strained is back swinging the bat in the sixth
inning when he flied to the right-field warning track. He struck
out Ellis Burks to open the Giants sixth, but then gave up a double
to Bonds off the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi made it a close play when his strong throw just
missed getting Bonds and punched the air in disgust. So did Hoffman
when Jeff Kent followed with his second RBI double to cut the lead
to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki clutched his lower back as pitching coach Charlie Hough
came to the mound. The Dodgers turned to rookie left-hander Jeff
Kubenka, who won his first major-league game Sept. 8 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants pinch hit Joe Carter for J.T. Snow and Carter flied
to medium center. Roger Cedeno made the catch and Kent made an
ill-advised attempt to take third. Cedeno threw him out easily to
end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were back at in the seventh when Kubenka walked Hayes
to open the inning. Hayes was sacrificed to second and went to
third on Rich Aurelia's ground single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Kubenka came back to strike out pinch hitter Chris Jones before
giving way to the veteran Radinsky, who gave up the game tying
single to pinch hitter Bernard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
