<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 03:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     09-19 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL TWO BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Angels manager Terry Collins said before Friday
night's game with Seattle that the last thing he would tell his
team was ``We have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bull,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But down by one game in the AL West with with 10 play and a
Texas win already posted on the scoreboard, Collins didn't have to
tell his team it (begin ital)had(end ital) to win.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' managing in a 5-3, 12-inning loss before 39,992 at
Edison Field spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Collins yanked his starter (Ken Hill) after 32/3 innings when
Alex Rodriguez came to bat with two on and two out. He took out
Jason Dickson, who had retired all 11 batters he had faced, when
Ken Griffey Jr. came to the plate in the eighth. And in the most
telling move of the evening, he brought closer Troy Percival in to
face Edgar Martinez with two outs in the eighth inning of a 3-3
game.
</P>
<P>
   Collins pinch-ran for his best hitter (Tim Salmon) in the ninth,
brought in Rich DeLucia to face Rodriguez after Jarrod Washburn had
retired the first two hitters in the 10th. After the Angels fell
behind in the 12th, he even allowed crippled Darin Erstad to
pinch-hit.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' bullpen responded to its challenge by retiring 22
straight hitters between the fourth and 12th innings, but once
Seattle broke the spell, the Mariners drove across two runs to drop
the Angels two games behind the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter David Segui doubled in the go-ahead run off
Shigetoshi Hasegawa and Rodriguez singled in an insurance run off
the Angels reliever. DeLucia, who opened the inning by walking
Raoul Ibanez, was the loser. Mike Timlin pitched two scoreless
innings for the win.
</P>
<P>
   But the bullpen could hardly be blamed for another heartbreaking
Angels loss. Five pitchers combined for seven one-two-three
innings, but the Anaheim offense was almost as futile against the
notoriously suspect Seattle bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim managed only five hits after the fourth inning. It did
put runners in scoring position in both the 10th and 11th, but
neither Orlando Palmeiro nor Garret Anderson could get them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't score. There is nothing more to say,'' said
Angels manager Terry Collins. ``The bullpen did a tremendous job.
We have got to remain optimistic and not worry about what the
Rangers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play with the same desire and heart and it's not good
enough, it's not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival, who has been known to struggle in non-save situations,
didn't waver on Friday, striking out three of the four batters he
faced. After retiring the 16th consecutive Seattle batter in the
ninth inning, Percival left the field waving his arms, imploring
the home crowd for more support.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did in Texas on Thursday, the Angels got off to a
fast start.
</P>
<P>
   After Palmeiro flied out to lead off the bottom of the first
inning, Anaheim put together four consecutive hits, good for two
runs. Jim Edmonds drove in Randy Velarde with a double into the
right-field corner and Gregg Jefferies' single scored Edmonds. The
inning might have been bigger, but Seattle starter Ken Cloude got
Anderson to pop up and Matt Walbeck to strike out with runners on
first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Once again an Angels lead didn't last long. Seattle tied the
game 2-2 in the top of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who had retired the side in order in the first, gave up a
double to Martinez and a single to Ibanez to open the inning. Hill
nearly got out of the jam by striking out the next two hitters but
was touched up for a two-run double by Ryan Radmanovich. The
Seattle right fielder came into the game hitting .167 with five
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle took a 3-2 lead in the third on another two-out hit off
Hill. Martinez picked up his 98th RBI of the season when he singled
in David Bell, who had doubled with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude couldn't stand prosperity either as he grooved a 1-1
fastball to Edmonds leading off the Angels' third. The Anaheim
center fielder, who hit .360 on the road trip, deposited the
mistake into the right-field bleachers for his 24th home run of the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
