<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4045 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BOEHNER-CLINTO     09-19 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BOEHNER-CLINTON-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      BOEHNER: CLINTON SHOULD CONSIDER RESIGNING
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- An ideological and political opponent of
the Clinton administration since its first days, Congressman John
Boehner said he is disturbed by the allegations surrounding the
president and believes the public would be best served if Clinton
left office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the West Chester Republican will not publicly call for
Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer this drags out, the worse it is for the country,''
Boehner said. ``I am deeply troubled by the seriousness of the
charges against the president. ... The president should consider
doing the honorable thing at this point, which is to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike other members of the House of Representatives,
Boehner will not request Clinton step down. Instead, he will allow
the president to make that political calculation for himself while
Congress moves forward with impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should consider resigning for the good of the
county. It would certainly make it easier for Congress to move
forward with what we were elected to do if we didn't have to deal
with this. But I am not calling for it,'' Boehner insisted.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the House Republican leadership, Boehner predicted
the House will vote in early October to authorize the House
Judiciary Committee to begin an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   If the House Judiciary Committee determines the charges brought
against the president merit impeachment, the entire House would
then vote before a trial is conducted in the Senate. Sixty-seven of
the 100 Senators would have to vote for impeachment before
President Clinton is removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee members would begin with, but would not be
limited to, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report against the
president. The 445-page document cites 11 charges as grounds for
impeachment. Starr's report was accompanied to the Capitol by
thousands of pages of supporting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Clinton fall under three categories: perjury
before a grand jury, obstruction of justice, and abuse of the power
of the office of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report to Congress is a prosecutor's case, and Clinton's
lawyers have not yet had a legal forum to refute it.
</P>
<P>
   The president's attorneys claim he has not broken any laws. They
admit that while Clinton's behavior with former intern Monica
Lewinsky was inappropriate and unethical, he has not committed any
misdeeds worthy of forcing his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is the special prosecutor has sent a report to
Congress that makes a credible case for impeachment. I am deeply
troubled by the seriousness of the allegations and the detail in
the description of the charges,'' Boehner said. ``All of these
charges, if proven, are grounds for impeachment. ... We are talking
about the rule of law here, and every American is subject to the
law -- even the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of Congress are not being as cautious in their
criticism of the president. More than 50 congressmen -- including
Ohio Republicans David L. Hobson and John R. Kasich -- have already
called for Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner said he does not have a problem with their pleas because
he sees a difference between urging the president to step down and
saying the president should be impeached. The latter would imply a
congressman had prejudged the president's guilt before reviewing
the relevant evidence.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Republican leadership is urging members to be
``judicious and statesmanlike'' in their comments.
</P>
<P>
   While the headlines coming out of Washington are dominated by
Clinton's troubles and talk of impeachment hearings, Boehner said
Republicans have not lost track of their legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to show the country we are still doing their
work,'' he said, pointing out that most congressmen are working on
legislation even while the country is caught up in impeachment
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a unique responsibility to show the American people
that we can still do our jobs. It is very important, given all the
confusion, that we be businesslike,'' Boehner said.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions to publicly release Starr's report and to air the
president's videotaped testimony have drawn serious Democratic
opposition and created their own controversies. But Boehner said
both were good choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to release a report to 435 members of the
House and their 5,000 staffers, then the public and the media are
going to have it an hour later,'' he rationalized. ``It was going
to get out there anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The American people also have a right to determine for
themselves what is in the report and on the tapes, Boehner added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
