<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID SCANDAL, THE GOVERNMENT'S NOT NECESSARILY PARALYZED 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Given the sheer volume of energy expended in
weighing President Clinton's fate, given Washington's horrified
fascination with every tawdry detail of his behavior, it would be
easy to assume that the machinery of government and policy-making
has ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   But on Capitol Hill last week, the Republican-controlled
Congress began consideration of a tax cut, renewed its efforts to
limit some late-term abortions, started wrapping up the spending
bills needed to keep the federal government operating and pushed
ahead with an overhaul of the bankruptcy system.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled though he may be, Clinton set in motion an international
effort to contain the financial crisis that began last year in
Asia, considered a plea from the Pentagon for more money, received
a report from his advisory commission on race and directed that the
government purchase only recycled paper.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly business as usual, and the effect of Clinton's
woes on Washington will only grow with each congressional move
toward impeachment. At risk in particular are efforts to set the
nation's course on big, evolving issues that require strong
presidential leadership, like shoring up Social Security or dealing
decisively with ethnic conflicts and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some administration officials admit that it is all but
impossible to get the attention of the president or top White House
staff, boding ill for any policy initiatives working their way up
the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal government has tremendous momentum, and even in
times of war and political crisis it has a way of grinding
relentlessly on. Moreover, the very threat of drift and paralysis
in this case has provided both parties with tremendous incentive to
keep pushing a substantive agenda _ maybe even to push harder than
they would otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, confronting an electorate impatient with rabidly
partisan politics and uncertain about how Clinton's transgressions
should be punished, are hedging their bets; even as they turn up
the heat on the president, they are taking every opportunity to
tout their social and economic initiatives and their focus on the
people's business.
</P>
<P>
   Eager as well to probe for weakened resolve and cohesion among
Democrats, Republicans have also decided to see what happens if
they press on issues they had earlier given up on, most notably a
tax cut this year.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton said he should not be ``trying to obscure
my own personal acknowledgment and chagrin about what I did
wrong.'' But it does not take a ``Wag the Dog'' scenario for a
president to change the subject, as Clinton well knows, and last
week he was clearly taking the opportunity to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Halting the spread of the Asian financial crisis, he said, ``is
about the most important issue facing the world community.'' The
Republican plan to finance tax cuts by dipping into projected
budget surpluses could endanger the nation's fiscal health and
undermine efforts to shore up the Social Security system, he said,
fairly spoiling for an ideological, pre-election fight that could
help unify his demoralized party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Clinton, the situation creates a paradox. The more he
talks about issues, the greater the sense that he is deliberately
diverting attention from his own problems. Even pressing matters,
like striking back at terrorists or protecting the nation's long
economic expansion, can seem props in his personal drama.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Washington remember going down this route before.
Consumed by Watergate in 1973-1974, the nation floundered in many
ways, not least in addressing the economic turmoil set off by the
Arab oil embargo. Congress nonetheless found time to raise the
minimum wage, limit school busing and establish federal financing
of election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I was astounded at the resiliency both of the
government and of the people,'' said Bill Frenzel, who was a
second-term Republican congressman from Minnesota in 1974 and
served in the House until 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government did not fall down, and actually most decisions
that people could see and feel were made and the government went
right on operating and doing a reasonable job of it,'' he said. ``I
would say it's going to be similar this time. That is, we're at
risk of falling behind in foreign policy, trade and security, but
the things that people see and touch every day will reveal to them
an operating government that's doing just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Washington is a slave to the calendar. The
government's new fiscal year will start Oct. 1 regardless of
Clinton's troubles, and that means Congress and the administration
have to agree on 13 spending bills, many of which are ideological
battlegrounds, in the next few weeks. Presidential vetoes seem
likely, and a partial shutdown of the government is not out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment proceedings aside, Republicans were already on the
defensive over Democratic complaints that this has been a
do-nothing Congress, intent on little more than killing initiatives
like tobacco legislation and an overhaul of health care regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is an open question how much new policy will get a
hearing once the immediate issues are out of the way. Dana Mead,
the chairman of Tenneco Inc., a big manufacturer, was in Washington
last week talking to administration officials and members of
Congress about issues of concern to the Business Roundtable, an
organization of corporate chief executives that he heads.
</P>
<P>
   Mead, who watched Watergate unfold as a domestic-policy adviser
in the Nixon administration, came away wondering whether the White
House and Congress would be able to take on any but the most
pressing issues, especially if the impeachment process moves ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that they must do, things that are
important to their constituents or the national interest or both,''
Mead said. Beyond that, he said, the ``nice-to-do items'' will
languish and a kind of rationing of time and attention will kick
in.
</P>
<P>
   There is already evidence of that phenomenon at work. Democrats
despair that a weakened Clinton has been less effective than he
would have been otherwise in rallying support this fall for an
increase in the minimum wage and action on health care. The White
House spin machine, which made an art of promoting small-bore
policy initiatives, is now consumed with the president's day to day
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Policymakers within the administration and some politicians from
both sides of the aisle in Congress already admit to being
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   After the campaign-finance overhaul bill that he co-sponsored
suffered another procedural defeat earlier this month, Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., was asked if he would continue bringing up the
bill in the hopes of creating more pressure for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as long as the president has got the problems he has,''
McCain said. ``We don't talk about HMOs anymore, we don't talk
about taxes anymore, we don't talk about Social Security anymore.
There's only one thing on everybody's mind and everybody knows
it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
