<HEADER>
A4093 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-AFGHAN-REVIEW-NY     09-19 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-AFGHAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN FINDS A NOT-SO-GREAT SATAN ON ITS DOORSTEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `i' code) 
(bl) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who's afraid of Afghanistan? Iran, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Republic has positioned as many as 70,000
Revolutionary Guards and volunteers on its border with Afghanistan.
And perhaps 200,000 regular soldiers are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Iran fears an air and ground assault like the one
Saddam Hussein launched from Iraq 18 years ago this week. That
action triggered an eight-year war that by some estimates left
between 600,000 and 1 million people dead and cost both sides
hundreds of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan's Taliban have only about 40,000 men under arms, so
the primary threat to Iran is not military. It is instead a threat
that is deeply political, and quite humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since its revolution nearly two decades ago, Iran has
proclaimed itself the model for the world's Muslims. One of the
most controversial articles of its constitution plainly states that
the Islamic Republic shall make ``every effort to realize the
political, economic and cultural unity of the world of Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the Taliban. Instead of showing Iran a little respect,
the four-year-old Sunni Muslim movement, which follows a rigid,
repressive version of Islamic law and controls most of Afghanistan,
has nothing but contempt for its neighbor to the west.
</P>
<P>
   In Taliban writings, members of the Shiite branch of Islam, to
which most Iranians belong, are ``hypocrites pretending to be
Muslims.'' And Iran is branded the ``mother of all hypocrites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they have the purest Islamic regime in the world,''
said Barnett Rubin, an Afghan scholar at the Council on Foreign
Relations. ``Now they are trying to develop a strong central
government around the principle of Islamic law _ and win
recognition as the government of Afghanistan.''
</P>
<P>
   For Iran, the Taliban are just a bunch of backward peasants with
Pakistani and Saudi support who have given Muslims a bad name.
Disregarding the international shock that greeted Iran's own
repression of its people in the name of Islam, the Iranians now are
criticizing the Taliban for going too far.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, for example, women have to cover their heads and
bodies, but can drive cars, vote, hold jobs and seats in
Parliament; in Afghanistan women cannot work or go to school and
must even cover their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, what is happening in Afghanistan today is a
disgrace to Islam,'' Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   So Iran has opposed the Taliban ever since its fighters began
seizing chunks of territory. In loose collaboration with Russia,
Iran now supplies other factions with weapons, money and logistical
support in an effort to prevent a consolidation of power by the
Taliban, who are not recognized as Afghanistan's government by most
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for sending troops to the border was the Taliban's
seizure of a group of Iranian diplomats several weeks ago. Most of
the diplomats have been killed, and last week their bodies were
sent home, where they were praised and mourned.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other reasons as well. Iran's leaders claim their
national security is threatened by the instability of Taliban rule.
Iran still shelters 1.5 million Afghan refugees from a variety of
factions who fought the Soviet army in the 1980s _ and Iran fears
that some among them could be criminals or, eventually,
anti-Iranian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Iran also fears that the Taliban will launch a campaign of
ethnic cleansing against the Shiite population of Afghanistan, a
development that could drive even more refugees over the border if
it is not sealed. In addition, Iran is used by the Afghans as a
market and a transit route for much of their opium crop, which the
massive troop presence has at least temporarily disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, continuation of the civil war in Afghanistan prevents
Western oil companies from building pipelines to transport Caspian
Sea oil and gas across Afghan territory. Iranians still hope that
if they wait long enough, the United States will change its policy
and allow a pipeline to run through Iran's territory.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Iran has been trying to convince the
rest of the world _ with little success _ to mount a vigorous
mediation effort to stop the Taliban. Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami is planning to use a speech to the United Nations General
Assembly on Monday _ during his first trip there, and his first to
the United States _ to call for international action in resolving
the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to take entirely seriously Iran's charges that
the Taliban's seizure of Iranian diplomats was an egregious
violation of international law, considering that Iran held more
than four dozen U.S. diplomats hostage for 14 months in 1979-81 and
still has a bounty of millions of dollars on the books for anyone
who assassinates novelist Salman Rushdie for his ``heretical''
writings about Islam.
</P>
<P>
   But the massing of hundreds of thousands of troops on a border
has a way of focusing attention on an issue, and U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan has called for a high-level meeting on
Afghanistan this week.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, meanwhile, the Afghan crisis has prompted an
extraordinary public debate among the top leaders about whether to
go to war. Khatami has said he hopes Iran ``will not have to resort
to non-diplomatic methods, '' and former President Ali Akbar
Hashemi Rafsanjani suggested in a recent sermon that the United
States was behind a plot to weaken Iran by pushing it into war and
that Iran had to resolve the crisis in a prudent and calculated
way.
</P>
<P>
   Where the country's supreme religious leader stands is more
uncertain. Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who is also commander in chief
of the armed forces, has now backed away from a previous
declaration that Iran would not get involved militarily in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning remark that seemed to leave the door open for
groups that might welcome a war fever _ the hard-line Revolutionary
Guards, for example _ he said last week that he was ``waiting
impatiently for our statesmen'' to decide whether to declare war or
not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
