<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-OIL (Eket, Nigeria) _ Denny Sansom of Mobil Oil has the
ocean behind him, seven million restive Nigerians of the Niger
River Delta in front of him, huge reserves of oil beneath him and
hundreds of thousands of angry complaints against his corporation
threatening to sink him. The trouble began on Jan. 12, he recalled,
when a 24-inch underwater pipeline from Mobil's Idaho production
platform three and a half miles offshore had snapped, creating a
huge oil spill and releasing the pent up anger of people living in
poverty in an oil-rich nation. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Two weeks before the Oct. 4
election, in which President Fernando Henrique Cardoso is to seek
another term in office, the financial tornado that has devastated
parts of Asia and Russia has begun spinning toward Brazil. By Diana
Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECONOMICS (Tokyo) _ They were the world's richest and
shrewdest investors, and they rode a wave of globalization to buy
bonds in a promising developing country. When the country
defaulted, they were livid. It all sounds a bit familiar, but the
year was 1842 and the developing country was the United States.
Globalization, in other words, may not be quite as fresh as it
sometimes seems. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ For the first time in a career that
capitalized on conflicts, President Boris Yeltsin last week backed
away from a certain showdown with the parliamentary opposition over
the nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister. In
Russia's play-for-keeps politics, a compromise _ in this case, the
nomination of Primakov _ carries with it the faint aroma of defeat.
By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Islamabad, Pakistan) _ Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif leaves for the United States on Saturday and could not have
picked a better time for a getaway, with people here feeling he has
just tried to eliminate democracy from the constitution. Whatever
lies ahead for him this week _ and his schedule includes meetings
with President Clinton and Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee of
India as well as a speech before the United Nations _ the days
should seem tranquil compared with those he just left behind. By
Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-ELECT (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Sweden this weekend is
staging its quadrennial political fete, a national election, and
the exercise is uneventful and unimpassioned, indeed, barely
detectable. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Panama City) _ As minister of housing for the last
four years, Francisco Sanchez Cardenas was supposed to improve
other people's living conditions, not his own. But with the United
States turning hundreds of homes of departing military officers
over to Panama as stipulated by treaty, he and other leaders of the
governing party have got the best residences for themselves. A
result has been popular outrage and a political scandal that
threatens to cripple the governing Democratic Revolutionary Party
in elections scheduled for next spring. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ASSESS (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Wars, elections, coups and
riots come and go in Cambodia, but the unhappy entanglement of the
Prince and the former Communist, it seems, is never-ending. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RANGE-CATTLE-WAR (Ervay, Wyo.) _ In this modern range war,
radical environmentalists seek to force grazing cattle off public
land by cutting fences and otherwise carrying out economic sabotage
against ranching operations. With beef prices low, many Western
ranchers already have their financial backs to the wall. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-POLITICS _ Across the country this election season,
scores of candidates for Senate and House seats are focusing on
schools, vowing that if sent to Washington, they will get the
federal government involved in cutting the nation's class sizes,
repairing school buildings and making them safer for learning. But
while education has long been one of the voters' top five or six
concerns, along with crime, drugs, the economy and foreign threats,
the issue is frequently cited by pollsters this year as the voters'
primary focus. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGWAR-OVERHAUL (Washington) _ U.S. border inspectors searched
slightly more than a million commercial trucks and railway cars
entering the United States from Mexico last year. They found
cocaine stashed in cargo compartments on only six occasions, said
Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the White House director of drug control
policy. He cites the dispiriting statistic in pressing for an
overhaul of the strategy for stanching the flow of illegal drugs
into the United States. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   N.J.-CASINO-GAMBLE (Anadarko, Okla.) _ Three years ago, the
mayor and business leaders of Wildwood, a struggling resort on the
Jersey Shore, were certain that the path to prosperity ran through
this parched corner of western Oklahoma. The idea seemed inspired:
Take a bit of city land _ a two-acre parking lot, actually _ and
give it back to Oklahoma's Delaware Indians, whose ancestors were
pushed out of New Jersey in the 1830's. The Indians would open a
casino, and Wildwood would finally tap into the river of dollars
flowing to the mighty resort casinos of Atlantic City, 30 miles up
the shore. It has not worked out that way. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   LASKER-AWARDS _ Six scientists who made discoveries dating to
1960 that identified the genetic basis of cancer and improved the
diagnosis and treatment of certain types of the disease will
receive this year's Albert Lasker awards. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-AIDS-DEBATE (Bangor, Maine) _ In Maine, a judge has sided
with an HIV-positive mother who refuses to treat her HIV-positive
son with accepted treatments. A look at the issue.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE (Washington) _ On Monday, when the videotape
of President Clinton's testimony is released by Congress, the
public will see a more complex president than the one in Kenneth
Starr's 445-page report, Clinton's allies and friends have argued.
While Starr's report drew on many sources, particularly on Monica
Lewinsky's testimony, to painstakingly chronicle what Clinton did,
it did not describe in detail the president's justifications for
his actions. By James Bennet and Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ On Aug. 3, in the White House Map
Room, President Clinton rolled up his shirt sleeve in the presence
of an FBI agent and a prosecutor from the office of the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. The White House physician, Dr.
E. Connie Mariano, drew a vial of the president's blood. Clinton
considered it the ultimate indignity in a year of public
humiliations, a friend said. By John M. Broder and Don Van Natta
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHRISTIANS (Washington) _ This should be a time of
triumph for the conservative, overwhelmingly pro-Republican members
of the Christian Coalition. The Democratic, baby-boomer president
they have long considered a moral disgrace now faces talk of his
impeachment. And yet, in the hallways and during coffee breaks at
the three-day Christian Coalition convention here, many delegates
said they were despondent about opinion polls showing that most
Americans do not share the conviction that President Clinton should
resign or be impeached. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Washington) _ As the debate intensifies over
President Clinton's political future, a new magazine will be
introduced this week that is devoted to the post-Clinton era in
American politics _ and, apparently, to the election of Vice
President Al Gore in 2000. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET (Undated) _ Congress' decision last week to
release the Starr Report over the Internet was seen as a defining
moment for the global computer network, a test of both its
technical infrastructure and its ability to play a critical role in
the political process. In many ways, the ad hoc experiment in
electronic democracy was a big success. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ It was inevitable, of course, that
lawyers would destroy civilization. Shakespeare warned us to kill
them all. We didn't. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ A few months ago a guy said to me, ``If the
economy is doing so great, how come I'm broke?'' A new study out of
Washington shows that there are an awful lot of Americans who might
ask the same question. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK TIMES PARTNERS: &LR;
