<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROUCHO-MARXISM-REVIE     09-19 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUCHO-MARXISM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUCHO MARXISM: THE NON-COMMUNIST PARTY OF THE FIRST PART WAS AN
UPSTART 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDITORS: Text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There comes now news that the FBI kept a file on the late
Groucho Marx while in dogged pursuit of Communists during the Cold
War. This was disclosed in The Nation last week by Jon Wiener, a
University of California professor who obtained 186 pages of the
file under the Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Wiener says much of the FBI scrutiny came in 1953 at a time when
Marx's band leader, Jerry Fielding, was being pressured to name
Groucho as a communist in his testimony to the House Un-American
Activities Committee. Fielding did not, and was later dismissed by
Marx under pressure from his TV sponsors, a move Groucho later said
he regretted.
</P>
<P>
   The newly disclosed material does not mention Fielding. But
while repeatedly misspelling either Groucho's first or last name,
it provides details of the comedian's apparently modest involvement
in left-wing causes in Hollywood in the 1930s and '40s. And it
includes letters from angry citizens to FBI Director J. Edgar
Hoover, complaining about jokes that Groucho cracked on his TV show
``You Bet Your Life,'' which aired in the 1950s and early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, here is compelling evidence that Marx _ Groucho, never mind
Karl _ was a subversive.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he was, and proud of it. And the FBI apparently missed
some of the strongest evidence: Groucho's own writing. Excerpts
follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   From the Actual FBI File:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)A 1953 internal F.B.I. memorandum to Hoover
discussed Groucho's possible links to the Communist Party:(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Subject is a radio and TV comedian currently starring in TV show
``You Bet Your Life'' sponsored by DeSoto-Plymouth Dealers over
NBC. Rank and file member of Communist Party (CP), San Diego
County, recently remarked to confidential informant that GRAUCHO
(sic) MARX contributes heavily to CP; however, original source gave
no basis for this allegation. Los Angeles informants familiar with
CP activity in Hollywood motion picture and radio industry
throughout 1940's state MARX was never affiliated with CP and never
a contributor as far as informants are aware.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical Corroborating Evidence:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Nevertheless, Groucho's 1963 book ``Memoirs
of a Mangy Lover'' included a chapter conspicuously titled
``Marxist Philosophy, According to Groucho.'' Among his social
dictates: ``The nation needs a good ham sandwich.'' He doesn't stop
there: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Another national need is laundries that will send you a sheet of
pins with every shirt instead of making you pick the pins, one at a
time, out of the collar or (if you don't spot them in time) your
neck. My own laundryman and I have an understanding. Every time he
sticks me with a pin I stick him with a bad check. . . .
</P>
<P>
   We need, too, a vacuum cleaner that won't scare the daylights
out of you by whining like a B-707 jet when you try to snatch a
brief four-hour afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   From the Actual FBI File:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The same 17-page memorandum to Hoover quotes
positive remarks made about Groucho by a columnist for the
Communist Party newspaper, The Daily Worker:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   GRAUCHO MARX is of working class origin. His father was an East
Side tailor, and his mother sewed in sweatshops. . . . Today he is
one of the most diverting entertainers in America. He has never
forgotten his origin _ and his nonsense contains, as many have
felt, considerable satire and passionate thrusts at contemporary
society.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical Corroborating Evidence:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Passionate thrusts indeed. As Groucho notes
in ``Memoirs of a Mangy Lover'':(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I am not prepared to say that all American husbands are untrue
to their wives. Au contraire, I think most husbands are faithful in
their fashion. Horace says . . . ``I have been faithful to thee,
Cuynara, in my fashion.'' This is a pretty qualified statement, and
Horace should be ashamed of himself.
</P>
<P>
   From the Actual FBI File:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The memo to Hoover notes that Groucho
opposed the authoritarian, anti-communist regime of Gen. Francisco
Franco in Spain:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The People's World, Communist periodical for the West Coast, in
its issue of April 25, 1945, page 2, column 4, carried a news item
from San Francisco, California, under the caption ``Anti-Franco
Forces Open Office in SF.'' GRAUCHO MARX was indicated in the
article as active in a new committee called Friends of the Spanish
Republic, which had been formed to insure that no recognition
should be accorded to the Franco government at the United Nations
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical Corroborating Evidence:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Groucho signaled his scorn of authoritarian
Latin governments in his 1959 memoir ``Groucho and Me,'' recounting
a paid junket to Mexico:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The first day in Mexico City, we were all herded into a large
assembly room where a representative of the government was
explaining in endless detail where and what our activities were to
be for the entire week. . . .
</P>
<P>
   At one point he said, ``I am deeply honored to inform you that
at 4 o'clock tomorrow afternoon you are all invited to meet the
President at the palace.'' I raised my hand. The translator noticed
me and said, ``Yes, what is it, Mr. Marx?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``What assurance have I got that he'll still be
President by 4 o'clock tomorrow afternoon?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the Actual FBI File:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) A television viewer wrote to Hoover on June
17, 1960: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that the TV entertainer Groucho Marks (sic) be
investigated as being a Communist. Last night on his program both
my husband and I understood him to pronounce ``The United States''
as ``The United Snakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Groucho and Me,'' he speaks quite affectionately
of Charlie Chaplin, who is a well-known Communist. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Please, Hoover, investigate Groucho Marks.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical Corroborating Evidence:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In ``Groucho and Me,'' Groucho did indeed
write of being buddies with Chaplin in the early days. But this
involved visiting a house of ill repute, which may not qualify as
comradeship in the strict communist sense: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   He was a strange little man _ this Charlie Chaplin. The first
time I met him he was wearing what had formerly been a white collar
and a black bow tie. I can't quite explain his appearance but he
looked a little like a pale priest who had been excommunicated but
was reluctant to relinquish his vestments.
</P>
<P>
   We became real chummy in the ensuing weeks. He was terribly shy,
and I particularly remember a night when we all went to a sporting
house in Salt Lake City just for laughs. The madam took a shine to
Charlie, but he would have none of her, nor did he want any of the
younger girls. Instead he spent the entire evening lying on the
floor playing with the madam's English bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   From the Actual F.B.I. File:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Groucho made fun of the FBI, according to a
1960 bureau memo logging a complaint from a ``You Bet Your Life''
viewer: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   (The viewer) called on 2/29/60 to advise that he had been
listening to the captioned program on last Thursday, 2/25/60, on
NBC, Channel 4 and that . . . when this contestant, whose name he
did not recall, stated he had been a bootlegger, Marx asked, ``You
mean you were a bootlegger for the F.B.I.?'' in an apparent effort
to be funny. . . . There was little laughter from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsical Corroborating Evidence:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Groucho had his share of clunkers. In
addition, he was frequently irreverent toward the federal
government, as in ``Memoirs of a Mangy Lover'': (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   I was at an obnoxious little dinner party the other evening,
talking about world affairs, when this fellow said suddenly,
``Let's run Groucho Marx for Vice President.'' Naturally I was
touched. I asked, why I should be singled out for this honor? Why
should my friends want me to be Vice President?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' snarled my sponsor, ``the Vice President generally
keeps his mouth shut. It might be an interesting experience for
you.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   I remember about 40 years ago a Vice President made himself
famous merely by announcing that what this country needed was a
good 5-cent cigar. What this country really needs is a good 5-cent
nickel. And barring that, a good 5 percent income tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
