<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4112 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DEMOCRACY-REVIE     09-19 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S FINE ART: LINGUISTIC SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `a' code) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Although the world has focused its attention on the
one-sided battle between the Chinese Communist government and the
political dissidents who press for radical change, there is also a
large population here of intellectuals, many of them scholars or
former officials, who work openly to nudge the system in a more
democratic direction.
</P>
<P>
   These people, known as liberals, borrow a term from pingpong to
describe their strategy for stretching the bounds of political
debate. They speak of hitting a ``touch-ball'' _ one that just
grazes the edge of the table. A risky hit, yet one that scores.
</P>
<P>
   In this metaphor, the ping-pong table stands for the
ideologically correct thoughts of the moment. Impatient
progressives, as they write and speak, try to incorporate as much
of the day's official jargon and ideas as they believe, or can
stomach, while probing as far as they dare on issues like free
speech, rule of law and political pluralism.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the size of the table is constantly
changing, and such people spend enormous amounts of time monitoring
official talk and watching the experience of colleagues to figure
out just where the limits are at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hit it just right, then you can get away with saying
something new or provocative,'' said a Beijing law professor. ``If
you miss the table, you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lose'' might mean anything from a reprimand at work to forced
retirement, with a de facto ban on publication. Or the writer could
descend into the ranks of the ``dissidents,'' who are harassed and
detained by police.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the liberal scholars and officials are not to
be confused with the beleaguered democracy dissidents, who push
more directly, persistently and actively for radical change. The
liberals hope instead that their more academic discourse will plant
the seeds of a more open system.
</P>
<P>
   Because every camp, from Communist leaders to dissidents, uses
terms like democracy and the rule of law, it can be hard to tell
who really stands for what.
</P>
<P>
   But in China, where ideas drove a revolution and words can bring
jail, people are exquisitely attuned to linguistic cues. What might
seem verbal hairsplitting in America is taken here with utmost
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   In today's parlance, for example, the need for ``political
structural reform'' is voiced by Communist leaders, starting with
the president and Communist Party chief, Jiang Zemin. This seems to
mean things like improving government efficiency, ending corruption
and better enforcing party-dictated laws.
</P>
<P>
   Those with more Western notions of democracy often leave out the
word ``structural,'' and talk of ``political reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's definition of democracy seems, again, to focus on
improving ``oversight'' and ``supervision'' of bureaucrats, to make
sure they honestly carry out Beijing's edicts. (Genuine direct
elections are limited to administrative jobs in villages.)
</P>
<P>
   Thus at the Communist Party Congress last fall, Jiang could
declare, according to the official English translation, ``We should
promote democracy, improve the legal system and build a socialist
country ruled by law,'' even as he reaffirmed the Four Cardinal
Principles that the late Deng Xiaoping issued in 1979: keeping to
the socialist road, upholding the dictatorship of the proletariat,
upholding the leadership of the Communist Party and upholding
Marxism-Leninism and Mao Tse-tung Thought.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's reference to a ``country ruled by law'' in that speech
last fall caused no end of analysis among the cognoscenti, because
of the particular Chinese characters used in the official
transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leaders, and emperors before them, had long used one
term to call for what is often translated as ``rule by law'' or ``a
strengthening of the legal system.'' This term is taken to mean
improving the use of law and institutional channels to carry out
party rule _ an improvement over the highly personal rule of the
past, but hardly Western democracy.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, liberals have used another term _ which sounds
the same in spoken Mandarin but is written with a different
character; this one is often translated as ``rule of law,'' meaning
that the entire nation, including the party, is governed under the
law.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent essay, Li Shenzhi _ a former vice president of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences who was sacked for not
supporting the 1989 crackdown on student demonstrations _ writes
that there is a big difference: Under ``rule of law,'' he says,
``no one is above the law or exempted by it.'' Not even a party
chief.
</P>
<P>
   So heads turned when the official written Chinese version of
Jiang's speech used that second formulation. Was Jiang floating a
serious change in attitude? Or was his speechwriter merely toying
with the country's intellectuals?
</P>
<P>
   Li's essay appears in a recent book, ``Political China: Facing
the Era of Choosing a New Structure'' (China Today Publishing
House), in which Li shows himself to be an aggressive touch-ball
player. At one point, he writes that China ``should quickly adopt
the common concept of the world: `Human rights are civil rights.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The book, which includes articles by scholars and former
officials, exemplifies the touch-ball approach. The clear intent is
to foster discussion of serious change.
</P>
<P>
   Yet facing the title page is an artfully selected quotation from
Deng, whose vaguest utterances, now elevated to the level of
theory, are used by Jiang to legitimize his program. The quote
reads, ``If you only carry out economic system reform and not
political system reform, then economic system reform will not
work.'' It continues, ``Whether all of our reforms ultimately
succeed is dependent on political system reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent homage may signal that the book is not intended to
challenge the system brazenly in the manner of an impudent
dissident like the exiled Wei Jingsheng.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the book ever include words like ``multiparty
politics'' or ``direct election of national leaders.'' Aiming that
far off the table would have guaranteed that the book would be
banned.
</P>
<P>
   The book prudently includes a spectrum of views, including an
essay by a close adviser to President Jiang, Wang Huning. He calls
for ``political structural reform'' in order to build a ``socialist
political system with Chinese characteristics'' _ under the party's
leadership. That, of course, lands well in the middle of the
ping-pong table.
</P>
<P>
   A spray of touch-balls, in contrast, comes from Liu Junning, a
political scientist at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences who
prefers exploring ``liberal democracy'' to ``people's democracy.''
In one essay, ``The Market Economy and Limited government,'' he
writes, ``Individual property rights and a free market economy will
not automatically lead to democracy, but without property rights
and markets, it's absolutely impossible to have democracy.'' He
also writes, ``Guaranteeing property rights not only needs
democracy, it also needs constitutional government and rule of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   But many liberals find it puzzling and frightening that the
authorities recently arrested one of the two journalists who were
the book's editors. Shi Binhai, a senior editor of The China
Economic Times, was detained Sept. 5 by state security agents who
gave his family no reason. Shi's associates say they do not believe
his involvement with the book, which continues to sell in Chinese
bookstores, was the reason. Apparently it was through some other,
undisclosed, activity that Shi missed the edge of the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
