<HEADER>
A4117 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-POLITICS-AR     09-19 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING SCHOOLS BECOMES BATTLE CRY FOR FALL ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ky., Tenn., Calif., Ill., Texas, Md., wash., Ore.,
Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate for governor in South Carolina, Jim
Hodges, has chosen as his logo a drawing of the back of a school
bus and the slogan, ``It's all about our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Republican Gov. George W. Bush is running a television
advertisement that declares, ``No goal is more important than
making sure all Texas schoolchildren are able to read.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, voters ended 30 years of bilingual education by
referendum in June and face another initiative over reduced class
size in November.
</P>
<P>
   And across the country this election season, scores of
candidates for Senate and House seats, like the Democrats Charles
Schumer of New York and Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas, are focusing
on schools, vowing that if sent to Washington, they will get the
federal government involved in cutting the nation's class sizes,
repairing school buildings and making them safer for learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a single motivating force in my public life,''
said Rep. Glenn Poshard, an Illinois Democrat running for governor,
in a comment that is echoed by candidates everywhere, ``it is to
provide a meaningful education to every child in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   While education has long been one of the voters' top five or six
concerns, along with crime, drugs, the economy and foreign threats,
the issue is frequently cited by pollsters this year as the voters'
primary focus, especially in the many states with gubernatorial
elections. Democrats are emphasizing their traditional stake in
education policy while Republicans, whose attention has been
focused on the Clinton scandal, are seeking to make the education
issue their own.
</P>
<P>
   But the impact of all this attention is far from clear,
education advocates say. Is the talk of standards, class size and
safety leading to improved education or merely serving candidates
as ``family values'' campaign themes?
</P>
<P>
   Chester Finn, a senior fellow at the Hudson Institute in
Washington and a leading conservative voice in education, says the
vast majority of new state standards for students, instituted under
political pressure, are too low to be meaningful and the bulk of
campaign talk about education is useless or misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in so many other policy debates, much of the education
campaigning is based on focus groups and political consultant
input,'' Finn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Clinton's and other people's class-size reduction
scheme,'' he said. ``It is costly and problematic. Costly, because
you have to hire more teachers and payroll is already the largest
portion of the budget. Problematic, because there is so little
evidence that, apart from kindergarten and first grade, class-size
reduction produces any better education.''
</P>
<P>
   Finn added: ``American class sizes have been shrinking for 50
years. Many countries that beat the pants off of us in
international comparisons have much larger class sizes than we do.
The biggest immediate effect of reducing class size in most places
will be to draw more unqualified people into teaching and suck good
teachers out of urban into suburban schools. Nonetheless, everyone
is proposing class-size reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the focus on education has produced results.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schwartz, president of Achieve Inc., a bipartisan and
corporate-government partnership to improve schools, says efforts
have paid off in states like Kentucky, Maryland, Washington and
Oregon, where reasonable standards have been established,
businesses are focusing on applicants' school records in hiring,
and accountability procedures have been instituted for schools.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that teacher quality has come under greater scrutiny as
well, with many states raising the bar for teacher certification
and some, like Massachusetts, using budget surpluses to lure better
candidates into the teaching profession with signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that in a significant number of states, the
political conversation about education is qualitatively different
than it was in the past,'' Schwartz said. ``This is not just the
equivalent of family values as a campaign theme. Many states have
not only adopted standards but put in place assessments and systems
of accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Albjerg Graham, a professor and former dean of the
Harvard Graduate School of Education, said: ``The most important
result of this prolonged debate on education has been the
widespread conviction that children of all social classes are now
expected to learn academic material. The idea that educational
achievement is for everybody is revolutionary. That's real
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over education often tracks the conservative-liberal
divide over school governance and standards. Generally,
conservatives favor local control and more rigorous standards,
while liberals tend toward a national approach and, while mindful
of the need for standards, they emphasize inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it hard to believe we are going to achieve national
standards on education because liberals oppose standards and
conservatives oppose national,'' mused Arthur Levine, president of
Teachers College at Columbia University, who has been receiving a
growing number of calls from politicians seeking briefings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, what is striking about the debate is that if there
is not agreement on the means, there is near-universal consensus on
the ends of this education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditionalists have won,'' remarked Larry Cuban, an
education professor at Stanford University. ``New math and
whole-language reading are in retreat. Today there are more
phonics, more multiplication tables, more tests. There is a
consensus between the public and officials that the basic,
traditional model is the one to pursue. Whatever experimentation is
occurring today challenges the boundaries far less than two to
three decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that in their public appearances both Democrats and
Republicans are saying rather similar things about education _
vowing to provide more of it with better equipment, safer
classrooms and better teachers _ with their disagreements focused
on how to get there: whether to confront teachers' unions or
cooperate with them, raise taxes or shift revenues, focus on
traditional public schools or on alternatives, like charter schools
or government vouchers to pay for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the voters to be unsure which path is the more
efficient _ they tend to favor most options that sound like they
would lead to improvements _ suggesting that candidates are
competing over driving home their message that they care.
</P>
<P>
   One reason there seems to be such a consensus on education is
that the economic rationale for schooling has triumphed. As the
economy has shifted from an industrial to a white-collar base,
Americans have become increasingly persuaded that their children's
personal financial success will depend on what kind of education
they receive. This means that campaigning about education does not
displace campaigning about the economy _ it is a proxy for it.
</P>
<P>
   But economics aside, the prominence of education as a political
issue results from a confluence of factors.
</P>
<P>
   First, ever since the explosive 1983 report ``A Nation at Risk''
that attacked the quality of American public schools,
policy-makers, including President George Bush and President
Clinton, have focused on schooling, and the impact of their
sustained attention is being felt. Second, the 1990s, dominated by
the breakup of the Soviet Union, a rising stock market and a
plummeting urban crime rate, shifted the nation's focus away from
traditional front-runner issues, granting education more attention.
Third, the demographically powerful baby-boom generation has
children throughout the school system, so the boomers' attention is
focused on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with the military draft ended, the public school system
is one of the remaining places for large-scale inculcation of
values. The system has had to bear a growing share of societal
goals _ fighting poverty, absorbing immigrants, preparing the
public for a multiracial future and instilling in the young a sense
of moral order and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   On this last point, many experts see voter concern over
education to be largely anxiety over their children's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astute politicians realize that a lot of us are worried about
our kids,'' said Theodore Sizer, an author and advocate of school
reform. ``The moral dimension and the safety dimension overlap.
More and more families are frightened by what they see.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Glenn, a professor of education policy at Boston
University, agrees. ``There is a diffuse, general idea that America
is going to hell on issues of moral character,'' he said. ``Most
parents say they are worried about discipline. What kind of kids
will my kids be in contact with? Are my kids going to come home as
strangers with different values than mine? Conservatives talk about
school choice because they see the current monopoly of content to
be relativistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives also focus on school choice because they think it
will improve schools generally. They say that one of the most
positive results of all the recent attention on education has been
to open up school systems to competition from charter schools and
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, President Reagan tried to free markets from
a lot of impediments like unions and taxation,'' remarked former
Education Secretary Lamar Alexander, who is expected to seek the
Republican presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``His idea was, if we free the market, we can get a good
economy,'' Lamar said. ``That's what we need to do with schools. We
need to free the schools from all those impediments like unions and
outdated practices. Let them flourish. America does best when we
pursue freedom and choice and allow ingenuity to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a Republican president to lead the charge and
give courage to governors and education entrepreneurs,'' he said,
``sometime in the next 5 to 10 years we would see real results with
higher academic achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see the issue differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were serious about our educational problems, we would go
see what other nations are doing,'' said Marc Tucker of the
National Center on Education and the Economy. ``Not one of them is
using vouchers as the secret of its success. They set high
standards and have exams and curriculum to match. There is very
little choice in the curriculum. This is true from Singapore to
Japan to Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is universally applicable,'' he said. ``Yet it doesn't
apply here? That's absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, tests and standards are slowly being installed in
many states. In New York, for example, high school students will
soon have to pass Regents examinations on more and more subjects to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   All experts questioned said the real political test would be how
voters react when, or if, many children fail such exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is for high test scores till their kids get low test
scores,'' Sizer remarked. ``There is a kind of unreality to the
policy debate. Are we really going to shut down schools that don't
perform? I think the rhetoric and self-righteous table pounding
will stop when the reality sets in. The attention will shift to a
more varied approach. If all this attention doesn't lead ultimately
to improved education, we have certainly blown it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
