<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-OIL-ART-1100(     09-19 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-OIL-ART-1100(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIAN POOR MOPPING UP ON MOBIL OIL SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EKET, Nigeria _ Denny Sansom of Mobil Oil has the ocean behind
him, 7 million restive Nigerians of the Niger River Delta in front
of him, huge reserves of oil beneath him and hundreds of thousands
of angry complaints against his corporation threatening to sink
him.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began on Jan. 12, he recalled. Sansom, a Texan who
is Mobil's operations manager, walked into his 6:45 a.m. staff
meeting and was told that despite full production at Mobil's 57
offshore wells, oil was not reaching shore. ``Shut it down!'' he
hollered. ``Shut everything!''
</P>
<P>
   The order came too late. A 24-inch underwater pipeline from
Mobil's Idaho production platform three-and-a-half miles offshore
had snapped. Flying 26 miles out over the Atlantic in a helicopter
that afternoon, Sansom saw 26 miles of oil. ``The slick was moving
like a giant ship,'' he said. ``That thing about killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Nigerian coast, the spilled oil has now become a
subject of vehement dispute, a catalyst for pent-up claims fed by
poverty and state neglect. In few places on earth do the West's
richest corporations and millions of the world's poorest people rub
shoulders with such intensity or such potentially explosive
consequences as in the Niger Delta, the fifth-largest source of
America's imported fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are very turbulent,'' said Ernest Ukocho, a community
leader in the villages surrounding Mobil's operations at Eket. ``We
are trying to maintain calm, but there has been some rioting. The
fact is, everyone wants a piece of the Mobil cake.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil _ 40,000 barrels of it, or roughly one-sixth of the
giant Exxon Valdez spill in Alaska _ drifted west, thus avoiding
nearby Cameroonian waters to the east and an international fiasco.
The fiercely secretive former regime of Nigerian Gen. Sani Abacha,
who died in June, also helped keep the Mobil spill largely out of
the news.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Niger Delta everyone quickly knew of it. Sansom has
been held hostage, repeatedly rebuked and now spends 70 percent of
his time on ``community issues'' _ essentially trying to stop
resentment from turning to rioting.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria approaches a delicate transition from military rule
to democracy, which is supposed to take place next year, the
delta's long-festering problems pose the threat of widespread
violence. In the wetlands, the world's largest mangrove swamp,
unrest now seems close to boiling over, with sabotage against
pipelines becoming routine and intermittent acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The spill _ dwarfing those caused by sabotage _ made Sansom's
position doubly difficult. Scientific evidence shows that
environmental damage was slight. But for people long subjected to
the stunted development apparently willed on the delta by Nigerian
military governments, that spilled oil was a bonanza beckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand these people,'' Sansom said. ``They're poor. So
they think we're all Howard Hughes. One Saturday morning alone, I
had $4.5 billion in claims _ that's 45 percent of the total oil
revenue of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Since oil was discovered here 42 years ago by Royal Dutch/Shell,
enormous wealth has been taken from the area by Mobil, Chevron,
Shell, Texaco and other Western companies, and by Nigeria's
generals, who have ruled for 28 of the last 32 years. But, as a
result of apparently gross neglect by the military government that
takes the bulk of the country's oil revenue, life for the people
living in the wetlands has scarcely improved.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nigerian writer Ken Saro-Wiwa had the temerity to point
this out, demanding compensation on the grounds that the entire
region, and his Ogoni people, remained poor, Nigeria's generals
hanged him in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The pretext was a flimsy charge of involvement in a murder,
upheld by a kangaroo court of military officers. The real issue was
_ and remains _ where and how the more than $10 billion Nigeria
receives annually from oil is invested.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other Western leaders expressed indignance
at Saro-Wiwa's execution _ although not enough to impose oil
sanctions on Nigeria, where U.S. investment totals $7 billion.
Three years later, the 7 million delta people _ of whom the Ogoni
form a minority of about 500,000 _ still appear mired in a
paralyzing web.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official at Nigerian National Petroleum Co. conceded,
albeit on condition of anonymity, that after years of taking oil
from the delta and plowing the profits into northern Nigeria _ the
base of the ruling generals _ that policy is increasingly fraught
with risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see an escalation,'' the official said.
``We're taking oil from one part of the country and investing it in
the north. I do not think you can go on taking money from a place
without enhancing life there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, Abacha's successor, has indicated
that he wants reform. He made a conciliatory gesture this month in
releasing several Ogoni prisoners who had been held on charges
similar to those against Saro-Wiwa. But the problems are so
deep-rooted that such gestures are unlikely to have immediate
effect.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of state investment _ Nigerian authorities have
built no schools in the Eket region for several years _ Mobil has
effectively become the local government: the object of all claims,
all hope of jobs, money or investment, all aspirations for
electricity, or hospitals or running water _ and all resentments.
</P>
<P>
   To travel the Eket region _ an area of about 100 square miles
that might reasonably be renamed Mobiland _ is to encounter a
fantastic array of complaints leveled at the U.S. company: gutters
not deep enough; roads and clinics promised but not built;
oil-polluted sea waters now allegedly emptied of fish all the way
to Cameroon; zinc roofs rusting because of the flares; even doors
and walls vibrating from earth tremors allegedly caused by Mobil's
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come to me asking for Mobil to build a water supply
system'' Sansom said, ``and I say, why don't you go to the water
board and ask the same question? And they say, because the water
board would shoot us!''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. ``You know, the naira these local governors get from
the military government would not buy you a piece of chewing gum.''
Yet more than 60 percent of the revenue from Mobil's joint venture
goes to the government.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense the oil companies are unfairly criticized: the
government takes over 70 percent of Nigeria's oil revenue and could
clearly have invested more of it in the delta. But Western
companies effectively acquiesced in the region's impoverishment so
long as they could pump oil and get their money out: their push for
``community development'' in recent years, and especially since the
death of Saro-Wiwa, may have come too late.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To Western oil interests, generally synonymous with Western
political interests, stability has been of paramount importance in
Nigeria: the country's oil is ecologically desirable to America
because it is unusually sulfur-free and strategically desirable
because it represents diversification from Middle Eastern sources.
</P>
<P>
   That stability has been preserved at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of interethnic tensions, and memories of Biafra's
secession in 1967, the northern generals who have governed Nigeria
have mainly sought to keep the delta area poor and backward on the
basis that a region with oil and development might be tempted to go
it alone again. The then-Republic of Biafra comprised much of the
oil-producing region; its independence was quashed in a three-year
war that cost 1 million lives.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies, meanwhile, have long taken the view that
their obligations are met by paying taxes and royalties to the
authorities. Oil production, not regional development, has been
their role. Although this approach is now changing, the delta still
bears heavy scars.
</P>
<P>
   Potholed roads, rundown schools and isolated villages without
running water dot an area that produces over 90 percent of
Nigeria's hard-currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Only the widely resented flares of the oil companies that light
the night sky betray the fact that this land is rich. Because the
oil companies are far more visible in the area than the military
government, they are the main focus of ire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were from the delta, I would long ago have joined an
armed struggle,'' said Bola Ige, a prominent Lagos lawyer and
former governor of the southern Oyo state. ``What else can you
reasonably be down there but a guerrilla leader?''
</P>
<P>
   And what else could Mobil's oil spill reasonably provoke, in
such an environment, but dreams of sudden wealth?
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax, Va.-based company, which produces about one-third
of Nigeria's total oil output in a joint venture with the
state-owned Nigerian National Petroleum Co., moved fast as the oil
seeped into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous interests were at stake: Mobil has more than $2.5
billion invested in Nigeria; the Ubit offshore platform, pumping
250,000 barrels a day, is the company's largest single production
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom took over an emergency command center that he manned
almost uninterruptedly for over a month; helicopters and boats were
deployed to apply dispersants; containment booms and oil skimmers
were used; scientists and environmentalists were rushed in from
Lagos University and the United States to test the degree of
pollution; Mobil announced that it would compensate anyone
suffering injury.
</P>
<P>
   With disaster looming, weather and currents smiled on Mobil. For
a long time the bulk of the oil remained offshore, where warm winds
and the light nature of Nigerian crude favored evaporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Mother Nature and Mobil's highly effective and
targeted response,'' said David Page, a U.S. oil spill expert,
``the shoreline was spared what could have been a very serious
environmental event. The amount of oil that got ashore was minimal,
perhaps 1 percent of the spill, or 400 barrels, certainly no more
than 1,000 barrels.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, a chemistry professor at Bowdoin College in Maine who has
visited Nigeria three times since the spill, says hardly any oil
entered the sensitive mangrove creeks that lace the delta.
Certainly none is visible today. ``I'm not an attorney,'' he added,
``but it's fair to say that because so little oil got ashore, I'd
be very surprised if fishermen's livelihoods were cut off.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is emphatically not the view of hundreds of
thousands of poor Nigerians along the coast. Claims have been
pouring in to the U.S. company from Akwa Ibom state, home to Mobil,
from Delta state, from Cross River , from Bajelsa, from Lagos _
``the entire damn coast,'' in the words of Isong I Akpabio, a Mobil
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At Mobil headquarters in Lagos recently, Celia Onitiri, head of
the legal staff, was unavailable for comment. She was at home and
was said to be suffering from stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we wanted to be fair,'' said Paul Caldwell Jr., chairman
of Mobil Producing Nigeria Unlimited, as the company's Nigerian
venture is named. ``But this has turned into a major undertaking
and a big headache. The fact is, the communities look to us to
provide support that they are not getting from the Nigerian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Effiong Ikot, a fisherman and owner of a small business, is
among those who have made claims. He has demanded 490,000 naira of
Mobil _ about $5,700 _ for the loss of fishing nets. He regards
Mobil's offer of about $250 as insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Like other claimants, Ikot brought his bundles of nets to be
inspected by Mobil officials and insurance agents. Once the
inspection was completed, the nets were burned. ``How can I be
happy,'' Ikot said, ``when somebody burns my nets?''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the area, the chorus of indignation at the burning of
nets is overwhelming, driven by a sense that, as one local leader,
Chief Daniel Utong, put it, ``this act added injury to injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Akpakip, a mother of six, said her business had been
ruined. A single shark net, she said, cost at least $600, and ``how
can I live when my nets have been burned and I've yet to receive
anything?''
</P>
<P>
   But Grace Nwawo, a community affairs official for Mobil in Eket,
insisted that there had been no alternative but to burn the nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were usable,'' she asked, ``why were they brought in?
Where could we have stored them? How could we have found uncorrupt
guards to protect them? How would we have prevented them being sold
to the next village?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma of the nets illustrates Mobil's situation. In
strictly rational terms, the decision to burn them seems sound. But
in the world of poverty and vague fears that surrounds Mobil,
Shell, Texaco, Chevron and other oil companies in the delta,
symbols and fantasy tend to hold sway. And what could be a more
overwhelming symbol of a rich company trampling on poor fishermen
than the burning of their nets?
</P>
<P>
   The tranquil village of Itafre, a collection of mud-and-thatch
homes, lies in the midst of the mangrove swamp about 10 miles from
Mobil's Eket base. Like many settlements, it is inaccessible other
than by boat or helicopter. Mobil has built a school here and tried
_ with limited success _ to develop a cashew-nut farm.
</P>
<P>
   But resentment is strong, especially since the spill. Thomas
Ebitu, the village chief, acknowledged that Mobil had built his
house and the school and started the farm. But what about a road?
And why was the village without electricity? And where was the
running water that Mobil should provide?
</P>
<P>
   The assembled villagers nodded. They were asked if the federal
government might provide some of these services. Mobil, it was
pointed out, is an oil company, not a civil engineering company. It
spends over $8 million a year on improving conditions in delta
villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no government here,'' said Mike Maru, a
fisherman. ``Mobil is the only visible entity. They are making a
lot of money here, and we've been left like monkeys out here in the
swamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Maru added that he had lost 350 bundles of nets as a result of
the oil spill and had put in a claim for 300 million naira, or $3.4
million. The figure, in the context of the village, appeared
utterly fantastic. Another fisherman, Monday Smith, said he would
settle for $11,500. Both men said their nets had been burned and
asked how they were expected to live in the absence of
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In another village, Okuro Utip, a resident named James Nyoh
stood up and made a half-hour speech. He listed everything that
Mobil should provide: spill compensation, an education endowment, a
health center, a road network, clean water, jobs. The company, he
concluded, owes the village just under $100 million for the spill
alone.
</P>
<P>
   These claims are a very long way from Mobil's estimates. With
oil prices at a low ebb, the company is cutting costs. Of nine
exploration rigs that were operating in Nigerian waters, eight have
been shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nwawo said the company believed that a little over $100 was
fair compensation for each lost net. Although some payments will be
higher, Mobil believes most validated claims should be settled by
payments not exceeding $600.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the spill of about $600,000 worth of oil may cost the
company about $40 million _ $10 million in cleanup costs and $30
million to settle the mountain of claims. Payments have started but
are being widely disputed, and the process seems likely to continue
for a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom says he is determined to see it through. He is a
practical man, conveying a passionate sense of mission. In 21
months in Eket, he has been struck by the poverty, the lack of
family planning, the absence of state investment, the desperation.
``I want to do more than hold the line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He spends hours with community leaders in an attempt to find
middle ground. He is determined to maintain or increase the money
that Mobil spends annually on community projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planned parenthood is one key,'' he said. ``I had two women in
my office the other day with 28 children. Another key is
diversification.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansom's dreams of a better delta appear to have found an echo.
Despite the flood of claims, chiefs in the surrounding villages
described him as popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny is admired,'' Ikot, the fisherman, said, ``because he
likes to engage in dialogue and he has some good ideas to produce
electricity and bring in investors and use the model that made
Texas rich. Even if he's not on our side, we feel he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The other factor that helps maintain a tenuous peace is clearly
the precedent of the Ogoni, whose region has been hard hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a warning to us,'' said Ukocho, the community leader,
who like most people around Eket is a member of the Ibibio ethnic
group. ``The military almost wiped them out. So now we think twice
about taking the law into our own hands.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
