<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4125 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-4TAKES-     09-19 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND STARR, A MUTUAL ADMONITION SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Aug. 3, in the White House Map Room, President
Clinton rolled up his shirt sleeve in the presence of an agent of
the FBI and a prosecutor from the office of the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. The White House physician, Dr.
Connie Mariano, drew a vial of the president's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton considered it the ultimate indignity in a year of public
humiliations, a friend said. Starr would soon match the president's
DNA with a semen stain on a navy blue dress and would be able to
prove beyond almost all doubt that Clinton had engaged in some type
of sexual activity with Monica Lewinsky. Seven months of the
president's lies were about to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they took the blood from his arm,'' the friend said last
week, ``that's when it really hit home.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment in the Map Room was a culmination of years of
personal animosity and corrosive bitterness between Clinton and
Starr. Associates of both men say that their hatred _ and these
friends say that hatred is not too strong a word _ repeatedly
clouded their judgment and led to excesses on both sides that have
permanently tarnished both reputations.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ms. Lewinsky came to the attention of investigators,
Starr had spent 41 months investigating a variety of matters known
collectively as Whitewater. Although none of those issues were
included in Starr's impeachment referral to Congress, he and his
prosecutors had concluded that the Clintons and their lawyers had
sought to frustrate the Whitewater inquiry with legal challenges
and an aggressive, anti-Starr public relations strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the allegations about Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the
president contributed to Starr's distrust and his suspicions that
the White House had sought to hush her up, as he believed the
Clintons had with previous witnesses in the Whitewater
investigation, according to interviews with associates of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton has acknowledged that anger at Starr colored his
response to the investigation, including his initial denials and
his Aug. 17 speech to the nation acknowledging an improper
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern _ a
speech his aides now say they view as a major blunder.
</P>
<P>
   In an illustration of the reciprocal frustration that keeps
driving the crisis forward, that speech and the grand jury
appearance earlier in the day that sparked Clinton's fury caused
Starr to include far more scathing detail in the report he later
submitted to Congress, according to prosecutors in Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   So intense is Clinton's obsession with Starr that he has gone so
far as to tell several members of his administration that the
prosecutor was partly to blame for his affair with Ms. Lewinsky,
according to an official who heard the remarks. Clinton told these
associates that he was so angry about the intrusiveness of Starr's
inquiries that he sought comfort in a relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the president told an associate recently, he wakes up
every day angry at Starr, not only for cornering him on the
Lewinsky matter but for revealing the excruciating details of what
he did with Ms. Lewinsky that mortified his wife and daughter,
according to several presidential aides.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton blames Starr for damaging his chances to win a place
among the great presidents, according to a friend to whom the
president made this complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's defenders admit that he, too, has been blinded by his
distaste for Clinton and has committed excesses in his desire to
hold the president accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's 445-page report to Congress, packed
with almost pornographic sexual detail and damning commentary on
the president's motives, is the most glaring example of
prosecutorial overkill, some of Starr's associates say.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been others _ the parading of first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton past a phalanx of cameras into the federal
courthouse in Washington in January 1996; the threat, leaked to
reporters, to name Bruce Lindsey, the president's closest
confidant, an unindicted co-conspirator in a trial that ended in
speedy acquittals; the ostentatious display of the 36 boxes of
impeachment evidence on the steps of the Capitol the week before
last; the harsh treatment of the president in his Aug. 17
videotaped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought from day one, as I think today, that this was bad
for the country,'' said one of Starr's defenders who now questions
his tactics. ``Sometimes you have to exercise prosecutorial
discretion.'' Even though this defender of Starr said he believed
the president was guilty of significant misconduct, he said, ``the
cost to the country far outweighs the value of proving it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Starr denied that he or his office was motivated
by animosity toward the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made this personal,'' said Charles Bakaly III.
``We took an oath to uphold the law and we are doing that in a
professional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   While many believe that Clinton demeaned the presidency with the
Lewinsky affair, some argue that Starr's obsession with the
president's sex life has done even more to harm the institution.
Starr argues in his report that he was forced to pile detail upon
salacious detail because of the president's persistent mendacity.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's experience with years of Clinton's evasions, court
challenges and clever legalisms compelled him to include such
detail to make an incontrovertible case of perjury, his allies say.
The same allies also wondered last week whether Starr and his
prosecutors had other motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though Clinton disrespected the dignity of his office by
doing these things, making them public compounds the problem,'' one
associate of Starr said. ``One could argue that Starr has
contributed to it by making all this public as he did, for the
wrong motives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job and his place in history are in jeopardy. Starr's
reputation is in tatters. It was, said one former White House
lawyer, a ``mutual suicide.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The First Shot?
</P>
<P>
   `Your Boy's Getting Rolled'
</P>
<P>
   James Carville claims in his coming book about Starr, ``... And
the Horse He Rode In On,'' that he had an encounter with Starr
almost a year before he was appointed Whitewater independent
counsel, replacing a moderate Republican, Robert Fiske.
</P>
<P>
   Carville, one of Clinton's closest political associates, says in
the book that he met Starr in October 1993, in the USAir executive
lounge at Washington National Airport, although at the time he had
no idea who Starr was. Carville recalled that a stranger walked up
to him and ``started spouting an unsolicited and shameful tirade
against the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your boy's getting rolled,'' Carville said the stranger said
ominously to him before walking away.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he realized that Starr would be the new independent
counsel investigating Clinton, Carville returned his White House
pass and resigned his consulting post with the Democratic National
Committee so that he could attack Starr full time.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Leon Panetta, then the White House chief of
staff, Carville said that the appointment of Starr was ``a historic
and unconscionable violation of fairness and justice, and that his
appointment has been engineered by fanatical opponents of the
president and his agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But Panetta, on the advice of Lloyd Cutler, then White House
counsel, persuaded Carville to stay. They told him that Starr was a
reasonable man and that attacking him would serve only to worsen
relations between the office of the independent counsel and the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Carville reluctantly agreed, a decision he now says was the
biggest personal mistake of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton rapidly came to share Carville's view. Mrs. Clinton
became convinced that Starr had set his sights on indicting her, or
at least embarrassing her. Clinton was furious at the treatment of
many of his friends and associates in Arkansas, who he believed
were mistreated by Starr's agents and indicted on trumped-up
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him rant about Starr on lots of occasions,'' said
Jane Sherburne, the former deputy White House counsel who
coordinated the Clintons' defense in the Whitewater investigation
from 1995 to 1997. ``He felt a deep sense of outrage about how
Starr was trampling through the lives of really tangential
witnesses in Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the early days of the inquiry, it was Mrs. Clinton who
felt the most hostility toward the independent counsel, Ms.
Sherburne said. And Ms. Sherburne said the feeling in the
independent counsel's office was apparently mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``From early 1995 on, I saw a hardening, a deteriorating in the
relationship, but it was much more focused on Hillary _ the venom,
the conviction she was a liar, a determination to get her that they
just exuded in every conversation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sherburne recounted a conversation with Starr in which she
asked that prosecutors interview Mrs. Clinton at the White House
rather than subject her to a courthouse spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr just clasped his hands together and said, `I have
complete respect for the dignity of the White House and the first
lady, but I see this as a serious matter and she should be before
the grand jury,''' Ms. Sherburne said. ``It was unjustified
grandstanding. As we have seen from subsequent events, he is
capable of presenting information in a politically charged way to
inflict the maximum damage, whether legal or political.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, Carville began a campaign to raise questions
about the integrity of Starr and his assistants. Carville's efforts
were not lost on Starr, who soon realized that he was engaged not
merely in a legal inquiry but in what Carville has often described
as a war.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was one of the commanders, pressing aides daily to
find negative material on Starr and make sure it got into the hands
of reporters, according to a former White House official involved
in the effort. ``She was continually frustrated that progress on
that front did not happen more quickly,'' this official said,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Carville, White House officials and Democratic Party researchers
delved into Starr's legal clients, the political affiliations of
groups he spoke to, the financial interests of his central
witnesses and the political ideology of his lieutenants. Much of
this material did find its way into newspapers and later into
online magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was disturbed by questions about his ties to conservative
groups, his outside law clients and his numerous speaking
engagements, said a White House official who dealt with him in this
period.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady
</P>
<P>
   Starr Subpoenas Hillary Clinton
</P>
<P>
   For many White House aides, any hope of a civil relationship
with Starr ended abruptly on Jan. 22, 1996. On that day, Starr
served Mrs. Clinton with a subpoena to appear before a federal
grand jury to answer questions about the reappearance in the White
House of her long-missing billing records from the Rose law firm in
Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, Mrs. Clinton strode into the federal courthouse
here, besieged by reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   With a tight smile, she said afterward, ``I tried to be as
helpful as I could in their investigation efforts.'' But it was at
that point that the Clintons' legal defense team decided to be
anything but cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``His decision to humiliate the first lady was a turning
point,'' said Rahm Emanuel, the president's senior adviser. ``The
president had heard everything about what a reasonable man Starr
was, but he saw the only purpose of that grand jury appearance was
to intentionally hurt the first lady. For the president, that was
the beginning of the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In September of that year, Clinton's feelings toward Starr were
affirmed when he saw photographs of Susan McDougal, his former
business partner in the Whitewater land venture in Arkansas, led to
prison in handcuffs and leg irons for refusing to testify against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vented his anger about Mrs. McDougal's treatment
privately, but White House aides repeatedly warned him not to
discuss the matter in public. He was far ahead in his presidential
race against Bob Dole, they said, and no good would come of
answering any Whitewater questions.
</P>
<P>
   But the independent counsel's office asserted that Clinton, in
television interviews, did not rule out a pardon for Mrs. McDougal,
thereby perhaps encouraging her to maintain her silence. Clinton's
lawyers called accusations that he tried to insert himself into the
case ``reckless and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris, a sometime political adviser to the president, said
that Clinton ignored the advice to never discuss the case in
public, and allowed his hostility to Starr to affect his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously hates Starr with every fiber of his being,''
Morris said in an interview. ``After being deposed by some of
Starr's people, Clinton told me he'd never been with seamier,
dirtier, viler, uglier people. He said he felt like taking a
shower.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Telephone Call
</P>
<P>
   A Change of Focus, From Land to Sex
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, Starr's investigation appeared to be drawing to
a quiet conclusion. At the White House, senior aides were convinced
that Starr's prosecutors had come up empty. But on Jan. 12, Starr's
inquiry was abruptly and permanently altered by a telephone call
from Linda Tripp, a Pentagon employee whom Starr's prosecutors had
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp told Starr that she had recorded conversations that
proved the president had had a sexual relationship with a White
House intern and tried to cover it up. According to one Starr ally,
Mrs. Tripp's accusations were seized upon by prosecutors as ``a
gift from the gods,'' an opportunity to target the president for
possible crimes that were weeks old, rather than 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp's information confronted Starr with a choice. He
could refer the accusations to the Justice Department and recommend
the appointment of another independent counsel. Or he could ask the
court to grant him jurisdiction to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no debate,'' one Starr ally said. ``Everyone wanted
this one, and no one was going to let it get away.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior Justice Department lawyer said last week that the
department had ``no choice'' but to allow Starr to go forward. ``I
don't think it was a viable option for us to refer it to someone
else,'' said the lawyer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``We were boxed in'' by the evidence that Starr presented, the
lawyer said. But he added that ``we did get a glimpse of Starr's
zealousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno immediately referred the Tripp
accusations to a three-judge panel with a recommendation that Starr
lead the inquiry. In a matter of hours, the panel granted
jurisdiction to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   But the tenuous connection that had won Starr jurisdiction
further infuriated the Clintons and deepened their belief that the
independent counsel's office was out to get them, their friends
say. ``The president just went ballistic,'' said a member of
Clinton's legal team, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a character in a novel,'' Clinton told Sidney
Blumenthal, a White House political aide, according to Blumenthal's
grand jury testimony. ``I feel like somebody who was surrounded by
an oppressive force that is creating a lie about me and I can't get
the truth out.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Can Play
</P>
<P>
   White House Goes on the Attack
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the Lewinsky inquiry becoming public on Jan. 21,
prosecutors were confronted with a pivotal decision _ either
quickly offer Ms. Lewinsky immunity to get her to testify about her
sexual encounters with Clinton, or move on without her testimony
and turn over every stone to prove that the president and Ms.
Lewinsky had a sexual relationship and that the president and
others conspired to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   There were lengthy, heated debates in the office over what
course to take. One camp wanted to either indict Ms. Lewinsky or
conduct an exhaustive inquiry. Jackie Bennett, who had a reputation
as a pit-bull prosecutor, and Robert Bittman, a young, fiercely
aggressive prosecutor, led this camp.
</P>
<P>
   The other camp favored making a deal with Ms. Lewinsky and
conducting a short inquiry; this camp was led by a pair of
newcomers to the office, the career prosecutors Michael Emmick and
Bruce Udolf, voices of moderation on the Starr team.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the White House chose to unleash a furious
attack on Starr and his prosecutors. Led by Carville, White House
officials and allies portrayed Starr as an overzealous prosecutor
intent on destroying the president. Mrs. Clinton accused Starr of
being part of ``a vast, right-wing conspiracy'' against her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, a senior White House aide was blunt about their
motives, saying the White House was engaged in a ``continuing
campaign to destroy Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was working. By late February, some Clinton loyalists
were openly gloating. They bragged to reporters that they were
surprised at how easy it was to change the subject from the
president's relationship with a former intern to Starr's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But the attacks had an even more profound impact inside Starr's
office. ``One of the biggest mistakes was they underestimated
Starr's resolve,'' a Starr ally said. ``They set out to kill the
investigation, and the rule of law is what survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors _ and Starr himself _ became so angry that
some of their allies now acknowledge they were baited into making
ill-advised strategic decisions that the public found to be highly
questionable, even deplorable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first blunders by Starr was calling a low-level White
House aide named Bob Weiner before the grand jury to question him
about whether he had referred Mrs. Tripp for prosecution in
Maryland for recording Ms. Lewinsky without her permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should send a message that people should not try to
impede our investigation,'' one prosecutor snapped at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors were also widely criticized for calling Ms.
Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, before the grand jury. Videotape
of a distraught Ms. Lewis leaving court was played repeatedly on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing angered Starr more than what he believed was a White
House effort to smear two of his prosecutors, Emmick and Udolf,
allies said. In response, Starr subpoenaed Blumenthal and Terry
Lenzner, a private investigator with longtime Democratic Party
connections.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews at the time, Starr justified his office's actions
by arguing that ``misinformation or distorted information'' about
lawyers on his team had impeded his inquiry and may have been
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   But these remarks were widely criticized, even by leading
congressional Republicans. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a former
district attorney in Philadelphia, said, ``Ken Starr went too
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of harsh criticism ``hardened the resolve of
everyone'' inside Starr's office, one of the prosecutors said at
the time. ``It became very, very personal,'' a Starr ally said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Starr was and is very protective of the personal integrity
of his career prosecutors and the overall integrity of the
investigation,'' said Bakaly, the office spokesman. ``But every
prosecutorial decision has been based on the right thing to do
under the law and was consistent with all legal and ethical
guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the public clearly sided with the president over
Starr. In polls, Clinton's approval rating hovered around 70
percent. Starr's flirted with the single digits. The president was
keenly aware of the polls. A close friend of Clinton said last week
that the glaring disparity in the poll numbers comforted the
president and provided him and others inside the White House with a
false sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy for the president to deny everything and put up
roadblocks,'' the friend said. ``Remember, for a long time, the
president was winning.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Sample
</P>
<P>
   Drawing Blood, Recrossing Swords
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, six months after the inquiry began, not only was
Clinton winning but it appeared he would most likely outlast Starr.
Polls showed that the majority of Americans wanted Starr to drop
his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   On July 17, Starr took the extraordinary step of sending a grand
jury subpoena to the president. Because Clinton had rejected six
separate invitations to appear voluntarily, lawyers in the office
felt they had no choice but to compel his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The president was enraged, and he steadfastly refused to be
forced, as Mrs. Clinton was, to walk into the federal courthouse
before the television cameras. He told aides he did not want to be
the first sitting president to be subpoenaed to appear before a
grand jury in an investigation in which he was a potential target.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal team, including David Kendall, his private
lawyer, and his political advisers agreed that the president should
refuse to testify and challenge the subpoena on constitutional
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The president rejected that advice and instead agreed to
testify, but only at the White House and only with Kendall present.
But Starr also won some concessions, including that the testimony
be videotaped in the event that a grand juror missed the live,
closed-circuit video transmission inside the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to permit Starr to videotape the proceedings would
soon haunt the president.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Clinton agreed to testify, it also became known,
through news reports, that Ms. Lewinsky had turned over the navy
blue dress that she told prosecutors contained DNA evidence from
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr informed Kendall on July 31 that the office needed to draw
a vial of Clinton's blood. Clinton and Kendall considered the
possibility that it was a bluff on Starr's part. But later that
day, Starr wrote in his report to Congress, prosecutors assured the
president that prosecutors ``had an evidentiary basis for making
the request.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then, several of the president's advisers said, that
discussions began about what to say to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decided to insist that he had not lied in his deposition
in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit, and to do that he
developed a strategy of acknowledging only ``improper intimate
contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky, but refusing to answer specific
questions about their sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not want to give them anything,'' a friend said. ``He'd
only go so far. He refused to make it easy on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the issue of the potentially explosive grand jury
videotape, Starr and Clinton exchanged accusations of bad faith
last week. Kendall said that prosecutors had assured Clinton they
would destroy the tape after playing it for absent grand jurors who
missed the live feed.
</P>
<P>
   But in a scathing reply, Starr said he could not ethically
destroy the tape, because it was ``evidence of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Speech
</P>
<P>
   Lots of Seething, Not Much Contrition
</P>
<P>
   There is no more revealing and authentic artifact of the
president's tortured relationship with the prosecutor than his
four-minute address to the nation on Aug. 17. He delivered it at 10
p.m., after four hours of difficult questioning by Starr,
prosecutors and grand jurors in the White House Map Room.
</P>
<P>
   The president had several hours to prepare for his televised
speech. His aides, knowing that he was furious about his treatment
by Starr and his deputies, gave him a draft text that emphasized
``candor, contrition and closure,'' said Paul Begala, a senior
White House political adviser who helped prepare the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   When Carville left the White House shortly after 8 p.m., he was
convinced that Clinton was going to deliver a speech that did not
mention Starr. Carville said the president did not appear to be
angry. ``He looked tired, fatigued,'' Carville recalled. ``In
retrospect, it would have been smarter for him, and everybody, to
get a good night's sleep and take a crack at that speech in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   At 8:15 p.m., less than two hours before he was to speak,
Clinton ripped up Begala's draft and began writing his own.
</P>
<P>
   It was raw and bitter. The statement was neither candid nor
contrite, and rather than bringing closure, it opened a gaping
chasm. The president has acknowledged in several recent public
statements that he allowed his fury at Starr to affect his
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after his televised speech, he said that anger and
``the desire for recrimination against people you believe have
wronged you _ they harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead
to self-inflicted wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The president promised a group of religious leaders on Sept. 11
that in his quest for forgiveness he knew that he must renounce
``the pride and the anger which cloud judgment, lead people to
excuse and compare and to blame and complain.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Starr has expressed no apologies for any of his
treatment of the president and little explanation for the contents
of his report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Bakaly said: ``The statute provides no guidance to what form
or manner the referral should take. But we made every effort to be
fair and complete.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference outside his Virginia home in April, Starr
made his most extensive remarks on the Lewinsky scandal, saying
that he was not influenced by politics or by his personal feelings
about the president.
</P>
<P>
   He said that like Joe Friday on the television series
``Dragnet,'' he was interested in ``just the facts'' and was
certain that they would lead him to the truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
