<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-COP-STORY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-DEAD OFFICER GETS HIS DUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Somebody finally took the time to make it right by
you, Robert Normand.
</P>
<P>
   Finally gave you a fitting memorial for the pauper's grave you
were buried in 78 years ago after being shot and killed in the line
of duty.
</P>
<P>
   His name is David Kleinfeld, and he's a Burbank, Calif., police
officer, just like you were. Only they didn't call you police
officers back then, did they? They called you lawmen and marshals
in 1914, when you and Luther Colson joined the department in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Both of your names are up on the wall behind the front counter
of the Burbank Police Department, right next to the pictures of two
Burbank motorcycle officers killed in the line of duty in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinfeld used to stare at that wall last year on slow days when
he was pulling counter duty and nothing much was happening.
</P>
<P>
   He got to wondering what you and Luther looked like, started
thinking it wasn't right that you only had your names on the wall,
not your pictures, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it all began, Robert. One cop looking for the
pictures of two old lawmen to properly memorialize them on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinfeld began his research on his days off, finding department
records on how you guys died and where you were buried _ Grandview
Memorial Park in Glendale. He even ran down the original newspaper
stories on your deaths.
</P>
<P>
   It was all there.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank City Marshal Luther Colson, shot and killed Nov. 17,
1914, while walking along the Southern Pacific Railroad tracks
clearing out hobo camps.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank Deputy City Marshal Robert Normand, shot and killed July
30, 1920, at the U.L. Hood Tire Shop at 254 Second St. (now San
Fernando Boulevard). The story told how you and Township Constable
Henry Purrier caught four men burglarizing the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normand jumped onto the running board of the suspects'
Studebaker and told the driver to head towards the city jail,'' the
story said. ``Constable Purrier followed in his own vehicle. At
about Third and Tujunga, one of the men shot Normand, killing him
instantly. Purrier pulled his own car alongside of the suspects and
opened fire, wounding the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   It went on to say that even though hit by bullets himself,
Purrier drove you to the hospital, Robert, but it was too late. The
Burbank city trustees offered a $750 reward for your killers, who
were later captured.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating stuff, but there were no pictures with the stories,
so Kleinfeld continued searching, hoping to find any relatives you
and Luther might still have living.
</P>
<P>
   He was hoping to get lucky, maybe find your pictures stuck deep
in the back of some old family photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   To find relatives, Kleinfeld enlisted the help of Marsha Howard,
general manager of Grandview Memorial Park. She went deep into the
archives and found the yellowed interment records.
</P>
<P>
   The trail on Luther's relatives finally went cold up in Redwood
City, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Your trail never got started.
</P>
<P>
   ``His interment record was blank,'' Kleinfeld said. ``There were
no relatives listed. I was also shocked to find Normand's grave
unmarked. He was buried in a pauper's grave.''
</P>
<P>
   A pauper's grave. How could that be? No one from 78 years ago is
around to answer that one.
</P>
<P>
   It was right around this time, Robert, that Kleinfeld began
thinking less of finding your picture and more of correcting this
injustice.
</P>
<P>
   He went before the Burbank Police Officers Association with your
story and told his fellow officers it was only right that they chip
in for a headstone for a deputy marshal who was doing their job 78
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An old lawman lying in an unmarked pauper's grave not more than
10 miles from their own station house.
</P>
<P>
   The association anted up $590 to have a headstone made and
placed on your pauper's grave, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   It was put up on March 25 of this year without any fanfare. Only
Kleinfeld was there.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of guy he is, Robert _ quiet and unassuming. He
didn't want people thinking he was trying to take credit or make a
big deal out of finally making it right by you.
</P>
<P>
   Even this story came to me initially secondhand from another
Burbank police officer, Fay Malcolm. She had to talk Kleinfeld into
going public with it because he didn't want people thinking he had
done anything special.
</P>
<P>
   He has, of course. Very special.
</P>
<P>
   One last thing, Robert. For the first time ever, there were
flowers put on your grave July 30, the 78th anniversary of the day
you died in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Kleinfeld again.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
