<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHRISTIANS-80     09-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHRISTIANS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION LAMENTS LACK OF WIDESPREAD ANGER ABOUT
CLINTON'S BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Maine, Minn., N.J., Va.)  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE, CLINTON-GORE,
CLINTON-INTERNET.) 
(js) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This should be a time of triumph for the
conservative, overwhelmingly pro-Republican members of the
Christian Coalition. The Democratic, baby-boomer president they
have long considered a moral disgrace now faces talk of his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in the hallways and during coffee breaks at the
three-day Christian Coalition convention here, many delegates said
they were despondent about opinion polls showing that most
Americans do not share the conviction that President Clinton should
resign or be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   They said they feared that the American people cared more about
the decline of the Dow than the decline of morals. And they
speculated that the libertine legacy of the 1960s still held sway
over American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation is so grossly materialistic and so self-centered,''
said Brad Thomas, founder of Christ's Bride Ministries in McLean,
Va., as the convention joined in singing the national anthem. ``We
see that in the abortion debate. It's a matter of `me first.'
Supposedly there are many Christians in this nation, God-fearing
people, and yet Clinton can attend church and supposedly that makes
him godly, even when every policy he's had has been ungodly.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Johnson, an operations consultant for US West in St. Paul,
said during the lunch break Friday: ``The polls could be accurate,
and that makes me worried that the so-called liberalism that has
taken root in the last 20 to 25 years means that people can't think
clearly about perjury and obstruction of justice. It seemed clear
when Nixon was in office. Why isn't it clear now?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Christian Coalition held its first convention eight
years ago, the group's founders, Pat Robertson and Ralph Reed, have
issued dire warnings that the nation is facing moral collapse. They
have cited the end of prayer in the schools, the high rates of
teen-age pregnancy and the disturbing incidents of youth violence.
They have attributed social problems to the increasing
secularization of society, and said they were seeking to return the
nation to its ``Christian roots.''
</P>
<P>
   At this year's convention, which ends on Sunday, the group's
leaders used the Clinton scandal as the ultimate evidence that
Washington was in need of a restoration of ``family values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Character matters, and the American people are hungry for that
message,'' said Reed, the coalition's former executive director and
now a private political consultant. ``We care about the conduct of
our leaders, and we will not rest until we have leaders of good
moral character.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the group's rank-and-file members, there was
speculation that many Americans do not share the same sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why isn't there outrage over this?'' said Ronald J. Mossberg,
31, a computer systems analyst from Maplewood, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think people have just gotten themselves too busy,
taking care of the kids. Everybody's working. They listen to the
evening news and they become disengaged. The baby boomers were
raised in a permissive age, and Bill Clinton is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who attended the convention voiced suspicions that
the news media were intentionally skewing the poll questions to
make the results appear more supportive of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sick of hearing TV constantly quoting the polls, as if
that matters,'' said Cecilia Huckestein, 50, a portrait artist from
Westlake Village, Calif. ``The law matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Huckestein said that nobody she knew in Los Angeles wanted
Clinton to stay in office, so she could not imagine how the polls
were turning up such results. ``I haven't ever been polled,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll, conducted last week,
showed that of 1,813 adults nationwide who were surveyed, 6 in 10
Americans wanted Clinton to finish his term. And though 2 in 3
people polled said that Clinton did not share their moral values,
62 percent said they approved of the job he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such vexing poll numbers and convinced that the
American electorate is not as accepting of Clinton's behavior as
other polls indicate, the Christian Coalition sponsored its own
poll. Its survey asked 1,000 registered voters whether, regarding
morals and values, ``things are on the right track and getting
better, or on the wrong track and getting worse.'' In that poll, 63
percent said things were getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, the Christian Coalition's executive director, touted
the results of this poll at the convention, saying, ``The moral
crisis we now face is so obvious everybody sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me offer a small piece of advice to any candidate who is
on the wrong side of the values issue,'' said Tate, a former
Republican congressman from Washington state. ``You are going to
have one big problem on Election Day.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From the podium at the convention, several speakers criticized
Congress for indecisiveness on whether to call impeachment
hearings. Oliver North, who once found himself at the center of the
Reagan administration's Iran-contra affair, told the crowd, ``It is
now time for the members of Congress to stop reading the polls, and
screw up their courage and do their duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in interviews, many Christian Coalition members said they
were confident that legislators would eventually call for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're moving in the right direction,'' said Nelida
Kuhlmann, 50, an office manager from Westwood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Finks, 51, a former administrator of a Christian school in
Falmouth, Maine, said the system was working. In fact, he added,
the Clinton imbroglio presented Christian conservatives with an
unprecedented opportunity to define their position on values.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic event,'' Finks said. ``We've probably never
had anything that raised the character issue so clearly before in
the history of the American republic.''
</P>
<P>
   One critic of the Christian Coalition attributed the gap in
outrage to the Christian conservatives' narrow definition of
morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most Americans there's a lot more moral ambiguity in the
world than the average member of the Christian Coalition is able to
see,'' the critic, Barry Lynn, executive director of Americans
United for Separation of Church and State, said in an interview
during a break.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn attended the Christian Coalition's sessions Fridya and
offered a rebuttal at his group's noon news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Coalition folks do measure morality on the basis
of sexual behavior,'' Lynn said in the interview. ``To other
people, morality is a balance and could even include questions
like, Are more children going to bed hungry under this president
than before?''
</P>
<P>
   The concern that the American people are insufficiently outraged
is not confined to the convention here in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a letter to about 2.4 million supporters, James
Dobson, founder of Focus on the Family, a multimedia ministry in
Colorado, wrote, ``What has alarmed me throughout this episode has
been the willingness of my fellow citizens to rationalize the
president's behavior even as they suspected, and later knew, he was
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am left to conclude that our greatest problem is not in the
Oval Office,'' Dobson wrote. ``It is with the people of this
land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
