</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN CAMBODIA, TWO RIVALS ARE YOKED IN FRAYED HARNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Wars, elections, coups and riots come and go
in Cambodia, but the unhappy entanglement of the prince and the
former communist, it seems, is never-ending.
</P>
<P>
   This week, after swearing he would not, the royalist leader,
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, is to join his longtime antagonist, Hun
Sen, in a Parliament created by a disputed election nearly two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament is to convene on Thursday in Siem Reap, in the
shadow of the ancient monuments of Angkor Wat and under the
guidance of King Norodom Sihanouk, the constitutional monarch.
</P>
<P>
   If political horse-trading goes the way most analysts think it
will, the two antagonists will form a coalition government that
will in some ways replicate the disastrous recent partnership that
helped tear the country apart.
</P>
<P>
   That feuding co-premiership was created by the last election, in
1993, and lasted only four years, until July 1997, when Hun Sen
expelled the prince from government in a violent coup. The 1993
election followed a decade of civil war in which the prince was
part of an alliance that opposed Hun Sen's Vietnamese-backed
communist government.
</P>
<P>
   This time their uneasy coalition should be more stable, if only
because it is one-sided. Hun Sen and the Cambodian People's Party
will dominate, and the prince is unlikely to win a post with
far-reaching powers.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for an end to electoral protests, Sihanouk offered a
bottom line to Cambodia's long struggle to become a civil society:
Power still rules, he said, and the losers must submit, fair or
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a Cambodia that is not a state of law and not a fully
fledged democracy, I have no other choice than to advise the weak
to choose a policy that avoids misfortune for the people, the
motherland and themselves,'' the king said.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Hun Sen's coup succeeded. It fragmented the
prince's party and was followed by a campaign of intimidation by
Hun Sen's followers that reportedly included more than 100
political killings.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, and with the opposition almost entirely
excluded from the news media, many analysts say it is impossible to
consider the July election fair.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless Hun Sen's opponents made a respectable showing.
While his party won 64 parliamentary seats, the opposition won
almost as many, with the prince's party taking 43 and the party of
a third candidate, Sam Rainsy, 15. Thus Hun Sen needs to form a
coalition with the prince and others to gather the two-thirds
majority required in the 122-seat National Assembly to form a
government.
</P>
<P>
   Such a coalition might have come more easily had it not been for
the aggressive election protests led by Sam Rainsy. Asserting that
the voting, the ballot-counting and the seat-allocation formula had
been manipulated by Hun Sen's party, Sam Rainsy refused to accept
the results.
</P>
<P>
   The prince, who may have been seeking to strengthen his
bargaining position in any coalition with Hun Sen, joined Sam
Rainsy in demanding recounts, an examination of the ballots and a
revision of the disputed formula.
</P>
<P>
   The protests received little backing from the foreign
governments that had helped finance the election; most endorsed the
results.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests appeared to tap into a deep strain of
discontent, at least among residents of the capital, Phnom Penh,
who had given Hun Sen's party only one-third of their votes. A tent
city of protesters grew outside the National Assembly, and when it
was torn down by soldiers early last week, the city was convulsed
by riots.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen responded with his characteristic tactic: force.
</P>
<P>
   When demonstrators supporting the prince and Sam Rainsy filled
the streets, they were clubbed and shot and then forced aside by
thousands of highly organized counterdemonstrators trucked in from
the countryside and armed with sticks, stones and slingshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say it was hard bargaining, but not around a
table,'' a Western diplomat said. But something else emerged from
the week of turmoil. In a brief outpouring of something that looked
like ``people power,'' many thousands of Cambodians filled the
streets to cheer for peace and democracy. For the first time,
residents rose in defiance to demand an end to the violence and
power struggles that have ravaged their country for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``These protests revealed that, at least in the major city of
Phnom Penh, there is a growing middle class,'' a European diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was easily cleared from the streets by men with guns, but it
had announced its presence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
