<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORE-550&AMP;ADD-     09-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE HAS IDEAS FOR POST-CLINTON DEMOCRATS, AND THEY START WITH
GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE, CLINTON-CHRISTIANS,
CLINTON-INTERNET.) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the debate intensifies over President Clinton's
political future, a new magazine will be introduced this week that
is devoted to the post-Clinton era in American politics _ and,
apparently, to the election of Vice President Al Gore in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, a slickly printed quarterly, is named Blueprint:
Ideas for a New Century and is being published by the Democratic
Leadership Council, a centrist organization that Clinton once
headed and turned to for help in starting his presidential campaign
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or another, Clinton is not going to be president for
that much longer,'' said Andrei Cherny, a former senior
speechwriter for Gore who is editor of Blueprint. ``And the
Democratic Party needs to figure out where it goes after him and
what it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Al From, the publisher and head of the leadership council,
insisted that the magazine, with a circulation goal of 35,000, ``is
a project to put the best thinking forward of the `New Democrat'
movement _ it's not just a project to help one person get
elected.'' The magazine dwells more on ideas than practicalities of
a presidential campaign. But Blueprint, which is financed with
donations to the Democratic Leadership Council, clearly looks like
a Gore vehicle. Most references are not to the Clinton
administration but to ``the Clinton/Gore administration.'' The
staff is stocked with Gore loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the articles in the premier issue were written by former
Gore aides or current advisers. One article, about demographic
changes in the electorate, was written by Elaine Kamarck of Harvard
University, who ran Gore's reinventing government initiative in the
first term, and by William Galston, a former Clinton domestic
policy aide who is close to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Penn, the White House pollster who is expected to sign on
with Gore for 2000, wrote an article analyzing the Democratic
electorate of the future and is expected to have a standing
analysis in each issue. Another article, which explores ``the
growing phenomenon of economic free agents,'' is by Daniel Pink,
Gore's chief speechwriter from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One well-established weekly magazine, The New Republic, has long
been viewed in political circles as a booster of Gore. The editor
in chief, Martin Peretz, is a longtime friend of the vice president
and was one of his instructors at Harvard University, where they
met in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, other magazines have cropped up to push one
political position _ or candidate _ or another. Just last week,
Salon, an online magazine that is widely viewed as friendly toward
Clinton, stirred a partisan frenzy by disclosing that Rep. Henry
Hyde, chairman of the Judiciary Committee, had an affair three
decades ago. And The Weekly Standard was established after the 1994
elections to press Republican positions _ and as something of a
political antidote to The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Blueprint, with an estimated budget of $1.5 million, is expected
to cease publication after six or eight issues once the 2000
presidential campaign gets fully under way. The concept for the
magazine came from Donald Baer, a former Clinton communications
director and former assistant managing editor at U.S. News &AMP; World
Report who is close to Gore. He is the magazine's senior editorial
consultant.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the Gore loyalists on the staff, the magazine does not
hew to all of the vice president's policy positions. Though Gore
has been mounting aggressive appeals to labor and liberal
constituencies to help him in the Democratic primaries, articles in
the magazine suggest that people who regularly use computers on the
job have become more important politically than union members.
Another article said Democratic candidates no longer have to gear
their appeals to the left in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   For all its focus on the post-Clinton era, Blueprint carefully
avoids injecting itself into the scandal that has engulfed the
White House and that has left Gore's advisers unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to frame the scandal in positive terms for centrist
Democrats, From and Will Marshall, the top officials of the
leadership council and its spinoff policy institute, wrote,
``President Clinton's ability to sustain support throughout much of
his presidency _ despite the miasma of scandals and investigations
that hangs over Washington _ shows that Americans are ready to
reward pragmatic problem-solving over reflexive partisanship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
