<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-CANAL-540&AMP;ADD-     09-19 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMANIAN OFFICIALS TAKING FORMER U.S. MILITARY RESIDENCES AS
THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ As minister of housing for the last four years,
Francisco Sanchez Cardenas was supposed to improve other people's
living conditions, not his own. But with the United States turning
hundreds of homes of departing military officers over to Panama as
stipulated by treaty, he and other leaders of the governing party
have got the best residences for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A result has been popular outrage and a political scandal that
threatens to cripple the governing Democratic Revolutionary Party
in elections scheduled for next spring. And with the United States
obligated to give up half a dozen more military installations over
the next 15 months, longstanding concerns about the willingness of
the government here to administer the Panama Canal and the
properties around it fairly and honestly are resurfacing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely serious because of the symbolism involved,''
said Roberto Eisenmann, a prominent businessman who is chairman of
the Panamanian chapter of the anticorruption group Transparency
International. ``The Panamanian populace has always felt that the
canal should be above the political fray, but the fact that these
homes were assigned to Cabinet ministers said to us that finagling
is going on that we never expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The homes are among 462 residences at the former Albrook Air
Force Station, which the U.S. Southern Command handed over to
Panama last October in compliance with two treaties requiring the
United States to end its presence here by Dec. 31, 1999. The houses
were supposed to be offered for public bidding this summer, but the
most coveted were suddenly withdrawn from the market days before
the auction was to take place.
</P>
<P>
   When the country's leading newspaper, La Prensa, looked into the
matter, it found that the housing minister, who is also a deputy
chairman of the governing party, the minister of labor, Mitchell
Doens, and several other party luminaries had been allowed to rent
the houses by the Inter-Oceanic Regional Authority, the ostensibly
independent government agency that administers ``reverted areas.''
As tenants, they have an option to buy the houses at a price about
half of market value.
</P>
<P>
   The affair has put President Ernesto Perez Balladares on the
defensive. His party has a long history of corruption and abuse of
power, most notably when it was controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega a decade ago, and this latest episode was seen as a clear
sign that it intends to treat the former Canal Zone as a gift to
the party, not the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact of being a minister in this or the previous
government obviously should not be a reason to receive a house,''
Perez Balladares said at a recent news conference. ``But neither
should it be a reason not to receive one. They have a perfect
right, like any other Panamanian, to compete and try to obtain, if
that is their desire, a residence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Cardenas did not respond to requests for comment, but he
has previously denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Popular irritation with the real-estate deals has been cited as
a factor in the rejection last month by a margin of nearly 2 to 1
of a constitutional amendment that would have allowed the president
to seek a second term of office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sanchez Cardenas and Doens, who is also a party deputy chairman,
stepped down the day after the vote. With Perez Balladares now a
lame duck, the housing minister announced he would seek the
governing party's nomination for president, saying that his humble
origins make him the ideal candidate to administer the former Canal
Zone in the interests of the Panamanian people.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition groups have also aimed their fire at the director of
the Inter-Oceanic Regional Authority, Nicolas Ardito Barletta, a
president in the Noriega years, demanding that he resign. But
Barletta complained in an interview here that the issue of the
houses has ``turned political'' and rejected any accusations of
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to diminish what has been a task well done,''
said Barletta in an interview at the authority's headquarters in a
``reverted area'' that is being turned into a hotel and yacht
complex. ``Nothing illegal or immoral has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers and real-estate dealers here say that the two
Cabinet members should have been excluded from taking possession of
the houses as renters because they already own other homes.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the transfer of the Albrook Air Force Station, less
than half the 6,000 buildings and one-third of the land in the
former Canal Zone are under Panamanian control. The real windfall
comes in the next year, when the United States is scheduled to turn
over real estate valued at an estimated at $3.4 billion, including
nearly 2,500 houses at four different military bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
