<P>
   CLINTON-NEWT _ Washington _ In another time, Newt Gingrich would
have relished an all-out attack on President Clinton as much as any
Republican in the House of Representatives. He would have scoffed
at party elders who tried to rein in his speeches on the House
floor, speeches that first made his national reputation. But as the
Republican Speaker of the House, Gingrich is managing the most
delicate issue of his long career in Congress and he is keenly
aware _ unlike at some moments in the past _ that people are
parsing his every word. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CHECK-CASHERS _ WASHINGTON _ Check-cashing stores, once thought
of as part of the fringe banking community, are taking a step
towards the economic mainstream as an unintended consequence of a
federal program to pay benfits through electronic transfers rather
than by paper checks. U.S. Treasury officials estimate that as much
as $16 billion worth of government checks every year are sent to
citizens who do not have a bank. In an effort to grab a piece of
that business, the check-cashing industry and major banks have
formed an economic alliance that allows check-cashing stores to
begin handing out ATM cards to the ``unbanked'' starting next
month. This is yet another step in creating dual banking systems:
one for the affluent and a separate more expensive alternative for
low-income families. (Shepard and Jaspin, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Moved in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-SCOTCH _ GLEN LIVET, Scotland _ Robbie Hughes casts a
stainless steel cannister into the small natural pool, breaking the
glassy surface. He reels in the metal container and pours some of
the cold, crystaline water into glasses. ``Take a taste,'' he tells
his visitors. When the water is consumed, he opens the doors behind
a cabinet built by the water and pulls out a half full bottle of
pale, golden Tormore single malt Scotch. ``Now,'' he says,'' Take a
taste of this.'' For 60 years the rainwater has been filtered and
amended by the hills before bubbling up in the cold springs of Burn
Auchmochsen. As it passes through the rocky layers, gaining
minerals and peat, the water emerges just a little bit shy of being
this drink. ``Best bar in the world, isn't it,'' Hughes says
without expecting or getting any argument. It is also just about
the only place to get a taste of Tormore. Despite a growing
American demand for the special, distinct flavors found only in
single malt Scotches, modern economics are leading to the
extinction of single malt brands by the dozens. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SCOTCH-MALT _ GLEN LIVET, Scotland _ What makes single malt
scotch so special? How it's made, what makes it unique. (Roughton,
Cox News Service).
