   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE _ TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ The ugly memories of George Wallace
and what he did have faded somewhat, and, with his passing, Alabama
may finally be the ``New South.'' The new Mercedes plant is a
symbol of the change, as are the blacks returning to the state from
self-imposed exile. Today, relations between the races, while not
perfect, aren't as testy as a lot of big cities up north.
(MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NUWAUBIAN _ A separatist-group leader who relocated his base
from Brooklyn, New York to a farm in rural Georgia has been linked
to a wide range of criminal activity, including the re-activated
investigation of a 1979 assasination-style killing of a Brooklyn
community activist. Dwight York, also known as Dr. Malachi Z. York
and formerly known as Asi Muhammed, was from the late 1970s until
1993 the leader of a Muslim-oriented group called Ansaru Allah
Community, comprised of about 700 members living in a community of
about 20 to 30 apartment homes in the Bushwick section of Brooklyn.
York, 53, purchased a 400-acre farm in Putnam County in 1993 and
moved there with about 150 members of his group, which he re-named
the United Nuwaubian Nation of Moors. Though the group has kept a
relatively low profile since the move, Putnam County officials and
local black leaders have recently expressed concerns that York and
the Nuwaubians -- nearly all of whom are black -- are attempting to
stir up racial hostility and to build up their political power, to
the point where he can either dominate local politics or set up a
separate governmental entity. (Osinski, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 100-120.
</P>
