<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center of Tropical Storm Hermine with wind gusting over 45
miles an hour will approach the eastern Gulf Coast on Sunday
accompanied by showers and some heavy thunderstorms. The heaviest
rain is expected Sunday afternoon from northern Florida to southern
parts of Georgia and Mississippi where local flooding is possible.
Farther west, scattered thundershowers will brush the coast of
northern Texas and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly cloudy skies will linger near the central and southern
Appalachians, where moist winds ascend the sloping terrain.
Scattered showers and some afternoon thunder will occur in southern
sections. Meanwhile, partly sunny skies and rather humid air will
cover most of the northeast and middle Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   A band of showers and thunderstorms will accompany a front as it
moves into the eastern Great Lakes and central Mississippi Valley.
Cooler and drier air with gusty breezes will follow the front, but
some clouds and light showers will linger from northern Montana to
northern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Moist breezes from the east will promote clouds and showers
along the east slopes of the central and northern Rockies. Farther
south, ample sunshine will prevail from the southern Plains to the
southwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, some clouds and scattered showers will develop
under a whirlpool of chilly air aloft. Nevertheless, offshore
breezes will favor considerable sunshine east of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the center of powerful Hurricane Georges with central
winds over 120 mph will approach the northern Windward Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Helpful Hurricanes
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Typhoon Todd buffeted the coast of China while
Atlantic Hurricane Georges approached the Lesser Antilles. These
storms, like all tropical storms and hurricanes performed the
important function of moving heat from the tropics toward the
middle latitudes. In the cold season, powerful winter storms
transport frigid air toward the equator while circulating warmer
air toward the poles, helping to erase the natural global energy
imbalance. In summer, when midlatitude storms are weak, tropical
storms, both benign and destructive, help to balance the weather
budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
