<SLUG> BC-FBN-INSIDER-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH INSIDE LOOKS AT THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Colo.)  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two recent football books do something that most books of their
type don't: paint a realistic portrait of what happens in the lives
of the people who make up professional football.
</P>
<P>
   One is by Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf, titled ``The
Packer Way.'' In it, Wolf discusses some of the key decisions he
made to develop the Packers, the dominant team of the 1960s, into
one of the dominant teams of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the early 1990s, Wolf told the Packers' board of directors
that the player who was going to turn the franchise around was a
guy named Brett Favre. ``I even told them he would wear No. 4, and
he would be like what Lou Gehrig meant to the Yankee franchise,''
Wolf writes. ``You should have felt the silence and seen the
looks.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When Mike Holmgren was going through the interview process
before becoming head coach, Wolf writes, the general manager told
Holmgren that he had interviewed Bill Parcells. When Parcells
removed himself from the search, Holmgren was the guy Wolf wanted,
though he thought about Bill Cowher, now the coach of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before joining the Packers, defensive end Reggie White was the
most coveted player in free agent history. A number of teams
offered White all kinds of perks, and Wolf writes that the wife of
Art Modell gave White's wife, Sara, a $900 leather coat during
White's visit to Cleveland. How did Wolf wine and dine White when
he finally made it to visit the Packers? White and Wolf went to
lunch at a Red Lobster in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wolf, whose personnel decisions were among the main reasons
the Packers won the Super Bowl two years ago, the team's first in
29 years, credits Al Davis, Chuck Noll, Dick Steinberg and Ken
Herock with helping him form his drafting practices. Wolf also
writes that when he was with Davis in Oakland in the early 1970s,
helping to run the personnel department, Davis did not pay Wolf
what Wolf thought he was worth.
</P>
<P>
   Does Wolf worry that his book might upset some people? ``This
isn't that kind of book,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``It's
more of a how-to book, how to run a business or an organization.
I'm sure I'll offend someone, though, but I hope people
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The other book, written by Terrell Davis, the Denver Broncos
running back and Super Bowl XXXII most valuable player, is much
more gritty. In ``TD: Dreams in Motion, The Memoirs of the Denver
Broncos' Terrell Davis,'' the player writes that when he was young,
his father, who Davis says served several prison terms on robbery
and weapons charges, once lined up Davis and his brothers against a
wall in their bedroom and started shooting a .38-caliber handgun in
their direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to living with my pops,'' Davis writes, ``my
brothers and I saw guns so often, it became as routine as seeing
the ice cream truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' brother Bobby assaulted a pregnant woman during a robbery
in San Diego when Davis was young. The woman survived, but the baby
was stillborn and the case became a landmark event when it ignited
a debate over the legal status of a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   As for his football career, Davis, who just signed the richest
contract in team history with a nine-year, $56.1 million deal, came
close to quitting the Broncos his rookie year, 1995, because he was
frustrated with football. Two days before a preseason game against
San Francisco in Tokyo, he was trying to book a flight back to the
United States. But no operators spoke English, so he eventually
gave up and stayed. The Broncos are happy he did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
