u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      09-19 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JETS MAY BACK SEMINAR TO AID PLAYERS OFF THE FIELD
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets are among seven teams considering taking part
in an experimental program aimed at keeping National Football
League players out of trouble off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The program is modeled after the league's successful rookie
orientation symposium. The league wants to use a yearly three-hour
seminar to advise players on how to deal with such issues as
domestic violence, drug use, gambling, anger management, safe sex
and managing finances.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL hopes the seminar, which features lectures from experts
and skits performed by actors, will better educate its players and
thus cut down on what has been an embarrassing number of
off-the-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   While many professional sports teams put on such seminars for
rookies _ and the NFL's symposium for rookie players is considered
the best _ the league's attempt to reach veteran players on a
team-by-team basis would be the first of its kind in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The league approached the Jets first because Bill Parcells is
one of the game's most respected coaches, and the NFL figured that
if Parcells agreed to the symposium, then other teams would follow.
Parcells was excited about the idea and has been pushing for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were scheduled to hold the symposium during this week,
when the team has a bye after playing its third game Sunday against
the Indianapolis Colts. But the Jets are in an 0-2 minicrisis, and
Parcells may want to postpone the symposium until later.
</P>
<P>
   The league has at least six teams committed to using the seminar
this season. If the seminar is successful _ and most teams think it
will be _ it could spread to every team within several years. Some
league officials think the seminars may be the most important tool
to combat what they say is a growing concern.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DESPERATELY SEEKING QUARTERBACKS
</P>
<P>
   How desperate are teams to find good quarterbacks? After Rick
Mirer washed out in Chicago, he recently got a four-year, $8.55
million deal from Green Bay that included an $800,000 signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the payout is in the final two years. The
Packers think they can turn his career around.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many NFL personnel men think Scott Mitchell, recently
relegated to third string by the Lions' coaching staff, is done as
a starting quarterback. Look for the Lions to release him at the
end of the season and for Mitchell to be playing with a team like
Miami or Dallas as a backup next year.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL SAVVY
</P>
<P>
   A sign that times have changed in sports: With concerns that the
year 2000 computer bug could wreak havoc with some banks, one NFL
player called his agent last week and said that several players on
his team were going to pull all their money out of banks _ millions
of dollars _ and keep it in their houses. The agent advised the
player that it was a bad idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
