<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-MONDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' FIRST FOR 32 GIANT PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These impressionable New York Giants, the youngest team in the
National Football League, all grew up watching ``Monday Night
Football.'' As safety Sam Garnes said: ``I missed it once, when I
was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Since just 11 current Giants were born before the inaugural
``Monday Night Football'' game in 1970, and none were born before
1967, pro football's longest-running television series has been an
enduring backdrop to their football lives _ something that players
all around the locker room acknowledged this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, then, is a big day for them. Thirty-two Giants from the
team's active roster get their first chance to play Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants haven't been on ``Monday Night Football,'' the
league's grandest regular-season showcase, since their
season-opening game in 1995 _ a hope-dashing 35-0 home defeat by
the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   This Monday, when the Cowboys return to Giants Stadium, the
Giants will have only eight starters from that 1995 game.
</P>
<P>
   How the young Giants handle what can be a daunting atmosphere
will be one of the more revealing stories of this 1998 game.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel remade the Giants in 1997, weeding out players
from the Dan Reeves era in an effort to recast the team in a more
youthful, aggressive mold. When the Giants won the National
Football Conference East last year, Fassel's transformation of the
team was seen by many as a changing of the guard in the division _
especially since the Giants became the first NFC East team to go
undefeated in the division.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Fassel's charges have already staggered to an
inconsistent 1-1 start. Now they must show they can grow accustomed
to playing in the spotlighted games. It will be one of the foremost
challenges the Giants face this season. Monday's game is just the
first of three nationally televised Monday or Sunday night games
for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are old ghosts the new Giants must expunge, and
one of them is defeating the Cowboys on ``Monday Night Football,''
something the Giants have not done in five attempts since 1971.
Just playing on Monday night, and getting experience for a young
team, is a step.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants take the field with just four players who have
started more than one Monday night game. Across the line will be
the Cowboys, and while they may not be the power they once were, 17
of their 22 probable starters are NFL veterans who have started a
``Monday Night Football'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, too, will be making his first appearance as a head coach
on ``Monday Night Football,'' although as an offensive coordinator
and quarterbacks coach with other teams he worked the sideline for
several Monday night games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the second-year Giants head coach admitted it was a
special step for the franchise and his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about getting the organization back on `Monday
Night Football' when the schedule came out,'' Fassel said. ``It's
special and different. It means you did some things right the year
before or they wouldn't want to see your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the players if handled properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is also a division game, in a division where no
team won a game a week ago, a division in which a 1-1 record is
good enough for first place after the second week. In the 1998 NFC
East, an 8-8 record might be good enough for first place after the
17th week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real excited about playing on `Monday Night Football,'''
said Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead. ``But I'm more excited
about playing Dallas and getting some edge in the division. It
would be nice to play well so the world can see that we're a good
team, but the best way to do that is to start defending our title
the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants quarterback Danny Kanell will be making his first
``Monday Night Football'' appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm psyched,'' he said Friday. ``I've been watching it since I
was a little kid. There will be more adrenaline flowing, but for me
as a quarterback, I have to tone that down so I don't get too
emotionally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   As Fassel, whose debut as a NFL assistant coach _ with the
Giants in 1991 _ was on a Monday night, said last week: ``Once the
game starts, I put all the rest of the stuff away. It never occurs
to me. It could be Tuesday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy for Fassel to say. The Giants won that Monday night
game, Sept. 2, 1991, against the San Francisco 49ers. The Giants
haven't won a Monday night game at Giants Stadium since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
