<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INTERNET-760&AMP;     09-19 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERNET-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESS TO CLINTON DATA ABETS E PLURIBUS UNUM, '90S STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Mass., Minn.)  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE, CLINTON-GORE,
CLINTON-CHRISTIANS) 
(js) 
 By AMY HARMON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Ericson was not one of the millions of Americans scrolling
through the report by the independent counsel Kenneth Starr in
cyberspace last week. He read it in his local paper. Nor does he
plan to waste bandwidth downloading the videotape of President
Clinton's testimony when it is made available this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Ericson, a 33-year-old graphic designer from St. Paul, has
spent hours composing and absorbing a flood of e-mail about the
report from an online discussion group of about 400
fellow-Minnesotans. ``People have very different opinions, and I
haven't seen anyone giving way too much,'' Ericson said. ``But it's
only been a week. Our debate over carrying concealed weapons has
been going on heavily for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress' decision last week to release Starr's report over the
Internet was seen as a defining moment for the global computer
network, a test of both its technical infrastructure and its
ability to play a critical role in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the ad hoc experiment in electronic democracy was
a success. The extraordinary run on government and news sites _ by
one count, 20 million Americans had read parts of the report online
within 48 hours of its release _ reflected a public thirst for
instant, unfiltered information driven in part by the technology
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling web of chips and fiber strained under its heaviest
load ever but did not snap.
</P>
<P>
   But as part one of the stampede for the Starr report abates and
Webmasters brace for part two _ the expected release of the
videotape on Monday _ the real test of the Internet as a tool of
citizenship lies in politics beyond scandal and salacious details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we'll see millions of people downloading
Social Security reform legislation, but we could,'' said Jonah
Seiger, co-founder of Mindshare Internet Campaigns
(www.mindshare.net), a political consulting firm based in
Washington. ``This event on the Internet is changing the way people
perceive their role in our political system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, invented as a communications network for
scientists and academics and financed by the Department of Defense,
has had plenty of other milestone moments in the last three years
as it evolved into a mass medium and a global platform for
everything from electronic commerce to dating.
</P>
<P>
   When Diana, Princess of Wales, died in a car crash last year,
people the world over convened in cyberspace to mourn. When NASA
published Pathfinder's first pictures from Mars last summer,
millions logged on for a glimpse of the red planet. And when the
stock market took a nosedive last month, traffic surged to record
highs at some financial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in an unfolding national political
crisis, the Internet has become a place to turn both for
information and debate.
</P>
<P>
   From the rumors of President Clinton's affair with an intern,
first reported in January on the Web site of the Internet gossip
columnist Matt Drudge, to the revelation last week by the online
magazine Salon of Rep.Henry Hyde's extramarital affair 30 years
ago, the Internet has played a central and controversial role in
informing the public about the presidential sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   And at least for the moment, the medium seems inseparable from
that particular message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers go out with the recycling,'' said Jonathan
Zittrain, executive director of the Berkman Center for Internet and
Society at Harvard University. ``Once it's on the Web digitally,
your sister-in-law can send you the best parts by e-mail. It forces
a level of engagement with the primary material there's no way you
would have had otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marilyn Lyon, 54, of Mission, Kan., who read Starr's report
on the Internet the day it appeared, there is another advantage.
``The news today is so loaded with emotion and opinion that it
irritates me.'' Ms. Lyon said. ``This way I can read it without
commercials popping in all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet online activists warn that surfing the Web for alternative
news sources is very different from using the Internet to forge
political consensus over an issue as fraught with emotion as the
impeachment of a president. Access to raw data may make for a more
informed electorate, but not necessarily a more united one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy means more than just reading a document,'' said
Steven Clift, chairman of Minnesota E-Democracy, the group that
runs the e-mail list that Ericson subscribes to. ``What will
determine how the Internet does is what happens in the next few
months as we move from the reading phase to the discussing phase.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some longtime ``netizens'' argue that many Americans have formed
an Internet political habit that will extend beyond the current
scandal _ and beyond the Internet. Others argue that to exploit the
democratic potential of the medium, legislators will have to do
more than just publish the occasional high-profile document online;
they may actually have to interact in cyberspace with their
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure would be nice to see Congress come out on the Net a
bit and talk to people about these things,'' said Clift. He noted
that the Web site where the House of Representatives published the
Starr report has no area for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in private e-mail, on Web site forums and chat rooms and
voluntary online polls, Americans found a way to type their
politics into the ether in record numbers all last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clift tried to direct his discussion list back to
its regular diet of Minnesota politics, with only limited success.
It was a phenomenon not unique to Minnesota: As of Friday morning,
subscribers to America Online had posted more than 400,000 messages
in the area set aside for discussion of the president's affair with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conversations over the dinner table are fleeting,'' said Barry
Schuler, America Online's president for interactive services.
``With message boards, what you have is a real-time
member-published journal. Especially with a topic where there's so
much dissonance, it helps to have an ongoing dialogue that's taking
shape over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, part of the Internet's appeal is that it resonates
with an American political ideal of unfiltered, unmediated
communication. Now, at a time when national political participation
has been at one of its lowest ebbs _ turnout in the November
election is expected to be sparser than ever _ there is some hope
among the politically and digitally inclined that expanded access
to the Internet will encourage a more activist electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find most interesting about all of this is the way in
which the Internet has changed our expectations,'' said Jeffrey
Eisenach, president of the conservative Progress and Freedom
Foundation. ``It makes people expect information about government
and everything else to be available instantly and at almost no
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recent events in Washington have been exploited for
commercial purposes as well. Already, marketers have used the Starr
report in mass e-mailings known as spam as a way to tempt consumers
to read advertising pitches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
