<SLUG> BC-SWEDEN-ELECT-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TO TELL, BUT IT SEEMS AS IF SWEDES ARE VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden _ Sweden this weekend is staging its
quadrennial political fete, a national election, and the exercise
is uneventful and unimpassioned _ indeed, barely detectable.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Swedes will go to the polls to choose the 349 members
of their parliament, the Riksdag, and a multitude of municipal
officials. The results will determine whether the Social Democratic
prime minister, Goran Persson, will remain in office or if Carl
Bildt of the Moderate Party, the one-time chief foreign peace envoy
to Bosnia, will succeed in returning to the prime minister's post,
which he occupied from 1991 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   More than 85 percent of the 6.7 million registered voters are
expected to cast ballots, and that is not the only evidence that
Swedes take their elections very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Swedish politics have their focus more on bread-and-butter
issues of domestic security and stability than on exotic foreign
concerns or the personal appeal of the candidates, and the
campaigns follow this purposeful pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Since the administrations that emerge are generally cooperative
groupings of parties, the competition between them is respectful,
aimed at leaving few wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The billboards and posters that festoon buildings and light
poles in other democratic societies during voting seasons are
limited here to tasteful size and presentation and are permitted
only in public spaces. One can travel blocks through Stockholm and
its suburbs without sighting a single slogan. No sound-truck
summonses to action disturb the city's streets.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies conducted by the leaders of the eight parties are
orderly and unobtrusive, with some crowds as sparse as 10 to 15
people. There are no surprises on the stump. The party
presentations across the country are controlled from headquarters,
and candidates resolutely keep to the message.
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one scandal: Gudrun Schyman, the candidate
of the formerly communist Left Party and an ardent opponent of
illegal jobs and exploitation of women workers, was found this week
to have paid a 16-year-old girl to clean her house without
declaring it.
</P>
<P>
   Ethical standards in Swedish public life are exacting. Mona
Sahlin, a former deputy prime minister, had to abandon her campaign
for the top job in 1995 when it was found that she had used her
government credit card for auto rentals and chocolates and diapers
for her children.
</P>
<P>
   No party is expected to win an outright majority. The outcome
will depend on whether the party getting the most votes can forge a
loose coalition with other parties. The eight Swedish parties break
down into a socialist group led by the Social Democrats and a
nonsocialist one led by the Moderates.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats, who have run Sweden for 57 of the last 66
years, promise to increase welfare spending and lower unemployment,
now at 7.3 percent, a high figure for Sweden, which had negligible
joblessness until this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats have been alert to opinion polls that
portray a longing among the aging population for a restoration of
cuts in the country's vast welfare structure, which now already
consumes 46 percent of the gross national product.
</P>
<P>
   The Moderates propose lower taxes _ the rate is now nearly 60
percent on middle-class incomes _ and a reduction in labor costs,
which now oblige employers to pay up to 41 percent of salaries into
social security and pension plans. They also back Sweden's entry
into the European single currency, a position that enjoys scant
public support from Swedes. ``I don't care whether it's popular or
not _ it's right,'' the party leader, Bildt, said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show the Social Democrats with 36.8 percent of
the vote, the Moderates with 24.8 percent and the remaining parties
with vote projections that would give the Social Democrats a sure
grip on power leading a minority government.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an effort to inject some color into the gray goings-on this
year, the Social Democrats appealed to the 385,000 expected new
voters with a promotional video portraying a young couple in bed
with titillating copy about the ``first time.'' The ad provoked
objections and was pulled.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the party's youth wing, Niklas Nordstrom, said the
film was an effort to present politics ``with a glint in the eye''
and he protested people's characterizing it as pornographic.
``Those who think it pornographic,'' he said, ``must have awfully
drab lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
