u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT &LR;      09-19 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LEGISLATIVE PRATFALLS, PAKISTANI PREMIER HEADS FOR U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif left for the
United States on Saturday and could not have picked a better time
for a getaway, with people here feeling he has just tried to
eliminate democracy from the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lies ahead for him this week _ and his schedule
includes meetings with President Clinton and Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee of India as well as a speech before the United
Nations _ the days should seem tranquil compared with those he just
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two of Sharif's pet measures ran into unruly
opposition in Parliament. One was a bill that gave the prime
minister more power, all in the name of Allah, and the other was a
permission slip to sign a nuclear test-ban treaty as a means to
solicit aid from Western donors. In both instances, however worthy
his intentions, Sharif's political antennae relayed all the wrong
signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't seem to ever think before he does something,'' said
Maleeha Lodhi, a newspaper editor and former envoy to the United
States. ``He makes sudden moves and then ends up governing by
retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's plans to amend the constitution were announced Aug. 28,
an unhappy time for him when the only distraction from rising
prices in this near-bankrupt nation was the recent U.S. missile
attack on suspected terrorist bases in neighboring Afghanistan.
Sharif was widely thought to be insufficiently irate about the
bombardment of an Islamic neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   He chose this difficult moment to propose that Islamic justice
be made the supreme law of the land, a tactical mix of politics and
religion with a long history here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must go down on our knees and bow before Allah,'' said
Sharif, a millionaire industrialist. By his reckoning, holy
practices were the only way to end the nation's many years of
``corruption, gratification and maladministration.''
</P>
<P>
   What he meant by full Islamic law was left vague, although he
did promise to protect individual and minority rights. He denied
trying to remold moderate and modern Pakistan into something like
the Afghanistan of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   Even a number of the devout questioned the need for the
proposal. The constitution already proclaims Pakistan an Islamic
state, subject to the religion's fundamental principles.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the true motive for Sharif's bill rested less in piety
than in politics. It would change some essential numbers: in
matters of Islam, a simple majority in both houses of Parliament _
rather than the current two-thirds _ would suffice to amend the
constitution. Also, the prime minister would be empowered to issue
decrees that further entrenched Islamic practices.
</P>
<P>
   What would then stop him, critics asked, from pushing bills
through the legislature in the name of Allah? Could he dissolve
Parliament if he considered its actions un-Islamic?
</P>
<P>
   If Sharif expected support from Pakistan's small but vocal
Islamic parties, he was mistaken. ``He is exploiting the Koran to
serve his own interests,'' said Amir-ul-Azeem of the
Jamaat-e-Islami. ``If the government really wants to enforce
Islamic law, the laws are now sufficient. The problem is in the
practices, not in the laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the opposition, Sharif expected his bill to pass last
week. Instead even members of his own majority party, the Muslim
League, rebelled. They, too, questioned his motives. Some
threatened to quit. And, after a stormy late-night meeting
Thursday, Sharif announced that he was in no great haste to see the
law passed.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to get comment from Sharif's Information Ministry as
well as his minister for religious affairs received no response.
</P>
<P>
   Similar political pratfalls accompanied Sharif's request for a
resolution of support on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. He
seems inclined to forswear any further nuclear tests, such as the
ones he ordered in May after India, Pakistan's great rival and
neighbor, had exploded its own nuclear devices. But first he wants
the United States to end economic sanctions imposed after the
blasts _ and to help Pakistan get an aid package that would, at
least temporarily, keep it from defaulting on $30 billion in
international debt.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prime minister does not need legislative approval
to sign the treaty, he asked for it anyway. He had reason to expect
little resistance. His chief political opponent, Benazir Bhutto,
head of the Pakistan People's Party, has urged him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   But many members of Parliament were reluctant to agree without
knowing the details of negotiations with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   When Sharif was not forthcoming, most opposition parties
boycotted a special session of Parliament. The resolution was
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   What might have been termed a laudable effort at building
consensus instead became ``another bit of confused theatrics,'' the
newspaper Dawn noted in an editorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
