</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAME-OLD-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS MOTIVATES TEAM WITH `SAME OLD JETS' WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the most hated phrase any of them knew: ``Same Old
Jets.'' You remember, those three little words that fans,
announcers and headline writers paraded out at one of those
customary New York Jets moments _ failure when victory was
expected, and bizarre failure, at that.
</P>
<P>
   And who brought up that phrase last week? It was none other than
Jets coach Bill Parcells plotting for Sunday's game against the
Indianapolis Colts. For he admits he sees this game as a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was last Sunday's mistake-filled loss to the Baltimore
Ravens official than Parcells addressed the team. He told the
players to be prepared this week for the ``Same Old Jets'' mantra
from the cynics.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not happened. And more significant for the Jets, they
do not believe it. Because losing, even on the 0-2 Jets, is not
what it used to be. But the players knew exactly what Parcells was
talking about, even though only 17 of them had been on the 1996
team that hit rock bottom, winning only once.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Byars was not even here last year, but the 34-year-old
fullback understood. He faced the Jets twice a year with the New
England Patriots, and before that with the Miami Dolphins, after a
long career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the ones in the other locker room helping make
them the Same Old Jets,'' Byars said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning and losing is all about attitude. This organization
hasn't had a lot of success the last 10, 15 years. Come Halloween,
you start thinking about next year's draft.''
</P>
<P>
   So Parcells will still not allow his crew to forget the sins of
the past, including the Jets' distinction as the only National
Football League club around since the 1970 merger that has not won
a division title.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps many Jets thought they had heard the last of the Jets'
original sins last year, when Parcells helped transform them into a
9-7 team. Along the way, he scolded them for their record of
blowing second-half leads, or their failure to win on the road, or
their failure to win at home, or their failure to win late in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   And after each lecture, they usually responded. They believed
they were not the Same Old Jets. How could they be, if they won by
coming from behind, or holding a lead, or playing on the road?
</P>
<P>
   They may be in crisis, and they may have spent dozens of hours
preparing for the Colts, but Parcells found time this past week to
look at 11 tapes of special-teams players from around the league.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I might do something about that next week.'' He is
always tinkering. There has not been one business-as-usual moment.
</P>
<P>
   Next week is a bye week, presumably giving him time to augment
the team, if he wants to. While Parcells talks about the ``crisis''
of an 0-2 start, and while he says there are times he thinks that
``we'll never win another game,'' he has enough confidence in his
and the club's ability to turn it around.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in a moment of candor, he did something most professional
coaches will never admit: he allowed himself to think of games down
the road. He suggested that if the Jets defeat the Colts on Sunday,
and then the Dolphins in two weeks, the Jets would not only be at
.500, they would have a 2-0 record in their division.
``Indianapolis would have three losses in the division and the
Dolphins would have at least one,'' he said. ``We wouldn't have
any.''
</P>
<P>
   A 2-2 start would actually make the Jets healthier than at the
same time last year, when they also started at 2-2 but lost both
times to division rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Same Old Jets coaches would not have allowed themselves to
publicly suggest such things. And Same Old Jets players would never
imagine them. ``Bill's like me. I thought of different scenarios,''
said Corwin Brown, one of the coach's pets on the special teams.
``What being 0-2 means to me is that I know we can't slip up.
You'll see. We won't slip up. We don't do that anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Aaron Glenn is responsible for one of the more
egregious mistakes in recent Jets history, getting suckered by Dan
Marino in 1994 in the famous faked spike incident. Glenn relaxed,
Marino threw a touchdown over him, and the Jets fell into a vortex
until rescued by Parcells three years later. Glenn knew exactly
what Parcells meant when he brought up the Same Old Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it crossed my mind even before he said it,'' Glenn
said. ``We don't want people to think of what we did last year as a
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the locker room is an indication, if the players are
being honest, then they truly have shaken off that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   If some of them do a little research, they will discover that
getting into the playoffs following an 0-2 start is far from
impossible. Two teams in the last five years have got to the Super
Bowl after starting 0-2 _ the 1993 Cowboys and the 1996 Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 seasons, 10 teams made it to the playoffs
following an 0-2 beginning, and two of them were coached by
Parcells. His 1994 Patriots also made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to call us the Same Old Patriots in New England,''
Byars said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
