<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FRANCO, OLD WARRIOR, HAS BRUTAL NIGHT FOR METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco knows the drill for the drive back to
Staten Island, with the yowls of the pack still baying in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Punch the FM dial on the car radio. Stay away from the sports
shows on the AM dial, the Mets fans calling for his pelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to listen to it,'' he said dryly, after giving up
three runs that produced a 7-6 loss to the Florida Marlins on
Friday night, a defeat that kept the Mets a game behind the Cubs in
their race for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What would Franco put on the radio going home?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what kind of music? These details are important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he brightened, adding, ``Maybe, `The sun comes up
tomorrow,'' referring to the signature song, ``Tomorrow,'' from the
musical ``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun did indeed come up again, and Franco would report to
Shea Stadium for another game with the Marlins late yesterday
afternoon. He would follow the ritual of relief pitchers _ hours of
tedium, moments of terror.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night, Franco had pitched 830 times in the major
leagues without appearing in a post-season game.
</P>
<P>
   Franco and his manager, Bobby Valentine, share a certain lack of
fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday, the manager has now filled out 1,937 lineup
cards from Texas, to Norfolk, Va., to Chiba, Japan, to Shea
Stadium, without finishing first, ever. Of course, these two
grizzled legionnaires could not afford to think about that as they
go about their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot,'' Franco said, talking about reaching the
playoffs. ``But you can't do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the last days of a baseball season _ a torture more
exquisite than any other sport because it happens daily _ one man
really does stand alone. Before the term closer was invented, Ralph
Branca strode in from the bullpen in 1951 to pitch to a man named
Bobby Thomson. Twenty-nine years later, Goose Gossage allowed a
girder-rattling, playoff-killing home run to George Brett.
</P>
<P>
   However, few relief pitchers have faced a jury of their vocal
hometown peers, eager to ream him out in the native patois, as
often as John Franco, originally from Brooklyn. He has seemed to
make the occasional gesture back to the fans, when leaving the
field after a brutal performance, but his hide is tough. He wants
to play in a post-season game, but will not consider himself some
Ernie Banks of the bullpen set. ``If I would retire tomorrow, it
would not be a thorn in my side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco remembers coming into September in good position with
Cincinnati in 1987, then coming to the Mets in 1990 and being in
first place in September before being swept by Pittsburgh. ``Last
year we were close to Florida, but every time we won, they won,''
Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco called the recent series in Houston, with its long games
and its clutch home runs and three Mets victories, ``the best
single series I've ever been involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned 38 on Thursday and showed up Friday with a birthday
cigar in hand, ready for the daily ritual. ``You've got to do the
same stuff,'' he said. ``You can't try to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Some closers need the solitude of the clubhouse to prepare
themselves for the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage used to sit in his cubicle and listen to Willie Nelson
on the headset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of guys who slept for the first few innings,''
Franco said, shaking his close-cropped, energetic head. ``I've got
to be on the bench, being around the guys. Then I go to the bullpen
for a while. Around the sixth inning I go in and get my arms and
legs stretched. Then I go back to the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The chorus at Shea was not universally delighted to see Franco
emerge Friday into a pristine ninth inning, the Mets ahead by two
runs. We really do not need to dwell on the bloop, the two
bleeders, the line drive, Lenny Harris overthrowing the cutoff man,
and the sacrifice fly that delivered the third run. Franco was left
with no victories, eight losses, and eight bungled saves to go with
37 official saves, a Met record, for which he received absolutely
no slack amid the boos and screams and imprecations from the
so-called faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they think _ or if they think,'' Valentine
said of the fans who boo Franco. ``But, they pay their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Very soon after the game, a large contingent of news media
camped in front of Franco's locker. The pitcher materialized _ hey,
not all ballplayers do _ and he talked about his dreadful outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do the job tonight,'' he said. ``The Cubs lost, we
lost, we could have tied them. Tonight I probably won't sleep
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Footnote: when I left the ball park around 11:30 p.m., two guys
in suits were standing near an expensive car outside the Diamond
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was the clubhouse, pretty quiet?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``About as quiet as you'd imagine,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's Franco?'' the other asked. ``What's he got to say about
this one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professional,'' I found myself saying. ``He's got a big
heart. He'll be back tomorrow.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     09-19 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A RADIO GET-TOGETHER, IN TWO LANGUAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a glorious home-run summer that owes almost as
much to Sammy Sosa's ebullient salsa as Mark McGwire's meaty
decency, Julio Pabon's eight-year campaign to ``raise the
visibility of positive Latino role models'' seems to be reaching a
peak.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Pabon's Latin Sports Ventures awarded its ninth
Latino most valuable player award to Pedro Martinez, the Cy Young
Award winner now with the Boston Red Sox. Pabon owns the Latin
Sports Clubhouse (Roberto Clemente is the reigning idol), a
sportswear and collectibles shop on East 149th Street in the South
Bronx. He is publishing a print magazine. And with Ramon Jimenez, a
lawyer and writer, he hosts what they think is the only bilingual
sports talk show in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign began in 1990 when Pabon was strolling through the
lobby of a Puerto Rican resort hotel and overheard a group of men
muttering the words ``discrimination'' and ``outrage.'' He wanted a
piece of that; in those days, Pabon was a political activist who
worked for the president of the New York City Council. He was
disappointed at first. The men, local sportswriters and
broadcasters, were merely angry that Robin Yount of the Milwaukee
Brewers had been picked over Ruben Sierra of the Texas Rangers as
the American League's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time his family vacation was over, Pabon was
convinced that he had found another way to put Latinos on the happy
news network. He rashly promised on Puerto Rican talk shows to
sponsor an award for Sierra, despite the outfielder's initial
sheepishness at making a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York, the Yankees refused to sanction a Stadium
ceremony; they offered the parking lot. But when the newly elected
mayor, David Dinkins, for whom Pabon had campaigned, said he would
show up at the parking lot, the Yankees opened their gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like in politics,'' Pabon said, ``there's a way to make the
underdog the top dog. Sammy may be the one to crack this thing.
He's bubbly, I think he loosened McGwire up. And he put it all in
perspective when he said that this is no pressure compared to
working two factory jobs in the Dominican Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanics consider themselves to be the most fanatic sports
fans in the country, particularly during beisbol season. The
growing importance of the Latino player in the major leagues (they
represent about one-third of the player population) is a source of
great pride. Pabon's other Latino most valuable player winners _
Bobby Bonilla, Julio Franco, Carlos Baerga, Moises Alou, Edgar
Martinez, and, twice, Juan Gonzalez _ could be the core of a
franchise. Such Yankees as Bernie Williams, Tino Martinez and
Mariano Rivera have kept Yankee Stadium, according to Jimenez,
``the St. Patrick's Cathedral of sports,'' despite George
Steinbrenner's attacks on its South Bronx neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But Hispanics have also complained that Latin ballplayers,
particularly darker-skinned ones (activists call this ``shadism'')
have rarely received as much journalistic and commercial attention
as comparable Anglo players.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, perhaps the most complete outfielder of his time,
certainly the greatest humanitarian in the game, was almost
willfully misinterpreted as a sullen prima donna; a case could be
made that a comparable white player would be lauded for his
``intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Race and language are clearly factors, but Pabon, now a
businessman, is less interested in root causes (``I don't want to
politicize this'') than in pushing product; there are some 20,000
trading cards with pictures of Latino ballplayers in his South
Bronx store. He says he bought the cards, in Puerto Rico, for only
$380 and has already sold one Rey Ordonez for $100 and an Alex
Rodriquez for $55. But he sees the stacks of cards as still
tantalizingly out of reach of what he estimates as a $300 billion
American Latino market.
</P>
<P>
   Can Sosa bring them together?
</P>
<P>
   That theme ran through a night two weeks ago that began in New
Rochelle, at the studios of WVOX (1460 AM), a pot-luck, mostly
music, community radio station, where Pabon, 46, and Jimenez, 50,
yammered in sportspeak about Sosa, the Yankees and the Mets. The
weekly show, Tuesday nights from 7 to 8, is called ``La Hora
Deportiva'' _ ``The Sports Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Pabon, who mostly speaks Spanish on the show, is a measured Mets
fan who says it is possible to love both New York teams. A frothing
Yankee fan, Jimenez, a Harvard Law graduate who was once a housing
court judge, plays the provocateur, shouting in English that ``you
can't love both God and the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   The partners have also gone into the stands at the Stadium to
recruit listeners and to interview them, and have addressed
mainstream issues from a Latin perspective. According to Pabon, two
years ago when they asked Roberto Alomar why he didn't act ``more
manly'' in his confrontation at home plate with John Hirschbeck, he
told them he would have hit the umpire instead of spitting on him
if his arms hadn't been held at the time.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's 62nd home run had a salsa flavor, too. We watched it
on the big screen at Giovanni's on the Grand Concourse around the
corner from the Latin Sports Clubhouse. When Sosa ran in from right
field to hug his rival, Pabon shouted: ``Can you believe this? When
have you ever seen this before?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a cliche,'' said Jimenez, almost apologetically,
``but sports does bring people together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
