<SLUG> BC-LASKER-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 GET LASKER AWARDS FOR CANCER-RELATED WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Wash., Calif., Texas, Canada, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six scientists who made discoveries dating to 1960
that identified the genetic basis of cancer and improved the
diagnosis and treatment of certain types of the disease will
receive this year's Albert Lasker awards.
</P>
<P>
   The recipients' findings and subsequent research have
established that alterations in genes are the initial step in
producing human cancer, and these discoveries are helping to shape
the design of future cancer therapies, the Albert and Mary Lasker
Foundation said in announcing the awards.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical research awards are going to three scientists: Dr.
Alfred Knudson Jr., a former president of the Fox Chase Cancer
Center in Philadelphia; Dr. Peter Nowell, a professor of pathology
at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, and Dr. Janet
Rowley of the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The three scientists receiving basic medical research awards are
Dr. Lee Hartwell, president of the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center and a geneticist at the University of Washington in Seattle;
Dr. Yoshio Masui of the University of Toronto, and Dr. Paul Nurse
of the Imperial Cancer Research Fund in London.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh scientist, Dr. Daniel Koshland Jr. of the University
of California at Berkeley, will receive a special achievement
award.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be made at a luncheon in New York City on
Friday. They are often called America's Nobels because 59 Lasker
recipients have gone on to receive Nobel Prizes in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The clinical researchers to be honored came up with the first
evidence that cancers develop from mutations in particular genes
and rearrangements in chromosomes, the bundles of hereditary
material.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, few scientists believed that cancer had a genetic
basis. But in that year, Nowell, working with the late Dr. David
Hungerford, shattered that widespread belief by showing such a link
to a form of leukemia. Nowell's team discovered that individuals
with chronic myelogenous leukemia had an abnormally small
chromosome in all their cancerous white blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Goldstein of the University of Texas Southwestern in
Dallas, a Nobel Prize winner who headed the selection jury for the
Lasker awards, said, ``The discovery provided the first clear
evidence that a specific genetic defect in a single chromosome can
give a malignant cell and its clonal descendants an advantage in
growth over other cells.'' The defective gene occurred in the 22nd
chromosome and it became known as the Philadelphia chromosome after
the city where Nowell worked.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Rowley used a new chemical staining technique
developed in Sweden to discover that the Philadelphia chromosome's
small size resulted from exchanges of pieces of genetic material. A
crucial piece of chromosome 22 broke off and moved to chromosome 9,
while a piece of chromosome 9 jumped to the breakpoint on the 22nd
chromosome. The finding provided clear evidence that leukemia could
result after a segment of a chromosome detached from the nearby
genes that controlled its behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley went on to identify 10 of the 70 such translocations that
are now known to cause cancers by producing a cancer-promoting gene
_ an oncogene _ or by inactivating a tumor-suppressing gene, which
suppresses cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Knudson published a theory based on complex mathematics
to explain why an eye cancer in children known as retinoblastoma
occurred in both hereditary and sporadic forms.
</P>
<P>
   Knudson theorized that two mutations that arose differently were
needed to produce the hereditary and sporadic forms of
retinoblastoma. In the inherited form, one mutation was present in
every body cell. The cancer developed only when eye cells underwent
a second mutation, or a second hit, that was triggered by exposures
to environmental toxins, dietary factors, radiation or at random in
the normal process of cell division. Children who did not inherit
the mutation had to suffer two such hits in the eye cells to
develop retinoblastoma.
</P>
<P>
   Later research has shown that a segment of chromosome 13 is
missing in some individuals with the eye cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Knudson's work paved the way for understanding a whole new
class of cancer-causing genes called tumor suppressors, such as the
two breast cancer genes, BRCA1 and BRCA2, and another that causes
colon cancer,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The basic science awards honor research beginning in the late
1960s that led to the discovery of the universal machinery that
tells cells when to start and stop growing. The machinery controls
the division of cells containing nuclei in such different forms of
life as yeast, frogs and humans. Cancer results from uncontrolled
growth of cells.
</P>
<P>
   From yeast needed to brew beer and bake bread, Hartwell and
Nurse identified genes that are crucial to controlling the
intricate program of instructions that determines how a cell grows,
rests and divides to replicate itself.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell discovered a gene needed to complete the several steps
of cell division. Nurse identified the first protein in humans that
plays a role analogous to that of proteins found in yeast.
</P>
<P>
   Masui discovered a protein known as MPF, for maturation
promoting factor, that controls cell division in fertilized frog
eggs. Scientists later found that MPF contained a protein similar
to those that Hartwell and Nurse discovered in yeast.
</P>
<P>
   Koshland, a former editor of the journal Science, is being
honored for his work on insights into the functioning of enzymes
and proteins, including the ways cells receive and respond to
external cues. Koshland also showed that bacteria have a
rudimentary memory that affects their response to their outside
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
