<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 NL PLAYOFF TEAMS ARE PACKED AND READY TO GO, BUT TO WHERE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three National League teams have made their reservations for the
playoffs; they just don't know where those reservations are for and
might not know until next weekend, the final one of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to go to the last day,'' said Bobby Cox, manager of
the Atlanta Braves, winner of seven successive division
championships. ``I believe that. We could play one of three teams.
We don't know if we're going to open at home or on the road. It
complicates things a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Two factors prevent the Braves, the Houston Astros and the San
Diego Padres from knowing where and whom they will play next week:
the identity of the wild-card team and the identity of the team
among the three of them that will have the best won-lost record
come next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first season that record counts for the playoffs. In
previous seasons, the sites of the series were pre-determined by
division on a rotating basis. In the first round, one team would
have the first two games of the three-of-five game series at home,
and the other would have the next three. The sites of the
four-of-seven league championship series would also be set by
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The only definite was the wild-card team, once the wild cards
became part of the playoffs in 1995, could not have the home-field
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But people inside and out of baseball complained that teams were
not being rewarded for their regular-season records. The Braves
last year won 17 more games than the Astros, but the Astros had
what was considered home-field advantage, though some people
questioned the value of that advantage, too.
</P>
<P>
   This season the division champion with the best won-lost record
gets home-field advantage in the form of the first two games of the
first series and the fifth, if necessary, at home. That goal has
kept the Braves, the Astros and the Padres playing hard beyond the
day they clinched their division championships. It has also kept
the post-season schedule completely up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker, for one, acknowledged that he has adopted a
different strategy from the one he would have used in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to kind of walk a fine line between trying to get
guys rested and trying to keep winning,'' the Houston manager said.
But he quickly added that he had no complaints about the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' he said about the quest for the best record. ``I
think it's the best thing there could be. I'd rather not be where
winning or losing doesn't matter. Guys might want to rest, and we
might lose our edge and the momentum that we've had in getting
where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in format has created yet another new race. First,
there is the race for first place in the three divisions in each
league. Then there is the race for the wild-card spots. Then there
is the race for the best record and home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win games,'' said Padres manager Bruce Bochy.
``It's added incentive. We do think it means something. We have
been caught a little bit between the health of the ball club and
winning games. It's a fine line. You don't want to drive guys into
the ground to win games; I think the priority is to be healthy when
you get to the playoffs. But if guys are healthy they're going to
be out there. We want to win as many games as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   This new race has undergone changes in the past few weeks. The
Braves entered September with the best record among the three
teams, leading the Padres by one game and the Astros by three. The
Padres caught the Braves Sept. 5 but dropped back again the next
day. In the few days after that, the Astros leapfrogged past the
Braves and the Padres and held ``first place'' for five days as the
Braves slumped slightly, losing six of seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the Braves recharged themselves, clinched
first place in the East Division and snatched first back from the
Astros, who lost three of four to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, the Braves led the Astros by one game
and the slumping Padres (with five losses in six games) by four
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 priority is getting the team ready for the
playoffs,'' Cox said, ``but we always try to win. We have two off
days this coming week so it's not like we have to sit down guys to
give them a breather.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he, too, would take advantage of off days this
week. ``I'm going to play the main lineup and try to win,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the first series in the Astrodome would be a huge
advantage for the Astros because, as Dierker said, Randy Johnson
has been almost unhittable there. The dominating left-hander would
pitch the first game and the fifth, if that game becomes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cox pointed out, none of the three teams would take
extraordinary measures to gain home-field advantage. ``I don't
think Houston is going to pitch Randy Johnson the last day of the
season to win that thing,'' the Braves' manager said.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres seem to have little chance to catch the Braves in
this new race. Should two teams tie with the best record, they
would not play a playoff game for home-field advantage in the
playoffs. Records in the season series between the teams would
determine the ``winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres would lose a tie with either of the other teams
because the Braves and the Astros each have a 5-4 record against
them. The Astros beat the Braves, 5-4.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A Wild-Card Twist
</P>
<P>
   The division champion with the best record will play the
wild-card team unless they are members of the same division. That
part of the playoff format will add intrigue to the final series of
the season for two of the division winners.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the wild card would presumably be easier than playing
one of the division champions. In addition, the team that plays the
wild card gets an extra day of rest because that series starts
Sept. 30 instead of Sept. 29, when the other series starts. Next
weekend the Braves play the Mets in Atlanta and the Astros play the
Cubs in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Houston manager Larry Dierker said he would rather the Cubs did
not win the wild-card slot but he added, ``I'd rather play at home
and I wouldn't care who we played than to open on the road. The big
incentive to me is get the home field.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, beating the Cubs next weekend would serve a dual
purpose, as would the Braves' beating the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes any difference,'' Bobby Cox of Atlanta
said when asked for his preference. ``You've got to play good to
get through it. The talk is nobody wants to face Johnson, but you
have to face him eventually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
