<SLUG> BC-SWISS-TRAFFIC-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS HILLS ARE ALIVE WITH SOUND OF DIESELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTDORF, Switzerland _ At 4:45 a.m. sharp, the Alpine stillness
is broken by the roar of dozens of trucks. Having parked outside
the St. Gotthard Tunnel to observe the Swiss ban on overnight truck
traffic, the drivers now start their engines, and the noise echoes
down the narrow Reuss Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes a stream of trucks descends from the Alps. Since
the tunnel was opened in 1980, the number of trucks has risen from
80 a day to more than 4,000. ``It used to be just cowbells,'' said
Brigitte Camenzind, a homemaker who lives nearby. ``Now it is
absolutely impossible to open the windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the tunnel was opened, cars and trucks had to use the St.
Gotthard Pass, which was closed in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up from the Camenzind house, one sees a gorgeous expanse
of snow-capped mountains. Looking down, one sees the valley sliced
by a rail line and a four-lane highway, a major European truck
route.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's location means that much of Europe's north-south
traffic must cross this mountainous terrain. But the Swiss have
been at loggerheads with neighbors about how best to accommodate
the traffic without spoiling the scenic valleys.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the pollution and noise of heavy trucks, the Swiss
have adopted various measures aimed at forcing freight traffic onto
trains. In 1994 the Swiss approved a ``polluters pay'' tax on heavy
trucks that was expected to raise about $1 billion a year to help
remedy trucking's effects and improve rail networks.
</P>
<P>
   The tax is the centerpiece of a plan to balance the transport
needs of the 15-member European Union with the environmental
concerns of the Swiss, and Swiss voters face a referendum on Sept.
27 to finally approve the tax, four years after they voted to adopt
it in principle.
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions of the truck problem are fully apparent in Uri
canton. A few miles south of Altdorf, its capital, the St. Gotthard
Tunnel spews traffic into one of Switzerland's narrowest valleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the morning, when the traffic starts, the bedroom shakes,''
said Lori Epp-Zgreggen.
</P>
<P>
   At first locals did not oppose the highway, she recalled. Now
her husband, Urban, a retired postal worker, finds the noise so
intrusive that he rarely goes outside. They bought their
centuries-old farmhouse decades ago, knowing the freeway was
coming. ``But then the noise doubled, then tripled, and went on,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In this mountain valley, prone to rock falls and avalanches, the
thundering noise from the motorway has been known to shake loose
rocks that could set off bigger landslides. Mountain forests and
the tingling air have suffered too, locals insist.
</P>
<P>
   Dire predictions in the 1980s that Alpine forests would vanish
have not come true, but the tops of trees have fewer needles, said
a forest ranger for the canton, Toni Zberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, you can smell the air and get the feeling
something is wrong here,'' observed Martin Furrer, a local farmer.
``I don't mind the noise but I am really worried about pollution of
the soil and the air.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No one has documented pollution's potential effects on Uri's
36,000 inhabitants. But Dr. Toni Moser, a local physician, said,
``It is well known that truck diesel fuel has particles that are
not good for health.''
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide study in 1996 calculated that each year truck
pollution causes acute bronchitis in 10,000 children and 7,000
adults and sharply increases suffering for asthmatics. Moser said
his patients, particularly children, suffer from bouts of eye, ear
and throat irritation, especially in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic trucking interests oppose the tax, arguing that it will
cause widespread job losses and add $350 a year in haulage charges
to each Swiss household's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Crippa, chief executive officer of the Swiss Road
Transport Association, also insists the tax will not achieve its
goal. Transit trucks, he argued, are only a small portion of
overall truck traffic and will not generate enough money for the
two new Alpine rail tunnels that are scheduled to be built by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland is in a bind. If it wants to join in European
economic activity, it must align key policies with the European
Union. It is currently the only European country, for example, that
bars trucks over 28 tons.
</P>
<P>
   When neighboring Austria _ a European Union member since 1995 _
eased its truck restrictions, it experienced a 30 percent increase
in truck traffic, mostly through the Brenner Pass to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland is trying to strike an accord with the European
Union that would gradually raise the allowable truck weight to 40
tons, with big trucks paying a $225 fee for each trip through
Switzerland. Germany, for one, feels that is too high.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss government ministers warn that an accord permitting larger
trucks _ which would benefit Swiss farmers by increasing access to
the European Union market _ is doomed without the tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1605EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
