<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: HOME-RUN SEESAW IS ROCKING ON I-94 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It's always better when there are two, especially
when each needs to do more because of the other. It was this way
with Ali and Frazier, with Palmer and Nicklaus, with Russell and
Chamberlain, with Evert and Navratilova, with Affirmed and Alydar.
And now it's this way with Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing, nobody's ever done,'' McGwire was saying
after hitting his 64th homer here Friday night. ``Wherever the
number lands, that's where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The number, of course, is the eventual record total of home runs
that one or the other will hit.
</P>
<P>
   The sentimental scenario would be for them to finish with the
same number, to share the record. But whenever Sosa has approached
McGwire's latest number, the Cardinals' slugger has jumped ahead
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no control over it,'' McGwire said when asked about why
he has responded so often to Sosa's challenge. ``I just try to get
a pitch to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   On this next-to-last weekend of the National League season, they
are swinging for homers some 90 miles apart along Interstate 94,
which moves up the Lake Michigan shore from Illinois into Wisconsin
_ McGwire here at County Stadium against the Milwaukee Brewers,
Sosa at Wrigley Field against the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Mark hits one tonight,'' Sosa had said Friday after
going 0 for 4 in a Cubs' afternoon loss. ``I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   About two hours later, McGwire did just that. When the great
home-run hitters are up, any stadium is always silent in
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   When they really connect in that silence, the sound is that of a
thunderclap. And on Friday night, McGwire really connected with the
left-hander Rafael Roque's fastball, smashing it into the
left-center-field bleachers, an estimated 417 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ability to concentrate and take his swing is his biggest
strength,'' said Tony La Russa, the Cardinals' manager. ``He can
shut everything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe McGwire isn't thinking about Sosa's challenge, but he
often has responded, and quickly. Only once has Sosa been ahead of
him. Back on Aug. 19 in Chicago, the Cubs' right fielder hit his
48th homer in the fifth inning, but in the eighth inning McGwire
hit his 48th and in the 10th inning he jumped ahead again with his
49th.
</P>
<P>
   Going into September, each had 55, but McGwire quickly hit his
56th and 57th in Florida. The next afternoon, Sosa hit his 56th in
Cincinnati, and that night McGwire hit his 58th and 59th in
Florida. When Sosa hit his 57th and then his 58th, McGwire hit his
60th, and then his memorable 61st and 62nd in St. Louis as Sosa
watched. But on a five-game road trip to Cincinnati and Houston,
McGwire did not hit any homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically didn't know where I was for a couple days,'' he
recalled, referring to what might have been a mental letdown in
Cincinnati after the 62nd homer that broke Roger Maris' record.
``And in Houston they pitched me very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Sosa hit four in three games last weekend in Chicago
to tie McGwire at 62, the Cardinals' first baseman whacked his
63rd. And after Sosa tied him again with his 63rd on Wednesday,
McGwire hit his 64th.
</P>
<P>
   Even though McGwire insisted he has ``no control'' over
responding to Sosa's latest total, he hinted that he does have
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about being focused,'' he said Friday night, about
hitting homers in general. ``Because your mind controls everything
you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever McGwire has known he needs another homer to stay ahead
o Sosa, he somehow has been able to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, of course, could get the last shot in this day-to-day duel
if the Cubs and Mets tie for the National League wild-card berth.
Their one-game playoff would be Sept. 28 at Shea Stadium. Any
homers Sosa were to hit in that game would count in his
regular-season total.
</P>
<P>
   But barring a wild-card playoff, that eventual number of homers
_ the hope here is that they tie at 67 _ will be determined this
week with McGwire and the Cardinals at home against Houston and
Montreal, while Sosa and the Cubs finish on the road in Milwaukee
and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything happens from here on, it is a gift for me,'' Sosa
was saying after Friday's game. ``I just want to go out there and
hit and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' last regular-season game Sunday at Wrigley Field will
be ``Sammy Sosa Day.'' Among the dignitaries will be Commissioner
Bud Selig and Leonard Coleman, the National League president,
neither of whom was there a week ago when Sosa hit his 61st and
62nd homers.
</P>
<P>
   Told that opinion polls showed that baseball fans thought he had
been slighted, Sosa had the perfect answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of myself,'' he said with a serious smile, ``because
I know that people care about me.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an instinctively nice man who spent Friday night in his
sprawling 55th-floor condominium with his mother and other family
visitors from the Dominican Republic as they celebrated the first
birthday of Michael, the youngest of the four children that he and
his wife, Sonia, have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most beautiful thing that God gave me,'' Sosa said, ``is
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday is Sosa's last chance to hit any more homers this
season at Wrigley Field, where he is considered a civic treasure
and is expected to hit homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was that easy,'' Sosa said, laughing, ``I'd have 100 by
now.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Mark McGwire. On second thought, he would probably have
101.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
