<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOOSING-COLLEGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE HUNT IS EARLIER AND TRICKIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Minn.)  (lb) 
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRONXVILLE, N.Y. _ Like the proverbial tourist who knows he's in
Belgium because it's Tuesday, Philip Lutgendorf scratched his head
to reconstruct where he and his daughter Claire had been the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday they flew from their Iowa home to Boston to interview at
Tufts. Wednesday they were in Providence at Brown. Thursday, it was
New Haven and Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Lutgendorfs came to Westchester County to tour the
snug Tudor campus of Sarah Lawrence College. Saturday would take
them to the high rises of New York University.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every school you meet the same people doing the same
pilgrimage,'' said Lutgendorf, a professor of Asian studies at the
University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, he and Claire were on tour here with Belinda
Jackson and her daughter Briana, and Karen Mandabach and her
daughter Marisa. All three families had NYU on their schedule
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This is high season for campus visits. While high school seniors
cram for another go at the Scholastic Assessment Test, parents are
booking trips like seasoned travel agents and refinancing mortgages
to get spare cash for the first year's tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But life has accelerated for baby boomers and their children.
Those visiting colleges as the leaves turn gold find themselves
behind the curve, especially if they're competing for the most
prestigious schools. There, up to half of each class is chosen
through early decision, which is advantageous for the college but
forces unsure youngsters to rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   With early decision the norm, campus visits have been pushed
back to July and August, replacing lazy days at the shore or one
last summer at camp. In some cases, candidates are visiting during
their junior year in high school, if not before.
</P>
<P>
   Thyra Briggs, dean of admissions at Sarah Lawrence, said
families from the Northeast are the most aggressive in pursuit of a
child's education, because competition for slots is most intense
here. For such families, the blood sport of college applications
now includes private counselors in addition to those the high
school provides, and $100-an-hour tutors for the SATs rather than
the plebeian courses offered by Kaplan or Princeton Review.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briggs gets calls from parents asking advice on ``summer
options.'' Would their children be disadvantaged by spending the
summer working rather than going to science enrichment camp? The
parents do not give their names lest their pushiness mean a black
mark on the youngster's file.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Lawrence employees are not immune to such machinations.
The offspring of professors or administrators often have a practice
interview here, even if they have no intention of applying. Only a
rube would have interview No. 1 at a school that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Homans, a Minneapolis cardiologist touring with his
son Charlie, confirmed that Midwesterners were more relaxed about
the process. ``Most farmers know you can't make it rain based on
where you went to college,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Homans is considering Harvard. But, by and large, the
artsy types interested in Sarah Lawrence, with its arts and
creative writing programs, are not as ferocious as Ivy League
contenders. ``I don't feel a huge amount of pressure,'' said
Charlie, who wants to study political science and jazz guitar, easy
to arrange at a school like this one, with no formal majors.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Friedman-Cohen, an aspiring dancer, is way behind her
friends at a Massachusetts prep school. Until this week, her
research had been confined to viewing California campuses from the
car window while on a family vacation. Zoe's mother asked lots of
probing questions of the spiky-haired tour guide at Sarah Lawrence,
but confided that she hoped her daughter would take a year off ``to
find herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutgendorf offered proof that the college frenzy is an American
fixation. His daughter spent her junior year as an exchange student
in France. Returning in midsummer, Claire was greeted by the same
question from everyone she bumped into, adults and teen-agers
alike: What college are you thinking about?
</P>
<P>
   ``She hadn't thought about it at all,'' Lutgendorf said. ``So
she got a little flustered. But now she's getting into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
