<P>
   WOMEN IN SPORTS/A SEVEN-PART AJC SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Photos and graphics to accompany Part One will be available
Monday
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE: OVERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-INSPORTS _ Twenty-five years ago, the Bobby Riggs-Billie
Jean King tennis match was one of the most talked-about sports
event -- but as a circus-like exhibition. From that farce, women's
sports have gotten serious. Now there are so many more
opportunities, with two pro basketball leagues, soccer and hockey
in the works and thousands of college scholarships available to
young women. They are getting on TV and in the print media. And
their stars are becoming role models as well as marketing tools.
Women's sports is at a crossroads, with several road bumps ahead.
This sweep story will look at how big women's sports has gotten,
what's driving it, who the big names are. Plenty of numbers, TV,
marketing. (Schultz/Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 117.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBARS
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-COMPARE _ Some expectations that women will catch up
someday to guys may be fueled by vast improvements but experts say
that, while the gap is closing, the guys won't have to worry about
women matching their performances. (Fish, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 36.
</P>
