<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 9/19/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON-- Sept. 19, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 9-19 -- It
is no secret that independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, left, and
Bill Clinton, have nothing but the highest disregard for each
other. Associates of both men say that their hatred - and these
friends say that hatred is not too strong a word - repeatedly
clouded their judgment and led to excesses on both sides that have
permanently tarnished both reputations (Stephen Crowley, left, and
Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- NY-QUEENS-JAZZ, 9-19 --
Legendary bassist Milt Hinton practices in his home in the
Addisleigh Park neighborhood of Queens. ``Colored people like us
were just looking for a decent place to live, a quiet place to
raise children,'' says Hinton, 88, recalling why he and his wife
moved to Queens. The Hinton's were not the only ones. Many jazz
musicians including Count Basie, Mercer Ellington, Lena Horne,
Billie Holiday and Illinois Jacquet also called Queens their home.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept, 19. 1998 -- BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN, 9-20 --
From left Julio Pabon and Ramon Jimenez on their bi-lingual sports
radio show ``La Hora Deportiva'' on WVOX. ``It's such a cliche,''
says Jimenez, a Harvard Law graduate who was once a housing court
judge,'' but sports does bring people together.'' (Susan Farley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WILDWOOD, N.J. -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- N.J.-CASINO-GAMBLE,
9-19 -- Fred Wager, the Mayor of Wildwood, N.J., on the site that
the city offered to Oklahoma's Delaware Indians to build a casino.
But now the Delawares have filed a lawsuit claiming the entire city
as their ancestral land. An Indian casino was not even Wager's
first choice. While he was still a city councilman, in 1994, he
opened talks with a race track operator who talked of bringing in
riverboat gambling and even, the mayor says, an airborne ``Zeppelin
casino.'' (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- RANGE-CATTLE-WAR-2, 9-19 --
``It's not only shocking and frustrating, it's a little
frightening,'' says Gaynell Park, standing near a splice in fencing
along the ranch she operates with her husband Norman just southwest
of Casper. The Park's Dumbell Ranch runs cattle on 100,000 acres,
40,000 of which are owned by the family. The rest is Bureau of Land
Management land leased for grazing. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ERVAY, Wyo. -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- RANGE-CATTLE-WAR-2, 9-19
-- Wyoming rancher, Robert Hendry and his son J.W. makes a routine
repair a section of fence on his family's 150,000 acre ranch west
of Casper. In June vandals calling themselves ``Islamic Jihad'' cut
miles of fence on ranches in the area. ``For their own safety, they
better lay off,'' Hendry warns of the people who cut his fences in
60 places. ``If the right group finds them, they might get shot.''
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ERVAY, Wyo. -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- RANGE-CATTLE-WAR-1, 9-19
-- Robert Hendry recently chased down a fugitive steer at his
150,000-acre spread. In mid-June, as the Wyoming Stock Growers
Association was meeting in Casper, 40 miles east of here, a carload
of vandals traveled 100 miles up and down dirt roads here, cutting
260 sections of barbed-wire fence. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ITAFRE, Nigeria -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- NIGERIA-OIL-2, 9-19
-- ``I understand these people,'' says Denny Sansom of Mobil Oil.
``They're poor. So they think we're all Howard Hughes.'' Sansom a
Texan who is Mobil's operations manager, spends 70 percent of his
time on ``community issues'' or keeping the people happy. ``One
Saturday morning alone I had $4.5 billion in claims - that's 45
percent of the total oil revenue of the country.'' (Roger Cohen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ITAFRE, Nigeria -- Sept. 19, 1998 -- NIGERIA-OIL-1, 9-19
-- With Mobil responsible for an oil spill, villagers like Thomas
Ebitu, chief of Itafre - which has seen no Nigerian Government aid
- are making enormous demands. Ebitu acknowledges that Mobil had
built his house and the school, but that is not enough. (Roger
Cohen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
