<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-COMPUTER-700&AMP;AD     09-19 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-COMPUTER-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS SAY AN EXTRA PERSON CAN HELP DEFUSE A CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before anyone knows what caused the fire that
brought down Swissair Flight 111 off Nova Scotia on Sept. 2,
aviation experts are debating whether the 229 people who died would
have had a better chance in a plane with a cockpit crew of three,
not two, and whether the airlines' continuing drive to economize
with automation and smaller crews has taken a toll on safety.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Halifax, Nova Scotia, hinted on Thursday that
the investigation was still far from complete. But a suspicion
persists among some experts that the computers that replaced the
flight engineer on the Swissair jet, a McDonnell Douglas MD-11,
left the captain and first officer without a colleague who could
troubleshoot or innovate in a crisis. Others, though, say the
difficulties faced by Flight 111 _ and its failure to descend
immediately _ made the size of the crew irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Flight engineers, who keep track of a jet's fuel flow, engine
performance and other details, are usually pilots-in-training. With
an engineer, ``you've got that pilot mind there, a second pair of
eyes, and he's not that busy, he's not wrestling with the
airplane,'' said Donald Tynan, a retired American Airlines pilot
who once confronted a smoke emergency in flight. On Nov. 15, 1979,
on a flight from Chicago to National Airport in Washington, a bomb
exploded in the baggage hold of his Boeing 727, filling the plane
with smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Tynan said he was able to assign the other pilot to
communications, fly the plane himself, and dispatch the flight
engineer to the passenger cabin to assess the situation. Experts
say a captain is much less likely to send a crew member outside the
cockpit if there are only two of them.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the engineer saw smoke filling the cabin and
called for an immediate landing; Tynan brought the plane down at
the nearest airport, Dulles, so fast that, by his own account, he
never got clearance from air traffic control, came too close to a
plane already on the runway, and broke a Federal Aviation
Administration speed limit on the way down. But 12 of his
passengers suffered smoke inhalation; any delay, he said, and it
would have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Another oft-cited example of an extra crew member saving the day
is the July 1989 crash of a United Airlines DC-10 near Sioux City,
Iowa, after an engine disintegrated in flight and severed the
hydraulic system. A training pilot who was traveling in the
passenger cabin came forward to join the three-member flight crew,
and figured out that some control could be obtained by varying the
speed of the two remaining engines. Without that novel technique _
which required an extra person to manipulate separately the two
throttles that are normally moved together _ experts believe that
everyone aboard would have died; in the end, 112 died and 184
survived.
</P>
<P>
   But three-person cockpits are a historical artifact now _ all
the manufacturers have eliminated the flight engineer. The Boeing
747 was one of the last holdouts, but the current version, the
747-400, flies with a crew of two.
</P>
<P>
   The flight engineer contributes to safety, said Dr. Earl Wiener,
an expert on human factors in aviation and an emeritus professor at
the department of management science at the University of Miami.
``He may be the most mechanically sophisticated of the three people
in the cockpit,'' Wiener said. And if there is any thought to
pulling up the hatch cover behind the captain's chair and looking
down into the electronics bay beneath the cockpit, where
investigators think the Swissair fire may have occurred, a
three-person crew is much more likely to do that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiener added that captains never find it easy to supervise
flight engineers, who sit over their right shoulders, and the
dynamics of three people working together are more difficult than
with two. ``There's a coordination problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert van der Linden, the Smithsonian's curator for air
transportation, said the flight engineer was doomed by the
airlines' demands for lower operating costs and the arrival of
computers that can do the work of engineers. ``A third man wouldn't
have made a whit of difference'' in the Swissair accident, he said.
``He'd have died, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Van der Linden and others say that what killed the pilots and
their passengers was not immediately recognizing the severity of
their problem. Investigators in Halifax said on Thursday that the
cockpit voice recorder showed the first mention of a smell of smoke
about 3 minutes before the crew sent its first distress call, or 13
minutes before communications ceased, and 19 minutes before the
crash, relatively short periods for a plane flying at an altitude
of six miles, over water.
</P>
<P>
   The smell of smoke in airplanes is not rare, pilots say, and
they often hesitate to begin descent, for fear of crying wolf.
Tynan, who broke rules and saved his passengers and plane, had the
advantage of hearing the bomb explode and knowing quickly that
there was a problem; more often, smoke is slowly recognized and
turns out to be minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the last time, it was a Pop-Tart,'' said another MD-11
pilot, who spoke on condition his name not be used. Someone had
left it in a galley oven too long, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another MD-11 pilot said that the computers that effectively
replaced the flight engineer were very useful in an emergency
landing. The fuel dump system, for example, automatically sets
itself to get the plane down to maximum landing weight; the pilot
has only to push one button, one time. And no matter what the
weight, the computers tell the pilots what the minimum safe air
speed is, automatically taking into account flap position and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   A NASA expert on how pilots use computerized cockpits, Kevin
Corker, noted, however, that the flight engineer had been replaced
by several smart computers. ``There are more than three intelligent
entities on the flight deck now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, in Prescott, Ariz.,
William Waldock, the associate director of the university's Center
for Aerospace Safety Education, said that no matter how many people
had been in the Swissair 111 cockpit, the problem was the ambiguity
of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either one of them thought they had that serious
a problem,'' he said. ``By the time it got upgraded to a point
where the captain's beginning to think he's got a real emergency,
probably it was past the point where a third person would have made
a difference,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
