<HEADLINE>
YOUNG DEVILS GET A LOOK IN NIEDERMAYER'S ABSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ The longer Scott Niedermayer continues to
demand a $4 million-a-year contract to join the Devils, the better
the chances are for several promising players to take a spot on the
defense that was second-best in the National Hockey League last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer's absence will enable coach Robbie Ftorek to get a
closer look at his promising young defensemen starting with
Sunday's exhibition opener against the Montreal Canadiens at
Albany, N.Y., home of the Devils' top affiliate in the minor
leagues, the River Rats of the American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek has reminded reporters every day since the opening of
training camp here last Sunday that returning veterans will have to
lose their jobs to younger players by a wide margin, or a knockout,
as the first-year coach says. But without Niedermayer, someone will
have to be added to the list of at least seven defensemen the
Devils are expected to open the season with.
</P>
<P>
   The captain Scott Stevens, Ken Daneyko, Lyle Odelein and Sheldon
Souray will take the first four spots. If Niedermayer returns,
Souray, who was a rookie last season, will be relegated to the
fifth spot.
</P>
<P>
   The other three of four spots will be contested by Brad
Bombardir, Kevin Dean, Colin White, Geordie Kinnear, Vlastimil
Kroupa and Ken Sutton. Bombardir and Dean appear to have the edge
because they each played more than 40 games last season, but White
could jump two or three notches on the depth chart with solid
performances in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek will not single out anyone in training camp, but he has
said that the 20-year-old White has been ``progressing well _ that
he has sacrificed short term for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   White was sent back to his junior team when he was drafted 49th
overall two years ago. He was sent to Albany last season, when he
played 76 games in the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm ready; I've got to play like I'm ready for this
league,'' White said after a recent practice. ``I can't make
decisions for anybody. All I can do is open their eyes that I can
play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek will take a good look at White in the exhibition opener.
Ftorek had White paired with Odelein in Saturday's practice, and he
is expected to use him with Odelein against Montreal. The other
defensive pairings on Sunday will be Daneyko with Bombardir and
Souray with Kinnear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Niedermayer here,'' White said, ``it's an opportunity
for some of us guys to show what we can do. But the thing is that
this team needs Niedermayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Devils and their president and general
manager, Lou Lamoriello _ who is holding the line at a $2.5 million
offer in his negotiations with Niedermayer and his agent, Don
Meehan _ none of the other defensemen come close to having
Niedermayer's offensive attributes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
