<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO ACCUSES OPPONENT OF NAME-CALLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. Alfonse D'Amato assailed his Democratic
opponent, Charles Schumer, on Saturday for ``character
assassination,'' asserting that he was running a campaign based on
personal attacks, and predicting that it would fail by Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, in his first return to New York state since Schumer won
the Democratic nomination, complained that Schumer, in his
advertisements and public statements, had engaged in
``name-calling'' unbecoming a candidate for the U.S. Senate. The
two candidates exchanged harsh attacks last week, though on
Saturday the senator mentioned only Schumer's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is unfortunate that he has gotten into the
character assassination by the use of the pejoratives and the very
personal,'' D'Amato said as he waited at Fifth Avenue and 63rd
Street to begin the uptown march of the German-American Steuben Day
parade.
</P>
<P>
   And then, reminding his listeners of his opponent in 1992, the
senator said of Schumer: ``He said he was going to run on issues,
but I see that he's following the same pattern _ unnecessarily _
that Bob Abrams did in personalizing it with a whole series of
statements: sleaze, liar, untrustworthy. We have legitimate issues
that we differ on and I would hope that we would concentrate on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   With his remarks on Saturday, the Republican senator took
advantage of a waiting New York City press corps to assume what has
been a stance he had some success using against Abrams in 1992:
presenting himself as a victim of unfair attacks, while
simultaneously pummeling his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato made his remarks after Schumer broadcast a series of
television advertisements that contended that the senator had
distorted Schumer's record in Congress. ``D'Amato _ too many lies
for too long,'' the advertisements say. They appeared within hours
of D'Amato's commercial attacking Schumer as a ``New York City
liberal who proves it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign dismissed D'Amato's complaints as unfounded.
``Al D'Amato has spent his entire career misrepresenting his
extremist record and that of his opponents,'' said Schumer's
campaign manager, Josh Isay. ``We're not going to let him get away
with it anymore. For someone who has run slash-and-burn,
slice-and-dice campaigns for three decades, Al D'Amato has an
awfully thin skin.''
</P>
<P>
   In offering his harsh assessment of Schumer's candidacy, D'Amato
referred to a number of things that Schumer had said about the
senator since winning the nomination, asserting that Schumer had
crossed the line between legitimate political discourse and unfair
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you begin to personalize attacks by saying people are
untrustworthy or calling them liars or sleaze, that's unacceptable,
and after all, he's running for the United States Senate,'' D'Amato
said. ``If that is the manner in which he's going to conduct
himself, I think he'll have the same result as his predecessor.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   D'Amato said he had acted appropriately in calling Schumer
liberal at every opportunity, thereby making his political ideology
one of the two major themes of his criticism. But D'Amato seemed
flummoxed Saturday when asked about the second large theme of his
criticism: repeatedly reminding voters that Schumer lives in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know _ I'm trying to ask you, to what ad do you refer
to?'' D'Amato asked. The advertisement D'Amato put on the air last
week describes Schumer as a ``New York City liberal congressman''
and his campaign statements routinely refer to Schumer as a
``Brooklyn liberal congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said his campaign was not trying to stoke upstate
animosity toward New York City. ``I was born in Brooklyn,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me say something to you,'' D'Amato continued. ``There
are more than just people who live in any one community and I think
he ought to understand that this is a whole state and we should be
proud of representing the entire state. And I don't think the
congressman really understands this.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said he was unable to discuss any strategic
considerations in stressing that Schumer was from Brooklyn. ``I
can't get into the exact why that you make it exactly this way,''
D'Amato said of his ad. ``But it's an accurate description.''
</P>
<P>
   Isay declined comment on D'Amato's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato spent much of Saturday discussing Schumer's record,
pointing to votes on a number of issues _ in particular, against
some measures to restrict welfare, in favor of some increases in
taxes _ as he tried to portray Schumer as ideologically out of
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has voted as the classic liberal for more big government,''
D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, D'Amato complained about the way Schumer had
attacked him, which he described as mud-slinging. ``It's
unfortunate that the congressman has seen fit to engage in a series
of name-calling,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
