<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SAY DEFENDANT DESERVES EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the Brooklyn neighborhood where he lived, Jermaine
Page called himself the ``main man,'' prosecutors say. They are
happy to call him that, though not for a reason that makes Page
happy.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors say that Page, 24, was one of two armed robbers
who shot Marvin McIntosh while stealing his jewelry on a street in
the East New York section of Brooklyn in May 1996. Page, they say,
was the main assailant because his bullets were the ones that
killed the 28-year-old victim.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, as arguments and testimony began last week in
Page's trial in state Supreme Court in Brooklyn, prosecutors
maintained that he should be convicted of first-degree murder and
should be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Page's lawyers responded that the person who fired the fatal
shots was the one the prosecutors called the second gunman _ a
teen-ager to be tried later for second-degree murder, which is not
punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the defense lawyers told the jury, there had been no
robbery, but rather a dispute over a dice game that ended with the
teen-ager's shooting and killing McIntosh. The defense also
suggested that Page did not fire any shots at all in the incident,
which occurred not far from the building where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   And so the issues were joined in New York City's second
death-penalty trial since capital punishment was revived in the
state three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution clearly wanted to rivet the attention of the
jury immediately, because its opening witness was Latisha Mitchell,
McIntosh's 12-year-old goddaughter, who was with him when he was
gunned down two and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh, who lived in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, and worked for a
private mail-delivery service, was slain outside a girlfriend's
apartment, prosecutors said, after he refused to hand over some
conspicuous jewelry he was wearing: a gold chain and a pendant
shaped like a bulldog's head, with rubies for eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Latisha began crying as she told the jury in Justice Priscilla
Hall's courtroom that Page and a second man had approached
McIntosh. Under questioning by an assistant district attorney,
Joseph Alexis, Latisha said that the second man demanded what she
called ``the bulldog gold chain'' and that McIntosh _ whom she
referred to by his middle name, Naquan _ refused and began fighting
with that man.
</P>
<P>
   She then nodded toward the defense table, where Page, a man with
closely cropped hair and a slight goatee, regarded her without
expression. ``Him _ the man over there _ took Naquan and turned him
around,'' she said. ``He stepped back about 3 feet and started
shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not remember the other man firing or even
having a gun. Prosecutors have identified him as the teen-ager
awaiting trial _ Darryl Gilmore, 15 at the time of the killing and
17 now. He has pleaded not guilty to the second-degree murder
charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, a defense lawyer, Gary Villanueva,
sought to cast doubt on the credibility of Latisha's testimony by
establishing that shortly after the killing she told investigators
and a grand jury that both men had shot McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   When the Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, announced in
late 1996 that he would pursue the death penalty against Page, he
did not say why he had chosen to make a capital case out of this
killing, other than to say he had reviewed the ``aggravating and
mitigating factors'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But in his opening statement to the jury last week, a deputy
district attorney, Barry Schreiber, hinted at a possible reason
when he termed McIntosh's killing an execution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the state's first capital trial under the 1995 death-penalty
law, also in Brooklyn, the defendant, Darrel Harris, was accused of
the execution-style killings of three people in a robbery. In June,
a jury convicted him of first-degree murder and sentenced him to
death, rejecting the alternative of life in prison without the
possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as Page's jury heard the first witnesses, at least
one spectator made it clear that she was already convinced that he
deserved the ultimate sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should get the chair,'' said Martha Reese, 71,
McIntosh's grandmother. ``He didn't give my child a chance,'' she
added of her grandson, whom she had reared from age 2.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ms. Reese's wish is fulfilled, it will not be through the
electric chair, which was last used in the state in 1963. The
state's present method is lethal injection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
