<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-MCGWIRE-520     09-19 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-MCGWIRE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ROOKIE MAKES MISTAKE AND McGWIRE DOESN'T  
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This is a rewritten and expanded version of
BBN-CARDS-BREWERS, which moved Friday night.)  
(nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ For the most part, the Milwaukee Brewers had been
smart this season when facing Mark McGwire. They had pitched him
low, high, inside, outside, whatever was necessary to avoid being
bashed.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy had been as successful as any against McGwire, the
St. Louis Cardinals' barrel-armed slugger, allowing him only two
home runs in eight games. But on Friday night, the rookie Rafael
Roque scrapped his team's plan and challenged McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a blast into the left-center-field bleachers,
estimated at 417 feet, that drove the crowd of 48,194 at Milwaukee
County Stadium into a frenzy, even though the two-run shot tied the
score at 2-2 and helped the visiting Cardinals win, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Amid flashing cameras and screaming fans, Roque's fastball
rocketed off McGwire's bat, driving in Ray Lankford and increasing
McGwire's record-breaking season home run total to 64. It also
broke the deadlock that Chicago's Sammy Sosa had forged with his
63rd home run, a grand slam, on Wednesday night in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGwire's 451st career home run, and moved him to within
one of Carl Yastrzemski for 20th place on the career list.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who of late had been the hotter half of the
record-breaking duo, was 0 for 4 Friday at Wrigley Field in the
Cubs' 6-4 loss to Cincinnati and remained at 63.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, McGwire had not homered in 18 at-bats since he
had surpassed Roger Maris' record of 61 on Sept. 8. Now, two homers
in four games had given him back the lead in a race in which he
trailed only once this season, and then for less than a game.
</P>
<P>
   While all of America, and much of the world, is keeping tabs on
the race between McGwire and Sosa, McGwire insisted that it meant
little to him _ that it would not bother him if Sosa had more
homers when the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a big deal who finishes on top, but if you ask
Sammy or I, I don't think it really matters,'' McGwire said. ``What
we've done in the game of baseball nobody has ever done, so I don't
think it matters where we end up. We're both rooting for each
other, so where the numbers end up, that's where it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Roque walked McGwire on six pitches in the first inning and
appeared headed that way in the fourth. It did not seem the Brewers
would give McGwire much to hit. But with the count at 3-1, the
rookie left-hander threw a fastball over the outside of the plate,
and McGwire got all of it. There was no doubt the ball would land
at least 400 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch,'' McGwire said. ``It crossed the plate
over the corner and I just drove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason King, a 23-year-old waiter from Madison, Wis., dived from
the stands and into an exit well to retrieve the ball. He was at
the park in place of his brother, Dave Wilshire, who took care of
King's daughter so that King could come to the game. King said he
did not know what he would do with the ball eventually, but he
would take it home for now to show to his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to hold it in his hands because this is just as
much his as it is mine,'' King told The Associated Press.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The crowd almost got another treat in the fifth inning. After
throwing two balls high, reliever David Weathers put one in
McGwire's power zone. With one of his mighty cuts, McGwire drove
the ball high and into the upper deck, just 15 feet to the left of
the left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Weathers' next pitch looked like No. 65 as well,
but McGwire's drive to right-center was caught by right fielder
Jeromy Burnitz at the front of the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire walked in the first inning and fouled out to the catcher
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire will have two more games to thrill Milwaukee's fans,
facing the Brewers Saturday night and Sunday. Ticket sales for
those games, plus Friday night's attendance, add up to more than
154,000. Unless a game is rained out, there will be a new stadium
record for a three-game series, eclipsing the mark of 153,974 set
against Boston in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish every player could feel what I'm feeling,'' McGwire
said. ``There's nothing better than playing a baseball game in
front of a full house. A lot of fans all over America are coming
out specifically to watch me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire got an extra boost from the crowd because Green Bay
Packers' All-Pro quarterback Brett Favre was in attendance and took
batting practice with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you get to play in front of other athletes from other
sports, it's nice to do well,'' McGwire said. ``He admires the way
I go at it, and I admire the way he goes at it.''
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire is done taking his cuts at Milwaukee pitching, it
will be Sosa's turn. The Cubs play the Brewers on Tuesday and
Wednesday, and it's a safe bet that Sosa will put one, two or three
balls over the fences. In his 10 games this season against the
Brewers, he has homered 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire admitted that he was not himself during his recent
homerless stretch. ``There was so much built up to do what I did
that I didn't know where I was for a couple of days,'' he said.
``Then we went to Houston and they pitched me well. Then we went
home and I started to feel better. Everything goes in cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning that the Brewers had better watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McGwire said he would love it if he and Sosa
finished the race in a dead heat, and Saturday he implied that Sosa
had received less attention from the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to you,'' McGwire said to reporters. ``I would give
him as much publicity as I've gotten and I encourage you to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
