<SLUG> BC-NY-U.N.-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL STREETS NEAR U.N. TO BE CLOSED OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In addition to several dozen heads of state, this
year's annual debate at the U.N. General Assembly will bring even
tighter security _ and more detours for drivers and bus riders _
than usual in the wake of the American Embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, a weeklong marathon of speeches by world leaders,
begins Monday with President Clinton's address.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, police began closing off streets around the United
Nations. First Avenue between 42nd and 46th Streets is closed until
Sept. 28, as is a northbound lane on Second Avenue between 42nd and
50th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   During the Assembly's hours, the blocks between First and Second
Avenues from 42nd to 47th Streets will also be closed until Sept.
28, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that the 42nd Street exit off the
Franklin D. Roosevelt Drive would also be closed during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers include President Nelson Mandela of South Africa;
the president of Iran, Mohammad Khatami, who is making his first
trip to New York, and Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, the interim
president of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that the
security precautions were actually lighter than they were for the
50th anniversary of the United Nations in 1995, and urged New
Yorkers to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does create a burden for our citizens,'' Giuliani said,
``but there are tremendous benefits we get from being capital of
the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-MUNICIPAL-SERVICES     09-19 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MUNICIPAL-SERVICES-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEL OF GOVERNOR WHITMAN'S CONSOLIDATION PLAN IN AN UNLIKELY
CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST NEW YORK, N.J. _ In this densely populated town in northern
Hudson County, where municipalities bunch up like boxcars in a
train wreck, Dan McEldowney would often sit outside Engine Company
No. 1, where he works, and watch the fire trucks from adjacent
North Bergen barreling by toward fires on that town's eastern end.
</P>
<P>
   That North Bergen's firefighters have to go through West New
York to get to sections of their own town on the Hudson River has
long been a fact of life here. But it has never made much sense to
McEldowney and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy, because we would be closer to some of those
fires than they were,'' he said, shaking his head. ``We would just
wave at them as they went past.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the encouragement of Gov. Christie Whitman's
administration, the mayors of four tightly packed municipalities in
the area have embraced a plan to consolidate fire services, to save
money and to lower or at least stabilize property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, formally introduced last Wednesday at the town council
meetings of West New York, Union City, Weehawken and North Bergen,
would cut nearly $5 million from the towns' fire service budgets,
which now total $25 million. The job now being done by 347
firefighters would eventually be done by 302, and the area's 19
firehouses and 59 pieces of equipment would eventually decrease as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has made the area the poster child of Mrs.
Whitman's campaign to encourage local governments to consolidate
services, which she says could result in a savings of about $1.2
billion and lower local property taxes statewide.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the report by her Property Tax Commission, she
rejected shifting local costs to the state, as many had urged, and
instead offered a package of $35 million in incentives for local
and regional consolidations. And at a news conference in Trenton,
she singled out Mayor Albio Sires of West New York and his fellow
mayors for their willingness to take such steps.
</P>
<P>
   In this, the most densely populated section of the nation's most
densely populated state, consolidation would seem to fly in the
face of New Jersey's history of home rule. Addition, and not
subtraction, has been the predominant municipal math _ there are
566 municipalities, 611 school districts and more than 400 local
authorities in the state's 21 counties. If this has succeeded in
forging distinct local identities, it has also contributed to the
state's having the nation's highest average local property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And that northern Hudson County, of all places, should be
blazing a trail toward consolidation has prompted bemusement among
many in the state for other reasons. The area's storied past has
included such colorful characters as the political boss Frank
Hague, whose machinations made area politics as byzantine as its
boundary lines are serpentine. Patronage, turf wars and political
corruption have been the hallmark here, not government efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody plays the game, but we get the name,'' said Union
City's mayor, Rudy Garcia, lamenting the area's reputation for
corruption. ``I wasn't even born when that stuff was going on, and
the truth is that we in this area have been progressive for a long
time because our relatively low incomes have challenged us to find
savings without increasing taxes. The real question to me is, why
isn't it happening in places other than northern Hudson?''
</P>
<P>
   The desire to personalize services helps explain why
fragmentation has been more common than consolidation, many local
officials said. And once in office, those same officials have a
vested interest in maintaining their ability to control, target and
get credit for services.
</P>
<P>
   James McGreevey, the Democratic mayor of Woodbridge Township in
Middlesex County, said that while consolidation was ``good public
policy,'' few had been able to square the political risks with the
fiscal benefits. The governor's incentives had done little to alter
that situation he said, adding: ``Municipalities are not going to
rush to merge themselves out of existence. Survival is still the
prime motivation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Cannon, the mayor of Old Bridge Township in Middlesex
County and chairman of the Property Tax Commission, said one
problem was that people tended to see consolidation as synonymous
with disappearing. That need not be the case, and she predicted
that economies from consolidation would wind up looking different
all over the state. As an example, she pointed to her town, where
the local school district and the various public works and fire
departments had consolidated their vehicle fuel-purchase operations
in a town-built fuel dump.
</P>
<P>
   Many communities consolidate their recycling programs at the
county level, but that is the outgrowth of another broader
consolidation in the state that left a bad taste in the mouths of
many localities. New Jersey's nearly 20-year-old program of waste
flow control, which established county entities to control waste
disposal of all of their towns, was found unconstitutional by
federal courts, but for years many local officials viewed this
consolidation as both costly and inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   John Rooney, the mayor of Northvale in Bergen County and a
critic of that system, said that unlike flow control, the
consolidations encouraged under the governor's proposals were
voluntary and mirrored things that local governments have been
asking the state to help promote.
</P>
<P>
   Sires of West New York said that he and the other mayors had few
misgivings about consolidating their fire departments. Weehawken,
West New York, North Bergen and Union City are scheduled to vote
Sept. 30 on the plan, which would establish a single department
called the North Hudson Regional Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   More than 165,000 people live in the 80-by-30 block area of the
four municipalities. The idea of consolidation had been studied and
restudied since the '60s, but it was not until a new generation of
mayors, all in their 40s, began to replace longtime incumbents that
the process took hold. The other two mayors are Richard Turner of
Weehawken and Nicholas Sacco of North Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opposition of Sires' predecessor, Anthony DeFino, a
24-year incumbent, that was the last barrier to fall away when
Sires succeeded him three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the legacy of the past dies hard, and in proposing a
five-member commission to run the fire services, the mayors put in
a requirement that there be a ``super majority'' of four-to-one to
approve most actions. It was a recognition, Sires said, that
politics can still be ``hardball,'' and is often a ``team sport''
with coalitions arrayed against a single opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in pressing the plan, the mayors were determined not to
alienate the politically powerful firefighters unions _ all eight
of them among the four towns _ by promising to use attrition,
retirements and buyouts in cutting personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The result, said Joseph McLean, a 17-year veteran of the West
New York Fire Department, is that the unions like the plan and
younger members of the various departments see it as opening up
chances for advancement that were few in the smaller units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, it means greater safety because under the plan there
will be twice as many firefighters responding to a fire than there
are now,'' he said. ``They aren't forcing something on anybody,
because it makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the incentives announced by Mrs. Whitman was one to
promote consolidations by giving localities state funds to assist
in offering early retirement and buyout packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been heading in that direction,'' Sires said, ``but
the governor's plan for early retirement incentives is a real boost
for what we are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
