<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RIPKEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES WILL DISCUSS ENDING RIPKEN'S STREAK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Baltimore Orioles are on the verge of
elimination, and after a extremely disappointing season, they are
headed for a period of upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Roberto Alomar and first baseman Rafael Palmeiro
will become free agents after this year, and owner Peter Angelos
must select a new general manager to replace Pat Gillick, who is
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But Orioles Manager Ray Miller said the team will put off a
decision on how and when to end Cal Ripken Jr.'s consecutive-game
streak, which has reached 2,632. Ripken, 38, is batting .275 with
14 home runs and 61 RBIs, giving the Orioles the worst third-base
run production in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   There has been sentiment in the organization for some time to
end Ripken's streak, rest him more often and incorporate other
players.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the streak would be discussed during the off season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like that to be his option,'' Miller said. ``If it's
the right thing to do'' _ meaning ending the streak _ ``it will be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles recently promoted Willis Otanez, a Class AAA third
baseman, after he had a great minor league season. But because
Ripken remains the everyday third baseman, Otanez was shifted to
right field, a position he has rarely played, and he broke his
wrist trying to make a diving catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles also promoted a young power-hitting third baseman,
Ryan Minor, for the final weeks of the season, but on Friday, Minor
started at first base, instead of third, because of Ripken's
streak.
</P>
<P>
   But maintaining Ripken's streak, and maintaining Ripken's status
as an icon, would also maintain his status as financial asset for
the club. Ripken, too, has financial reasons to continue the
streak, because his marketability is as an ironman who plays every
single game.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the club's front office said the issue of the streak
would most likely be discussed during the last week; if the Orioles
or Ripken wanted to end it without fanfare, they could do so in the
final days, when the team is playing on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
