<SLUG> BC-NY-BOOK-THIEVES-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ARRESTS, A DENOUEMENT IN THE MYSTERY OF THE PURLOINED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, people in the book industry have assumed
that the best sellers available from New York City street vendors
at bargain prices were stolen. But publishers and booksellers said
they had no idea how these books made their way onto the sidewalk
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Now the mystery is beginning to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   One publisher recently determined that books were disappearing
from its TriBeCa warehouse, apparently with the help of two
warehouse workers who have since been fired. When that avenue was
closed off, the police said, a longtime employee of the publisher
was offered the chance to make fast money by stealing books from
his employer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he told his bosses about the overture, and the police
stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting sting operation led to the arrest on Sept. 11 of
two men on charges of receiving $35,000 worth of stolen Zagat
Survey restaurant guides.
</P>
<P>
   New York City police officials said on Friday that the arrests
were part of a citywide investigation into the wholesale illegal
distribution of books.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests also represented the culmination of several months
of efforts by Tim and Nina Zagat, co-publishers of the restaurant
guides, to end an escalating problem that they estimate has cost
them $100,000 in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Zagats said they first learned from a reporter about six
months ago that heavily discounted copies of their guides were
turning up on sidewalk tables throughout Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, they said, owners of some of the stores that
carry the guides began complaining that the books, which have a
cover price of $11.95, were being sold by street vendors for as
little as $4, well below the wholesale cost of $6. Some vendors
displayed signs boasting of their low prices for Zagat surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the books had to be stolen,'' Zagat said. But under
state law, he said, they needed proof that the vendor was knowingly
selling stolen goods.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it became clear that the books were coming from the Seeford
Organization warehouse on Varick Street, the only warehouse the
Zagats had used since the early 1980s. One clue was that some
street vendors were also offering copies of ``Miss Lea's Bible
Stories,'' a book that the couple had published in 1994. Copies
could only have come from the Seeford warehouse, the Zagats said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeford's president, Samuel Goldstein, said the books were
pilfered behind his back, and the Zagats said they believe him.
Goldstein fired two employees in his shipping department, including
one who had worked for him for more than nine years, but they have
not been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Zagats switched warehouses. They also hired a
lawyer, Robert Tucker, with experience representing companies whose
products have been copied by counterfeiters and sold by street
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker brought in private investigators, who staked out street
vendors in various neighborhoods. At the end of August, vendors at
18 stands were photographed and given a letter informing them that
the Zagat books they were selling had been stolen, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the vendors responded by removing the books, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Zagats' decision to switch warehouses resulted in a lucky
break for them _ and for the police.
</P>
<P>
   Using an alias, Oscar Rosa, 32, a deliveryman for an office
supply company next to the Seeford warehouse, approached a longtime
Zagat Survey employee in charge of the shipping department at the
publishers' Columbus Circle offices and, describing himself as ``a
friend of a friend,'' asked to buy copies of the 1999 Zagat survey,
the police said. The Zagats and the Manhattan district attorney's
office asked that the employee remain anonymous for his protection.
</P>
<P>
   The employee reported the offer to the Zagats and arranged to
sell Rosa 3,000 copies of the 1998 guide for $3,000. (The 1999
survey does not go on sale until November.) On Sept. 11, Rosa gave
the Zagat employee _ who was wearing a taping device _ a partial
payment of $700, and Rosa's co-defendant, Timothy Cromwell, 34,
loaded the books into a van, according to a court document, as the
police videotaped the transaction from the Zagat Survey offices on
the fifth floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa and Cromwell were arrested and charged with grand larceny
and receiving stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   Cromwell's lawyer, Robert W. Jones, said his client worked for
the same office supply company where Rosa was employed, and thought
he was making a routine pickup. ``He didn't even know he was doing
anything wrong,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, who has been convicted twice for armed robbery and was on
parole at the time of his arrest, according to the district
attorney's office, was released on $5,000 bail. He was arrested
again on Friday after surrendering to the police to face an
additional charge of tampering with a witness. The police said he
called the Zagat employee a snitch and told him, ``I'm going to get
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa's Legal Aid Society lawyer, Gene Pudberry, said his client
would plead not guilty. Rosa has been fired from his job.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the wake of Rosa's arrest, the Zagats say they believe that
they have solved a puzzle that had bedeviled them for months.
</P>
<P>
   They say they have spent $20,000 on the investigation but
maintain that they had to act to avoid giving the impression that
they were dumping books on the street because of poor sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to spend whatever it took to dry it up,'' Ms.
Zagat said. ``It wasn't just because we were trying to do the best
thing for society. It was also because we felt it was really
damaging our brand to have our books out there on the street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
