</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEMPORARY-SYNAGOGUE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGREGANTS UPROOTED BY FIRE FIND HOME FOR HOLY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only three weeks ago, flames engulfed Central
Synagogue in midtown Manhattan, badly damaging the 126-year-old
architectural landmark.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday night, the synagogue's members will have a huge,
but temporary, house of worship, big enough to fit all 3,500
congregants. For the first time in memory, the entire congregation
will be able to honor the High Holy Days of Judaism together,
starting Sunday night with Rosh ha-Shanah, the first day of the new
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've been able to pray together in one
place at one time,'' said Laurence Rubinstein, a rabbi and
congregant.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary synagogue is the Seventh Regiment Armory on the
Upper East Side _ a cavernous space covering an entire block at
66th Street and Park Avenue. The armory was the only place in the
region that was available for 10 days and big enough to fit
thousands of worshipers. Rubinstein, for one, sees a ``wonderful
irony'' in the site: ``We are going to pray in a building meant for
weapons and military drills.''
</P>
<P>
   But before any praying can begin, Gov. George Pataki issued a
declaration of emergency to suspend a law that bars the use of
public spaces by religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   And the task of turning a drill hall into a synagogue has been
enormous, requiring the help of hundreds of people: from buildings
and fire inspectors to a high-society party designer to a Lutheran
mover and a 6-year-old boy who donated his tooth fairy money.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you create an environment for a congregation that feels
dislocated at sea?,'' said Peter Rubinstein, Central Synagogue's
senior rabbi. ``How do you make a place that feels proper and
spiritual?''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with an impossibly tight deadline. Until midnight
Saturday night, there was an antiques show at the armory. Robert
Isobel, who arranges expensive parties, and his staff can not begin
work until 2 Sunday morning. That gives them 18 hours to set up the
pulpit, lectern and ark, 3,800 folding chairs, and the carpets and
30-foot-long curtains around the armory's perimeter. There will be
a sound system and video screens projecting the services to
congregation members sitting in the back or on the sides.
</P>
<P>
   The armory design, said Rabbi Rubinstein, ``will evoke as much a
sense of our own sanctuary as possible.'' The floor is to be
carpeted in dark red, and the interior will be surrounded by dark
red curtains, allowing congregants to focus on the rabbi and the
ark. Some fire-damaged pieces will be carried over: four heavy
wooden pews and the ornately carved pulpit, as well as prayer
books. The five Torahs _ a synagogue's most sacred and essential
objects _ were undamaged because they were being stored outside
Central Synagogue at the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll use the scarred pulpit, and use the water-stained
mantels to cover the Torah,'' said Rabbi Rubinstein. ``That's OK.
Life isn't beautiful all the time but it's still to be
celebrated.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But many other items were donated by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The classical-style organ, for instance, was lent by a Long
Island organ shop. Claire Arnold, co-owner of the shop, even
persuaded a devout Lutheran mover to deliver it on Sunday.The huge
ark, which contains the five Torahs, came from a synagogue just
outside New York City. And a downtown Manhattan manufacturer of
religious objects contributed holders and mantels of fine fabric
for the Torahs.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue has bought hundreds of new prayer books, yarmulkes
and prayer shawls. A trailer parked outside will provide facilities
for the men's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   All this is costing more than $200,000, Rabbi Rubinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the initial shock of the fire has passed, many
congregants are feeling philosophical and excited about the idea of
worshiping in the huge makeshift synagogue. Judith Hertz, the
congregation's secretary, said: ``The idea we could all come
together lends a certain power and energy to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Old habits, said Edward Skloot, director of the Surdna
Foundation in Manhattan, are being shaken. For one thing, people
will not be sitting in the pews reserved by the amount of a
family's donation. ``We will have to mix and mingle and sit next to
new people. It's a remarkable way to begin something new.
Everybody's going to be talking about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, his 15-year-old son and the chaplain of the youth group,
said that people are becoming closer, more of a community. ``It was
devastating,'' he said. ``But a lot of people that usually only
come once or twice a year are really connecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Rubinstein said that this new year will be ``very powerful
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one we would have chosen,'' he said. ``You can't
choose the hand that's dealt you. But you can make the best of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
