<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MEDICAID-DENIALS-9     09-19 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-DENIALS-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME INSPECTIONS FOR MEDICAID SEEKERS STIR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lilia Cuji did not dare ask for welfare last summer
when she ventured inside the Jamaica, Queens, outpost of the city's
Human Resources Administration, a six-story brick building wedged
between Caribbean delis and a topless bar called Dreams. Ms. Cuji,
who immigrated from Ecuador six years ago, applied only for
Medicaid health-insurance benefits for her 2-year-old son, and she
provided all the documents necessary to prove his eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   But in a little-noticed pilot project that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani plans to expand to the rest of the city next year, the
Jamaica center required something more of anyone seeking Medicaid:
a home investigation by the same city unit that screens welfare
applicants for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The two investigators who went to Ms. Cuji's apartment on Aug.
5, 1997, examined the same documents she had shown at the Medicaid
office, she said, and sharply questioned her about her lack of a
green card. Then they walked into her bedroom, peered into her
closet and spotted the evidence they later used to recommend
rejection: a pair of blue jeans _ men's jeans, they insisted _
hanging among her dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cuji's son was one of more than 4,480 Medicaid applicants
recommended for rejection by Eligibility Verification Review
investigators. That figure represented 36 percent of the applicants
who underwent home investigations between October 1996 and June 30,
1998, according to city figures.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for denial include an applicant's failure to keep an
appointment with investigators, providing false information, or
withholding information about income, resources or living
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say home investigations are a reasonable way to
screen out people who lie on their Medicaid applications. But many
advocates and health-care providers assert that home investigations
for Medicaid raise a frightening and unnecessary new barrier to
health care for many low-income children and adults, just when
federal and state officials are trying to make it easier for
families to obtain government-sponsored health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   So far, New York City appears to be alone in imposing such a
requirement, federal health officials said; 33 states allow
application by mail.
</P>
<P>
   To advocates for the poor, it illustrates how a get-tough
approach in welfare is spilling over into health-care programs,
despite a congressional decision to preserve Medicaid as a federal
entitlement and to uncouple it from cash assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the city is doing is in direct conflict with what's going
on in health-insurance policy and health-care policy,'' said Suri
Duitch, a health specialist at the Citizens' Committee for
Children, a nonprofit advocacy organization in New York. ``It just
doesn't make sense to be limiting access in somewhat arbitrary
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Sproles, a spokeswoman for the Human Resources
Administration, defended the investigations, calling them a way to
ensure that applicants told the truth about residence and income.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program integrity initiative was established to make sure
that only eligible people receive Medicaid,'' she said. ``People
who don't need it and aren't eligible for the service, we don't
want them on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sproles said she could not discuss the case of Ms. Cuji, who
says that the jeans in her closet were her own. But Ms. Sproles
added: ``If they based their conclusion just on pants without
further investigation, that would not be the general rule. You
would investigate that further. If the investigation should find
out that the woman has misrepresented her situation and is living
with her spouse, you could understand their drawing that
conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   About one out of three Medicaid applications is rejected
citywide, advocates say. The 36 percent rejection rate by home
investigators in the pilot project represents a 3 percentage point
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel costs for the city's pilot project in Jamaica and
Bushwick, Brooklyn, will be $585,000 this year, officials said.
Citywide costs are projected at $6.2 million for the investigation
unit and another $715,000 for additional Medicaid employees.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for poor people acknowledge that the investigations
will allow the city to uncover genuine cases of fraud, but question
how these can be worth the cost. Some say the home investigations
are reminiscent of the indignities of welfare in the early 1960s,
when inspectors routinely poked through recipients' medicine
cabinets looking for men's toiletries and staged midnight raids to
see whether female welfare recipients were living with men.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the chilling effect of such examinations, they say,
the Medicaid application process is too difficult and intimidating
for many who are eligible, especially the disabled, elderly and
mentally ill, and illegal immigrants applying for their American
children, like Ms. Cuji.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after little people, and it doesn't seem fair when
there's a lot more fraud and abuse at other levels,'' said Mark
Laster, a specialist in managed and geriatric care at New Hope
Guild, a nonprofit network of clinics for the mentally ill in
Queens and Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The city and the state equally share half the costs of Medicaid
and the federal government pays the other half. Last year, 414,000
people who were not on welfare were certified for Medicaid by the
city, and their medical expenses totaled $5.1 billion, according to
state figures.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money goes to institutions that bypass the new
investigation unit, however, like hospitals billing retroactively
for inpatient care, and nursing homes at which Medicaid patients
include elderly people who have legally transferred their assets to
their children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To state and federal officials, who have been trying to stem
recent declines in Medicaid enrollment and to reduce the welfare
stigma associated with government health coverage, the Jamaica
project and its expansion came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Tarlton, a spokeswoman for the State Department of
Health, said the city's use of welfare-fraud workers to screen
people seeking health care constituted a change requiring a formal
filing with the State Office of Temporary and Disability
Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Wescott, a spokeswoman for that office, said a letter
from the city proposing to expand the pilot to eight or nine new
sites was received late last month, and was being reviewed to
determine if it was consistent with department regulations meant to
ensure that eligible children and adults receive needed medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent August morning, the applicants who crowded the
Medicaid office in Jamaica included Rosalina Bulatao, 77, who said
she had worked as a home health aide until she suffered a stroke
last year, but now could not afford to buy blood-pressure
medication, costing $50 a month, on her monthly Social Security
stipend of $518.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bulatao had no complaints about the two investigators who
had spent about 20 minutes in her home politely reviewing documents
she had already shown in two previous visits to the Medicaid
office. The problem, she said, was that the Medicaid card she had
finally received in the mail still had not been activated.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the home investigation had added a new obstacle
to many others. One woman, speaking on the condition that only her
first name, Minerva, be used, said this was the third day she had
been forced to take time from her $6-an-hour job in a supermarket
to reapply for Medicaid for herself and her sons.
</P>
<P>
   Her first Medicaid application had been rejected, she said,
because she took nine days instead of seven to return a form from
her employers stating that they did not provide health insurance.
Because she was working when investigators came to her home, she
said, the resulting denial for failure to cooperate delayed a fresh
application for another month.
</P>
<P>
   Minerva, 27, said she could not afford medical care for her
children, an 8-year-old with asthma and a 3-year-old whose care at
the St. Joseph's Hospital emergency room recently left her with a
bill for $180. She said she and the children originally lost
Medicaid coverage in May after her public assistance case was
closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I still have two asthma pumps,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To some analysts, the kind of hard-line approach used to deter
welfare fraud can backfire when applied to health care, in part
because preventive care is often much cheaper than trips to the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 295,000 children in the state and 4.5 million children
nationwide are now eligible for Medicaid but not enrolled,
according to estimates by the Urban Institute, a nonpartisan social
research organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cuji's case illustrates the contradictions that can result
when health and welfare policies pull in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after investigators discovered the blue jeans, Betty
Perez, an advocate at the Center for Children and Families, a
nonprofit maternal and child health program in Queens, called the
Medicaid information line to check on the family's Medicaid status.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Perez said she was told that Ms. Cuji's son had been denied
``because they found men's clothing,'' but that Ms. Cuji herself
had active Medicaid coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation? Ms. Cuji was pregnant, and under state policies
intended to lower infant mortality, her prenatal clinic had been
able to process her application directly, bypassing the Jamaica
center.
</P>
<P>
   But, Ms. Perez said, it took another six months and a new
application before the boy was finally enrolled. There was never
any legal basis for denying his application, Ms. Perez said. Even
if the boy's father had been living with them, it is unlikely that
the family income would have exceeded Medicaid limits.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Cuji, who recently lost her job in a nail salon, is
afraid her son and the new baby will lose Medicaid again when she
has to apply for yearly recertification.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, the children's father, who has no green card and
works irregularly in day-labor demolition jobs, recently rejoined
the family after being injured, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand,'' she said in Spanish. ``I only apply for
my children. Why do they have the power to go into my home asking
questions about my intimate life?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
