<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-CHAVEZ-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA STANDS AND FIGHTS, SENDING CHAVEZ TO HIS CORNER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It was not the outcome that anyone expected. Great
Mexican champions do not go out on their stools. They go out on
their shields. But Julio Cesar Chavez, a six-time world champion
and arguably the greatest boxer in Mexico history, quit on his
stool at the end of the eighth round against Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez went out with a golden parachute, earning $6 million for
the loss. And De La Hoya (29-0) retained his World Boxing Council
welterweight championship with the victory on Friday night before a
screaming throng of 17,125 fans at the Thomas and Mack Center here.
</P>
<P>
   More ignominious than the loss for Chavez (101-3-2) was that De
La Hoya beat him at his own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar fought a stupidly brilliant fight,'' said Lou DiBella,
HBO's senior vice president of programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stupid of Oscar to stand right in front of Chavez and
trade punches with him. But he knew he was going to have to do that
in order to ever get Chavez's respect and the respect of the
Mexican fans. They wouldn't have accepted a victory by him any
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's full frontal assault against Chavez was against the
wishes of his corner. Trainers Robert Alcazar and Gil Clancy wanted
De La Hoya to outbox Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans in the stands, many of them Chavez fans from
Mexico, wanted to see De La Hoya trade punches with Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got caught up in the whole event,'' De La Hoya said. ``So,
for a few rounds I went toe-to-toe and fought his fight. I'm sure
the fans enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's face paid the price. He wore dark sunglasses after
the fight to hide the large swelling around his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   A Chavez fan yelled to De La Hoya at the post-fight news
conference to take off the sunglasses. De La Hoya said he couldn't
because he was doing a promotion for the sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez landed a highest percentage of punches against De La Hoya
(47 percent) than any of De La Hoya's previous 28 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth and deciding round when a total of 173 punches
were thrown, Chavez landed 38-of-90 punches and De La Hoya landed
45-of-83. They took a toll on Chavez, who could be seen shaking his
head ``no'' in his corner before the fight was stopped by his
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, Chavez walked around the ring waving his
glove as if to say goodbye.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Perhaps his corner decided to stop the fight because they didn't
want to see Chavez battered and embarrassed over the final four
rounds. Chavez, his lower lip split open and blackened with dried
blood, appeared at a post-fight news conference set up in the ring
and vehemently denied any involvement in the stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make something clear,'' Chavez said. ``I wanted to
continue to fight. My corner was the one that stopped the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   That was contrary to what Chavez told De La Hoya in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he did,'' De La Hoya said. ``He told me: `You beat
me. I don't want anymore.' I was more satisfied that he quit.
Believe me when I tell you he quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he quit in this fight, Chavez announced that he wasn't
giving up the game.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to fight once more at 140 pounds and then call
it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum, president of Top Rank Boxing, said he will
try to make a fight between Chavez and Vince Phillips, the
International Boxing Federation junior welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   As for De La Hoya, he has a Nov. 21 date in the same arena
against Ike Quartey, the former World Boxing Association
welterweight champion who is nicknamed ``The Bazooka.'' He didn't
get that moniker by handing out love taps, so De La Hoya will
probably be more cautious against a younger former champion than he
was against an aging legend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
