<SLUG> BC-FBC-PRINCETON-CORNELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 PRINCETON DEDICATES NEW STADIUM WITH 6-0 WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM N. WALLACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ The home team scored on its first two drives
in its new home Saturday, and went on to dedicate Princeton Stadium
with a 6-0 victory over Cornell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' ace place-kicker, Alex Sierk, made field goals of 47
and 37 yards following impressive drives, and that was good enough.
Perhaps the team in orange, black and white was inspired by the
first capacity crowd at a Princeton home game in four decades.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 27,800 tickets, bargains at $5 each, were sold and most of
the seats occupied for the unveiling of the $45 million stadium,
the Ivy League's first new football facility in 14 years and only
its second in 71 years. It was the largest crowd at a Princeton
game since 38,000 saw the 1989 game with Yale in Palmer Stadium,
which had 45,750 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The sparkling new stadium was more exciting than the game, a
dull one because the defenses limited big plays and scoring
threats. Dropped passes on both sides also crimped the offenses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cornell's only scoring threat came late in the first half, and
failed. A 48-yard completion from Mike Hood to wide receiver Kevin
Farese brought the Big Red to the Princeton 16-yard line. But
penalties and losses followed before John McCombs' 27-yard field
goal attempt went wide.
</P>
<P>
   A Cornell drive ended in the last minute of the fourth quarter
with an interception by Tigers cornerback Gerry Wilson at his
21-yard line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cornell had something new too in Pete Mangurian, the Big Red's
first-year head coach. Mangurian spent the last 10 seasons as an
assistant in the National Football League, and he has on his staff
Bill Arnsparger, head coach of the Giants from 1974 to 1976. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last season Princeton won five of 10 games, but only one in Ivy
competition, against Yale. Cornell was 5-5 and 3-4. Expectations
are that both will finish in the middle of the league this season.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton Stadium, which may get a new name should a major donor
come forth, went up in 18 months on the site of Palmer Stadium,
which was built in 1914 and was deemed beyond the point of repair
by engineering studies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is the first new Ivy facility to be built since 1984, when
Columbia's Lawrence Wien Stadium opened. The other six were built
between 1903 and 1927. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Princeton, officials at Harvard and Pennsylvania
chose to keep their stadiums and have poured thousands of dollars
into their ongoing rehabilitations. Harvard Stadium, 95 years old,
is the nation's oldest. Penn's Franklin Field, in its present
conformation, dates to 1921. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the kickoff all former Princeton football players
present, 280 of them, paraded onto the field and spread over it
from one goal to the other. The youngest were those from the 1997
team, which played all of its 10 games on the road while the
stadium was being built, and the oldest from the 1927 squad. They
marched beneath huge orange and black banners designating their
years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TICKETS-475     09-19 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TICKETS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE PLAYOFF SALES TEST LOYALTY AND LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one told The Ant about The Random Number Wristband
Distribution Procedure. So when Antoine ``The Ant'' Hill and his
friend Lee Boogie heard that Yankees postseason tickets would go on
sale Saturday morning, they arrived Thursday night to be first in
line.
</P>
<P>
   For 36 hours, they crouched, sat, slept and curled up on the
cold concrete outside Yankee Stadium. By Saturday morning, tickets
weren't all they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preparation H,'' Boogie said. ``You sit on that concrete all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet after all their devotion and discomfort, Boogie and Hill
were not assured of getting tickets. Why? As a means of
discouraging ticket scalping and preventing a stampede on the
ticket booths (as happened in 1996), the Yankees were using a
random distribution system that rewards luck as much as loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the playoff tickets are already taken. But the 2,000 or
so fans who waited Saturday morning in 19 police crowd control pens
were hoping for a chance at the limited, but unspecified, number of
tickets available to the public. They could choose either a blue
wristband for Division Series tickets or a red wristband for League
Championship tickets. Each wristband was numbered, and tickets
would be sold after a number was picked in a random drawing later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Donald Simpson, 38, a member of the Section 39
``Bleacher Creatures,'' got wristband No. 1111 and the chance to
buy as many as four tickets. But if the number selected in the
random drawing was 1112, then Simpson would be considered last in
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``George, in previous years, has always accommodated us because
we're an integral part of the stadium,'' he said, speaking of the
Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner. ``Without us, it's
like you woke up and you're not wearing your underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bleacher Creatures sit in the cheapest outfield seats. They
chant the name of outfielder Bernie Williams until he tips his cap.
They call new initiates CITs, for ``Creatures in Training.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hill and Boogie arrived Thursday, no one else appeared
until Friday, when Dirk Bernold and Kurt Snyder, both 26, arrived.
Others, like Simpson, began arriving as well. Even when everyone
learned it was not first come, first served, they stayed anyway.
The police prohibited tents, sleeping bags (though some people
brought them anyway), chairs, coolers and alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stupid experience,'' grumbled Snyder, a student at Albert
Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx. Then, explaining why he
stayed: ``I was too lazy to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment was hard to come by. The Friday morning crash of a
freight train on the nearby Metro-North tracks provided some
excitement. When newspaper photographers arrived late Friday night,
people responded with what Bernold called the ``paparazzi'' chant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You killed Lady Di!'' the crowd chanted. ``Bring back Lady
Di!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bernold reached page 480 of James Michener's 1,130 page
``Hawaii.'' Snyder concentrated on ``The Catcher in the Rye.'' One
group of fans managed, miraculously, to sleep almost without
interruption.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Snyder stretched, then unwrapped the remains
of a Wendy's chicken sandwich from the night before. He ate it for
breakfast. It was no comfort that the fans who came Saturday
morning had just as good a chance to buy tickets. And they smelled
better, too.
</P>
<P>
   What all the waiting did provide, though, was time for fans like
Simpson to assess the greater meaning of the Yankee universe. ``Oh,
it was terrible,'' he said of the concrete. ``But being so close to
home _ Yankee Stadium _ it was warm from that.''
</P>
<P>
   His father first took him to Yankee Stadium in 1967 at the end
of Mickey Mantle's career. So when the Yankees made the World
Series in 1996, he took his father.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Simpson said the Bleacher Creatures are desperate. He
cannot imagine a Yankees postseason game without himself. He said
there are more than 100 Bleacher Creatures, and they insist on
sitting in Section 39. ``Creatures sitting all over the place isn't
good,'' he said. ``We've got to be united to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   So Saturday morning, Simpson called on a power even higher than
Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody say a prayer for the Creatures,'' he solemnly
intoned. ``We need them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
