<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-TARPON-NYT &LR;      09-19 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-TARPON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG ONE THAT OFTEN GETS AWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GREG THOMAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Florida Keys tarpon is an impressive, intimidating animal.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the foredeck of a flats skiff, 40 feet of fly line
coiled near an angler's feet, a 3/0 tarpon fly resting in one hand,
a 12-weight flyrod clutched in the other, an angler must ask
himself, ``Do I really want to hook that fish?'' when a
hundred-plus pounder swims by. Instead of casting, he might
consider dropping the rod and securing a life vest.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpon, by virtue of their size and disposition, are capable of
swamping small, shallow-water flats skiffs. Large tarpon have an
ability to jump _ as high as 10 feet and up to 20 feet horizontally
_ and some anglers have endured a giant tarpon in their lap. But
most anglers are willing to take that chance; it is said that a
giant tarpon is the consummate game fish and that an angler who
catches one may never feel equal elation. At the moment of capture,
some may have one word for the world: perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The world-record tarpon, a 283-pound Goliath, was landed in
Venezuela in 1956. However, an estimated 350-pound tarpon was
caught by commercial fishermen at Hillsboro Inlet in Florida in
1912. That fish measured 8 feet 2 inches long. Typically, a
six-foot tarpon weighs about 100 pounds. A seven-footer goes about
200 pounds and a 300-pounder measures eight feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   There are several places in the world where flyfishers harbor a
chance to hook a fish meeting those dimensions and one of those
spots is the Florida Keys, where fish that average 60 to 110 pounds
invade the shallow, fertile flats each May and June. That is
exactly where my father, Fred, and I found ourselves in June, fully
revved up for our first saltwater fly-fishing excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Before the late 1800s, giant tarpon, those fish that range
between 70 and 300 pounds, were considered not catchable on
conventional sport tackle, let alone on a flyrod. But, in 1898
Edward Von Hofe landed a 210-pound tarpon on sport gear. By 1933, a
136-pound fish had been taken by George Bonbright near Long Key,
Fla. In 1967, Stu Apt landed a 151-pound tarpon that ranked as the
largest ever taken on a flyrod.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, 1980s and through this decade, advances in
fly-fishing equipment, including reliable monofilament leaders and
fast-action graphite rods, led a wave of fly-fishers to pursue
tarpon.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tempted to say those advances swayed the odds in favor of
the angler, but that simply is not true. Each large tarpon tests
equipment and an angler's ability to the max. Some experts estimate
that, even today, anglers lose nine of every 10 tarpon hooked.
</P>
<P>
   I will never forget my first tarpon, although I must admit, it
wasn't one of the big boys. We were motoring out of a channel, 15
minutes into my inaugural day chasing saltwater fish, when I
spotted several large shadows stalking across the shallow flats. We
cut the engine and just before those silver slabs reached the edge
of the flat, I cast a fly over the grass, let it rest momentarily,
then stripped the pattern twice. A fish peeled out of the pack,
hesitated, then engulfed the fly. I hollered gleefully and set the
hook. As the line came taunt, the tarpon felt the sting of a hook
and leaped into the air, just the tip of its tail scraping the
ocean's surface. I let out another scream, kept solid pressure on
my eight-weight rod, and settled in for a fight. Fifteen minutes
later, I stood on the stern, cradling a 60-pound silver king, a
grin extending from ear to ear, confidence beaming from my bones.
</P>
<P>
   There are many epic tarpon battles to relate, some won by the
fish, others, much less often, by the angler. Unfortunately,
battles lost are often more memorable than those that end with a
tarpon in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The depression involved in losing a large tarpon cannot be
overemphasized. That mental roulette stems from difficulties that
must be overcome just to get a fly in front of a tarpon's mouth,
let alone to achieve a take.
</P>
<P>
   During our trip, I repeatedly stumbled on the rocking boat,
gathered my footing and attempted to shoot line through the guides,
trying desperately to punch that tarpon fly and a 12-weight line
through the tropic wind.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the running line wrapped around my sandal's Velcro
strap or looped around the anchor cleat. My cast might stop dead in
the air, snap back toward the boat, short, again, of my target. All
incredibly frustrating, especially because our host, an art
publisher, had bought my plane ticket from Seattle to accompany my
father, the artist, on a reference-gathering trip. We needed
close-ups and underwater shots of giant tarpon and I, the hot-shot
Rocky Mountain fly-fisher, was supposed to catch them. As our trip
dwindled, I realized that I'd failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, on the last day of our nine-day stay we encountered
a huge school of tarpon, maybe 100 or more fish, all balled up in
the shallows.
</P>
<P>
   I was using a standard 3/0 tarpon fly, as I had engaged the
entire trip. But now, instead of inspecting the streamer, those
tarpon just whirled away from my offering. Time was running out,
the sun rising higher in the sky, our departure imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic, I pilfered my fly box and tied on a size-6 crazy
Charlie _ a bonefish fly of all things.
</P>
<P>
   I backcast, shot the line and stopped the fly about 10 yards to
my side of a pod. The fish charged, I saw the telltale underwater
silver flash, then felt the line tighten. That tarpon made a quick,
30-yard run that terrified me (when would the line go slack, I
wondered), leaped into the air, then settled back into the glassy
sea to test my endurance.
</P>
<P>
   I worked that fish for 20 or 30 minutes, bowing the rod when it
jumped. Then, the leader parted and my big tarpon slid over some
dark turtle grass and disappeared. We reluctantly headed home.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m. we were strapped into our seats, settled on the
tarmac, our Florida Keys trip hitting its end. I engaged a man in
conversation before the props fired up, and told him about my
experience: about a first-day tarpon, a permit hooked and lost, six
tarpon takes one morning, and the crazy Charlie. The man, who had
fished extensively around the tropics with a flyrod, told me
bluntly, ``If I were you, I'd change my flight plans in Dallas.
Don't fly to Seattle. Go straight to Las Vegas. You're the luckiest
man alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
