<HEADER>
A4323 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE-1ST     09-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIDEOTAPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY OVERVIEW: CLINTON VOICES CONCERN FOR LEWINSKY AND REGRET
OVER AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct quote in graf beginning: The pillars of ...)   (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-CHRISTIANS,
CLINTON-INTERNET.)  
(js) 
 By JAMES BENNET and JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In more than four hours of testimony before the
grand jury, President Clinton painted a picture of himself as a
concerned and even tender friend to Monica Lewinsky, lawyers
familiar with the Aug. 17 proceeding said.
</P>
<P>
   That image is starkly at odds with that of the callous
manipulator conducting an illicit affair portrayed in the
impeachment report to Congress by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   At several points in the testimony, the president expressed
embarrassment and regret about the affair, the lawyers said. After
one five-minute break, he told the grand jurors, ``I'd give
anything in the world to not admit what I had to testify to
today,'' the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Such moments of remorse were mixed with flashes of fury at the
prosecutors. As one of Starr's deputies pressed him on his efforts
to help Ms. Lewinsky find a job, the president lashed out, saying,
``You have made this the most important issue in America,'' the
lawyers said. Clinton even accused the prosecutors of impairing his
memory by increasing the already considerable pressure on him over
the previous four years, they said.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, the president delivered what one lawyer called
a ``diatribe,'' in which he criticized the prosecutors for swooping
down on Ms. Lewinsky upon learning of their relationship. ``Monica
was kept by five of your lawyers and five of your FBI agents,'' he
said, according to the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when the videotape of Clinton's testimony is released
by Congress, the public will see a more complex president than the
one in Starr's 445-page report, Clinton's allies and friends have
argued. While Starr's report drew on many sources, particularly on
Ms. Lewinsky's testimony, to painstakingly chronicle what the
independent counsel says are impeachable acts, it did not describe
in detail the president's justifications for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times was not provided with a transcript or
videotape of the president's testimony in advance of the public
release of the material, which was approved by a House Judiciary
Committee vote on Friday. This account is based on descriptions
provided by lawyers with detailed knowledge of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's friends, advisers and supporters on Capitol Hill have
repeatedly argued that Starr's report did not fully present his
side of the story. ``The referral itself is an extremely one-sided
and unfair document,'' said a Clinton ally, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``It does not fairly reflect the
president's testimony and the only purpose of the excessive graphic
detail is to harm the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's supporters have argued that he was forced to include
such graphic detail. They say they did it to prove that Clinton
lied when he denied having ``sexual relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky
in a deposition on Jan. 17 in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit and because he refused to answer in detail their questions
in his grand jury testimony last month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his grand jury testimony on Aug. 17 at 1:03 p.m.,
in the Map Room of the White House. In a high-backed chair, the
president sat facing three lawyers from his team, with Starr and a
row of prosecutors to his right and a lectern and a camera in front
of him. As four prosecutors took turns questioning him under oath,
Clinton was at times evasive, angry, cajoling and even
philosophical, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said that he believed that both Clarence Thomas
and Anita Hill thought they were telling the truth in their
confrontation over her accusations of sexual harassment before the
Senate Judiciary Committee in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most mysterious area of human life,'' the
president told the grand jury, the lawyers said. From the federal
courthouse a few blocks away, the grand jurors were watching
Clinton on a live, one-way closed-circuit transmission.
</P>
<P>
   The president then extended a rare olive branch to Starr and his
team, thanking them for having provided broad immunity from
prosecution to Ms. Lewinsky and her mother, Marcia Lewis. Referring
to Ms. Lewinsky, he added, ``It breaks my heart that she was
involved in this,'' the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the exchanges with prosecutors may prove
embarrassing to Clinton when they are played and replayed on
television in the coming days, his advisers believe.
</P>
<P>
   One such exchange came at the beginning of the testimony, when
Robert Bittman, a member of Starr's team, spent about seven minutes
questioning Clinton about whether he understood the meaning of the
oath he had taken to tell ``the whole truth.'' As Bittman
repeatedly pressed him, Clinton skirted some of the questions, the
lawyers said without providing more details.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after that exchange, Bittman asked the
president if he had been intimate with Ms. Lewinsky, the lawyers
said. Clinton responded by reading a statement that he had had
``inappropriate intimate contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky ``on certain
occasions in early 1996 and once in early 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that what began as a friendship came to include this
conduct,'' Clinton said, according to a copy of the statement that
was provided to The New York Times. ``And I take full
responsibility for my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton repeatedly rebuffed questions about the details
of his sexual encounters with Ms. Lewinsky, referring back to the
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   The president denied trying to influence the testimony of his
secretary, Betty Currie, in conversations he had with her shortly
after his deposition in the Jones case, the lawyers said. He
characterized those talks as efforts to warn Mrs. Currie of an
impending media frenzy over his dealings with Ms. Lewinsky and an
effort to find out from her why the Jones lawyers had asked him so
many questions about the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At several points in the testimony, Clinton faced a barrage of
questions about gifts he exchanged with Ms. Lewinsky, in particular
two neckties she may have given him.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors asked him why Bayani Nelvis, a White House steward,
wore a tie to a grand jury appearance that Ms. Lewinsky said she
had given to the president, lawyers said. They also asked why on
Aug. 6, the day Ms. Lewinsky first appeared before the grand jury,
Clinton, at a Rose Garden ceremony that day, had worn another tie
that she said she had given him.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors wanted to know if the ties were meant as signals
to keep Ms. Lewinsky in the president's camp, lawyers familiar with
the inquiry have said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was said to have smiled in response to the questions and
expressed bafflement. He said he did not know if the ties had come
from Ms. Lewinsky, and that he gave away some of the many ties he
received, the lawyers said. The president was asked about other
gifts he gave the former intern, especially some New York
souvenirs, including a Rockettes throw _ a small blanket or rug
from Radio City Music Hall _ the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has charged the president with trying to obstruct justice
by concealing such gifts from the independent counsel's office. The
Jones lawyers had subpoenaed Ms. Lewinsky to turn over any such
presents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly said that he did not consider the gifts an
important matter, the lawyers said. He testified that he
specifically told Ms. Lewinsky that if the Jones lawyers requested
the gifts, she should turn them over, a statement reflected in
Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described his efforts to help Ms. Lewinsky find a job
not as attempts to win her silence, but as sincere efforts to help
an anxious friend. ``I wanted to help her get on with her life,''
the lawyers quoted him as saying. If he was trying to keep her in
his camp, Clinton testified, he could have ordered that she be
hired at the White House, a step he did not take despite her
repeated pleas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pointed out that he had tried to keep Ms. Lewinsky
at arm's length after ending the affair in early 1997. ``When I did
the right thing and made it stick, she felt a greater need to
cling,'' the lawyers quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly said that he tried to be truthful in the
Jones deposition without answering more than they specifically
asked. The president accused the Jones lawyers of using a
``wrecking ball'' to damage him, one lawyer said. The lawyer said
that Clinton testified he deplored the work of the Jones lawyers,
adding: ``I was determined to walk through the minefield of this
deposition.'' He said that he believed he had, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But events leading up to the president's grand jury appearance
created an array of legal dangers for him. Clinton's lawyers began
negotiating to have him testify voluntarily before they knew that
Starr had obtained physical evidence, a dress of Ms. Lewinsky's
that was stained with the president's semen. That evidence meant
that any categorical denial of an affair with Ms. Lewinsky, such as
the unsworn public denials the president had issued in January,
would almost certainly trigger an impeachment referral on perjury
by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to his grand jury appearance, the
president and his lawyers built a new line of defense. Clinton
would admit to an ``inappropriate, intimate'' relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, but deny perjury in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The pillars of this new defense were Clinton's opening statement
and a one-sheet definition of sexual relations that was used in the
Jones case. That page contained three definitions, only one of
which was permitted to be used by the judge hearing the case. The
president circled it with a pen. It said that a person engages in
``sexual relations'' when that person ``knowingly engages in or
causes contact with the genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner
thigh, or buttocks of any person with an intent to arouse or
gratify the sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   To the grand jury, Clinton testified that most people defined
sexual relations as sexual intercourse, which he did not have with
Ms. Lewinsky. He testified that oral sex did not fall within the
definition of sexual relations in the Jones case. And he testified
that touching Ms. Lewinsky's breasts and genitalia would fit the
Jones definition, but he denied having done so, according to
Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in August, after receiving immunity from prosecution,
Ms. Lewinsky told Starr's team that the president had touched or
kissed her breasts on nine occasions and described four contacts
with her genitalia, the Starr report said. She also said her affair
with the president began in late 1995. He testified that it did not
begin until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 11 impeachable offenses Starr referred to the
Congress involve accusations that Clinton lied in the Jones
deposition and in his grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also questioned Clinton about his relationship with
Kathleen Willey, a former White House volunteer, the lawyers said.
They pressed him on why he had not turned over letters from Ms.
Willey to the Jones legal team. The White House released the
letters, most of which were warm greetings to the president, last
spring after Ms. Willey appeared on the CBS program ``60 Minutes''
and accused the president of groping her in the White House.
Starr's report said he was still investigating whether there were
efforts to influence Ms. Willey's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the questioning, Starr asked David Kendall, one of
the president's private lawyers, if they could exceed their
agreed-upon four-hour time limit, excluding breaks. Kendall
refused.
</P>
<P>
   It was only very late in the testimony that Starr himself put
two questions to the president, both dealing with his invocations
of executive privilege, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning and end of the testimony, which concluded at
5:55 p.m., Clinton and the prosecutors made a show of handshaking
and cordiality. But the anger in the room was palpable, lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the anger was still there four hours later, when Clinton
returned to tell the nation of his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky,
speaking from the same high-backed chair. He again lashed out at
Starr, demanding his privacy back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
