u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-925&AMP;ADD-     09-19 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FURNISHING A HOME OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As telecommuting and home-based businesses become increasingly
common, the traditional home office _ the card table in the corner
of the family room or the kitchen table cleared after dinner _ has
become a thing of the past. These days, home-based-business
consultants say, establishing an efficient home office generally
entails carving out a dedicated space _ a whole room or part of one
_ and adapting it to suit the business's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to ensure that you have as much privacy as possible,
both visually and acoustically,'' said Albert Zaccone, an architect
who works out of an office in his home in Ridgefield Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The installation of a solid-core door, for example, can go a
long way toward keeping household noises and annoyances away. And
if a home has significant noise producers, such as young children,
it might be worthwhile to install acoustic insulation in the walls
and ceiling separating the office from the rest of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The insulation ``can be installed relatively easily by taking
the sheetrock off one side of the wall,'' Zaccone said.
</P>
<P>
   It is often also useful, he said, to separate the utility
service. ``We'll often recommend installation of an electrical
service and subpanel exclusively for the office,'' he said. In
addition to making it possible to keep track of office utility
expenses, he said, a separate service prevents home-office computer
systems from suddenly shutting down if someone in the house turns
on another appliance and inadvertently trips a circuit breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also helps to separate the heating and air-conditioning if
possible,'' Zaccone said, explaining that portable heaters and
window air-conditioners can save money in the long run by
eliminating the need to heat or cool an otherwise empty house just
to make it comfortable in the home office.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Gordon, president of Gil Gordon Associates, a telecommuting
consultant in Monmouth Junction, N.J., said that those without a
spare room for an office should focus on buying the right kind of
home-office furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of years, a tremendous number of
home-office furniture suites have come on the market,'' Gordon
said. ``They look like they belong in a home, but they have design
qualities equal to that of good office furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Such home-office suites, available at most office-supply stores
at prices ranging from about $500 to about $2,000, typically make
more efficient use of limited space.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a small footprint and lots of vertical storage,''
Gordon said, adding that consumers should be cautious about
elaborate, expensive furniture that sacrifices ergonomic qualities
for a fancy appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People fall into the trap of becoming enticed with the nice
oak-grained finish and ignore the fact that the unit may be poorly
designed,'' he said. Before spending hundreds, perhaps thousands of
dollars on an elaborate office-furniture suite, a consumer should
spend time sitting at the desk to determine whether drawers,
keyboard platforms and storage spaces are conveniently placed,
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprisingly efficient office furnishing strategy, he
said, is to use a stained or painted solid-core door set
horizontally on bricks or cinder blocks, and get movable plastic
file boxes on wheels or casters. The door provides plenty of desk
space, its height is easily adjustable, and the file boxes can be
rolled underneath when they are not needed.
</P>
<P>
   If the budget is limited, he said, all other office furniture
considerations should take a back seat, so to speak, to the office
occupant's back and seat. ``I urge clients to put every available
dollar into buying a good chair,'' Gordon said. ``You want
something that has five legs, wheels or casters, and as much
adjustability as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But comfort goes only so far, he said _ it is usually wise to
resist the temptation to be too comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think, `Here's my chance to put my desk by the window
and get a view of the backyard,''' he said. ``But what you end up
getting is a headache when your eyes have to constantly adjust from
the computer screen and the bright outside light.'' And reversing
the setup _ with the desk facing away from the window _ can be just
as difficult if glare from the window falls on the monitor's
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably better off setting the desk at an angle to the
window,'' he said, adding that the furniture should be arranged on
a sunny day so that any problems are immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Edwards, a Santa Monica, Calif., writer who with her
husband, Paul, has written several books on working from home, said
that those considering a home-based business should determine the
maximum number of telephone lines available.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume they can have as many lines as they want,'' Ms.
Edwards said. ``But in some buildings _ particularly older New York
City apartment buildings _ there are only a limited number of lines
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards said that although she and her husband have five
telephone numbers in their California town house, they had to
borrow the fifth line from a next-door neighbor _ a strategy that
those who live in apartment buildings might also be able to use.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, anyone who depends on a computer or fax
machine in the home should invest in the best backup power supply
they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can buy a big unit for the whole circuit or a small one
just for the computer,'' she said, adding that a small unit, also
known as an ``uninterruptible power supply,'' or UPS, can be
purchased for less than $100.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For those whose attempts to organize their home office are
little more than a cyclical battle between order and chaos, there
is always professional help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could talk for hours on this topic,'' said Harriet
Schechter, an organization consultant in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schechter said that the most important thing for anyone
working at home to remember is that the only way to stay organized
is to establish a system for dealing with the reams of paper that
the so-called paperless office seems to produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to set up stacking-tray systems so you can see where
things are and still have a way of organizing them,'' Ms. Schechter
said, adding that for those who would rather not see where things
are, filing cabinets are usually a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't get stuck thinking that you need a big four-drawer
vertical cabinet,'' she said. ``There are some nice lateral file
cabinets available that actually work much better in a home
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ms. Schechter said, it is possible to keep the home
office organized even when the office is the dining room and the
desk is the dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make sure you keep as much as possible on flat trays that
you can move when you have to,'' she said. ``That way you can get
everything off the table, eat and still be able to find what you're
looking for when you put everything back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
