<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A SWISS BANK'S INDUSTRIAL-STRENGTH TRADING CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES S. RUSSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If investment banking has always seemed tradition-bound,
presenting a reassuring solidity through hushed, dark-paneled
quarters swaddled in deep carpets and soft leathers, a 960,000
square-foot complex in Stamford, Conn., offers a revisionist view.
Within the ruddy granite-like precast-concrete exterior, the
Warburg Dillon Read Center works more like an industrial plant than
a brass-lamped men's club.
</P>
<P>
   In the hour or so before the East Coast markets open, traders
spill out of five levels of parking into a glass-walled atrium
where elevators whoosh them up to a factory-sized trading room.
There are few pinstriped suits and no power ties. The trading floor
is a place of polo shirts and chinos.
</P>
<P>
   There is wood paneling and carpeting _ even backlit onyx stone
panels at the lobby _ but the 800 men and women who sit
elbow-to-elbow on what Warburg Dillon Read claims is the largest
column-free trading floor in the world, measuring 158 feet by 240
feet, for a total of 38,000 square feet, have little time to
appreciate it. They each face up to four computer screens and a
bank of phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   This trading operation is the heart of the Warburg Dillon Read
Center, which is entirely devoted to the investment-banking
operations of UBS AG, the Swiss-based banking giant. The trading
floor occupies only one level of the complex. Elsewhere, 1,400
additional staff members are involved in other aspects of
investment banking or in supporting the trading operation (running
the training center or conference areas, for example). As the
newest and perhaps most ambitious large-scale investment-banking
operation to be built in America, UBS has made a $180 million
commitment so far to its vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   In a business as volatile as financial services, a building
project of this scale risks obsolescence the day it opens. During
the project's more than four years of planning and construction,
the Internet and such other middleman-threatening technologies have
become part of the financial scene. Competitors became ever larger
and more diversified _ including UBS itself.
</P>
<P>
   The project was instigated by Swiss Bank, which later bought the
Warburg and then the Dillon Read operations. In June, Swiss Bank
completed a merger with the Union Bank of Switzerland, so the
center, which opened last October, has already been rechristened.
Instead of trying to predict the future, UBS hopes it has built a
facility flexible enough to adapt to it.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the trading center, for example, is a 13-story
office building. The master plan for the center envisions the
addition of two more towers, but if business conditions change, any
or all of the towers could be rented to other tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Another element of the center's adaptability is its expression
of the bank's horizontal organization. ``The bank was not
interested in creating lavish suites that distinguish hierarchy,''
said Mustafa Abadan, the architect in charge of the project for
Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill. ``The managers sit on a mezzanine above
the trading floor. The cafeteria can spill out to terraces. They
put the meeting areas and training areas at the top of building
where the views are best. The idea is that amenities are accessible
to all.''
</P>
<P>
   The trading floor is among the most technology-intense
white-collar environments, and this, too, is in the service of
flexibility and quick response. The wiring for the telephones and
computers alone fills a 4-foot- deep cavity under the floor. It is
readily accessible for the constant rewiring needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can raise the floor level or lower it to make a tiered
trading floor,'' said Markus Buergler, UBS's executive director of
corporate real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement would form ``pits'' such as the ones at
commodity exchanges. ``We have elected to go with a level trading
floor, but we could change it at any time,'' Buergler said. At
present, the company trades in stocks, bonds and foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the wiring cavity is a 1-foot-deep cavity for the
air-exhaust system that draws off the enormous heat generated by
the computer displays. Below that, an entire floor is devoted to
the data systems that support the traders.
</P>
<P>
   Four adjacent pantries and a nearby cafeteria minimize the time
traders are off the floor. They can also refuel at UBS's own
Starbucks coffee bar.
</P>
<P>
   With the immense number of information resources available at
traders' fingertips, crowding so many people into a single room may
seem anachronistic. For all its high-tech trappings, the UBS
trading room bears more than a little resemblance to the grand
skylighted spaces of the great 19th-century bourses, under which
shouting traders frantically waved buy and sell orders.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Buergler said, the trading operation is
appropriately old-fashioned. ``Trading is a group effort,'' he
said, ``not an isolated effort of people looking at a screen or
working by themselves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2NDTA     09-19 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: by themselves.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He described an intricate hierarchy akin to a conductor and
orchestra. Senior traders, or ``market makers,'' use voice and
gesture to guide the work of trading subgroups and junior traders.
Also, a sudden spike in activity across the room may cue traders to
important breaking news outside their market segments. The traders
can react before the news is broadcast. These seconds or minutes
offer his traders a key competitive edge, Buergler said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an environment is not unique to UBS, said Steve Apking, the
interior design partner at Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill. ``Senior
traders everywhere demand these large floorplates,'' Apking said.
``They want visual contact with everyone else and they want maximum
flexibility to grow and shrink groups according to the demands of
clients or markets.''
</P>
<P>
   To offer maximum visibility and layout flexibility, Skidmore
designed the trading floor without columns. Unusual in modern
trading floors, but akin to historic ones, UBS's north face is
wrapped in glass. The daylight balances the electric light for
better screen viewing, and the changing light offers welcome relief
to the stresses of trading, Buergler said.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Bank's expansion outside of its two principal locations in
Manhattan _ most of the employees now in Stamford came from offices
in midtown and downtown _ was controversial. According to Buergler,
30 sites were considered, most within existing buildings, and most
in Manhattan. But there are few New York City sites that could have
accommodated the floor size wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In Stamford, the biggest floor is 106,000 square feet, according
to Abadan, 65,000 of which are devoted to the trading floor _
38,000 square feet of which has no columns. A biggish Manhattan
office building has 40,000 square feet on a floor, and the stairs
and elevator shafts run right up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   No small consideration for Swiss Bank, too, were the financial
incentives and development assistance offered by Stamford and the
state of Connecticut. The state forgave corporate taxes on a
sliding scale that reflects profits and employees at the site. The
writeoffs have been valued at $125 million. Stamford also gave some
of the 12-acre site to the bank and condemned the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford and the state's commitment appear to have paid off in
other ways as well. When Swiss Bank first approached Connecticut
officials in 1993 (actually calling the state's toll-free
business-development line), the city's Class A office-space vacancy
rate was 24 percent, said Stamford Mayor Dannel Malloy, and ``two
or three'' buildings were entirely empty. Stamford's vacancy rate
today, he said, has dropped to 6 percent in Class A buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many positive developments in Stamford,'' Malloy
said, ``but Swiss Bank is a flagship and has certainly assisted in
focusing people's attention on the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stamford did not want another corporate behemoth that
spilled cars but not people onto local streets, so it asked for
design concessions. The architects placed building lobbies and
retail space (including a Morton's steak house) along the street
edges, disguising five levels of parking for 1,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   The company built a small park on the western edge of the site.
It improved sidewalks and planted trees along the side of the site
that parallels Interstate 95. And it contributed funds to extend a
store-lined concourse under the highway, restoring a
downtown-to-rail station link that had been severed by the highway.
</P>
<P>
   If UBS grows as planned, the trading floor can be extended 120
feet east. Full buildout would bring the project to over 2 million
square feet, with 8,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Buergler would not say when the next stage might begin, but he
did say that the trading floor had opened with 800 positions,
thanks to the Swiss Bank-UBS merger, when the original plan was to
start with only 600. For now, at least, the building is adapting to
the financial world's volatility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
