A4330 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-19 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY RACE THAT COUNTS IS THE ONE ON THE FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home-run history. McGwire-Sosa. Sosa-McGwire. First, the chase
for 62. Now, the race for the most. These most glorious of baseball
moments have created a scene remarkably close to goodwill on earth.
</P>
<P>
   How does it compute that a couple of ballplayers swinging for
the fences could have had such a feel-good impact on so many
people, including the nonsports fan?
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully you weren't naive enough to assume Utopia would last.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in today's social environment, the shelf-life for
something this good figured to be about a week. Bingo. Within a
week, a large crane moved in with a wrecking ball attached to its
cable. Let the tearing down process begin.
</P>
<P>
   Racism has become the new focal point. Sammy Sosa, so I've read
and heard, has become the victim of racist motives by the national
sports media and by baseball's hierarchy. In truth, I haven't come
across a definitive charge of racism. But there's been plenty of
hints at it by small minds, many of whom are the usual suspects
when it comes to hiding behind the R-word.
</P>
<P>
   It's an outrageous assumption, and a discredit to Sosa and
everything he's stood for throughout this home-run chase.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, Sosa has become the most popular Latino
athlete this country has ever known. This means he's been embraced
by mainstream America. This means white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's been another Latinino even close to
Sammy in reaching the masses _ not just in baseball, but in any
sport,'' said Luis Mayoral, of the Rangers front office. ``Roberto
(Clemente) became very much respected, but the acclaim for him came
after his death.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral was a long-time media voice in Puerto Rico, and a close
friend of Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy touches everyone in this country, no matter the color or
the nationality,'' he added. ``Sammy really has an angel on his
shoulder because he has the personality and the lifestyle to go
along with his awesome talent. Very, very rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who once shined shoes and sold fruit on the streets of the
Dominican Republic, taught himself English. He speaks well and with
confidence when dealing with a mostly gringo media. But Sammy also
speaks from the heart, and that's why he has become special. Along,
of course, with his home-run swing.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Sosa rained home runs out of Wrigley Field, and
five days after Mark McGwire hit No. 62, so did Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the social commentary from some quarters. Why was
Sosa's No. 62 not given the same national media hysteria treatment
as McGwire's No. 62? And where was commissioner Bud Selig to emcee
the same elaborate postgame ceremony as was held for McGwire? Was
it racism?
</P>
<P>
   Listen closely to the answer. At that particular point, Sosa
didn't deserve what McGwire had received.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy was the second in history to hit 62. Who was the second
person to fly the Atlantic? Did your junior high history book ever
give you that name? There was no record available when Sosa hit his
62nd. McGwire already had done it.
</P>
<P>
   Selig screwed up one thing. Once Sosa reached 60, his office
should have ordered the baseballs used in Cubs' games to carry the
special mark. For Sammy's No. 62, the ball needed to be immediately
identified and shipped to the Hall of Fame. Otherwise, get off
Selig's back.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's regular season ends Sunday. What happens between now
and then will determine if Sosa earns more of the spotlight than
McGwire. The first to reach 62 was once the emphasis. But hitting
the most is the ultimate goal. Who knows, it could be an
achievement that stands for another 30 or 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a week, and home-run history will come full circle. It
will be glorious again. But I do dread to think what might happen,
media-wise, in the next seven days. It was ``racism'' last week.
What's next, Kenneth Starr releasing testimony Monica Lewinsky was
spotted this summer in the clubhouse of both the Cardinals and the
Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   As far as a personal preference for the player who hits the
most, I defer to commentary made a month ago in this newspaper. My
choice then was Sosa, and it's still Sosa. As a Rangers' farmhand,
he was a kid with a delightful personality and outlook on life.
Fame has not changed him one bit.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, I guess, could claim reverse racism. If not, somebody
else probably will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
