<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ARCHERS TAKE AIM AT THE YEAR'S FIRST BIG-GAME SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first big-game hunting season of the year is right around
the corner, but you won't hear any shots fired. Stealth, quietness
and a bit of luck will determine which hunters bag a deer during
the monthlong archery-only season.
</P>
<P>
   The season runs Oct. 3 through Nov. 1 statewide. In addition to
a valid Texas hunting license, archery hunters are required to
purchase a $7 archery stamp, which can be bought separately or when
combined with a Super Combo or Texas resident hunting license.
</P>
<P>
   Because the archery stamp is included in the two license
packages, it is difficult for parks and wildlife officials to
estimate the number of hunters who will take part in the
archery-only season. In 1996, when hunters had to purchase the
stamp separately, the number was estimated at more than 76,880.
</P>
<P>
   In most counties, deer-bag limits are for all seasons. In Brown
County, for example, the limit is four deer, no more than two bucks
per year regardless of whether the deer are taken during the
archery-only season, general season or both.
</P>
<P>
   Turkeys also can be taken during the archery-only season,
although few are harvested by archers, parks and wildlife officials
said. Also, crossbows can be used during the archery season for
deer and turkey only by hunters with an upper-limb disability.
</P>
<P>
   When hunters take to the fields Oct. 3, they likely will find
lots of fresh rubs made by white-tailed bucks. The deer have begun
scraping the velvet from their antlers, although no signs of
rutting have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Recent observations of deer in the Palo Pinto County area, for
example, indicate bucks began losing their velvet about two weeks
ago. Although some deer remain in the velvet, virtually all bucks
are expected to have hardened antlers when the archery season
opens.
</P>
<P>
   The number of white-tailed deer in Texas is estimated at 4
million. Most are in good physical shape despite drought conditions
recently broken in several parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Late-summer rains have turned some areas, such as Lampasas and
portions of Southwest Texas, green almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Antler development might be slightly below average in some areas
hardest hit by the drought. Overall, most adult bucks are expected
to be found with average-size antlers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's archery-only season was plagued by warm to hot
weather. The type of weather hunters can expect this season remains
a mystery, but the recent cool spell at least has given hunters
some hopes for a pleasant opener.
</P>
<P>
   Acorns, one of the deer's favorite natural foods, have begun
falling throughout much of the Cross Timbers and Hill Country
areas, but reports indicate the acorns might be in poor condition
in dry areas. If so, hunting around wildlife feeders might be
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   During any archery-only season, archers should take extra
precautions in mild to warm weather. Rattlesnakes and copperheads
will be moving about, and snake-proof leggings would be a good
addition to hunting gear.
</P>
<P>
   Although the archery season begins more than a month before the
regular season (Nov. 7 in most counties), that doesn't mean archers
have an advantage over hunters who use firearms.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, archery hunting is regarded as the most challenging
type of deer hunting. To be successful, a hunter must be extremely
close to his quarry.
</P>
<P>
   Most firearm hunters will agree that a reasonable shot can be
made at a deer 200 yards away or less. With a bow and arrow, most
archers will not attempt to make a shot at more than 30 yards. Many
hunters limit their shooting range to about 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Many archers will go the entire season without letting a single
arrow fly. The hunting experience and the fellowship with other
hunters will bring them back again next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
