<HEADLINE>
WHICH IS MORE EXCITING _ OPEN-WHEEL OR STOCK-CAR RACING? OPEN
ROCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get two things straight about real race cars:
</P>
<P>
   1. Real race cars have engines in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   2. Real race cars are open-wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Tradin' paint at 180 mph in a fake ``four-door'' NASCAR Winston
Cup Ford Taurus at a venue like Texas Motor Speedway rightfully is
considered an art.
</P>
<P>
   If so, where does that place the art of racing an open-wheel
Indy-car at 220-plus mph at TMS?
</P>
<P>
   On the cutting edge of both chassis/engine technology and driver
courage.
</P>
<P>
   The margin for error in a 1,500-pound Indy-car powered by an
engine cranking out 700 horsepower is next to zero. Every fight for
position has to be measured against the consequences of rubber tire
contacting rubber tire and a probable trip into a concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   Long before NASCAR's act was spiffed-up by R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co. and neatly packaged by ESPN, A.J. Foyt was making a name for
himself in the Indianapolis 500 against an international field.
When Mario Andretti, another Indy 500 champion, felt compelled to
measure himself against the greatest drivers of his day, he went
Formula One racing and won the World Driving Championship.
</P>
<P>
   In their spare time, both icons raced in NASCAR _ and won a deal
called the Daytona 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
