A4334 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-FACEOFF-CON-TEX     09-19 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FACEOFF-CON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH IS MORE EXCITING _ OPEN-WHEEL OR STOCK-CAR RACING? STOCKS
RULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY D. BOGGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's see. Open-wheel racing has the Dallara/Aurora, Lola T-9800
and Nissan Infiniti Indy V-8. ... Stock-car racing has Fords,
Chevrolets and Pontiacs.
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel racing has Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course and the
1.82-mile, 14-turn street circuit winding around Concord Pacific
Place in downtown Vancouver, British Columbia. ... Stock-car racing
has ``the lady in black'' and the ``Bristol stomp.''
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel racing has Mauricio Gugelmin and Marco Greco. ...
Stock-car racing has ``Rainbow Warriors'' and ``The Intimidator.''
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel racing has Robby Gordon. ... Stock-car racing ``had''
Robby Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   There's simply no comparison. Even at open-wheel racing's
ultimate arena, Indianapolis Motor Speedway, it's stock-car racing
that rules.
</P>
<P>
   And little wonder. After all, this American original has actual
``fenders''. Sure, the days when you could drive your Hudson Hornet
from the car lot to the speedway to race are over. But for a real
adrenalin rush, there's nothing better than a Ford and Chevy
tradin' paint on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, let fans settle the matter. Today's Indy Racing League race
at Texas Motor Speedway might draw 70,000. The Texas 500 NASCAR
Winston Cup race in April drew an estimated 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Any questions?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
