<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NEEDS TO BE SMACKED BACK TO REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling David Stern to the principal's office, David Stern to
the office. Now!
</P>
<P>
   It's time for a paddling.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel a sudden swoosh of air during this painful process,
that's Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and America's born-again past-time
leap-frogging your NBA in our popularity poll.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't feel a rush of guilt melting over you for
basketball's impending work stoppage, we're prepared to make you
feel it via a swift kick in the ... right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Plain and simple: You and your greedy owners are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of NBA training camps opening Oct. 6 and the regular
season tipping off Nov. 3 are slimmer than Shawn Bradley, and it's
your fault. In 1995 you signed a Collective Bargaining Agreement so
lucrative that owners rewarded you with a five-year, $40 million
contract. Now you're telling us it's a bad deal and that the league
isn't profitable enough.
</P>
<P>
   We've had one gray-haired leader lying to us all summer, don't
you start.
</P>
<P>
   How much is enough? You are the highest-paid commissioner in
sports, your deputy commissioner (Russ Granik) takes home $4
million and your coaches average more than your players. Above and
beyond that, just last year you signed a new television contract
worth $3 billion. Excuse us if we don't feel moved to pass the hat
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, your stubbornness is a public relations
disaster. If you haven't noticed, baseball is back and Michael
Jordan probably won't be. Despite a riveting Finals in June, us
fans were already getting turned off by rising ticket prices,
falling scores and Gen-X thugs like Latrell Sprewell and Chris
Webber.
</P>
<P>
   If you draw your line in the sand any deeper, just keep on
digging your own grave.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the salary cap has become a mockery with 24 teams and
Jordan by himself over it last year. But how can we believe your
claim that half your 28 teams lost money last year if you refuse to
open your books to an independent auditor?
</P>
<P>
   The way we hear it, the players are willing to compromise. On
Aug. 6 you were presented with a proposal that included testing
players for marijuana use, upping the three-year rookie wage scale
to five and lowering the automatic salary increase from 20 percent
to 11, a move that would save your owners $50 million. And your
reaction? You walked out.
</P>
<P>
   We understand you want a hard salary cap with no exceptions and
that you're seemingly willing to jeopardize the season to get it.
Understand this: you're not going to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The Larry Bird exception _ the one that allows teams to pay its
own free agents regardless of the salary cap _ must fly in some
form. It's called free agency, and it's here to stay. Deal with it.
Seems like the best compromise is to limit it, say allowing a team
to use it only once every five years or so.
</P>
<P>
   After the players miss a couple of checks, you say you will see
their unity crumbling. You can then herd them into a favorable CBA
and harness salaries back to 50 percent of all NBA revenue, even
though both the NFL and baseball operate at a figure over 60
percent. And as for us fans? You're figuring the reason baseball
took such a hit was because it cancelled the 1994 World Series. No
big deal to lop off a month of regular-season games in November,
right? Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There's a drastic difference between the ``financial
instability'' propaganda you promote and the ``yeah, but we could
be making a lot more if we didn't give it to the players'' truth
you feel. As fans we usually don't pick sides in labor wars, but
this one's too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Now get back to class and remember, if it ain't broke ... don't
stall trying to fix it, or hockey might run you over in the hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1902EDT &QL; 
