<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-BRAZIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOYS FROM BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARRETOS, Brazil _ Behind the bucking chutes at the largest
rodeo in South America, Brazil's most popular rodeo athlete
finishes a TV interview then squats for a photo between two small
boys.
</P>
<P>
   Adriano Moraes is larger than life at Brazil's premier rodeo in
Barretos. A massive billboard picturing Moraes stands at one of the
fairground's entrances. Inside booths on the grounds, Moraes is
displayed on life-sized cardboard cutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Moraes, who migrated to Keller five years ago to launch his
bull-riding career in North America, is one of the ``Boys from
Brazil.'' Bull riding was implemented into Brazilian rodeos only 18
years ago, but the country now is producing some of the best bull
riders in the world, like Moraes, a multiple world champion who
makes enough money to commute to North American shows by jetting
from South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most popular cowboy in Brazil,'' said Jose Wilson,
promoter of the annual Professional Bull Riders show in Barretos
that pits North American and Australian competitors against
Brazilians during the city's annual August rodeo. ``Even before
Adriano went to the United States, he was a champion rider in
Brazil. With Adriano doing so well in the United States, it helps a
lot here. It also helps get good cowboys to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, bull riding has become as big as the humps and horns
on the country's rampaging bulls. But the daredevil sport virtually
was non-existent 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many Brazilian rodeos offer trucks and motorcycles
winning bull rider. There are about 150 competitors on the
Brazilian rodeo circuit led by stars like Moraes, the 1994
Professional Bull Riders champion, and Rogerio Ferriera, who is a
nationally ranked competitor on the PBR circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started liking the challenge that bull riding
represented,'' said Tiao Procopio, who is credited with introducing
bull riding to Brazil 18 years ago. ``Until then, prizes were
really low; the bigger prizes were offered in the horse riding
events. But when bull riding prizes were raised in 1989, bull
riding became a big challenge.''  &LR; subheds:Brazilian shuttle
</P>
<P>
   The successful transplant of Moraes' career from South to North
America has spurred the sport's burgeoning growth in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Moraes was inspired to compete in North America
after attending a 1991 bull riding school in Brazil taught by
another ground-breaker, Charlie Sampson, who in 1982 became the
first African-American to garner a Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association world title.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Moraes attended the 1992 National Finals Rodeo in
Las Vegas with Sampson and decided to compete in the United States.
In early 1993, Moraes announced his serious arrival on the North
American rodeo circuit by winning in Tucson, Ariz., which ranks
among the PRCA's top 20 rodeos in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Moraes, then living in Keller, turned heads by winning
the inaugural Professional Bull Riders Bud Light Cup Series title.
The same year, he became only the third man to make qualified rides
on all 10 bulls at the National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has endured groin injuries and two broken legs the
past four years, Moraes has been a regular world title contender.
He now flies to each show from Brazil, making him the first rodeo
competitor to regularly commute to North America from another
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Each trip begins with a two-hour drive from his 150-acre
Brazilian ranch to the Sao Paulo airport. From there, it's a
5,000-mile, 10-hour flight to Dallas. Then there's usually another
connecting flight lasting one to three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Though a round-trip ticket might cost $1,000, the shuttle from
Brazil is financially feasible. A win at a PBR cup series show
offers a competitor about $20,000, making commuting affordable for
a high-profile bull rider like Moraes.
</P>
<P>
   When Moraes stays in the U.S. longer than a weekend, he resides
in the Fort Worth area, his home between 1994 and 1996. But staying
more than a weekend has become a rarity for Moraes, who anxiously
returns to Brazil to join his wife, Flavia, and their first-born,
seven-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so bad,'' Moraes said of commuting. ``I usually can
find a row of seats to lie down on and sleep on the plane. I think
it's a pretty normal way to travel. It's only a 10 hour flight.''
 &LR; subheds:Brazil's blue-chippers
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed as South America's star fullback of rodeo, Moraes, 28, is
among several hard hitting front runners produced in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Among Brazil's bull-riding backfield are colorful players
ranging from Rogerio Ferreira, who has than $100,000 in the PBR
earnings the past two years, to 18-year-old Paulo Klimber who may
be the Brazil's next big international star after pocketing $18,000
in Barretos, to 36-year-old Miltom Rosa, a hearty competitor
despite losing an eye in a rodeo accident.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, a relatively elderly age for a prize winning bull rider,
Rosa probably never will compete in North America. He appears to
love the simple life, working on a cattle ranch about 11/2 hours
away from Barretos. When he is bored, Rosa rounds up a bull and
takes a wild ride, which prepares him for a weekend rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Zealous of bull riding, the sport has been unkind to Rosa. Two
years ago, Rosa lost his right eye when he was hit by a bull's
horn. He declined to compete at Barretos this year after sustaining
an arm injury.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries usually don't deter Rosa's upbeat attitude. ``When
I make a good ride, I feel like Superman,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Rosa, Klimber is among a new breed of Brazilian bull
riders with big dreams traveling and accelerating to stardom in
North America. The son of a restaurant worker, Klimber said his
parents at first balked at his bull riding career.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents thought it was dangerous,'' he said. ``But now that
I'm doing well, my parents are happy. I'm surprised with the
success because I'm so young. But I work hard at this. I train and
exercise every day. I ride about four bulls a week. I swim, I ride
bikes and horses. I don't drink or smoke and I go to church
regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Klimber turned heads at Barretos, winning the first round and
finishing second overall after staying on four of five bulls to
earn $18,000, which should be enough to qualify for the PBR
November Las Vegas finals.
</P>
<P>
   Like a blue-chip college player being signed in the pro draft,
Ferreira, 25, was recruited to the North American circuit a year
ago after finishing second in Barretos for $15,000. It was enough
to advance Ferriera, who regularly stays in the Fort Worth area
when competing in the U.S., to the PBR's 45-man finals last
October.
</P>
<P>
   The boys from Brazil are a special lot in their country. Not
only do they receive some of the billboard treatment Moraes enjoys,
but the sport has afforded them an opportunity to escape the
low-wage life (more than two-thirds of Brazilian households have
total annual incomes of less than $4,300) working on a farm or a
ranch or even in a store in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can to work for $300 a month on a farm or they can put
their lives on the line and ride bulls and make $18,000 in a
week,'' said Forth Worth cowboy Philip Elkins, who has competed in
Brazil on 11 different occasions. ``For them it's a chance of a
lifetime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
