<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4337 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODEO-BARRETOS-TEX     09-19 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-BARRETOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRETOS RODEO IS A SPECTACLE OF SPORT AND CARNIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARRETOS, Brazil _ On a sunny Sunday afternoon at one of the
world's largest rodeos in this country-and-western craving,
agricultural-oriented city, more than 40,000 romping and stomping
fans pack a bowl-shaped rodeo arena, sporting the same look and
hype as a New Year's Day football game.
</P>
<P>
   An invigorated announcer paces the arena floor, kicks up the
dirt and dances a jig as loud, upbeat music cranks. Then, like a
raging bull, he charges toward the crowd, pointing and chanting
into his wireless microphone:
</P>
<P>
   ``Segura!''
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd chants back:
</P>
<P>
   ``Segura!''
</P>
<P>
   The echoing refrain in Portuguese, often repeated before a ride,
translates into ``hang on tight,'' and it pumps the adrenalin of a
cowboy readying himself to lock spurs in a high-leaping, twisting
2,000-pound bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riding in Brazil is like the time I went to a big-time fight
at the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas,'' said Adam Carrillo, a former
National Finals Rodeo qualifier from Stephenville who competed in
bull riding at Barretos. ``It was jam-packed and people were
chanting. It's the same atmosphere at the rodeo in Brazil. They're
yelling loudly because they're loving what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barretos rodeo in Brazil, an 11-day event traditionally
staged in mild August South American winter weather, is like the
Super Bowl in the United States or any NASCAR race with its massive
attendance, spectacles in and around the competition and a carnival
midway surrounding the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Even bigger than the nationally acclaimed Southwestern
Exposition and Livestock Show in Fort Worth, Barretos stages the
marquee livestock and rodeo entertainment extravaganza in Latin
America, this year drawing 1.3 million attendees.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeo has grown so much in Brazil that promoters pay all the
expenses for renowned Fort Worth area bull riders such as Tuff
Hedeman, Adam and Gilbert Carrillo, Philip Elkins, Scooter Hamilton
and Troy Dunn to compete. The sport may be second only to soccer
with 1,200 events contested last year, luring an estimated 45
million fans.
</P>
<P>
   In less than half a century, rodeo has emerged as a big-time,
booming sports business with the 43rd Barretos rodeo billed as
Brazil's inaugural and premier show. Barretos is a remote, small
city, comparable to Waco or Wichita Falls, and located about six
hours northwest of the massive metropolis of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed as the Festa do Peao, or the Festival of Cowboys, the
Barretos stages the nation's equivalent to North America's National
Finals Rodeo, the grand round-up of the nation's elite horsemen and
cattle punchers.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally conducted over the last two weekends in August,
the Barretos rodeo gorges its final performance with more than
twice the spectators as North America's marquee shows such as the
century-old Cheyenne (Wyo.) Frontier Days and the Fort Worth Rodeo
.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Houston Livestock Show Rodeo, which recruits
high-profile singing stars for each performance, fills the
Astrodome with up to 60,000 fans and holds a rodeo in conjunction,
would rival Barretos' attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Through performances running six hours or more, fans sit and
wave their arms and stand and dance the ``Macarena'' atop concrete
bleachers. In Barretos, this is the party of all parties, featuring
fire-works that rival Las Vegas lights, air shows with
smoke-streaming jets and the traditional roping and roughstock
riding events to boot. Eventually, the bull-riding event bucks
between midnight and 2 a.m., the average running time of an entire
performance at Fort Worth's Stock Show Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if people don't know much about the bulls, they come to
the rodeo because they enjoy the party atmosphere,'' said Jao
Marcelino, a Brazilian cowboy who has visited the United States
several times to hone his cutting horse riding skills. ``Ten years
ago, rodeo wasn't respected very much in Brazil. But the mentality
about rodeo is changing. Now, the middle- and high-class people are
beginning to get involved.''  &LR; subheds:A festive outing
</P>
<P>
   At the massive Barretos fairground, which encircles the rodeo
arena, rows of people camp in tents, cook out and bask in the
festive atmosphere, similar to the rush of activity of the infield
during a Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Cowboys football game at Texas Stadium, the rodeo arena
in Barretos is crowned with skyboxes inhabited by high-profile
corporate sponsors ranging from Chevrolet to Brahma, a bullish beer
company. Large balloons with corporate business logos dangle over
the sports facility.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-based American Airlines, which carries about the
majority of air traffic between North and South America, is another
key player. The airline's logos are painted across a bucking chute
and printed on riders' shirts. When sponsors are introduced in the
arena by flag carrying horseback riders, American's slogan,
``Something special in the air'' is sung in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   When fans converge on the town of 110,000 for the weekend, local
residents often rent their homes and leave during the bustling
celebration. In Barretos, on the final Saturday night, the town's
streets are abuzz with cars, rumbling motorcycles and loud music.
Neighborhood streets are lined with vehicles. Amid a brick street
in a residential area, several young girls stand in a straight line
and dance in unison to loud, upbeat music.
</P>
<P>
   At the fairgrounds, which consists of blocks of booths and
exhibits, the influx of patrons turns the facility into a trash
heap, with little effort to toss litter in the scarce drums. As a
result, many locals garner a few extra dollars for bagging the mass
of aluminum cans in this lean area where the minimum wage is $130 a
month. In Brazil, only 1.5 percent of wage earners have annual
incomes of above $17,000, and 52 percent earn less than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are warned to stuff their wallets inside their boots to
avoid thievery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, the police say they will control it and manage''
the unruly behavior, said Nonota de Oliveira, a local English
teacher who served as a translator for North American competitors.
``The police are tolerant as they can be because they are afraid if
they do too much, the tourists won't come back. As a result, it's
pretty dangerous to drive around. People drink, they fight and the
paint the town red.''  &LR; subheds:Southern exposure
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association and
Professional Bull Riders circuits that have garnered a loyal fan
base from cable television, Brazil has no national television
contract that exploits its top rodeos and stars. Yet many TV
cameras converge on the Barretos rodeo, shooting local news pieces
and documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are clued in on the prowess of the nation's top rodeo
athletes by a fast talking announcer who points at a rider in the
chute and rapidly reels off his accomplishments. There's a massive
television screen in the arena end zone that posts competitors' mug
shots and televises their rides live and by instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, no national association existed to sanction all
of Brazil's rodeos. But during the Barretos rodeo, it was announced
that a national organization had been formed to better organize the
burgeoning growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodeo here is not as professional as in the United States,''
said Antonio Carlos Rodriques da Masengo, a popular Brazilian
bullfighting clown. ``The rodeo here is less than 50 years old. By
comparison, it's more than 100 years old in the States. We're still
learning how to rodeo here. The cowboys are good, maybe as good as
the United States, but professionally, we've still got lots to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian rodeo events are almost identical to those in
North America, with calf and team roping, bronc and bull riding and
women's barrel racing. Trucks, however, are awarded to winners in
each event. A $20,000 (U.S.) prize was awarded to the bull riding
winner and the event was sanctioned by the PBR.
</P>
<P>
   All that attracted prominent North American competitors such as
former National Finals team roping qualifier J.D. Yates, Calgary
Stampede $50,000 Ride-off bareback riding winner Roger LaCasse and
Dunn, an Australian transplant from Stephenville. Last year he won
the average at the Professional Bull Riders World Finals in Las
Vegas and finished the year with more than $250,000 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was among 23 bull riders from the PBR, a thriving North
American organization, to compete in Barretos and each traveled at
least 5,000 miles and stayed in South America almost a week. With
competitors from the U.S., Canada, Australia and the United States,
Barretos officials boasted on posters and T-shirts of conducting
South America's largest international rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like riding at the Olympic games,'' Dunn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
