</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS BACK NO LONGER ACHING, STARS' BELFOUR FORESEES `BETTER' SEASON
AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Ed Belfour walked through Stars training camp like
a tourist on a fall retreat.
</P>
<P>
   There were no on-ice incidents to spark controversy, few
requests for interviews, and little time spent camping out in the
training room. Instead, the Stars' emotionally mercurial goalie was
the picture of calm and perfect health _ almost a non-factor.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour passing through camp problem-free might be the best sign
of the times to come out of the five-day workouts in the Rocky
Mountains. The man who fought physical and emotional demons last
year and still posted the lowest goals against average in the NHL
is predicting an even better season in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back feels better than it ever has,'' said Belfour, who
spent an average of three to five hours a day last season tending
to his tender muscles. ``So yeah, I think I should have a better
season. I think I'm going to have a better season.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, to coach Ken Hitchcock, is like the sweet drones of the
bluegrass music he loves so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare him to the start of camp last year when he was
just trying to fit in, I remember he was such a big factor that
everyone was worried about,'' Hitchcock said. ``Now, he just slides
in and slides out, gets his work done and moves on quietly. He
hasn't been a big story here by design, yet we know how important
he is.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense will be the focus this season in part because
Belfour has helped take care of the defense. After coming to the
Stars as an unrestricted free agent, struggling to fit in with his
new defensemen and nursing a back that was constantly a concern,
Belfour still was able to post one of the best campaigns of his
career. Along with the career-best 1.88, the second most wins in
the NHL (37) and the eighth best save percentage (.916), Belfour
also registered the lowest goals-against average in the playoffs
(1.79) among goalies with more than three decisions.
</P>
<P>
   While he finished on a sour note, giving up a some bad goals
while losing a 4-2 Western Conference Finals series to the Detroit
Red Wings, Hitchcock said he couldn't have asked for much more from
the man behind the mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who blames Eddie for us losing, I don't agree with that
at all,'' Hitchcock said. ``If (Red Wings goalie) Chris Osgood had
lost that series, everyone would have been blaming him. He had as
many mistakes as Eddie. Where we fell short is we didn't score
enough goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour twice lost 2-0 games and lost once 3-2. The 3-2 Game 4
loss in Detroit might have been the most difficult because Belfour
took a costly penalty by slashing Martn Lapointe in the groin _
leading to a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no finger-pointing on this team, and that's what makes
it a good team,'' Belfour said. ``I could have made fewer mistakes,
but so could have the rest of the team. You always want those games
back, but you learn from them and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, in fact, earned even more respect from his teammates
when he made an emotional speech to the team after the series loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what kind of personality he has, that he has his
oddities about conditioning and equipment,'' defenseman Craig
Ludwig said of Belfour's back therapy and skate-sharpening routines
that often kept him around the locker room for hours a day last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing about Eddie is he doesn't want any excuses. He
doesn't want to look back and say he didn't give it his best, and
that's the kind of guy you need in there.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars moving out of the Central Division and playing
the Red Wings two fewer times this season, there will be less made
of Belfour's career struggles with the Red Wings. The 33-year-old
Belfour has a 14-24-7 lifetime regular season record against the
Wings. What's more, his past three playoff campaigns have ended in
losses to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and I swept them in four games in 1990,'' he said.
``Those were old times with a different team. I don't think I have
any problem with them. They're a good team and I like playing
against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour acknowledges the Stars' path likely will go through
Detroit if they hope to capture the Stanley Cup this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely one of the teams we'd have to play,''
Belfour said. ``All I can say is if it happens, I know we'll be
ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
