<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARVARD-COLUMBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONS OVERCOME WORRIES TO ROUT IVY CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Columbia's football team had worries to spare. It was
not sure its quarterback, Paris Childress, was good enough to beat
Harvard, the defending Ivy League champion. It feared that its
secondary could not stop Rich Linden, Harvard's dangerous passer.
It did not know how a team that finished a shaky 4-6 last year
would fare against a team that finished 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Saturday, in the season opener for both teams,
Columbia all but humiliated the Crimson in winning, 24-0. The Lions
shut down Harvard's vaunted offense. They made key interceptions,
one putting the ball on the Harvard 1-yard line. They piled up
running yards. They even used Jason Bivens, their strong safety, as
an occasional and successful quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard had won seven straight games, its longest streak since
the 1968 team won eight in a row. The 6,000 or so Homecoming Day
spectators at Columbia's Wien Stadium were hardly prepared for
this.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia dominated from the start. In the first quarter, Bivens
ran a yard for a touchdown. In the second quarter, Neal Kravitz
kicked a 36-yard field goal. In the third quarter, Childress
connected on a 25-yard touchdown pass to Mark Cannan and, 27
seconds later, after linebacker Paul Roland returned an
interception 35 yards, Norman Hayes crashed a yard for the final
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   No part of this upset was more intriguing than the heroics of
Bivens, a 5-foot-7-inch, 185-pound senior from Richmond, Calif. In
high school, he was an all-league quarterback. Two years ago, he
was Columbia's starting tailback. Last year, he injured a knee in
the second game of the season and did not play again. This year, he
was listed as a strong safety (or, in Columbia's terminology,
rover) and played there Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's offense normally plays from a pro set. Here, it mixed
in occasional split backs and I formations. It also had a few
Bivens specials, all run from an old-fashioned wishbone. One of
those plays, a naked bootleg, gained 11 yards.
</P>
<P>
   For a university renowned more for academics than athletics,
Harvard has a distinguished and wide-based sports history. It
fields teams in 41 men's and women's varsity sports, more than any
other Division I college in the nation. Almost one of every five
Harvard students is a varsity athlete, and the school has more of
them than Michigan and Ohio State combined.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Ivy League football title last year was its first in
10 years. The nine victories were its most since its 1919 Rose Bowl
champion won nine. Last year's 301 points were the most for a
Harvard team since the 1894 _ that's right, 1894 _ Harvard team
scored 334 in 13 games. And that 1894 team fattened up by beating
two prep schools (Exeter and Andover), the Chicago Athletic Club
and the Boston Athletic Association by a combined score of 170-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
