<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARCA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCA VICTORY EXHAUSTS GIBSON AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mark Gibson didn't get to enjoy his victory
in the ARCA Z-MAX 250 until about an hour after taking the
checkered flag yesterday at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of the late summer heat and the emotions of
winning left Gibson physically and mentally exhausted, and after a
short ceremony in victory circle he was taken to the infield care
center.
</P>
<P>
   After being cooled down and rehydrated, Gibson finally was able
to savor the victory.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't mind waiting a few extra minutes, though. He has
already been waiting a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just the emotional part of it as much as the
physical part of it,'' Gibson said. ``We won a year ago last
weekend at St. Louis, and we expected to win three, four, five
races this year. We have been close. We've had a good year but not
a great year. We wanted to win this so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson got his second career victory by nine seconds over Bill
Baird, who finished second for the third consecutive race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's getting old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering he wrecked his primary car in practice Friday
morning and had to qualify and race in his backup, he'll take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened to me this weekend, tearing a new car up,
we're happy,'' Baird said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ciochetti was just behind Baird, followed by Bobby Gerhart
and Gus Wasson.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had come close several times this season, with two
second-place finishes and three thirds. Although he hadn't won a
race, he came to Texas second in the Automobile Racing Club of
America points race.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a distant second behind Frank Kimmel, who has won
nine races.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel looked like he was going to make it 10 in the early
stages yesterday. He sat on the pole and led the first 27 laps.
However, on the 32nd lap, the handling problems that plagued him in
practice and qualifying resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel got loose coming out of Turn 2 with Gibson right behind
him and went sideways. Gibson hit the brakes and might have given
him a slight tap before Kimmel slid down and hit the retaining wall
down the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't Mark's fault,'' Kimmel said. ``I was loose before he
got to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kimmel out, Gibson began to dominate. He took the lead on
the 43rd lap and was in front for 119 of the final 125 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it would have been different if Frank had been
there,'' Gibson said. ``He had as good a car, or close to as good a
car, as we did. But we'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The only suspense came after a restart on lap 128.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had pulled away on every other restart, but Baird and
Ciochetti got around him this time.
</P>
<P>
   Baird held the lead for three laps, then Ciochetti went in
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we went by them and pulled away from them, I thought
it was ours,'' said Ciochetti, who was looking for his first ARCA
victory. ``But you've got lapped traffic, guys running 50 miles an
hour off the pace and you're trying to be cautious to not run into
one of them, and the others guys got a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird and Gibson got around Ciochetti when he got caught in
traffic, then Gibson passed for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic might have been a factor at that moment, but it didn't
have anything to do with who won the race. Gibson gradually pulled
away during the final 32 laps and won easily.
</P>
<P>
   His crew had put on scuffed tires instead of brand new slicks on
the final pit stop, and he said it took a few laps for them to warm
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had already run that set of tires, so we knew what we could
do after about three laps,'' Gibson said. ``I was surprised they
got by me, but once the tires came in I knew we still had the
dominant race car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
