u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     09-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALTIMORE BEATS NEW YORK, 5-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The paleness in David Cone's face over the last week
run contrary to his insistence that his flu had dissipated. ``I'm
getting a better,'' he would say, in a congested and nasal voice.
</P>
<P>
   Cone treats illness the way he pitches: just find a way to get
through, just figure out a way to survive. Try as he might on
Saturday, however, Cone could not force his body to respond, in a
5-3 loss to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Ponson, the Orioles' hard-throwing rookie, shut the
Yankees down for the second time this season, holding them
scoreless into the eighth inning. The Yankees have 47 losses (and
106 victories), and even if they won each of their final nine
games, they cannot match the single-season record for victories,
116 by the 1906 Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitched seven innings to surpass 200 for the season,
activating a clause in his contract that gives him the option of
playing for the Yankees for $5.5 million next season or becoming a
free agent. Cone and Yankees General Manager Brian Cashman say they
have not discussed the 1999 season, though hope something is worked
out; logic suggests that once the season is over, Cone will try
parlaying his option into a longer contract.
</P>
<P>
   Cone earned his 18th victory on Aug. 17, with six weeks
remaining in the regular season. Cone's first 20-victory season
since 1988 seemed certain. But Cone (19-7) has only won once in his
last six starts, and he pitched Saturday at far less than optimum
condition.
</P>
<P>
   A flu-like virus began moving around the Yankees' clubhouse in
New York last week, with Tino Martinez, Tim Raines, Manager Joe
Torre and then Cone all infected. Martinez and Raines lay on tables
in a trainer's room last Sunday, side by side.
</P>
<P>
   But they recovered, and Torre has improved. Cone, however,
remains affected. As the team flew here from Tampa, Fla., late
Thursday night, a wave of nausea came over Cone, and he dragged
himself into the clubhouse Friday. There was never any doubt he
would pitch Saturday, Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   A neon sign on the facing on the third deck of the left-field
stands indicated that Cone was throwing relatively hard, his
fastball 90-92 miles an hour (on a radar gun with liberal
readings), and yet early on it was apparent that his pitches did
not possess their typical sharpness. All day he would be plagued by
cheap hits, bloopers _ unlucky, in one sense, and in another, a
sign that Cone was having trouble mustering enough to put away
hitters as he does normally. Cone had 10 or more strikeouts in each
of his last three outings before Saturday, but had only five
against the Orioles, reaching 201 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   He competed gamely, calling out his catcher Joe Girardi in the
first inning to discuss a possible adjustment, staring in several
times in disagreement with Umpire Fieldin Culbreth's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, as the Yankees walked off the field, Martinez, the
first baseman, tapped a downcast Cone on the backside: hang in
there, man.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles opened the game with four consecutive hits,
scoring two runs, and before Cone pitched his way out of further
damage. In the third inning, Cone allowed a high, chop hit with two
outs _ Cone shaking his head in disbelief _ and then walked Rafael
Palmeiro, before retiring the rookie Calvin Pickering on a fly to
left. B.J. Surhoff blooped a hit in the fourth, and the Orioles had
two on and two out when Roberto Alomar smacked a high drive down
the right-field line, where Paul O'Neill charged and slid and
caught the ball, saving two runs. Surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson opened the fifth with a double, however, the ball
pressing the chalk of the right-field foul line, and Eric Davis
bounced a double off the right-field wall and Palmeiro lined a
single to left-center, three batters and three hits. A double play
prevented further damage, with the Yankees trailing Ponson, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson pitched six and two-thirds shutout innings against the
Yankees June 16, and dominated them Saturday in much the same
manner: Power stuff, fastballs of 94-95 mph and hard sliders, lots
of strikes. Of the 125 pitches Ponson threw in seven and a third
innings, 79 went for strikes. He allowed just two walks, and the
Yankees did not get their first hit until the fourth, when Bernie
Williams singled.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson struck out Chuck Knoblauch and Derek Jeter to begin the
game and never really was in any jeopardy. Only twice did a
Yankees' base runner move into scoring position _ Scott Brosius in
the fifth inning, and Jeter in the sixth _ and Ponson got through.
</P>
<P>
   Cone will have one more chance for his 20th victory, when he
faces Tampa Bay at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
