<SLUG> BC-FBC-RUTGERS-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE ROMPS, AS RUTGERS MAKES IT EASY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ A high snap. An interception. A fumble. All
within 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers took the quickest path to defeat against heavily favored
Syracuse Saturday: self-destruction. Not that fewer mistakes would
have changed the outcome. There are only so many turning points in
a 70-14 rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to play a perfect game to win this football
game and turnovers would have to go our way,'' Rutgers linebacker
Aaron Brady said. ``That didn't happen for us. Pretty much anything
that could go wrong went wrong for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the soul-searching resume for the Scarlet Knights (1-2, 0-2
Big East). Rutgers has lost its last three games to Syracuse by an
aggregate 162-17 score and has dropped the last 12 games in the
series, which the Orangemen lead, 24-4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights' losing streak against Division I-A teams
grew to 16 as they gave up the most points in a game since Yale
beat them, 70-0, in 1890. Coach Terry Shea's three-year record at
Rutgers is now 3-22.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights have a week to regroup for their homecoming
date with Army, which is 1-1. Syracuse (2-1, 2-0), which is ranked
No. 13 in the Associated Press poll, resumes its difficult
non-conference schedule at North Carolina State (2-1) after a bye
week.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Syracuse held leads of 35-0 and 42-7 before halftime.
In moving to three of its first four scores, Syracuse had to travel
a total of 55 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen got three short touchdown runs by fullback Rob
Konrad, two long touchdowns by receiver Kevin Johnson and two
medium sprints into the end zone by running back Kyle McIntosh. The
Orangemen rushed for 346 yards to Rutgers' 55.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't stop them from the first quarter to the fourth
quarter, so we've got some real areas of concern right now,'' Shea
said.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's lopsided victory hurt quarterback Donovan McNabb's
Heisman chase. McNabb, who was benched after one series in the
second half, completed 8 of 12 passes for 119 yards and 1
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb's most spectacular play did not show up on his stat
sheet. With Syracuse ahead, 35-0, McNabb sold the Rutgers defense
on a fake handoff to McIntosh, hid the ball behind his back and let
Johnson pluck the ball on a reverse. Johnson raced 52 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Rutgers could glean anything positive from the game,
defensive back Alan Davis hesitated, exhaled loudly, and said, ``I
don't think we gave up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0188 </DOCNO>
