u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TAPES-BOS &LR;      09-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE BRACES FOR RELEASE OF CLINTON'S TESTIMONY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials braced for a new blast of
damaging revelations from the scheduled release tomorrow of
President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony and reams of
graphic material involving his affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The volumes of such sexually explicit minutiae, a Democrat on
the House Judiciary Committee said, ``will send America into a
fury.''
</P>
<P>
   But in sharp contrast to the elaborate, two-part rebuttal the
White House issued to the first round of disclosures from
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, Clinton's damage-control team
was preparing no major counterattack tomorrow. White House
officials were hoping instead for the new burst of material to blow
up in the hands of House Republicans who engineered its speedy
release.
</P>
<P>
   As both parties tried to stake out the high ground, House
Judiciary Committee member Martin T. Meehan of Massachusetts on
Saturday echoed many fellow Democrats and White House officials in
criticizing the release of another round of provocative material.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Judiciary Committee is expected to
vote by early October to recommend launching a full impeachment
inquiry of Clinton on 11 allegations of perjury, witness tampering,
obstruction of justice, and abuse of the power of his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't think people need this kind of detail,''
Meehan said of the sexually explicit material that is scheduled to
be unsealed. ``It could conceivably backfire on the Republicans for
releasing it so quickly, particularly without even reviewing all of
it first.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle is scheduled to start tomorrow at 9 a.m., as
several television networks begin airing an unedited, four-hour
videotape of Clinton's testimony before Starr's prosecutors. The
remarkable session is expected to show Clinton as the public has
never seen him, in a testy encounter marked by anger, profanity,
and, Starr alleges, perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's deputies will be seen asking Clinton intimate details
about his liaisons with Lewinsky in a hallway and bathroom near the
Oval Office, and about his alleged attempts to cover up the
adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders continued to come under fire Saturday
for scheduling the videotape's release on the Jewish New Year and
on the day Clinton delivers his annual address to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the videotape, 2,800 pages of supporting
documents are scheduled to be released tomorrow, including
transcripts of Lewinsky's grand jury testimony and her interviews
with the FBI, which provide extremely explicit details of her
sexual episodes with Clinton in the White House and in telephone
conversations. The material is expected to be distributed on the
Internet as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope parents will exercise parental guidance,'' said
Representative Lamar Smith, a Texas Republican who serves on the
Judiciary Committee. ``We made a good-faith effort to try to
eliminate the public disclosure of the most salacious material, but
there are a few exceptions we deemed necessary because they go to
substantiating Starr's report.''
</P>
<P>
   The material to be released tomorrow also includes Secret
Service records of Clinton's and Lewinsky's White House movements,
telephone records, Lewinsky's computer messages, and her written
notes. It also includes documents on efforts by Vernon E. Jordan
Jr., a prominent Washington lawyer and Clinton insider, to help
Lewinsky find a job in New York as part of the president's alleged
attempt to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the documents are said to include transcripts of
Clinton's phone messages to Lewinsky, a list of items the FBI
seized from Lewinsky's apartment, and FBI lab reports on Clinton's
blood and on Lewinsky's blue dress.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the Goverment Printing Office were working through
the night to print the 2,800-page volume for the 535 members of
Congress, hundreds of news media outlets, and the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee blacked out about 120 sections of the
material they considered sexually explicit and irrelevant, possibly
damaging to individual reputations, or vital to national security.
</P>
<P>
   But some members, including Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia
Republican and dogged Clinton foe, won support from the GOP
majority to make public several of the censored sections involving
crude details of the sexual relationship between Clinton and
Lewinsky. ``If Americans have a problem with the detail,'' Barr
said, ``then they have a problem with the activity the president is
engaged in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton avoided public comment on the matter Saturday as he
mingled with House members who attended his weekly radio address in
the Oval Office. But several Democratic lawmakers spoke out after
the session.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Melvin L. Watt, a North Carolina Democrat who
sits on the Judiciary Committee, said the highly partisan,
preliminary review of Starr's allegations provides scant evidence
that ``we're going to have a fair process.''
</P>
<P>
   Watt said he hoped the public reacts to the Clinton videotape
``with outrage at the notion that we have undermined our most
serious constitutional obligation ... to protect individual
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The material to be released tomorrow is part of the 18 boxes of
material that Starr recently delivered to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining in the other boxes is the grand jury testimony of
other witnesses, including Jordan; Lewinsky's former friend, Linda
Tripp; and Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Under a House resolution, all the material must be released by
Sept. 28, except sections that are blacked out or withheld by the
Judiciary Committee. The panel has yet to schedule a meeting to
discuss additional releases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PENNSTATE-PITT-NY     09-19 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNSTATE-PITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NITTANY LIONS HOLD ON FOR 20-13 VICTORY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Joe Paterno might not have stuck around for 301
victories if they all came like this, with far too many turnovers
and dropped passes to satisfy a perfectionist.
</P>
<P>
   But with Penn State clinging to a 13-6 lead over Pittsburgh in
the final minute of the third quarter Saturday, Kevin Thompson
lofted a pass along the sideline and Charlie Fields snuck around
cornerback Tray Crayton, caught the ball at the Panthers' 40-yard
line and raced untouched for a 60-yard touchdown. The eighth-ranked
Nittany Lions held on for a 20-13 victory, improving to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to dismiss the game as a letdown, a blip on the
schedule for Penn State between Paterno's 300th victory celebration
last week and a meeting with No. 1 Ohio State on Oct. 3. But it's
never just another game when the opponent is Pittsburgh, in what
could be one of the final meetings in a rivalry that has lasted for
105 years.
</P>
<P>
   With conference schedules taking precedence over tradition and
emotion, and the rivalry set to expire after 2000, Paterno and the
Nittany Lions had no chance of overlooking this one. How could
they, as the streets surrounding Pitt Stadium filled with fans of
both sides chanting the taunts that have lasted through 94
meetings? The crowd of 56,743 was the largest at Pitt Stadium since
the same two teams combined for a record crowd of 57,158 nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was over, the fans who had driven two and a half
hours from Happy Valley had the last word. But Penn State won only
after shaking off a sloppy start. The victory was Penn State's
sixth straight over the Panthers, with two more games scheduled in
the series. Penn State holds the series lead with a 49-41-4 mark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the third-quarter touchdown, Thompson had receivers far
more open on many occasions, but the junior quarterback was too
strong, overthrowing them time after time. Finally, he simply
lofted the ball up and let Fields find his way to it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The play gave the Nittany Lions breathing room and allowed them
to attack Pittsburgh quarterback Matt Lytle. Running for his life,
Lytle was sacked twice on the next drive and the Panthers did not
cross midfield again _ on a pass-interference call _ until 4
minutes 46 seconds remained in the game. Lytle scrambled for a
24-yard gain that gave Pittsburgh a first down at the Nittany
Lions' 16-yard line. Two plays later, Lytle's pass for Kenney
Ketchen in the end zone was broken up, but the Lions were whistled
for pass interference again and the Panthers had first-and-goal
with 3:30 to play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lytle, despite the pounding he had taken in the second half,
kept the ball himself and ducked under defenders to score on a
quarterback sneak with 3:26 to play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' defense then held, getting Lytle the ball on the
Pittsburgh 43-yard line with under two minutes remaining. But on
first down, Lytle was sacked by Courtney Brown and LaVar Arrington.
On the next play, linebacker Brandon Short chased Lytle down,
forcing Pittsburgh into a third-and-25 at its own 28-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   With 56 seconds left, the Panthers called time out, with Coach
Walt Harris scouring his playbook for an emergency play. But he
received only more of the same, as Arrington pulled Lytle down for
a 2-yard loss. On fourth down, Lytle fired deep for Ketchen, but
Askari Adams broke up the play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions struck first, scoring on a 16-yard run by
fullback Mike Cerimele in the first quarter; even on that play,
Cerimele fumbled as he reached the goal line. Cerimele was able to
recover the ball in the end zone, but it nevertheless was one of
three Penn State fumbles in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State was able to take a 10-0 lead in the second quarter
after a Pittsburgh fumble gave the Nittany Lions the ball at the
Panthers' 23-yard-line. Travis Forney connected on a 34-yard field
goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh racked up 153 yards of offense and 12 first downs in
the half, but could not get on the board until the final minutes
when Paul Ruzila converted a 45-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, not content to sit on the ball, tried again to push
toward the end zone, but Sam Crenshaw dropped a short pass and
Thompson then overthrew Corey Jones as he streaked down the left
sideline, 5 yards beyond the nearest defender. It was fitting that
the half ended that way for the Lions, who began the game with a
16-yard run from Cordell Mitchell, but saw him ruin a 9-yard run on
the second play by fumbling the ball away. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
