<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PATTERN-BOS &LR;      09-19 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PATTERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S FATE MAY LIE IN HUNT FOR COMMON THREADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The implication was first made in Attorney General
Janet Reno's request to expand Kenneth W. Starr's investigation in
January: that some of the Clinton scandals might have common
elements, involving improper attempts to influence witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   It was raised again this summer by House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
who declared that it might be necessary to show ``a pattern of
criminal behavior'' to justify impeaching President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the House Judiciary Committee grapples with Starr's
report on the president's relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky, and
Starr investigates further allegations of obstruction of justice,
many in Washington are wondering about the extent to which other
Clinton scandals could become part of the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fate, some increasingly believe, may lie in the
committee's ability to move beyond the sex-saturated Lewinsky
matter to a broader indictment of the president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's report reveals some links among the claims against
Clinton, such as Vernon E. Jordan Jr.'s role in securing job offers
for Lewinsky and Clinton confidant Webster Hubbell, and the sheer
number of alleged attempts to hide physical evidence, from
Lewinsky's gifts to the famous box of billing records from Hillary
Rodham Clinton's law firm.
</P>
<P>
   But whether those similarities and the broad arc of allegations
against the Clintons amount to a pattern of behavior, let alone one
worthy of impeachment, are matters of sharp disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Some constitutional scholars reject the idea that acts that
would not by themselves justify impeachment could, when lumped
together, imperil Clinton's presidency. And they warn that playing
connect-the-dots with Clinton's scandals can be inherently
prejudicial, that merely adding to the number of suspicious acts
does not prove that even one of them is a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's critics insist that Clinton, in lying about
his affair with Lewinsky and covering it up, was merely acting out
a career-long pattern of subverting the truth. Focusing narrowly on
the Lewinsky matter, they say, obscures the fact that Clinton's
deceptions go way beyond his personal life, and pervade his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have obstruction of justice and perjury in nearly every
Clinton scandal, which explains why these other scandals, Chinagate
and Filegate in particular, should be looked at before the Monica
Lewinsky case,'' said Larry Klayman, chairman of Judicial Watch, a
conservative legal group that has filed 19 cases against the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen it in a number of different settings _ an effort to
destroy evidence and silence witnesses,'' Klayman added.
</P>
<P>
   Most legal scholars consider Starr's allegation of obstruction
of justice by Clinton, if proven, more worthy of impeachment than
his claim that Clinton perjured himself by lying about his affair
with Lewinsky. The case for obstruction centers on Clinton's
alleged retrieval of gifts he gave to Lewinsky, at a time when she
was under subpoena to turn over the items to lawyers in the Paula
Jones sexual-harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   According to Starr, Lewinsky testified that she suggested to
Clinton on Dec. 28, 1997, 11 days after receiving the subpoena,
that she might be better off returning the gifts, and that he
responded either ``Let me think about it'' or ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, the president's secretary, Betty Currie, picked
up some of the presents from Lewinsky's apartment. Lewinsky said
Currie told her Clinton had sent her to collect the items. Currie,
however, testified that she believes Lewinsky, not Clinton, had
asked her to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   In past allegations, members of Clinton's inner circle have been
accused of shielding potential evidence. On the evening of the
suicide of White House deputy counsel Vince Foster in 1993, Maggie
Williams, chief of staff to Mrs. Clinton, searched Foster's office
and carried out some folders, according to testimony by a Secret
Service officer. Williams testified that she removed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Foster had been advising the Clintons on some aspects of the
Whitewater real estate case. Investigators were interested in
documenting the extent of Mrs. Clinton's legal representation of
James and Susan McDougal, the Clintons' business partners. Billing
records were important for a range of reasons, including verifying
some of Mrs. Clinton's statements.
</P>
<P>
   The records, believed to have been obtained by the Clintons
during the 1992 presidential campaign, were subpoenaed in 1994. Two
years later, they turned up on a table in the White House book
room. No one has offered an explanation for the two-year delay in
producing them.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in a case examining whether the late Commerce
Secretary Ron Brown rewarded top Democratic campaign contributors
with seats on overseas trade missions, Brown's business partner,
Yolanda Hill, said in an affidavit that Brown told her that two top
Clinton aides asked him to delay turning over key documents until
after the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   After obstruction of justice, a major assertion in Starr's
impeachment report is that Clinton attempted to interfere with
potential witnesses against him, principally by attempting to
secure Lewinsky's silence by having Jordan help her get a job.
Lewinsky, who had already requested Clinton's help in her job
search, suggested that Jordan might provide some contacts. Later,
Jordan testified, he briefed Clinton after obtaining an offer for
Lewinsky from a holding company controlled by Revlon head Ronald
Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a Revlon board member, had earlier used his company ties
to secure $63,000 in consulting fees for Webster Hubbell, at a time
when Hubbell was under criminal investigation. Hubbell subsequently
refused to cooperate with Starr, leading Starr to investigate
whether the White House helped arrange contracts for Hubbell in an
attempt to buy his silence.
</P>
<P>
   Another claim of interfering with a potential witness arose
recently when Dolly Kyle Browning, a high school classmate of
Clinton's, filed suit against the president, saying a top White
House aide threatened her into watering down the story of her
sexual relationship with Clinton. Browning later was a witness in
the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   To some conservatives like Ann Coulter, an attorney and author
of a book making an argument for Clinton's impeachment, these cases
and many others paint the picture of a president who repeatedly
subverts justice.
</P>
<P>
   But some specialists say Coulter, Klayman, and other legal
conservatives are mixing unlike elements in their zeal to tar
Clinton. For example, they say, Clinton never has been implicated
in the missing billing records or the alleged retrieval of items
from Foster's office. And to invoke those cases as arguments for
impeachment, they say, Clinton's critics would have to show he at
least had knowledge of alleged abuses going on around him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
