<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NEVADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON IS TOLD TO WAIT ANOTHER 14 DAYS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ Mike Tyson kept his cool on Saturday. Now he
will have to cool his heels for another two weeks, until the Nevada
State Athletic Commission meets again to consider his application
for a license to box in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing that lasted 6 hours 15 minutes in a suite at
Cashman Baseball Stadium here, the members of the commission voted
to continue their hearing until Oct. 3. The chairman, Elias Ghanem,
told Tyson that the commission wanted him to undergo a
psychological evaluation and have a report back to the commission
no later than Sept. 28 if he wanted it to render a decision as to
his mental fitness to return to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   After arguing between Tyson's lawyers and lawyers from the
Nevada Attorney General's office, an agreement was hammered out in
a hallway adjacent to the suite during a 45-minute break near the
end of the hearing that will allow Tyson to choose to be evaluated
at either the Mayo Clinic, the Scripps Clinic or the UCLA Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing needs Mike Tyson if boxing can stand Mike Tyson,'' said
Glenn Carano, the newest member of the Nevada commission, who has
been with the group for just a year. ``To Mike Tyson's credit, I
appreciated his remorsefulness today and I think he feels sorry
about the biting incident. Now, it's just a matter of his mental
fitness to return to the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Carano would not say how he would have voted had he needed to
Saturday, and he would not divulge how he will vote if the
psychological evaluation comes back and Tyson is deemed mentally
fit to return to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   During a contentious exchange between Tyson's lawyer, Dale
Kinsella, and a senior deputy attorney general, Kirk Hendrick, over
whether Tyson would waive his right to confidentiality with regard
to the psychological report, Tyson said: ``Nothing in my life is
private. What do you want to know?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's boxing license was revoked by Nevada after he bit
Evander Holyfield on both ears during their heavyweight
championship bout in Las Vegas on June 28, 1997. Tyson was allowed
to re-apply for his license after a year, although the commission
made clear Saturday that the revocation was for life and it was
under no obligation to hear any more testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Nave, a commission member and a vocal critic of
Tyson's new adviser, Shelly Finkel, said he was torn. He said he
liked Tyson and did not want to deny his application, forcing him
to sit out another year, but he also did not want a decision
Saturday to come back to haunt the commission. Nave was concerned
that Tyson had spent a total of only 19 hours with psychologists
and psychiatrists over the last few months, and his time with them
had come recently. Nave was also critical of Finkel's decision to
take Tyson before the New Jersey State Athletic Control Board
first, before coming back to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unsatisfying conclusion to a long day for all
involved. Unlike the New Jersey hearing in July, when a Tyson
outburst during the final stages was captured on camera, Tyson
managed to keep his emotions in check Saturday. The only visible
signs of frustration were when he would rub his head with both
hands and cover his eyes during the tedious legal arguments being
volleyed back and forth by the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who had arrived on a red motorcycle, left the meeting
without commenting. When he tried to leave, the motorcycle would
not start. He asked Finkel whether anyone had tampered with his
motorcycle before he slammed his helmet on the ground, hopped into
a green Mercedes and hustled up a ramp leading out of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expected they were going to rule,'' Finkel said. ``It was
frustrating. I came in thinking we had done everything necessary to
get it done. But in two weeks we'll have a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee seemed divided over whether to grant Tyson a
license Saturday, without any stipulations that he get
psychological counseling, or whether to reject his application
outright and make him wait another year to apply. Commissioner
Luther Mack said he was troubled by allegations that Tyson was in a
scuffle with two elderly men after a traffic accident in
Gaithersburg, Md., last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella told the commissioners that they could not ask Tyson
questions about the allegations that he had punched one man in the
chest and kicked another in the groin, because the matter is
pending before the courts. Tyson has been charged with misdemeanor
assault in connection with the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella tried to assuage the commissioners' concern over the
incident by releasing a report from a private investigator who had
interviewed a police officer on the scene who said that one man did
not look like he had been struck and from a witness who said that
Tyson had not done anything but get out of his car following the
accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
