<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SOLHEIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLE GETS DEEPER FOR EUROPEANS AT SOLHEIM CUP  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ For the United States at the Solheim Cup, it was
another day of steady play under pressure, with many players making
important contributions. For Europe, it was another day of missed
opportunities, missed putts and deflating defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Moving closer to victory, the United States won five of eight
matches Saturday to take a commanding 10{-5{ lead over Europe in
the biennial match-play competition. As the defending champion, the
United States needs just 3{ points in Sunday's 12 singles matches
to reach the 14 points needed to retain the cup. As the challenger,
Europe needs 9 more points to take the cup away.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult will it be for Europe to win 9 points on Sunday?
Consider this. The United States has dominated singles play in the
previous two Solheim Cups, holding an 18-4 advantage. By the time
play ended Saturday, even Europe's top players admitted they were
in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all play to our potential, I believe we can still win
the Solheim Cup, but if we don't, we're going to get beaten quite
badly,'' said Laura Davies, who was one of the few bright spots for
Europe Saturday, winning both of her matches. ``So far, we haven't
holed enough putts.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has been making putts all over Muirfield
Village Golf Club. Juli Inkster earned Saturday's final point in
dramatic fashion, making a 45-foot birdie putt that gave her and
Meg Mallon a 2-and-1 victory over Liselotte Neumann and Charlotta
Sorenstam in fourball competition. In Saturday afternoon's other
fourball matches, Annika Sorenstam and Catrin Nilsmark of Europe
defeated Betsy King and Rose Jones, 5 and 3; Davies and Lisa
Hackney defeated Tammie Green and Chris Johnson, 2-up, and Donna
Andrews and Sherri Steinhauer of the United States defeated Marie
de Lorenzi and Helen Alfredsson, 4 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   However, the United States set the tone in the morning, winning
three of four foursomes matches by riding the strong play of Dottie
Pepper and Pat Hurst, who both raised their records to 3-0. Pepper
and Inkster defeated Alfredsson and de Lorenzi, 1-up; Hurst and
Kelly Robbins defeated Neumann and Nilsmark, 1-up; and Andrews and
Steinhauer defeated Annika Sorenstam and Catriona Matthew, 3 and 2.
Davies and Charlotta Sorenstam recorded the only morning point for
Europe, defeating Brandie Burton and Mallon, 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the day's matches were symbolic of how the competition
has unfolded. When the United States has needed key shots or
crucial putts, many players have stepped forward. And as the
competition has progressed, Europe has become more frustrated.
Davies, the longest hitter in the competition, was furious on the
11th tee Saturday afternoon, upset that the tee box had been moved
to the left after the morning matches. The new position made it
more difficult for Davies to reach the par-5 hole in two shots, but
an LPGA official, Jim Haley, denied that the tee box had been moved
with Davies in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not set up the course for any individual player or
team,'' Haley said.
</P>
<P>
   The morning's final two matches were both decided on the par-4,
395-yard 18th hole, and both matches went to the United States.
Pepper and Inkster were tied with Alfredsson and de Lorenzi as they
walked to the 18th green, and with the United States holding a
6{-3{ lead, both teams knew that Europe needed a victory, or at
least a half point. Pepper and Inkster made par, but de Lorenzi hit
a poor chip shot from the rough that rolled 15 feet past the hole,
and Alfredsson missed the difficult par putt wide right.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes later, things got even better for the United
States and worse for Europe, when Robbins and Hurst secured their
victory on the 18th hole. Nilsmark had a chance to make a 20-foot
putt for birdie that would have won the hole and evened the match,
salvaging one-half point for Europe. Nilsmark struck the putt
smoothly, and it looked as if it might fall, but it rimmed the cup
and stayed out. Nilsmark stared at the hole dejectedly. That gave
Hurst a chance to win the match with her 6-foot par putt, and she
did not miss. When the putt fell, Hurst and Robbins hugged in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought that Hurst, a Solheim Cup rookie, would
be 3-0? ``I never dreamed that,'' said Hurst, winner of one LPGA
major this year, the Nabisco Dinah Shore. ``But I'm really enjoying
all of this. We just have to keep it going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
