<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      09-19 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT MARLINS, 4-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The pressure was squarely on John Franco's slight
frame once more. And it was excruciatingly heavy. But instead of
buckling Saturday as he did on Friday night, he survived a scare
and kept the Mets from missing another opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath a blanket of boos, Franco walked two Florida Marlins
batters to open the ninth inning and hit another. But he escaped
from a bases-loaded situation with a strikeout to save a 4-3
victory, one that allowed the Mets to tie the Cubs in the National
League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster was averted. Franco leaped in the air, a far cry from
his slumped-shoulder walk off the field Friday night. This time he
did not allow the Marlins to slip away. And once again the Mets did
it the only way they know how: with dramatic flair.
</P>
<P>
   They also pulled off the victory with the help of the animated
Turk Wendell and the understated John Olerud. Further proof that
something wild can coexist with something mild in the Mets'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain togetherness about this team that spills onto
the field, and it has led them to this point: The Mets tied the
Cubs for the wild-card berth with six games left in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   There was Wendell, practically frayed at the edges from the six
straight appearances he had made, hopping out of the bullpen to end
pending disaster for the Mets in the seventh, while the calm Olerud
continued his uncanny hitting by going 3 for 3 with a run scored
and one driven in.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets knew the opening was there for them to tie the Cubs. As
the last out was made in the bottom of the sixth, the letter ``F''
flashed on the Shea Stadium scoreboard next to the Cubs' 7-2 loss
to the Reds. The crowd of 55,775 roared in approval.
</P>
<P>
   There was a buzz in the air because the Mets had a 4-1 lead at
that point. But all it took was a two-run home run served up by
Masato Yoshii to Mark Kotsay in the seventh to send the crowd
squirming in its seats.
</P>
<P>
   As Yoshii left the field with one out in the inning, the
untiring Wendell came bounding out of the bullpen like a coiled
spring for his sixth appearance in six games. He had not allowed a
run in his last eight and two-thirds innings. After hitting Derrek
Lee, he walked Kevin Orie. Wendell then got the pinch-hitter Brian
Daubach to miss a 2-2 pitch to end the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a perfect opportunity to add to their 4-3 lead in
the bottom of the seventh, but with two outs and two men on, Luis
Lopez struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud kept himself squarely in the race for the National League
batting title, a competition that has become an undercard fight
compared to the hype surrounding the wild-card race and the
home-run race between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud would not have it any other way. He would rather be in
the background and is thriving in his anonymity. While the crowd
sways on every movement Mike Piazza makes, and all eyes are focused
on the Cubs, Olerud just plugs along on the fringe of the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Friday night's ugly scene, when Franco gave up a
two-run lead in the ninth inning, everything seemed a little
brighter and lighter for the Mets. Although Yoshii followed his
pattern of struggling with his control early, the Mets countered
with the reliable Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   His r.b.i. single in the Mets' two-run second inning helped put
the Mets ahead by 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little comfort in that lead. The last-place
Marlins, and downtrodden teams like them, have been able to cast a
spell on the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   As dangerous as the Mets are to the elite teams in the league,
they have been caught with visions of post-season scenarios dancing
in their heads when faced with also-ran opponents. So losing Friday
night to the Marlins, a team with just 51 victories, was not
surprising. It was devastating, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to make up a game on the Cubs,'' Olerud said.
``But I know this team, and I believe we'll bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   They bounced right back into a tie with the Cubs. And Franco
leaped right with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
