<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WOODWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY WINS WOODWARD STAKES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Skip Away raced into thoroughbred history
Saturday when he won the 45th Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park
against an all-star field. With the victory, his ninth straight, he
drew ever closer to the stature and the money record of the great
Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   The durable gray 5-year-old, purchased three years ago for
$22,000 by the trainer Sonny Hine for his wife, Carolyn, won by a
length and three-quarters over Gentlemen, the 6-year-old iron horse
from Argentina, with Running Stag third, Free House fourth and
Coronado's Quest fifth and last. Coronado's Quest, the only
3-year-old in the field, saw his five-race winning streak end.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, who won his fourth Woodward Stakes and his third
in the last four years, including two aboard Cigar, was asked to
rank Skip Away and Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having two kids,'' he said. ``Which one do you love
most?''
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Hine, clamoring for respect for his horse for months,
said: ``He is some horse, the best there is. He is one of the best
I've ever seen. He is so brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Hine said, ``We want him to get the respect he
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mandella, the California trainer whose Dare and Go ended
Cigar's winning streak at 16 two years ago, led the cheers for his
Gentlemen but acknowledged Skip Away's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the top of the stetch, I thought we had a big chance to win
this one,'' Mandella said. ``But Skip Away just got away from us.
He showed everyone just how much of a tremendous horse he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shug McGaughey, the trainer of Coronado's Quest, said:
``Skip Away is getting close to making history. Everyone thought
this would be a great race, but it didn't really shape up like
everyone thought. Coronado's Quest and Free House did not run their
races, and maybe Skip Away made them not run their races.''
</P>
<P>
   For a quarter of a mile, Skip Away ran a length or so behind
Coronado's Quest, who flew the first quarter-mile in 22 3/5
seconds. After half a mile, which was run in 45 2/5 seconds, Skip
Away had the lead with Coronado's Quest second, Free House third
and Gentlemen fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After three-quarters of a mile, which Skip Away ran in a
sizzling 1:09, Gentlemen was replacing Coronado's Quest as the
pursuer, with Free House fourth. And as they turned into the
stretch, it was Skip Away by two lengths over Gentlemen, who was
opening daylight on Running Stag, the 46-1 long shot from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As they flew across the finish line, Skip Away had a length and
three-quarters on Gentlemen, who had six lengths on Running Stag.
Nine lengths farther back came Free House, the recent winner of the
$1 million Pacific Classic, who outdueled Coronado's Quest for
fourth place by the length of his neck in a short but distinguished
field.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away ran the mile and one-eighth in 1:47 4/5, paid $4.20
for a $2 bet to win as the favorite and added $300,000 to his
bankroll. He has earned $9.5 million, putting him within less than
$500,000 of Cigar's record total of just under $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The day's races, which drew 20,237 spectators, had two other
stakes with stars.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ruffian for fillies and mares, it was all Sharp Cat, who
won her fourth straight start. The 4-year-old daughter of Storm
Cat, trained by Wally Dollase and ridden by his son-in-law Corey
Nakatani, led all the way and won by three lengths over Furlough,
who had half a length on Stop Traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Storm Cat had already won the Matron at Belmont Park as a
2-year-old and the Acorn as a 3-year-old, and she was no surprise
to anybody. She ran the mile and one-sixteenth in 1:42 2/5, paid
$3.50 for a $2 bet to win as the favorite and banked $150,000 for
career earnings of $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a special animal,'' Dollase said. ``You couldn't ask for
a horse to do any better. She does everything so easy, you don't
have to train her.''
</P>
<P>
   The third stakes on the board, the Jerome, is the second-oldest
in the United States, having been been run for 130 years at four
tracks. It was won in the homestretch by Limit Out, who had not won
since the Bay Shore last April.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, he outran a good field of 3-year-old colts,
winning by 2\ lengths over Grand Slam, winner of the Peter Pan this
year and the Champagne and Futurity last year. And Grand Slam, the
favorite, had half a length on Scatmandu, who won three straight
races earlier this year before testing the heavy hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Limit Out, trained by Allen Jerkens with Jean-Luc Samyn riding,
made his move from fifth place on the rail and won the homestretch
duel.
</P>
<P>
   He ran the mile in 1:36 1/5, paid $9.20 for a $2 bet to win and
earned $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat behind the speed, stalked them and waited until the top
of the stretch,'' Samyn said. ``When you're in a position where the
only option is to go inside, you go inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
