<SLUG> BC-FBC-CINCINNATI-ARMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CADETS RALLY TO MAKE THEIR DEBUT MEMORABLE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Army began a new chapter in its storied
football history Saturday when the Cadets made their debut in the
3-year-old Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Ending 108 years as an independent, Army became a conference
member in auspicious style, recovering from a 20-16 deficit in the
second half to score three unanswered touchdowns and beat
Cincinnati, 37-20, before a crowd of 32,775 in Michie Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those touchdowns came on big-yardage plays: a 44-yard
touchdown pass from Johnny Goff to halfback Bobby Williams that put
Army ahead for good, 23-20, late in the third quarter, and a
79-yard interception return by free safety Kenny Rowland three
minutes into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was particularly satisfying for Army considering it
had been projected to finish last in an eight-team league that
includes schools like Southern Mississippi, Houston and East
Carolina. The Cadets play at Rutgers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win, and a great turnabout, for us,'' said Bob
Sutton, the Army coach. ``We ran the option much better and, over
all, were much better offensively. And our defense came through in
big spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Rowland's touchdown run, the biggest Army defensive
play came with 5 minutes 29 seconds left. With the Cadets leading,
30-20, linebacker Nate Hunterton and cornerback Tony Coaxum stopped
Cincinnati runner Orlando Smith for no gain on fourth-and-1 at the
Army 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge play for us,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case when Army wins, its ground game and
defense were largely responsible. Led by Williams and Goff, who ran
for 108 and 92 yards, respectively, the Cadets rushed for 317 yards
against 162 for the Bearcats. Cincinnati, 0-3, was more effective
in the air, passing for 214 yards to 82 for Army.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four of Cincinnati's passing yards came on three passes
by the versatile Chad Plummer, who was even more effective as a
receiver, catching 11 passes for 128 yards. Those 11 passes were
thrown by sophomore Deontey Kenner, with whom Plummer alternates at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The game was marked by six fumbles and three interceptions.
Cincinnati took a 17-13 halftime lead, largely because of
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Army's Hunter Hill fumbled a punt following the game's opening
series _ the first of two punts fumbled by the junior _ giving
Cincinnati the ball on the Cadets' 16-yard line. Two plays later,
Plummer found Jason Collins-Baker wide open in the end zone. Then
in the second quarter, with Army leading, 13-7, following Eric
Olsen's second field goal, Bearcat linebacker Hassan Chapman picked
off a pass by Goff at the Cincinnati 35. The Bearcats then drove 65
yards on 9 plays, the last of which was a 23-yard touchdown pass
from Kenner to Cornelius Bonner. That gave the visitors a 14-13
lead, which they widened to 17-13 on a 40-yard field goal by Joe
Judge on the last play of the half.
</P>
<P>
   After misfiring on all five of his passes in the opening half,
the left-handed Goff was 4 for 4 for 82 yards and 1 touchdown in
the second half. Two of those completions came on the Cadets' first
possession, which ended with Olsen's third field goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to come out in the second half and
re-focus,'' said Goff. ``The team was behind me and picking me up.
I took control and tried to lead the team.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 40-yard field goal by Judge had put the Bearcats ahead
by 20-16, Army regained the lead when Goff hooked up with Williams
with 2:23 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati appeared on the verge of retaking the lead when it
marched to the Army 21. But Kenner, under pressure from linebacker
Derick McNally, threw a wobbly pass into Rowland's hands near the
right sideline, and the sophomore raced in for a 30-20 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
