<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARCA-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN'S DREAMS GO UP IN FLAMES IN ARCA RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Billy Meazell was in pain. He had just returned
from the Texas Motor Speedway's infield care center, where he was
treated for bruises and a slight burn sustained in a fiery crash on
lap 81 of yesterday's ARCA Z-MAX 250. His flaming car hit the wall
three times and flipped up on the right-side wheels for a few
frightening feet.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what hurt. Looking at the charred wreck that had
been the only car in his self-owned and self-operated racing team,
now ``that'' hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more pain in seeing this car than in anything
else,'' said Meazell, a native of Frankston, in East Texas. ``I'm
mad, disgusted. That's the only car I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Meazell and his crew, which includes his brother
Steven and step-brother Dennis Taylor, will try to salvage what
they can from the 1994 Chevrolet Lumina they had brought to TMS to
run in their first Automobile Racing Club of America event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just small-town East Texas people with a small family
budget,'' Steven Meazell said. ``We don't have any sponsors. This
hurt us bad. The car's almost outdated, but we've still got over 60
grand in it. We came here looking to catch someone's eye and get a
sponsor, and to do that, we figured we'd have to put the car near
the front.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the wreck, they were doing just that. Billy
Meazell, a longtime dirt-track racer, had moved as high as second
during the race, and was running a solid third when he came out of
Turn 4 and ``couldn't turn left.''
</P>
<P>
   The steering wheel turned but the car wouldn't respond. As he
hit the outside wall, the left side of the car burst into flames.
He slammed hard into the outside wall again on the front stretch,
slid across the track and hit the inside wall, knocking the car up
on its right-side wheels. He made it out of the car on his own soon
after it rolled to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in the garage was that either a tire had blown or an
oil line ruptured, coating the tires with slick oil and starting
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the Meazells were left wondering what to do.
This week, they had already shelled out $16,000 _ money that comes
from Billy Meazell's mobile home and truck business _ on a new
engine after blowing one in practice Thursday. They installed the
new motor barely in time to become the last car out on the track
for Friday's qualifying and proceeded to post the ninth-best
qualifying speed at 168.539 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that mattered after the wreck. All that was left was
a search for a sponsor and the hope they would be able to replace
the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not giving up,'' Steven Meazell said. ``We're going to
keep on pushing. We can run with the big boys. We just need some
help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     09-19 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERPAID DODGERS ARE A TOUGH FIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even with all that energy and enthusiasm, Kevin
Malone is a realist.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are not a quick fix _ even if next year's payroll
reaches a staggering $70-75 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I am confident we can be right there next year, there
has to be a lot of planning long term,'' Malone said Thursday.
``You have to create some room to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's strength at player evaluation is buried under the $53
million his predecessors committed to 12 players for 1999. In
addition, he inherits $34 million for five players in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he could try to ship Bobby Bonilla back to Baltimore and
tell Orioles owner Peter Angelos the Dodgers will pick up half the
$11.8 million the 35-year-old Bonilla is owed for the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the lack of flexibility that will make the recovery so
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the guarantees, the Dodgers cannot sign a No.1
starter like San Diego's Kevin Brown, who might command $10 million
a year on the free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Malone watched the San Francisco Giants crush the Dodgers 18-4
on Saturday. But the real pain was knowing the Giants are
contending with a $40 million payroll they want to keep in place
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants built their payroll around option years that will
help them maintain some fiscal sanity.
</P>
<P>
   Do they pay Orel Hershiser, who has one victory in his last 12
starts, $3.2 million next season or exercise a buyout of $200,000?
Do they pay J.T. Snow $3 million or $700,000 and let him become a
free agent? Charlie Hayes $1.7 million or the $275,000 buyout? The
same questions are being asked about shortstop Rey Sanchez ($1.4
million or $100,000) and reliever Julian Tavarez ($1.2 million or
$200,000).
</P>
<P>
   Granted, all that lends itself to some uncertainty for Giants
fans, but it seems to bring a more competitive team.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers handed Malone a $15 million brick from last May's
Mike Piazza trade with Florida (Gary Sheffield $9.5 million,
Bonilla $5.9 million).
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the guaranteed money, the Dodgers still have to
deal with a considerable group of players eligible for salary
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charles Johnson enters his fifth year with a chance to
make $4.5 million next season. Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek could
get a raise to $2.5 million. Left-hander Carlos Perez could get $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ismael Valdes, the culprit in Saturday's meltdown, could
get almost $4 million in arbitration. If Valdes had any kind of
season, he could have gotten a long-term contract worth quite a bit
more.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is going to have to convince some team that the
overpriced veterans can put them over the top. And because the
expectations are so high in a major market like L.A., he is going
to have to keep big names in the lineup while rebuilding the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Not that big contracts are all bad. After the 1996 season,
franchise player Mike Piazza asked the Dodgers for a six-year deal
worth $60 million. The Dodgers laughed and Piazza accepted two
years for $15.
</P>
<P>
   The next year they gave Raul Mondesi $36 million for four years
with two option years that could make the deal worth $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is gone after wanting $105 million for seven years, and
people are still wondering about Mondesi's potential.
</P>
<P>
   What about Leyland: With General manager Dave Dombrowski signed
and the rest of the front office taking shape, prospective Marlins
owner John Henry now will turn his attention to convincing manager
Jim Leyland to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, 49, called Leyland on Saturday to introduce himself to
Leyland, who has three years left on his contract after this season
but has an out clause that allows him to leave if the team is sold.
Henry plans to meet with Leyland and Dombrowski sometime this week
after the Marlins return home from their road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland, as he has all along, refused to comment on his
situation except to acknowledge that he had spoken with Henry by
phone and that he probably would see him at one of the Marlins' six
remaining home games.
</P>
<P>
   When Dombrowski signed his five-year, $5 million contract
extension last week, he said he'd do what he could to convince
Leyland to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the priority is keeping Jim Leyland,'' Dombrowski said.
``He's one of the best managers in baseball, so obviously you want
him to stay. But he has to do what's best for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyland left Pittsburgh after the 1996 season because he was
worried it would take too long for the Pirates to rebuild and he
wanted to win right away, which he did with the Marlins. Henry has
said he'll spend to make the Marlins competitive again, but not
right away, and if Leyland decides he doesn't want to wait, he
could leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind building some,'' Dombrowski said. ``I don't know
if Jim feels like that. He has to make that decision. He knows we
would like to have him back, but all I can do is tell Jim how it
stands. I can't keep pushing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Big contract: Bret Saberhagen improved to 14-7 on Wednesday
night after receiving a new three-year contract (with an option for
2002) on Sunday. The deal is worth $12.5 million plus incentives
for the first three years. The fourth year, which can be triggered
by innings pitched, has a $4.5 million base.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 victories are the most Saberhagen has had since he went
14-4 for the Mets in '94. He had reconstructive shoulder surgery
after the '95 season, missed all of 1996 and all but six starts of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   He's back throwing in the low 90s with excellent control. The
Sox have made it a point not to push him past 100 pitches this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think if (my injury) had happened 10 years ago that
I'd be pitching,'' Saberhagen said. ``Modern medicine took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Future in Twin Cities? Marty Cordova was American League Rookie
of the Year four years ago, but now the Twins are wondering if he
is part of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova is a big reason why the Twins are finishing their sixth
consecutive losing season for the first time in franchise history.
He is hitting just .255 with only 10 homers and 67 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   He's already been through two dreadful slumps: The 0 for 29 that
went from Aug. 31-Sept. 14 and an 0 for 22 that went from July
17-26.
</P>
<P>
   Some on the Twins staff are convinced that Cordova can no longer
hit a quality major-league fastball. Manager Tom Kelly has tried
talking to Cordova a couple of times recently and hasn't felt that
Cordova is receptive to help. Hitting coach Terry Crowley on
Wednesday declined comment when asked to evaluate Cordova's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back is up against the wall, but I've been here before,''
Cordova said. ``I'm going to have to do something or something is
going to be done to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers gone? Among the few bright spots for the A's this season
was Kenny Rogers (14-8, 3.16), but after regaining his spot as one
of baseball's better left-handers, it looks like he might want out.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Dodgers' Jeff Shaw, he is in the middle of a multi-year
contract and can demand a trade. He could return to Texas, where he
had his best seasons, or Tampa Bay, near where he lives in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my wife had said at the beginning of the year that she
couldn't deal with my being on the West Coast, I wouldn't be here
now,'' said Rogers, who has two young children. ``I enjoy playing
the game, but I don't enjoy the time away from my family.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's don't want to have to think about life without Rogers,
who is due to get $5 million in 1999, half of that paid by the
Yankees. The A's picked up Rogers from New York in exchange for
Scott Brosius last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe the A's a lot,'' he said. ``They gave me a chance after
New York, when other teams might not have. When we're talking about
next year, I won't forget that I owe them.''
</P>
<P>
   News and notes: Boston's John Valentin appears to have settled
in at third base after losing his shortstop job last year to Nomar
Garciaparra and struggling with a move to second. Valentin has
committed 12 errors in his first full season at third and none in
the second half.... Orel Hershiser, with one victory in 12 starts
since July 21, retired the first 12 batters Wednesday on his 40th
birthday. But Arizona batted around in the bottom of the sixth,
scoring four runs.... The Cubs' Kevin Tapani (19-7 with a 4.60) has
a chance to become only the 12th pitcher since 1920 to win 20 games
with an ERA above 4.00. He would be the first since Jack Morris in
1992, unless Texas' Rick Helling (19-7, 4.30) beats him there.
Others who won 20 with a 4-plus ERA: Jim Merritt in 1970, Lew
Burdette in 1959, Murry Dickson in 1951, Bobo Newsom in 1938, Wes
Ferrell in 1936, Vern Kennedy in 1936, Lefty Gomez in 1932, Ray
Kremer in 1930, George Earnshaw in 1930 and George Uhle in 1922....
Seattle RF Jay Buhner, who missed most of the first two months this
year after knee surgery, underwent a ``Tommy John'' surgery on his
right elbow and probably won't play for the next 6-9 months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOP OF THE ORDER
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing feeling in and out of baseball that the Cubs'
Sammy Sosa has been slighted during his race with Mark McGwire for
the all-time single-season home run record. Commissioner Bud Selig
wasn't there when Sosa hit No. 62 and there was no ceremony to mark
the occasion. They also stopped giving the baseballs a special
stamp so Sosa's No. 62 is still missing. Today, Selig and
representatives from the Maris family will be there for a party for
Sosa at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ROTISSERIE WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Despite their great season, Cubs fans were still upset the team
traded leadoff hitter Doug Glanville to Philadelphia during the
winter. But after a hot first half, Glanville is batting .210
(38-181) since July 31, dropping his overall average from .314 to
.285. What's worse is that Glanville has walked just 12 times in
that stretch and scored only 20 runs. The Phillies are thinking
about taking Glanville out of the top spot in the order next
season.
</P>
<P>
   STAT OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Manny Ramirez hit five homers in two games. The five homers came
in six at-bats Tuesday and Wednesday. He hit four in four at-bats _
three homers in his last three at-bats in a 7-5 victory over
Toronto on Tuesday and a three-run homer in the first inning on
Wednesday. On Tuesday he drove in five runs. Wednesday he drove in
four. Ramirez has 42 homers and 133 RBI _ far and away career
highs.
</P>
<P>
   THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden is the leading candidate to replace Pat
Gillick when he formally steps down. The Orioles received
permission to interview Bowden on Tuesday, and he has strong
support within the organization from old friend Syd Thrift,
Baltimore's director of player development. Other candidates:
Cleveland exec Dan O'Dowd, former Dodgers GM Fred Claire, former
Yankees GM Bob Watson and Braves assistant Dean Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is special, but I don't know if anybody else
does.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Angels coach Larry Bowa, after there were 9,000 empty seats at
the Ballpark in Arlington for Wednesday's Rangers-Angels game for
the AL West lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
