<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M STORMS PAST SOUTHERN MISS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Rain swept from offshore into the Gulf
States yesterday afternoon, but it was Texas A&AMP;M that blanketed
Southern Mississippi with a case of tropical depression.
</P>
<P>
   Missing prime bad-weather fullback D'Andre Hardeman _ who has
been suspended indefinitely from the team _ the 17th-ranked Aggies
relied on two lightning-strike touchdown runs by Dante Hall and its
Wrecking Crew defense for a 24-6 victory over the crestfallen
Golden Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very good football team we played,'' USM coach Jeff
Bower said.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M spoiled the home opener for Bower's Southern Mississippi
team that had vowed redemption after falling out of the preseason
Top 25 with a 34-7 loss at Penn State two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Playing before only the fifth sellout crowd (33,323) in Roberts
Stadium history, A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum was concerned before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been worried about this game since last spring,'' Slocum
said. ``But I thought we took some of the momentum out of the crowd
early in the game because our defense was getting after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 2-1 is a good place to be. It would just be so different
now if you come in here and lose and have to go back and play North
Texas. You can't get the monkey off your back. So I'm very pleased
with this win. Getting out of a hostile environment like this with
a victory will help us when we open \RBig 12\S conference play at
Kansas \ROct.3\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall pulled a small muscle in his calf on Wednesday and was
doubtful before kickoff. But he had immediate impact when he
entered the game with 5:16 left in the first half as the Aggies
clung to a precarious 6-0 lead on two of Russell Bynum's three
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   On his second carry, Hall took it outside and broke four
tackles, sprinting 44 yards down the left sideline to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the big plays in the ball game,'' Slocum said.
``That run really came at a good time. We were only up by six and
needed to get some distance between us and them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall struck again in the third quarter, two plays after Jason
Webster's 30-yard return to the USM 25 after one of three Aggies
interceptions. Hall gained 9, then cut over the right side and
faked out a final defender at the 5 on his way to a 16-yard scoring
run with 4:29 left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hall finished with 76 yards on eight carries, but gained it all
on his first four calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could play today, but I hadn't practiced all week, so
it wouldn't have been fair to the other guys not to give them a
chance,'' Hall said. ``I had some great blocks from the line \Ron
the 44-yard run\S that enabled me to get into the end zone. On one
play, the muscle tugged a little bit. But other than that, I felt
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's defense also recovered a pair of fumbles. The five
turnovers led to 13 points. The Crew also sacked USM quarterback
Lee Roberts five times for losses of 26 yards _ an important factor
on a day in which the A&AMP;M offense managed just 171 yards and nine
first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Warrick Holdman led the Aggies defense with seven
tackles, two for losses, a sack and batted down a pass at the line
of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line was the key to our defense,'' Holdman said.
``They put a lot of pressure on the quarterback, which enabled us
to make some big plays.'' Extra points Four Aggies running backs
gained 127 yards on 33 carries. ... Ja'Mar Toombs, the only
freshman to play for A&AMP;M this season, started in place of suspended
D'Andre Hardeman. ... Punter Shane Lechler averaged 50.1 yards on
nine kicks. ... Sophomore field-goal kicker Russell Bynum is now
5-for-5 and has converted all six extra points.  &LR; tagtop:Mike Jones,
(817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
