<HEADLINE>
BRACK DOING FINE JOB OF REACHING HIS GOAL: WINNING RACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fans of the Pep Boys Indy Racing League
haven't started wearing their ``Anybody But Brack'' T-shirts. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, Brack's record-setting three-race winning
streak might be a blessing for a series still auditioning for more
than one marquee player. With reigning champion Tony Stewart headed
for a full-time NASCAR Winston Cup ride in 1999, Brack is heir
apparent to the title of ``IRL Poster Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   As Stewart noted, ``It beats having your face on a milk
carton.''
</P>
<P>
   But does Brack want the job?
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal isn't to be the guy that gets the most PR,'' said
Brack, the championship points leader who starts 10th in today's
inaugural Lone Star 500K at Texas Motor Speedway. ``My goal is to
win races _ because if I win races, everyone has to write about me
anyway. I can deal with all of that other stuff, but the main thing
for me is a good race result.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two months of the IRL schedule, Brack's results
have been impeccable. His consecutive victories at Charlotte Motor
Speedway, Pikes Peak International Raceway and Atlanta Motor
Speedway have stolen the spotlight at A.J. Foyt Racing from injured
teammate Billy Boat _ Foyt's de facto No. 1 driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's just got a roll going,'' said Boat, winner of the True
Value 500K here in June, but out of the title chase after missing
two races with a broken leg and pelvis. ``I've been trying to find
out what Kenny's eating, what he's drinking and where he's hanging
out, because I'm trying to get a little bit of it to rub off on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack chased Boat and Plano's Greg Ray across the finish line
during the True Value 500K night race June 6. That event, Round 4
of the series, was Brack's second consecutive top-10 result. He
finished 18th and 10th in the next two races before unlocking the
door into Victory Lane, times three.
</P>
<P>
   At Charlotte, Brack led on seven occasions for 76 laps. He
grabbed the front spot from Jeff Ward with 13 laps remaining on a
1.5-mile facility that is a sister track to TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Brack passed Robbie Buhl of archrival Team Menard with three
laps to go to win at Pikes Peak. For added drama, Brack's fuel tank
was empty and his engine dead when he crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta, another 1.5-mile oval in Bruton Smith's empire,
Brack passed Ward for the victory with 14 laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest drive I had in terms of wearing myself out
probably was at Charlotte, because they put us down in every pit
stop,'' said Brack, driver of Foyt's No. 14 Power Team
Dallara/Aurora. ``Every time we went into the pits we were leading,
and we'd come out fifth or sixth. The other two have been hard as
well. There are no easy victories. At least I haven't had any.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Sweden, Brack came to this series in 1997 after
making a splash in the International Formula 3000 Championship. He
was runner-up in that open-wheeled series in 1996, scoring three
victories and three poles in nine races. That performance earned
Brack a look from Arrows Grand Prix as its Formula One test driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't really see a future for me in Formula One,'' said
Brack, 32. ``I knew that a newcomer into Formula One wouldn't get a
McLaren or Ferrari drive straight-away. And honestly, if I looked
two, maybe three years up the road, I couldn't see a path leading
to that. I thought that's not for me. I want to race to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack's F3 successes, and his championship in the Barber Saab
Series in this country in 1993, ultimately landed him an IRL ride
with Galles Racing International last year. Hired as a substitute
for the injured Davy Jones, Brack drove in seven races and posted
two top-five finishes. He led three races for a total of 35 laps.
Brack also was the highest-qualifying rookie on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny brought a lot to our team last year,'' said Galles, who
reluctantly parted company with Brack after selling his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't win as many championships as he's won without a lot
of talent,'' said Galles, now general manager of Nienhouse
Motorsports, which fields Reebok-sponsored cars for Davey Hamilton.
When Foyt fired Hamilton after last season, he extended free-agent
Brack a contract. Brack will start today's race with a 23-point
lead over runners-up Hamilton and Stewart with only this event and
the season-ender at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on Oct. 11 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that Kenny's made Foyt's team, rather than the
other way around,'' Galles said. ``Kenny's a quick-learner and
very, very serious about his racing. Once he learned how to run on
an oval _ and certainly Foyt has a lot of experience in that area _
Kenny brought a lot to that team.''
</P>
<P>
   For Foyt, first four-time champion of the Indianapolis 500, the
Americanization of the guitar-playing, Harley-Davidson-riding Brack
has included having him move to Houston, Foyt's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny is a hell of a good racer,'' said Foyt, winner of a
record 67 Indy-car races. ``He's still got a lot to learn. And
that's one thing, he works real good with me. I've been trying to
help him that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack said this winning streak is exactly what he envisioned
when he signed with the often ornery Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we got together was because I knew he would give me
a car I can win races with,'' Brack said. ``I mean, I guess he took
a chance on me because I had only seven races under my belt in
America last year. But I know I can win races if I have a car that
can win races. So I expected to win races this year, for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
