<HEADLINE>
STEWART SETS STANDARD IN PRACTICE, BUT SHARP, GOODYEAR READY TO
TUSSLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tony Stewart set the standard during
yesterday's final practice session for today's Lone Star 500K with
a lap of more than 224 mph. But Scott Sharp and Scott Goodyear
might have convinced some that today's race could be more than a
battle between Team Menard and A.J. Foyt Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, who fell from first to fourth in points after an
18th-place finish at Atlanta on Aug. 29, posted a speed of 223.464
mph, which is second behind Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp will start today's race in his Delphi Automotive Systems
Kelley Racing entry in third, behind Billy Boat and Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to win this race and get the maximum points we can
get doing it,'' said Sharp, who is 36 points behind standings
leader Kenny Brack.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows exactly if this track is going to be exactly the
same as it is right now. You got to sort of guess. When you get in
there it is going to be subtle changes you make on the pit stop
(that make the difference). You got to hope when you make an air
pressure adjustment or a wing adjustment it is enough or in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear posted a speed of 223.187 mph during the final
practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
