<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ANGELSTAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STAYING TOUGH, ANGELSTAD KEEPS STARS INTERESTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Mel Angelstad has bounced around enough
minor-league hockey teams to know that it's just about impossible
to play for the Fort Worth Brahmas one season and the Stars the
next.
</P>
<P>
   But he's hoping to pull off the impossible this season.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old winger, who logged 19 games and 102 penalty
minutes with the Brahmas in the Western Professional Hockey League
last season, has a two-year contract with the Stars. He is slated
to be the tough guy for their International Hockey League
affiliate, the Michigan K-Wings.
</P>
<P>
   But Angelstad also is the backup to tough guy Brent Severyn. And
if Severyn is hurt or the Stars develop the need for extra
toughness, Angelstad is now just a phone call away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is trying to earn a job, and I'm no different,'' he
said. ``I just want to perform my role as well as possible, and the
rest will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelstad, who played 63 games and had 321 penalty minutes with
the Orlando Solar Bears of the IHL last season, has an angel in the
organization. New K-Wings coach Bill McDonald has coached Angelstad
in Thunder Bay, Ontario, and Fort Worth and says that making the
jump to the NHL isn't inconceivable for his favorite tough guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the system, they need some depth at that position, and
Mel is that depth,'' McDonald said. ``All I know is that Mel can
fill that role if given the chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-NY-POP-WARNER-NYT     09-19 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-NY-POP-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP WARNER TEAM HELPS RESPONSIBLE YOUTHS GROW ON A DUSTY FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SOLOMON B. DAVIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In October 1995, after returning to New York City
from the Million Man March in Washington, two former college
athletes, Chris Legree and Ervin C. Roberson, vowed to transport
the march's spirit of racial responsibility to their home
neighborhood in Brooklyn. Since both men had used scholarships to
attain college degrees, they decided to use sports as their vehicle
for change and brought Pop Warner Little Scholars football to a
dusty patch of field underneath the No. 3 train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mo' Better Jaguars have barnstormed throughout the East,
defeating well-established Pop Warner football teams from Syracuse,
N.Y. to Baltimore, and making state history by winning the Empire
State Classic Football Championship in their inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all 15 of the team's coaches say they derive less
satisfaction from perfect spirals or smashing hits than hearing
mothers talk about their children's academic improvement and the
boys themselves testifying about turning down offers to run with
the wrong crowd because they prefer the camaraderie of the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are black men out here teaching black boys how to be black
men,'' said Everton Baker, a conductor for the New York City
Transit Authority and second-year coach of the 11- to 12-year-old
junior midgets team. ``For these inner-city kids, the coaches may
be the only black-male role model they'll have.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 54 percent of black children are reared in
single-female households, and the Jaguars saw organized sports as a
conduit to re-establish contact between concerned black men and
black boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider them one of the upper echelon programs in the
United States,'' said Wesley Johnson, the founder, general manager
and coach of the Pop Warner Maryland state midget champions, Hanlon
Park. ``They're a quality organization with committed coaches,
parents and kids. Not only are they making better boys, they're
making better Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for inner-city youths to play organized football,
because of the high equipment costs and lack of playing fields. Yet
the Mo' Better team has made it possible for 120 youngsters, aged
7-14, to participate in the sport each of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Legree, a 42-year-old electrical engineer for Con Edison and
director of operations for the football program, said: ``We wanted
to create a vehicle that was capable of establishing a bond between
the youth of Brownsville and concerned strong black men and women
and to embed in the residents a sense of community pride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We put this together with spit and Scotch tape, and we're
winning championships,'' said Roberson, a 38-year-old architect who
is executive director of operations. ``Imagine what we'd be like if
we had funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by the formidable task of raising $40,000 to fund the
program, the Jaguars have met their budget through a yearly $10,000
donation from Jay Jordan of Chicago-based Jordan Industries (Jordan
met Roberson and Legree when they were competing as athletes);
appropriations from Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp.'sSafe
Haven Program; contributions from local stores; and team
registration fees and the sale of team merchandise, raffle tickets,
bus trips and car washes. When all else fails, the coaches dig into
their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, as the Jaguars were on the verge of winning the
regional quarterfinals in Syracuse, the coaches were brooding over
how to finance the semifinal matchup in Marlboro, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches took up yet another collection and were saved by
Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp., said George Corbin II,
executive director of planning for the Jaguars who works for the
restoration corporation's Safe Haven program.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the seemingly never-ending struggle for funding, the
educational component of the program takes precedence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to produce a pool of kids who are academically
ready to compete first at Poly Prep, Xaverian, Christ the King and
Stuyvesant High Schools,'' said Roberson. ``And then on to Harvard,
Stanford and Tennessee,'' added Corbin.
</P>
<P>
   All players must take tests in reading and mathematics. Those
who have difficulty with certain subjects must enroll in tutorial
programs operated by Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration Corp. Coaches
visit the schools during the year, and for three hours before every
practice session a licensed teacher assists the players with their
homework.
</P>
<P>
   Players in need of additional attention are referred to school
tutorial services.
</P>
<P>
   Pop Warner, as the national youth sports organization is known,
emphasizes education. A 73 average is one of the eligibility
requirements for individual players and teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wasn't in football, my average was about 70; now that I
play for Mo' Better and hear what the coaches say about getting a
good education, my average stays at 80 or higher,'' said Eric
Figueroa, an 11-year-old second-year player. ``They challenge me to
do better and really want me to work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days a week, Figueroa and his teammates practice on Betsy
Head Park's parched grass field. On game days, visiting teams,
accustomed to playing on well-maintained sod, reluctantly square
off on the dusty terrain.
</P>
<P>
   A continual source of emotional support is a group called the
Team Mothers. The eight women, some with children on the team and
some without, help organize fund-raisers, assist in recruiting
players and participate in strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like,'' said Pat Parker, a school secretary at Public
School 13 in Brooklyn, and one of four team managers, ``is the fact
that no matter how well you play, or even if you can't catch a
ball, every child gets a chance to play. The idea is to bring black
boys into contact with positive black men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I envision this program becoming a model to be emulated in
urban areas across the country,'' said Legree. ``A lot of sports
programs out there distinguish themselves solely for athletic
success. We are a surrogate family that uses football to reacquaint
black men with black families in general, but black boys more
specifically.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
