<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-N.C.-STATE     09-19 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-N.C.-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR STUNS N.C. STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ One week after upsetting No. 2-ranked Florida
State, North Carolina State's players received the shock of their
lives yesterday afternoon at Floyd Casey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on grit and determination, the Baylor Bears built a 26-0
halftime lead, then hung on and edged the 20th-ranked Wolfpack,
33-30, in front of 28,734 fans. The victory was a
confidence-builder for a Baylor team that was only 2-9 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really thrilled for our football team,'' Baylor coach Dave
Roberts said. ``That will really help Baylor _ for a football team
that just beat Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we had some good plays, and offensively, we had
some bad plays. We were just fortunate to win and delighted to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   It marked the Bears' first victory against a ranked team since
they defeated 25th-ranked Fresno State, 42-39, in 1993 in Chuck
Reedy's first game as coach. But yesterday's awe-inspiring outcome
wasn't decided until four seconds remained, when Baylor cornerback
Gary Baxter zipped around left end and blocked a 39-yard field-goal
attempt by Kent Passingham that would have tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   During a timeout before Passingham's kick, Baxter played the
role of a psychic, predicting he would preserve the Bears' victory
with a blocked field goal. Earlier, Passingham had missed 41- and
45-yard field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was going to block it, because I wanted this
game more than anybody,'' Baxter said. ``I had a vision. I told the
team we worked too hard to let them come back and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I was going to give them my 110 percent, and I
pulled my goodies out of my bag and gave it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning its home opener, Baylor is 1-1. N.C. State drops
to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State coach Mike O'Cain bristled at suggestions that his
team might have come in smug and overconfident after handling
Florida State, 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great concentration coming in,'' he said. ``Baylor may
have been better than we thought they were. It was hard for us to
tell with just one film.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great running backs and an outstanding quarterback.
They played harder and wanted it more than we did, especially in
the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, about that first half.
</P>
<P>
   That was as close to a perfect half of football as the Bears
could imagine. It was as if the football gods permitted Baylor to
do whatever they wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Bears scored a pair of touchdowns and a
field goal when they had the ball and tacked on a TD and a safety
when the Wolfpack had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Bryant opened the scoring with a 32-yard field goal. The
Bears went up, 5-0, when N.C. State punter Scott Earwood _
stationed deep in the end zone _ fumbled the snap from center,
which teammate Corey Lyons recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor fullback Derek Lagway then produced one of the
magnificent runs of this young season. Taking a simple handoff,
Lagway rambled through the middle of the line and broke six tackles
en route to securing a 27-yard touchdown and a 12-0 lead late in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had me wrapped up, but I just kept my feet moving,''
Lagway said. ``When I broke loose the second time, I saw the end
zone, and I just dove in.''
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State, which didn't get its initial first down until 1:37
was left in the first quarter, threatened when a 57-yard reception
by Torry Holt got the Wolfpack to the Baylor 7. But on
third-and-goal from the 4, nose tackle Ronald Smith jarred the ball
from quarterback Jamie Barnette with a ferocious blindside tackle,
and Kenyada Parker scooped it up and rambled 82 yards for a 19-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   That 14-point swing came back to bite the Wolfpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a blitz, and I came outside and the ball bounced up
in my hands,'' Parker said. ``I know I looked slow, but I knew I
was going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Wolfpack, Holt caught touchdowns covering 80 and 11
yards. He finished with 11 catches for 255 yards _ the receiving
yards are the most ever against Baylor _ while Barnette completed
24 of 55 passes for 469 yards and three TDs.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor quarterback Odell James scooted around right end for a
4-yard TD that bumped Baylor's lead to 33-23 at the outset of the
fourth quarter. Then the Bears sweated it out in the waning
seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
