<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees showed they are human by losing 11 of their last 19
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfair that every time we lose, people say we're
flat or say we're not playing for anything,'' shortstop Derek Jeter
said. ``Sometimes we're going to get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre isn't worried. ``I think we can rise to the
occasion,'' Torre said. ``We're playing well, but you lack a
certain amount of intensity after you clinch.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Toronto's Jose Canseco has hit the 100-RBI mark for the
first time since 1991. ... The Orioles' loss of assistant general
manager Kevin Malone to the Dodgers was a big one, considering that
everyone expected Malone to replace current Baltimore GM Pat
Gillick. ``It's a big loss for me personally,'' O's manager Ray
Miller said. ... If Yankees right-hander David Cone wins another
game, it will be his 20th and will give him the record for greatest
number of years between 20-win seasons; Cone last won 20 in 1988.
Tommy John, who holds the current record, won 20 in 1966 and 1974.
... Hideki Irabu, in danger of being left off the Yankees' playoff
roster, might have helped himself with eight innings of two-hit,
shutout ball Thursday. ... He hasn't had a great season, but Tampa
Bay's Fred McGriff has 17 homers and 75 RBIs. ``I'm working on
stuff now for the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   White Sox outfielder Albert Belle can become a free agent after
the season because of a clause that allows him to void his current
contract if he is not among the three highest-paid players. But it
is unlikely anyone is going to pay him more than $11 million a
season. ``Right now, I'm not going anywhere,'' Belle said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Since the start of the 1996 season, the Tigers have lost
286 times. ... Royals infielder Terry Pendleton apparently will
retire after this season. ``Trust me, we will know before this
season is over whether I'll venture into trying to make another
ballclub next year or go home,'' the former Brave said. ``My family
has already put their vote in. I won't say (what they voted). It's
truly up to me.'' Pendleton has played in 75 games this season,
hitting .253 with three homers and 29 RBIs. ... Minnesota's speedy
Otis Nixon has only four triples this year, but it is his career
high. ... Indians first baseman Jim Thome, who rehabbed his broken
hand in the minors, said of a recent, long bus trip, ``It was like
`Bull Durham' all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Relievers rarely pitch out of the windup, but that's exactly
what Rangers closer John Wetteland has been doing lately.Wetteland
had struggled recently, with his ERA rising from 1.68 to 2.02
before dropping back under 2.00. He thinks the full windup will
help his rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: One leftover that went almost unnoticed from the day
after Mark McGwire hit No. 62: Mariners slugger Ken Griffey Jr. had
a congratulatory banner flown over Cinergy Field for the
Cardinals-Reds game the day after the historic homer. ``He's in
Cincinnati, my hometown, and it was something to say: `You've
worked hard to get where you're at.' I wanted to say (the Griffey)
family appreciated what he did.'' ... When Angels general manager
Bill Bavasi was recently asked how badly he wanted to make the
postseason, he said, ``How bad do you want oxygen?'' ... Oakland's
Ben Grieve certainly didn't help himself for Rookie of the Year
when he went 109 at-bats between homers. ... Griffey, who has 53
homers and 20 stolen bases, is just the third player ever to hit 50
homers and steal 20, joining Willie Mays (1956) and Brady Anderson
(1996).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
