<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    D-backs deal Embree's relief
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With one June airplane ride, Alan Embree gave up some
40 victories in the standings, an annual date in the playoffs and a
chance to prove himself at the game's highest level. In turn, he
found some peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   From where the ex-Braves reliever sits in Arizona's clubhouse
today, he thinks that's a pretty good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcomed it,'' Embree said of the June 23 trade that sent
him to the Diamondbacks for reliever Russ Springer. ``I wasn't
throwing much. I was getting frustrated just wondering, `Hey, wait
a minute. I'm doing everything you ask me to do but I'm not getting
into games.' They just had a different plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Embree took a string of 16 appearances with just three earned
runs allowed into Saturday night's game against the Braves. His ERA
since leaving Atlanta is an unimpressive 4.41, but much of that
stems from repeated abuse from the Chicago Cubs, who have scored
eight runs off him in four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   After the last game Aug. 3, when he gave up three runs without
retiring a batter, Embree changed from an abbreviated windup
installed by Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone back to his old
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have tweaked a little too much,'' Embree said. ``My
arm was getting sore from what we tried in spring training and I
was tired of getting my brains beat in. I was throwing without
getting anything on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   His current streak (1.69 ERA in 16 games) is what followed. But
Braves followers who watched Friday night's ninth inning witnessed
the sort of frustrations that prompted Atlanta general manager John
Schuerholz to send Embree away.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a five-lead, Embree walked Gerald Williams to open
the inning, then gave up a rocket to Chipper Jones that third
baseman Matt Williams was able to glove and turn into a double
play, catching Williams off first base.
</P>
<P>
   And still, Embree could not finish the inning. Ryan Klesko,
hitting just .203 against left-handed pitching, singled and Andruw
Jones followed with a double into the left field corner. That was
enough for Arizona manager Buck Showalter, who had to bring in his
closer, ex-Brave Gregg Olson, for the final out. He needed just
three pitches to retire Andres Galarraga on a ground-out,
preserving a 5-0 shutout for starter Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Braves) had to see what John (Rocker) can do,'' Embree
said. ``Rocker has really had a solid year. I wound up being the
odd man out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
