<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League Notes
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies might trade ace Curt Schilling this winter. General
manager Ed Wade isn't sure, but he said, ``I'm not doing my job if
I'm not thinking about who we could get for Curt Schilling or Scott
Rolen. Does that mean I'm going to pick up the phone and try to
trade them? No. But you have to think about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Braves right-hander Mark Wohlers finished the season with
33 walks in 20 1/3 innings. That's 14.61 walks every nine innings,
the third-worst ratio in major-league history behind Rob Dibble
(15.72) in 1995 and Ralph Lumenti (15.43) in 1958. ... Why are the
Braves pulling for the Giants to win the wild card? They are 7-2
against San Francisco this year but just 18-18 against San Diego,
Houston, the Mets and Cubs. ... If Jim Leyland leaves the Marlins,
expect the club to give strong consideration to putting player
development director John Boles in the manager's uniform again.
Boles replaced Rene Lacheman on a temporary basis two years ago.
... Hideo Nomo is just 6-12, but the Mets think he will turn it
around next season. ``I think it's as much confidence as much as it
is anything else right now,'' general manager Steve Phillips said.
... Former Brave Felix Millan, who had been working as the Mets'
Latin America coordinator, has left the team. Millan's plan is to
run a baseball school with Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   Central
</P>
<P>
   The home-run race between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa has been a
regular subject on the David Letterman show, and recently the comic
did a top 10 list of things Babe Ruth would say if he were alive
today. Among them were, ``You call this a baseball team? Where are
all the fat guys?'' and, ``I can't believe all these naked photos
of me on the Internet.'' Also, there was, ``If that's the case, I
would have been impeached from the Yankees 500 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Poor Steve Trachsel. The Cubs starter not only gave up
McGwire's 62nd homer but also was the starting pitcher in the game
in which Sosa went deep for his 62nd. He will be remembered as the
answer to a double trivia question. ... Speaking of McGwire, he is
the only player ever to ask for a cut in salary in the arbitration
process, which he did in Oakland after the 1991 season when he hit
.201. ... With all the Mc-Gwire memorabilia in Cooperstown,
attendance is up more than 7 percent at the Hall of Fame. ... The
Cubs don't sound confident that Kerry Wood will be back this
season. The rookie has a sore throwing elbow, and manager Jim
Riggleman said, ``If we don't get to use him in the stretch, we're
grateful for what he gave us, and we'll try to get it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   West
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Shawn Estes, who won 19 games last year, missed
two months and has given up 24 runs in four starts since his
return. Is his shoulder still giving him problems? ``I'm fine
physically, but I thought I'd be able to turn it on mentally,''
Estes said. ``It's not as easy as I thought. My focus is not
there.'' And largely as a result, the Giants have all but fallen
out of the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Fans in Denver finally are starting to get tired of
Colorado's play on the field. The club did not sell out any games
on a recent seven-game homestand. ... The Dodgers will be looking
for a new manager after the season, but don't expect it to be
Leyland. Insiders say he doesn't want to live on the West Coast.
There have been rumors that the Dodgers will call the Expos to ask
for permission to talk to manager Felipe Alou. New Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone held the same job with Montreal and has a good
relationship with Alou. ... San Diego's Tony Gwynn, who has been
bothered by a sprained right thumb, is back earlier than expected,
saying, ``I've got to get back in there to get my swing down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
