<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-HUMMER-CO     09-19 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For a night, Atlanta rivals Vegas _ OK, not really
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- This fight night, to get to your seat, you did not
pass through the jangle of slot machines or meet the glassy stares
of sleep-deprived card counters. The gambles of an evening card at
the Georgia Dome were more subtle. Should you really risk eating
that yellow stuff on top of the nachos? Might you get lucky in
Buckhead later?
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal did not shake hands with Kevin Costner, who did
not hug Nicole Kidman before the main event. They must have been at
the Tyson hearing. Let's face it, the star quotient in this part of
the world is not high, especially if politicians or country radio
DJs don't really count. Here, it is sometimes more important to see
than be seen.
</P>
<P>
   This crowd, while game, did not wear the usual quantity of
jewels and glitter. What is the deal with dressing up for the
fights, anyway? You should dress for such an event the same as you
would for a Gallagher concert.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being decked out in neon, this fight locale was
ringed by inspirational banners bearing the Don King logo. ``Only
In America.'' ``Liberty Freedom Honor.'' ``Live Free or Die.'' King
has become the Thomas Paine of his generation. If any state ever
runs out of mottoes for its license plates, there's a shock-haired
fight promoter who would be happy to supply it one _ for 30 percent
of the take.
</P>
<P>
   By none of the usual measures is Atlanta a fight town. But it
played one on cable television Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   What this place lacked in traditional ambiance, it more than
made up for in enthusiasm Saturday. Even while the punches from the
early bouts echoed through a mostly empty Dome, officials were
expecting nearly 40,000 to occupy the place by the time Evander
Holyfield took the stage. It was a shocking pronouncement, a last
burst of optimism that was light years away from the reaction when
this idea was first hatched.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have really thought the town would turn out like this
for an event that featured neither linebackers nor monster trucks?
We are not going to bounce any of the usual sites as Mecca for the
fight game until there are blackjack tables in the Margaret
Mitchell House. But for one evening, this place rocked to the
syncopation of flying fists.
</P>
<P>
   This was a powerful testament to Holyfield. ``The Champ Hits
Home'' was the working title of the promotion. And home hit back.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, Holyfield achieved the status of a soloist with
overwhelming drawing power. The kind not seen in this building
since Michael Jordan came calling, back when there was an NBA.
Seven years ago, Holyfield couldn't create much of a stir in the
Omni. Now, he's creating big Dome buzz. He's making fine progress.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, for those in the Georgia Dome's upper tier last
night, it was a prizefight going on down there on the floor, not a
flea circus.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dome slowly filled with the curious, the growing throngs
were treated to an undercard that was at least as varied as any
carnival midway. There was a fight amongst women (Christy Martin is
still the only name to know, if you must), one that called for a
good amount of kicking (no, Mike Tyson was not involved), something
called an interim world middleweight championship (aren't they
all?), and a really fine battle among featherweights whose combined
weight was just 4 pounds less than Vaughn Bean. All a part of the
endless pageant of professional boxing.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, the city was poised to buy the whole package,
both the courageous and the ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
