<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-MOORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's nuttier, Tyson or the commission?
 &HT;    By Terrence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Boring fight after boring fight, the boxing universe
spins closer to what it needs most among heavyweights. We're
talking about Holyfield-Tyson III, minus Iron Mike's tribute to
cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   The only questions are these: Which century will the fight
occur, and will both guys enter the ring with walkers?
</P>
<P>
   What Evander Holyfield likes to say about facing Mike Tyson
again is that he'll never say never. Good. In boxing language, that
means it all depends on the bucks on top of the bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney, who shrugged
before Saturday night's fight at the Georgia Dome against Vaughn
Bean and suggested that the chances of Holyfield-Tyson III rank
with those of the Pacific exchanging places with the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander already has beaten Tyson twice, so there isn't an
incentive to fight him again,'' Thomas said. ``Evander's goal now
is to fight the guys who will help him unify the division by
getting the belt (WBC) that he doesn't have. For Evander to fight
Tyson again, there really would have to be a compelling reason for
him to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   To translate, Holyfield-Tyson III is a certainty. We've already
told you about those bucks on top of the bucks. Although Thomas
said that Holyfield never schedules fights for money, it's like
this: The man doesn't have an estate in Fairburn. He has an entire
state. It costs Holyfield $1 million per year just to keep the
lights on.
</P>
<P>
   There will be Holyfield-Tyson III, all right. This was apparent
long before Holyfield threatened to embarrass Bean before the
Georgia Dome masses screaming for the hometown boy. And that was
long before the Nevada State Athletic Commission embarrassed itself
Saturday in Las Vegas with six hours of nothingness in search of
silliness.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you recall how Tyson's teeth sort of caught Holyfield's
ears during their meeting last summer. Well, the commission quickly
revoked Tyson's boxing license in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Tyson is seeking to regain his license after waiting
the required year, the members of this holy commission want Tyson
to prove something that nobody else has been forced to prove in
this unholy sport since cavemen threw the first punches. That's
civility.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but whether Tyson kicked, punched or even bit a couple of
folks last month after a car accident in Gaithersburg, Md.,
shouldn't factor into the commission's decision. Neither should
Tyson's explosion during a July hearing to get a boxing license in
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Tyson sat out a year and lost enough
millions by not fighting to increase his mighty financial woes. He
paid the commission a $3 million fine. He said he was sorry about
the biting thing. So let's move on with our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the commissioners want Tyson to pick one of three
psychiatrists to evaluate whether he's eligible to join the U.S.
Supreme Court or maybe pilot the next space shuttle. The
commissioners said they'll meet with Tyson again in two weeks after
reviewing the psychiatrist's report.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said he feels like Norman Bates, and he should. That's
because this entire process by the commissioners is psycho.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
