<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Little E' growing up
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- He doesn't look much like his father, but on the
Busch Grand National tracks, there's no mistaking him as a younger
version of Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   He has the aggressiveness, the temperament and, OK, the dents in
his fenders. No one is calling Dale Earnhardt Jr. the Little
Intimidator yet. The handle is ``Little E.''
</P>
<P>
   But give him time.
</P>
<P>
   In his third season on the Busch circuit, Junior has displayed
some of his father's fiery style while dashing to the front of the
point standings. In June, after the Pikes Peak 250, he was fined
$5,000 ``for actions detrimental to racing,'' which is a fancy way
of explaining his postrace shoving match with Tony Stewart's crew
chief in the NASCAR trailer. There had been some bumping during the
final laps.
</P>
<P>
   He was black-flagged in July's South Boston 300 and held for one
lap after running into a lapped driver's back bumper and turning
him sideways into the outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   But Junior is learning to keep his temper under control, and the
result is six victories, including last weekend's Busch race at
Richmond, where he led nearly all the way. He has 13 top-fives in
25 starts and has earned $662,135.
</P>
<P>
   The fine didn't break him, but it might have taught him a
lesson. What money couldn't fix, Dale Sr. could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a little talk with him after the races sometimes,''
Dale Sr. said. ``As the car owner, I'm very proud of him.
Hopefully, we can carry on through the year if he can keep his cool
and think about points. As competitive as he is and the team is, we
want to go out and win races and win the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks must be doing some good. Little E thought the better
of retaliating against Kevin Lepage in the Food City 250 at Bristol
late last month, even though Lepage caused him to wreck and settle
for 15th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like tearing up race cars,'' Junior said. ``We don't
like having to fix torn-up race cars. We've got a championship to
win, and Kevin Lepage is the last thing on the list, as far as
items to think about. We're going to concentrate on winning the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Junior, 23, hadn't won a Busch race or a
pole. His best finish was seventh in nine career starts. The sudden
success and celebrity have accelerated his growing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea we were going to do this well,'' he said. ``But
we came out of the box running good, and we've become a hot topic.
We've had to become somebody right way. I had never met with
sponsors before. I'd done some autograph sessions, but nothing with
like 3,000 race fans standing in line. I've just always been a
T-shirt and jeans guy. But I don't think that's what cuts it
anymore. I've got to clean up my act a little bit, start shaving
every day, things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he is so young and so new to victory lane,
Little E is not that eager to move to Winston Cup, but those are
the plans. He will compete in a few Winston Cup races in 1999, then
go full time in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not anxious to get there on a full-time level yet,'' he
said. ``I've still got a lot of time before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious to see about the competition, see how the show is
run, so to speak. See how much different it is on and off the race
track, compared to the Busch series. Then after running a couple of
those races, I'll know how long I need to prepare for a full
schedule in the Cup series.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
