<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR Notes
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News ServiceWINSTON CUP
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clean racing pays for Burton
</P>
<P>
   After his victory at Richmond, Jeff Burton had an answer for
those wondering why he didn't put Jeff Gordon in the wall in last
year's Southern 500 at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came last Saturday night, when Gordon showed Burton
the same respect he had received last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always driven Jeff clean, and he drove me clean at
Richmond,'' Burton said. ``I feel what I gave last year came back
to me. Had we wrecked at Darlington, I bet the outlook at Richmond
would have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon acknowledges he could have taken a cheap shot at Burton,
but said, ``I like racing a guy hard and clean and trying to make
the pass that way. Jeff raced me the same way. It was a heck of a
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Park cleared
</P>
<P>
   Steve Park has been cleared to drive in today's MBNA 400 at
Dover. Park crashed Monday while testing at Homestead and was
hospitalized for a short period of time. He was released after a
CAT scan and X-rays indicated no head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baldwin Jr. is the new crew chief for Bill Davis Racing.
Baldwin comes to Davis from Junie Donlavey and replaces Chris
Hussey, who served as crew chief for the No. 22 team since 1994.
Hussey will be reassigned at Davis Racing. ... Stat of the week:
Morgan-McClure is the only current single-car Chevrolet team to
have won a race since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Dover lover
</P>
<P>
   Going back to Dover for Saturday's Busch race was like B'rer
Rabbit returning to his briar patch for Ken Schrader _ it feels
like home. ``I don't know why, but Dover has been a real good track
for me,'' Schrader said. ``It's one mile and you slam down in the
corner, but you're running so fast, it feels like you're running a
quarter mile (track). Winning here (in 1989) was special because it
was my own team that ran on a part-time basis. I love the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Sadler finished sixth here a year ago and is bringing
the same car to Dover Downs. ``We tried something new in the
spring, and it didn't work out. So, we brought `Old Faithful'
back,'' said Sadler. ... NASCAR Busch Series regulars have
dominated Dover races. Bobby Labonte's victory in 1997 is the only
one by a Winston Cup regular in the past 13 races here.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Engines break
</P>
<P>
   Scott Walters went into Saturday's Ram Tough 200 at Gateway
International Raceway with redemption on his mind. Last week, his
team suffered its first DNF of the year, an engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are going to happen,'' Walters said. ``In no way
was it a reflection on this team and what we can do. Sometimes
things break.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other failure the team had this year was at Texas Motor
Speedway in April. Walters was out of contention when he tangled
with two other trucks. ``I got a few cuts and bruises in the wreck,
but we were right back in it the next week,'' said Walters, who is
21st in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week
</P>
<P>
   The 15 points by which Jack Sprague leads Ron Hornaday going
into this week's race is the smallest post-Labor Day advantage in
series history. The previous closest margin, 31 points, came in
1995, when Mike Skinner led Joe Ruttman after his victory at
Martinsville. Skinner ultimately became the tour's first champion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
