<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERMOBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robert W. Sherman, longtime Cox exec., dies
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Robert W. Sherman, the first president of The
Palm Beach Post and its sister publications after they were
acquired by Cox Enterprises, died Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sherman devoted 50 years to the newspaper business, starting
as a classified ad salesman for the Dayton Daily News in 1928 at
age 18.
</P>
<P>
   He retired Jan. 1, 1979, as executive vice president and a
member of the board of directors of the Atlanta-based chain which
now owns 16 daily newspapers _ including ones in Atlanta, Dayton
and Austin _ and 11 weeklies.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was he the top executive of Palm Beach Newspapers Inc.
for six years, but Mr. Sherman helped negotiate the purchase from
John H. Perry in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob had a contact who worked for the (West Palm Beach) paper.
He and I went down and negotiated with Mr. Perry,'' said Carl
Gross, retired senior vice president of the Cox group.
</P>
<P>
   Some details of the purchase were worked out when Perry treated
the two buyers to lunch at Arby's.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase included The Post, the Evening Times, the Palm
Beach Daily News, Palm Beach Life magazine and weekly papers in
Delray Beach and Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Cox purchase, the morning Post and Evening Times
operated under a single editor and a unified staff. Mr. Sherman
divided them into separate newsgathering staffs, each with its own
editor.
</P>
<P>
   The evening newspaper was discontinued in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was a tall, Lincolnesque figure, very quiet. When he said
something, he meant it,'' said Charles Glover, who followed Mr.
Sherman through the ranks of Cox Newspapers and eventually became
president of the parent company, Cox Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Mr. Sherman was named chairman of the board of Palm
Beach Newspapers and resumed his duties as senior vice president
for development for the Cox group.
</P>
<P>
   He negotiated the purchase of the Austin American-Statesman and
other Texas papers in 1976, then took over supervision of the
construction of a Cox newsprint plant in South Carolina until he
retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in charge of development during one of the most active
periods in American newspapers. And he was very keen at it,'' said
Clarke Ash, retired editorial page editor of The Post.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sherman advanced through the ranks of the Dayton newspaper,
becoming personnel director in 1958 and business manager in 1961,
handling all the labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   He headed newsprint manufacturing for the Cox papers for several
years in the mid-1960s. When the Augusta mill was sold in 1968, Mr.
Sherman became Cox vice president for development.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sherman also served in the U.S. Army during World War II,
spending most of his tour in France.
</P>
<P>
   He received an honorary doctorate in humanities from the
University of Dayton in 1994, said June Sherman, his wife. Mr.
Sherman started a scholarship bearing his name at the university
because he wasn't able to attend college, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had an interest in helping young people,'' June
Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, June, two daughters and three
stepsons. A memorial service will be held 7 p.m. Tuesday at the
First Presbyterian Church in Boca Raton, 600 W. Camino Real. The
funeral will be held in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family has asked that donations go to
Hospice By The Sea Care Center in Boca Raton or the Robert W.
Sherman Scholarship Fund at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
