<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASS-FANS20-COX     09-19 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-FANS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans line river at dawn to watch someone else fish
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moline, Ill. -- There's usually not much to see from the 55th
Street boat ramp at 6 a.m. _ just some ducks congregating near the
Mississippi River shoreline, a barge carrying cargo downstream and
the reflection of the lights on Centennial Bridge, which links the
Quad Cities of Illinois and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   For the hundreds of fans who lined the river each day this week
to watch the pros blast off in the Wal-Mart FLW Tour World Bass
Fishing Championships, however, there was the bonus of seeing the
sport's best anglers hit the water, the blue-and-white night-time
lights of their boats blurring away up river at 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not something that'll raise goose bumps for many, but
it certainly brings out the bassin' fans, who mix dedication to
their sport with a good measure of insanity to get up before
daylight to watch someone else fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to watch the big boys launch,'' said Rick Salsman, a
second-shift welder from Coal Valley, Ill., who brought his teenage
daughter Mindy to be among the 300 or so at the ramp Thursday.
``The blastoff is pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're pretty nuts,'' Mindy added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishermen are nuts,'' her father clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Which might explain Fred Kuntz and Gary Dees, friends from
Moline, who had a breakfast picnic on a table near the activity.
The two weren't quite sure what was going on until someone told
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just hanging out,'' said Dees, who caught a channel
catfish and grilled it for breakfast. He pointed to the river:
``This is our TV.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll find as many different types of people at a professional
bass tournament as there are buzzbaits on sale to catch finicky
fish.
</P>
<P>
   There are family members of the anglers, who brave a hectic
schedule on the road traveling from tournament to tournament to
wish their loved ones well.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kron was in town from Maryville, Tenn., with her
husband, Ben, who was fishing in the nonboater, or amateur, class.
She stood under a street light with Ben's brother Richard and his
fiancee, Shirley, who live in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so bad to get up so early just to watch her husband
``as long as you get to bed early,'' Barbara Kron said. ``Last
night, it was 8 p.m. When the fisherman says it's time to go to
bed, you go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybelline Watts of Grove City, Ohio, was battling a sore throat
but still was able to attend the daily weigh ins at the Moline
Wal-Mart Supercenter to cheer her husband, Robert, also a
non-boater. Her eyes began to water as she explained why the hard
life on the road was worth it to see her husband, who retired two
years ago after battling lung and throat cancer, fulfill his dream
of fishing professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to be able to fish after two years of cancer
treatments,'' she said, ``it's just been a wonderful reward.''
</P>
<P>
   There are the serious anglers who hope to pick up something from
the pros they can use themselves. John Larson and his stepbrother
Jim Collins of East Moline are hoping one day to become pros and
rake in some money like the $250,000 first-place FLW prize offered
this week. They followed friend Wesley Strader, a young pro from
Spring City, Tenn. They were at every weigh in, most of the
launches and even had plans to get out on the water to learn what
they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him in a honey hole,'' Larson said about some advice he
tried to pass along to Strader. ``I just hope he goes there,
because there's fish in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the curious, like Phil Miles of Coal Valley, who
was one of 1,000 or so at the first-day weigh in, because ``I just
wanted to see a nice stringer of bass''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've also come to see the celebrities,'' Miles said. ``I see
them on TV. To see them up close and be able to talk to them is
pretty nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass fishing has thrived on its connection with its fans. Often
likened to the fan base of NASCAR auto racing, the fans flock to
the sport's bigger tournaments by the thousands to watch the pros
on the water and at the weigh ins.
</P>
<P>
   The BASS Masters Classic last month in Greensboro, N.C., had
crowds in the tens of thousands just to watch the anglers parade
one by one across the stage and listen to them explain how they
caught 'em or why they didn't. Hundreds more waited on the water
every morning to follow the top pros as they fished, much like a
gallery might follow Tiger Woods at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30 million Americans are bass anglers, resulting in
an industry worth $40 billion. Those numbers have tournament
organizers and sponsors, many of whom are not fishing-specific
companies, realizing the potential payoff in tapping the interest
of the fans, in part with the help of wholesome role models who
star on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the pros who are here are to some fans what Jeff
Gordon is to the racing fans,'' said James Key of Troy, Ala., a
representative of EverStar batteries, one of the FLW sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart FLW Tour, a significant player in the industry in
only three years of existence, had packed more than 10,000 fans
into a large air-conditioned tent by Saturday for the weigh ins.
Thousands more attended the FLW Family Fun Zone area surrounding
the tent, offering family activities like casting contests and
cookie decorating for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially millions more had the chance to see Saturday's final
weigh in, thanks to a satellite uplink that will broadcast the
proceedings to the monitors in the electronics departments at 1,900
Wal-Marts across the U.S. During that broadcast, which will show
the top five anglers going head to head for the top prize of
$250,000 in a format much like PGA coverage, fans will have a
chance via cellular phone to ask questions of the anglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use the analogy of like having the opportunity to
listen in on Brett Favre calling a play during the Super Bowl,''
says Brian Sayner, vice president of communications for Operation
Bass, which runs the Wal-Mart FLW events, ``and be able to ask him,
`Why are you running that play?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
