<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-TOUR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hite bags five fish to win close fight
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. _ Tommy Biffle's prediction that either he or Davy
Hite would win the largest payoff in bass fishing history was right
on the mark. The only problem, however, was that it also meant he
could finish second.
</P>
<P>
   Hite, a six-year pro from Prosperity, S.C., caught five fish
weighing 10 pounds, 13 ounces to beat Biffle, of Wagoner, Okla. _
who also caught five fish _ by 12 ounces to win the Wal-Mart FLW
Tour World Bass Fishing Championship Saturday. Hite, who also had
the highest cumulative total (21-6) for the four-day event on the
Mississippi River, won $250,000, paid to him in a suitcase full of
cash by an armed Moline police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money,'' said Hite after receiving the
briefcase. ``I don't think I've ever seen $250,000 in cash
before.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that it came down to Hite and Biffle. The two
had shared a productive small area of backwater north of Moline in
what is called Pool 13 the entire tournament and had agreed to
divide the spot. There were so many keepable (more than 14 inches)
fish in the weedy spot that it caused Biffle's prediction Friday
when the field was trimmed to five.
</P>
<P>
   Hite said when he found the hard-to-get-to spot during
pre-tournament practice he called his wife, Natalie, to tell her he
found an area that could win the tournament. He didn't think he'd
be sharing it until Biffle, who noticed the area on a map before
checking it out, showed up on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe with one other boat I thought I could still win it,''
Hite said, ``but not with more than one other boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Biffle, whose total included a 4-ounce penalty for returning
with a dead fish, finished second in the event for the second
consecutive year. He also finished second in the BASS Masters
Classic, the sport's other major championship, winning $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before the tournament that if I came in second place
again, I'd be mad,'' said Biffle, who'll get another chance at
redemption when the FLW Tour Championship is held on his home lake,
Fort Gibson Lake near Tulsa, Okla., next September. ``It's a big
disappointment, but one of these days I'm going to win one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Klein of Weatherford, Texas, was third with two fish
weighing 4-4, George Cochran fourth with 4-0 and Jerry Williams of
Conway, Ark., fifth with 3-9.
</P>
<P>
   All five anglers started from scratch Saturday, and were
weighed-in in front a crowd of about 1,200 under a large tent used
as a studio for upcoming broadcasts on ESPN. Each angler weighed
their fish one-by-one in a last-man-standing format. Hite needed
2-2 to beat Biffle when his final fish was weighed at 2-13.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
