<HEADLINE>
LUYENDYK SWITCHES TO BACKUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By LEN HAYWARD and JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Treadway Racing, which fields cars for Arie
Luyendyk, decided to pull its primary entry and use a backup car
for today's Lone Star 500K because of engine trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk had qualified 20th with a speed of 219.646 mph, but he
will start today's race from the back because of the switch.
</P>
<P>
   The team made three engine changes on Friday, and according to a
statement from the team, its third motor, which was the race motor,
``developed a problem that would eliminate it from competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The team had only one engine left and it was in the backup car.
Luyendyk also did not run during Saturday's final practice
session. &QL; 
CURRY DENIES FOYT CHARGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Curry, team manager of Team Menard, denied that he and
driver Tony Stewart were playing games Friday in the qualifying
line for today's Lone Star 500K.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt, owner of pole-winner Billy Boat's car, took exception
to a series of decisions by top competitors to pull out of their
originally scheduled spots in the qualifying order during the heat
of the day. Boat, the second driver to qualify, ran an IRL-record
lap at 225.979 mph on a track with a reported temperature of 127
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Boat then had to wait-out the session as pole contenders Greg
Ray (engine change), Arie Luyendyk (engine change), Scott Sharp
(wiring problem) and Stewart (engine change) pulled out of line.
Foyt interpreted those as deliberate moves to get to the rear of
the line, at a time when conditions theoretically would be cooler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear (the rule is) going to be different at Las Vegas,''
said Foyt, referring to the season ender Oct. 11. ``If not, we're
all going to change engines before qualifying. That's what I told
'em. I'm not going to be no goose like I was here, with them
shooting at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody burned their bridges'' Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Curry reiterated that his team had changed engines after blowing
a motor with 10 minutes to go in practice. And Menard confirmed
that the team also changed tires before Stewart qualified at
224.869 mph, to join Boat on the front row. Those moves were all by
the book, Curry said. &QL; 
RAY A MENARD CANDIDATE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Curry said that Ray, a resident of Plano, is a serious
contender for the seat at Team Menard that will be vacated by
Stewart at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the reigning IRL champion, is scheduled to run the
NASCAR Winston Cup schedule in 1999 for team owner Joe Gibbs.
Stewart will be a teammate to native Texan Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some discussions with Ray,'' Curry said. ``I would
say there's a very short list, and he's on that list.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry said team owner John Menard still is considering if he
wants to run a two-car team in 1999. Robbie Buhl is driving
Menard's second car this year. &QL; 
KITE SEARCHING FOR RIDE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After this year's Indianapolis 500, Georgia native Jimmy Kite
was one of the hottest drivers in the Indy Racing League. He had a
frustrating week at the famous track because he wrecked his Team
Scandia entry three times before he even attempted to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   He started 26th and ended up 11th, and was among six first-year
drivers to finish in the top 15.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Indy 500, Team Scandia announced that it was
going to take Kite stock-car racing. The team eventually wanted to
move up to Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That deal has since ended, and yesterday Kite was walking
through the garage with noted racing attorney Cary Agajanian trying
to find a ride for next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
