u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-HNS &LR;      09-19 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CITY MOVES ON UNEASILY AFTER MASSACRE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DUDLEY ALTHAUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENSENADA, Mexico _ As family members buried the victims of a
vicious gangland attack outside this booming weekend resort on
Saturday, many of the California tourists who flock here and the
Mexicans who attend to them tried to put the gruesome massacre out
of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury resort hotels serving tourists from north of the
border filled to near capacity. Two cruise ships pulled into the
harbor on a six-hour shopping layover, disgorging thousands of
consumers in shorts. Surfers, anglers and beer drinkers sprawled on
rocky beaches and lounged in the bars and restaurants downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Only an hour's drive by toll road south of the U.S. border,
Ensenada has become an increasingly popular destination for
Southern Californians looking for a several-day ``Mexican
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ensenada's marimba-and-margarita image has long
co-existed with a more sinister reality, which, authorities say,
expressed itself last week. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Eighteen people _ including a baby in diapers, several toddlers
and five other children _ were shot to death before dawn Thursday,
when as many as a dozen gunmen attacked a walled compound six miles
north of Ensenada. Cattleman and reputed drug smuggler Fermin
Castro and members of his extended family lived there.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Thursday's attack was somehow linked to drug
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   For years, cocaine from Colombia, heroin from Asia and marijuana
from Mexico have flowed from ships and planes through the Ensenada
area toward U.S. consumers. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Officials say Castro, a 38-year-old Paipai Indian and former
schoolteacher who had become wealthy in recent years, was one of a
handful of local smugglers who have made Ensenada increasingly
important in the narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   After apparently torturing Castro inside his house, the
attackers herded him and members of his extended family against a
low wall in the courtyard between the compound's three houses, then
shot them with automatic weapons and pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and a 12-year-old nephew were injured but survived the
shooting, authorities say. His pregnant 15-year-old daughter,
Viviana Castro Tovar, eluded the gunmen by hiding under a bed.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors trickled through Ensenada on Saturday that Castro had
died from his wounds, but government officials insisted that he
remained alive. Army troops guarded the Ensenada hospital where he
reportedly was receiving care.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Castro's family are worried about the safety of his
daughter, Viviana, who escaped the attack unharmed. The girl, who
is seven months pregnant, was taken by government officials for
``safe keeping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The police have Viviana Castro in protective custody,'' read a
typed note left anonymously under the windshield wiper of a
reporter's car. ``But what happens to her after she testifies?''
</P>
<P>
   Among those killed in the attack were Castro's wife and their
2-year-old son; Castro's sister, her husband and children; and
Castro's sister-in-law, her husband and children. Castro's in-laws
said the family buried the massacre victims in private ceremonies
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials say they still aren't sure about the
exact motive for the killings. They insist, however, that the
attack had no links to an ongoing struggle pitting a powerful
drug-smuggling clan in Tijuana against another narcotics
organization in Ciudad Juarez, across the border from El Paso. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Although shocked by the massacre, many people in Ensenada
insist that the killings have nothing to do with them or their
increasingly prosperous city.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of people die every year in gangland squabbles
related to the drug trade along the U.S.-Mexico border, innocent
people are rarely targeted. Some early theories about Thursday's
massacre suggested that the killings had more to do with personal
feuds or land disputes than narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is stuff between those families,'' real estate developer
Jorge Ramirez said of the massacre victims, who were killed a short
distance from a burgeoning development of luxury houses owned by
U.S. retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with these people,'' he said, nodding
toward the million-dollar houses that stand up the hill from his
office.
</P>
<P>
   A rapidly growing city of about 300,000 people, Ensenada's
economy has been shifting toward tourism and manufacturing since a
U.S. embargo of Mexican tuna has all but killed the local fisheries
industry in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   New hotels are springing up along the city's rocky coastline.
Foreign-owned factories that will produce electronics, clothes and
other goods for export are being built on the edges of town. A new
sea-front promenade has been constructed, downtown streets are
being improved, and docks for cruise ships are being expanded.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. dollars seem more welcome than Mexican pesos.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are as likely to speak English as Spanish, often
without an accent. Signs along the highway remind visitors _ in
English _ that littering is unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are in your own country, with all its customs,'' Ramirez
said of the city's attractions for Mexicans. ``But you are 50
minutes from the richest country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Tourism official Felizardo Palacios has expressed concerns
that the slaughter of unarmed men, women and children might stop
tourists from coming to Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, that has not happened. Palacios said more people
came to Ensenada this weekend than last, despite news of the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an annual chili cook-off with rock bands and yard
games kicked off on schedule at a hotel only a few miles from the
site of the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have anything to do with me,'' Roberto Adado, of
Riverside, Calif., said of the massacre, as he cast a fishing line
into the gray surf from a rocky beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrendous, but you're OK, if you mind your own
business,'' he said. ``Just like anywhere else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
