<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NEWT-COX     09-19 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEWT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich avoids scathing rhetoric
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In another time, Newt Gingrich would have relished
an all-out attack on President Clinton as much as any other
Republican in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   He would have scoffed at party elders who tried to rein in his
speeches on the House floor, speeches that first made his national
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich would have regarded his more reticent colleagues as too
timid at a time when they should have been pressing their partisan
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998, as the speaker of the House, Gingrich is managing
the most delicate issue of his long career in Congress by publicly
urging caution and forgoing by the dozen opportunities to speak
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do our duty. We won't rush to judgment. We won't
refrain from judgment,'' Gingrich said Friday at the Christian
Coalition's annual Washington conference.
</P>
<P>
   He is attempting to strike a balance between assuring
Republicans that their leaders are not backing down from their
pledges to pursue possible impeachment proceedings and reassuring
the wider public that the GOP is not intent on bringing down
Clinton at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Much is riding on Gingrich's performance. The one thing
Republicans cannot afford is public perception that they are not
being fair to Clinton. Congressional Democrats already are making
those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri, denouncing
the House Judiciary Committee's vote Friday to release Clinton's
videotaped grand jury testimony, specifically asked Gingrich to
``do more to ensure that fairness and bipartisanship will be the
guiding principles of this inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's aides have consistently referred questions about
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report to the committee,
declining to put Gingrich's imprimatur on the panel's work.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker has shown up at events on education and agriculture
and he has talked about the GOP's proposed $80 billion tax cut as
part of an effort to show that Republicans intend to take care of
the nation's business, scandal or not.
</P>
<P>
   Touting an education bill, Gingrich criticized a reporter who
asked about the Clinton testimony videotape by pointing out that he
had spent just 45 minutes on the topic out of a 14-hour work day.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has such a strong public image as a partisan that he
has to be especially careful. While his standing in public opinion
polls has climbed over the past year, nearly half those polled by
the Washington Post in July rated Gingrich unfavorably, compared to
a third who viewed him favorably.
</P>
<P>
   The polling issue relates directly to Gingrich's presidential
aspirations. If he turns in a statesmanlike performance, ``he could
come out of this greatly enhanced,'' said Ralph Reed, the
Republican political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would dispel some of the scars of 1995 and 1996,'' brought
on by the government shutdown and his violation of House ethics
rules, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's public demeanor has done little to dispel Democrats'
belief that the speaker is calling all the shots in the Judiciary
Committee's first look at the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) and other Democrats said they assume
Gingrich is aware, and at least tacitly approves, of Majority Whip
Tom DeLay's (R-Texas) attacks on Clinton or Rep. Henry Hyde's
(R-Ill.) position in favor of releasing the supporting materials to
Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   They also pointed to the letter Gingrich and other Republican
House leaders sent to FBI Director Louis Freeh to ask for an
investigation of allegations that the White House is conducting a
smear campaign against congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker also alluded Friday to the possibility of expanding
the committee's investigation to include such other topics as
campaign finance violations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican House members also have made clear Gingrich's
role in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker told a closed-door meeting of House Republicans that
they should push to make public Clinton's testimony and resist
calls from some in their own party to limit the release of
salacious material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't let Newt drive my train. I don't care what the speaker
says I should do,'' Republican Rep. Lindsey Graham of South
Carolina said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
