<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET PHYSICAL _ AND GET BURNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ UCLA cornerbacks Marques Anderson and Jason Bell used
the same coverage techniques they employed last week against Texas,
but with a wholly different result.
</P>
<P>
   Their physical style elicited five pass interference calls and
forced them to change their approach _ a change which left them
vulnerable to Houston's aerial attack.
</P>
<P>
   Cougars quarterback Jason McKinley completed 21 of 46 passes for
269 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get aggressive with them, get in their pads, then
the officials starting calling PIs (pass interference) left and
right,'' Anderson said. ``When they started calling them, we had to
ease up. We didn't do anything different than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's maximum-protection blocking scheme prevented UCLA's
blitzers from pressuring McKinley. Without effective blitzes,
Anderson and Bell were left in man-to-man coverage for unusually
long periods. When it's one-on-one in the open field, every second
counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave their quarterback an opportunity,'' Anderson said.
``They got some 15-yard comeback passes on me, and that's unheard
of in Division I.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars appeared to pick on Bell, a junior from Long Beach
who lacks Anderson's sprinter speed. Bell failed on several short
passes, but he did not allow any game-changing completions. In
fact, UCLA's cornerbacks allowed just one long touchdown pass _ a
34-yarder to Jerrian James _ and that came against reserve Ryan
Roques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell was unbelievable,'' defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti
said. ``What a great game. How many times was he out there
one-on-one?''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen update: Two true freshmen played for the first time,
cornerback Julius Williams and defensive tackle Anthony Fletcher,
meaning they are no longer eligible to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Williams joined the rotation earlier this week, when
second-string cornerback Damian Allen quit. The 6-foot-3, 292-pound
Fletcher, from San Dimas, was called upon Saturday after Kenyon
Coleman injured his knee in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a direct result of Kenyon's injury,'' Aliotti said.
``But I see (Fletcher) as being a good defensive lineman. He's big
and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Coleman sprained the medial collateral ligament
in his right knee and probably will miss 3-4 weeks. UCLA's goal
probably is to have him back for the Oct. 10 showdown at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very, very surprised if his (anterior cruciate
ligament) is injured,'' said UCLA physician Dr. Gerald Finerman.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, inside linebacker Tony White injured his right
shoulder and is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: The Bruins converted just 4 of 13 third-down
attempts.... Houston had 92 plays, UCLA 67.... Larry Atkins led
UCLA with 10 tackles and two pass breakups.... The Bruins had two
sacks, one by Ryan Nece, the other by Billy Pieper.... Nine Bruins
caught passes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
