<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-RAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY'S CAR OK, WILL START RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Greg Ray figures to be up-and-running for
today's Lone Star 500K in a car that spent most of yesterday in for
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, of Plano, spun out on the frontstraight and tagged the
outside retaining wall in Turn 1 with the left side of his car only
11 minutes into yesterday morning's practice. The left side
suspension on the No. 97 Best Access Systems Dallara/Aurora was
heavily damaged, as well as the left front wing.
</P>
<P>
   But team owner Thomas Knapp and his crew spent the day making
repairs, and Ray is scheduled to take the green flag from his
originally scheduled 12th starting spot for the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the car will be OK,'' said Ray, who missed the entire
final afternoon practice as repairs continued. IRL officials ``are
going to let us run a few laps (this morning). That's a safety
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said A.J. Foyt Racing and Team Menard offered to supply
parts to Knapp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had enough parts, and the ones we didn't have we went to
the Dallara trailer,'' Ray said. ``It was probably a $40,000
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray spent part of his downtime reviewing video of the crash
recorded by his in-car camera. Ray had turned a hot lap of 221.157
mph before returning to the pits for fresh Firestone tires. Ray was
in the process of warming those tires when his day went awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was right behind Robbie Buhl in turns 3 and 4, and the car
pulled hard left,'' Ray said. ``I kept turning into and then
basically drove right through the grass. When I hit the grass, the
car lost control and it swapped ends. I still can't tell what
happened. I was only doing 150 mph, still going straight, and it
pulled left.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said even his review of the video did not provide a
definitive explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence isn't shaken. When I get in the car, I always
drive the same,'' said Ray, who is eligible for the Texas Two-Step
bonus of $100,000 today. ``I've just had this real uneasiness all
day, because I don't know what happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
