<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-KING-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE OF THE PIGS  
 KING'S WIN WAS BIG BLOW TO CHAUVINISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many men felt like civilization as we knew it ended 25 years ago
tonight in the Houston Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   That evening Billie Jean King beat a 55-year-old hustler named
Bobby Riggs in a tennis match that had little to do with tennis and
everything to do with social change.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us who attended the ``Battle of the Sexes'' and openly
rooted for Mr. Riggs are still paying off bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folded the laundry?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet dear,'' we sing out from the kitchen, one oven mitt on
fire. ``I'll get to it right after dinner. Hope the casserole is
all right. It's a little brown on top. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King may have done as much in one night to empower
women and advance the women's movement _ and gender equity in
sports _ as Susan B. Anthony and Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   They should mint a coin in her likeness, or honor her with a
commemorative stamp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a foolish bet and a grave mistake to place our faith in
Riggs. But most males in the crowd of 40,000 did. We felt it was
our duty. Like fraternity brothers, we had to stick together.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early 1970s the women's lib movement was in full
flower. A showman and shameless self-promoter, Riggs earned
national notoriety by challenging the best female tennis players to
a winner-take-all match. Margaret Court accepted. Riggs beat the
No. 1 ranked woman convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   King was ranked No. 2. Riggs wanted her next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a woman wants to get in the headlines, she should have
quintuplets,'' Riggs declared. The 1939 Wimbledon champion and
card-carrying male chauvinist said he wanted to join the women's
pro tennis tour. Easy money. Riggs even offered to undergo ``the
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no choice,'' King recalled. She knew this was
vaudeville. Riggs' goading was pure shtick. ``But I had to play
Bobby. And I had to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the big night, the Astrodome was as divided as the House
Judiciary Committee. Four of us went together, a double date. The
seating arrangement was he, he, she, she. The guys were the ones
wearing ``Pigs For Riggs'' buttons in support of the aging sex
symbol, whose duck-footed walk and dinky style of tennis cast him
as a plucky underdog. Actually, Bobby was an 8-5 favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Females in the crowd stood as one when King entered the arena
carried on a Egyptian litter like Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   We counted on Riggs. The flamboyant huckster with his suitcase
full of vitamins assured us he would win. Riggs declared that if he
lost he would jump off a bridge, although looking back I don't
recall him ever saying which one.
</P>
<P>
   If I can ever bring myself to write a book about the experience
the title will be, ``The Night Tennis Went A-Ms.''
</P>
<P>
   Our man didn't just lose. Billie Jean woman-handled him.
</P>
<P>
   Then 29, at the top of her game, King had too much youth and
strength and speed. She took Bobby's moon-shot lobs out of the Dome
lights and rifled them back. She ran Riggs around like a show dog.
She owned the net.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second set, as our tiring standard bearer
wound down like a grandfather clock, members of the women's pro
tour happily began passing out gag tickets to a ``Bobby Riggs
Bridge Jump.'' King won in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   I recall walking with my buddy to the car in silence, two steps
behind our dates, avoiding their smug superior smiles.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface the match wasn't much more than a carnival stunt.
``It didn't mean that much to me personally because I didn't feel
like I beat anybody,'' King said. ``I think Bobby was born in 1918
_ the same year my dad was born. ``What I didn't expect,'' King
said years later, ``was how it helped women in general to gain a
little courage. Their self-esteem went up a little bit. I walked
into a newspaper in Philadelphia a few days later and the people in
the newsroom stood up and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women gathered around and said they had felt underpaid for
a long time. They deserved a raise, but didn't have the guts to ask
for it. They said, `The day after you played Bobby, we went in to
see the boss and asked for a raise.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `The important thing is, did you get it?' And they
said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People draw strength from odd places. If my winning encouraged
someone to take a little more control of their destiny, if it gave
them the guts to take a chance, even if they failed, then that
makes me happy.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
