<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-REDS-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA GOES 0 FOR 4; REDS BEAT CUBS, 7-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For their last homestand of the season, the Chicago
Cubs planned a full weekend of festivities to honor Sammy Sosa,
culminating in a ceremony before Sunday's game that the Cubs
promised would rival the gift-showering in St. Louis on Sept. 8
after Mark McGwire's 62nd home run.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the commissioner of baseball, has said he will attend
the game Sunday, and Saturday the Maris family made its first trip
to Wrigley Field to see Sosa play. And as the attention on the home
run chase grew _ if that is even possible _ Sosa went 0 for 4 with
three strikeouts in the Cubs' 7-2 loss to Cincinnati, their second
straight to the fifth-place Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has not hit a homer since he smacked his 63rd home run in
San Diego on Wednesday night; he is 0 for 12 since then, and 0 for
7 against the Reds. In his fourth at-bat Saturday, he grounded into
a double play to end the game; he has failed to hit the ball out of
the infield since coming home to Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Cubs back into a tie in the National League
wild-card race with the Mets, who beat Florida Saturday, 4-3. It
has now been 42 days since more than one game separated the two
teams in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sosa's three strikeouts, the 40,357 fans at Wrigley, led
by the Maris family in the front row behind the Cubs' on-deck
circle, vigilantly stood and cheered for his at-bats, trying to
will Sosa into hitting a home run. In a tally on the roof of one of
the houses across Waveland Avenue from the ball park, a giant 63
was changed to a 64 during every at-bat, and then returned to 63.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' starter, Jason Bere (2-2), gave up Sosa's 56th home
run here on Sept. 2. Saturday he pitched eight innings, his longest
outing in more than three years. He gave up a single to Lance
Johnson to start the game and then did not yield another hit until
the sixth inning; it was the only other hit he gave up. Cubs second
baseman Mickey Morandini hit a single in the ninth off reliever
Danny Graves, Morandini's 1,000th career hit, before Sosa hit into
the game-ending double play. The three hits for the Cubs brought
their total for the series to just nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sammy, you just have to challenge him and go at him,''
Bere said. ``I tried to mix it up a little bit, and today it
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Reds' pitchers again managed to baffle Sosa, the
sell-out crowd did get to witness a home run display by a powerful
right fielder; it just was not the one they came to see. Reds right
fielder Jon Nunnally hit two home runs and drove in four runs, both
of which tied career-best performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows I'm a human being,'' Sosa said after the game.
``The last couple of days they've just been pitching me great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
