<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-KANSAS-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' HEISMAN HOPES TAKE HIT AS LONGHORNS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN, Kan. _ For the second consecutive week, the Texas
Longhorns boosted the Heisman Trophy campaign of an opposing
quarterback and helped shovel dirt on the candidacy of their
record-setting tailback.
</P>
<P>
   For a second consecutive season, they will limp into a game
against Rice coming off abject humiliation on network television.
This time, fifth-ranked Kansas State inflicted the damage with
yesterday's 48-7 shellacking in front of 43,714 at KSU Stadium and
an ABC regional audience.
</P>
<P>
   What the rout lacked in terms of point differential when
compared to last year's 66-3 loss to UCLA was offset by the
across-the-board dominance of the beating. Kansas State scored
touchdowns on offense, defense and special teams. The Wildcats
stopped Ricky Williams from crossing the line of scrimmage on six
of his first 14 carries.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just in the first half, which ended with Kansas
State on top, 35-0.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Texas concluded its most lopsided loss to a
conference opponent since a 50-7 pounding by Baylor in 1989,
Williams' Heisman hopes were hanging by a thread, and the Longhorns
(1-2, 0-1 in Big 12) were conceding they were no match for the more
physical Wildcats (3-0, 1-0). Especially not with redshirt freshman
quarterback Major Applewhite (16-of-37, 232 yards) forced to make
his first start on a windy day against the nation's top-ranked
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outmatched and ran into a buzzsaw,'' said first-year
Texas coach Mack Brown, whose team was outgained 405-292 and lost
the turnover battle, 4-2. ``We're just not ready for a team like
this at this point in our program. To be honest, I was amazed ...
Major did as well as he did. This is the wrong place for a redshirt
freshman quarterback to make his first start.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite was forced into duty because of a broken finger
sustained by starter Richard Walton. Kansas State greeted him by
crowding nine men at the line of scrimmage to slow Williams, who
rushed for 375 yards and nine touchdowns in Texas' first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite never forced the Wildcats to change their defensive
approach, and Williams never gained more than seven yards on any of
his 25 carries. He was thrown for losses five times and finished
with 43 yards (1.7 per carry), his lowest output since _ all
together now _ last year's debacle against UCLA, when Williams
carried 13 times for 36 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they've got nine men waiting and you've only got seven
blockers, the numbers don't work out,'' said Williams, who watched
Kansas State quarterback Michael Bishop account for 223 yards and
three touchdowns in a second consecutive matchup of Heisman
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's rematch with UCLA, Bruins' quarterback Cade
McNown threw for 329 yards and three touchdowns in a 49-31 victory.
Being overshadowed by fellow Heisman candidates in consecutive
weeks ``is going to hurt me, but not kill me'' in the chase for
college football's most coveted honor, Williams predicted.
</P>
<P>
   More telling for Texas' bowl hopes will be shoring up a defense
that allowed 5.7 yards per snap and a punt-coverage unit that
watched David Allen average 43 yards on four runbacks, including a
93-yarder for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although Applewhite completed three passes longer than 30 yards
and connected with Wane McGarity on a 13-yard touchdown strike, he
also threw two interceptions. One killed a drive that reached the
Wildcats' 19-yard line, and the other was returned for a touchdown
by linebacker Jeff Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the way I played because of the
interceptions,'' said Applewhite, who nonetheless drew positive
review from coaches and teammates. ``Even though people expected me
to make some mistakes, it makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scoring on two returns, Kansas State turned three
Texas turnovers into touchdown drives of 23, 23 and 80 yards. They
also had touchdown marches of 80 and 69 yards, while Texas took
just three of its 65 snaps inside the Wildcats' 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't move the ball ... and we had too many turnovers,''
Brown said, summarizing the Longhorns' long day. ``Everyone feels
miserable.'' Extra points Williams' first-quarter fumble was his
first in 143 carries. ... Freshman defensive end Jermain Anderson
recorded his first career sack in the fourth quarter, prompting
Kansas State coach Bill Snyder to slam his headphones. ... Snyder
kept his first-team offense in the game until 2:53 remained.
</P>
</TEXT>
