<HEADER>
A4631 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-RECORD-AZ     09-19 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-RECORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MARIS' MARK DOWN, IS GRETZKY'S NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took 37 years before two sluggers named Big Mac and Slammin'
Sammy came along and broke Roger Maris' single-season home run
record of 61 set in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But with the final days of the historic 1998 baseball season
upon us _ as fans wonder how many more homers Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa will hit _ it spurs the question as the NHL preseason
unfolds: Will anyone ever come along to break Wayne Gretzky's
fabled single-season goal-scoring record?
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone even know what it is? Go ahead, guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, but I know it was a lot,'' said Robert Francz, a
1997 draft pick by the Coyotes who was born in Germany. ``How many
did he score?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-something, isn't it?'' asked Juha Ylonen, the Coyotes'
young center from Finland. ``It was 91, right? No, it was 92. Is it
92? I'm pretty sure it was 92.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was 92.
</P>
<P>
   And no, most people don't think it ever will be topped.
</P>
<P>
   As monumental as McGwire's and Sosa's personal Home Run Derby
has become, Gretzky's incredible run of 92 goals in 80 games during
the 1981-82 season with the Edmonton Oilers may stand the test of
time.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa have eclipsed Maris' record, but they haven't
buried it the way Gretzky shattered Phil Esposito's mark of 76
goals, which he scored in 78 games for Boston in 1970-71. The Great
One surpassed it by 16 goals. By comparison, that would be like
McGwire or Sosa swatting 77 homers _ something that obviously won't
happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne's record is safe, in my opinion,'' said Esposito, now
the general manager of the Tampa Bay Lightning, during a visit to
Phoenix last year. ``It just can't be done again.''
</P>
<P>
   Others share Esposito's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, nobody's going to score that many goals. Not in this day
and age,'' Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick said. ``The game has
changed too much. There's more of a defensive-style system now. The
players are better. The defensemen are better. The goaltenders are
much better. It's a much more controlled game. It's not sporadic.
People are in better shape. There's just too many things you can
associate with the game now that you couldn't before.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the biggest thing is, I just don't think there are any
players who were as good as Gretzky was when he was in his prime.''
</P>
<P>
   Some great ones have come along since The Great One. Mario
Lemieux. Brett Hull. Teemu Selanne. Paul Kariya. Jaromir Jagr.
Pavel Bure. Mats Sundin.
</P>
<P>
   A new brand of power-forward goal snipers also have burst on the
scene. Eric Lindros. Peter Forsberg. John LeClair. Keith Tkachuk.
But of all of them, only Hull and Lemieux have ever come reasonably
close to the magic No. 92 scored by the magician, No. 99.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988-89, his fifth NHL season, Lemieux pumped in 85 goals for
the Pittsburgh Penguins. He did it in 76 games, four fewer than
Gretzky played during his historic, record-setting year. In
1990-91, his fourth full NHL season, Hull did Lemieux one better,
scoring 86 goals for the St. Louis Blues that year, also in 76
games.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as it was, it was still six goals too few. And it
was only the third-best individual goal total to date. Gretzky
tallied 87 in 1983-84, playing in 74 games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hull came close. Lemieux came close. Others have sniffed
at the mark, too.
</P>
<P>
   During an 84-game schedule in 1992-93, Selanne and Buffalo's
Alexander Mogilny, who now plays for the Vancouver Canucks _ the
Coyotes' opponent today in a preseason game at America West Arena _
each tied Esposito's old standard by netting 76 goals to lead the
league. For Anaheim's Selanne, then a first-year player with the
Winnipeg Jets, it's a number that has remained in the record books
as the most ever by a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a guy who could do it, it might be Selanne,''
Roenick said. ``Maybe Kariya. Maybe even Bure, when he's lighting
it up. Forsberg, too, although he's a different kind of player
altogether. If they broke in back then, they could have scored 80
goals or more, easy. But it's different now.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't in baseball. Reggie Jackson is on record as saying he
could hit 70 homers or more if he were playing in today's game at
his prime. Expansion and weak pitching, he said, would almost
guarantee it. Fellow Hall of Famer Mike Schmidt virtually said the
same thing a week before.
</P>
<P>
   But expansion has hit the NHL, too, supposedly diluting talent.
There also are more great pitchers in baseball than there are great
goalies in hockey. And don't forget, the NHL has opened up the ice
this season, clamping down hard on obstruction penalties, moving
the nets up a few feet and putting tighter restrictions on goalie
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Is it certain Gretzky's 92-goal season is safe?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one who could have topped it would have been Mario
Lemieux,'' said Coyotes center Cliff Ronning, who scored 89 goals
during his last year in the Canadian junior leagues. ``Other that
that, I don't see it happening. Maybe 20 years from now, someone
will beat it. It'll be some young kid from somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith isn't so sure. Smith, the
No. 1 pick in the 1978 NHL draft, played against Gretzky for 14
seasons, including the memorable 92-goal campaign of 1981-82.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an absolutely unbelievable feat,'' said Smith, who
coincidentally had his best season the same year, scoring 43 goals
and 114 points. ``The thing about Gretzky is, he never quit. End of
the second period, up 5-1, he would go and get four points in the
third period. Mario Lemieux would stop. Up 5-1, he'd go into cruise
control and the game would end, 5-2. Gretzky, the game would end,
9-2, and he'd have another goal and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will ever happen again. Right through
coaching, from the time kids start to play hockey now, there's more
of an emphasis on defense. Pee-wee coaches want to have systems.
They use videotapes. It just seems so unlikely that record will
ever be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is from the same guy who initially thumbed his
nose at The Great One. Smith was entering his final season of
junior hockey when he was over at a friend's house and some kids
from nearby Brantford, Ontario, stopped by.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there's this kid from their hometown, Wayne Gretzky,
and he's going to play in the same league as you,'' Smith said.
``I'm like, `Yeah, sure. Right. I'll be sure to keep an eye open
for him. Whatever.' . . . Little did I know.''
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as scoring 93 goals in a single season might be,
Gretzky thinks the toughest scoring record in hockey to beat is the
one he set the same year for the fastest 50 goals from the start of
a season. Maurice Richard and Mike Bossy set the standard with 50
in 50 games. Gretzky shattered it by hitting the half-century mark
in just 39 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you never expect to score 50 goals in 39 games,''
Gretzky said. ``I never expected to score 50 goals in a season. I
don't know if anybody will ever score 50 goals in 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might happen. To say say it will never happen is wrong, but
I think that's going to be the hardest record for someone to
break.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2248EDT &QL; 
