<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA CLEARS HURDLE  
 DOMINANCE OF CHAVEZ STEP TOWARD GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya's victory Friday night over Julio
Cesar Chavez is a potential rite of passage in the career of a
young fighter trying to become a great one.
</P>
<P>
   In finally destroying his boyhood hero, De La Hoya, 25, took a
big step toward eliminating the boy in himself.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Often, it was downright painful. An hour after
the final blow, not even dark sunglasses could hide purple welts
that swelled beneath De La Hoya's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And it was wasn't always impressive. There were moments when De
La Hoya lost his balance and looked confused, even vulnerable, to
the aggressive, close-quarter tactics employed by Chavez, 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a smart plan,'' De La Hoya (29-0, 24 KOs) said
after he retained the World Boxing Council's welterweight title
with Chavez's surrender after eight rounds at Thomas &AMP; Mack Center.
``I did the total opposite of what we talked about. I was way too
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it seemed so tough. I could have stayed on my toes
and outboxed him. But people don't want to see that. They want to
see me fight.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be more chances to see De La Hoya fight. On Nov. 21,
he faces African Ike Quartey, who was stripped of the World Boxing
Association's welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey is an opening chapter in De La Hoya's career after
Chavez. It is the initial chance for him to define himself against
a young rival with recognized credentials. Quartey-De La Hoya looms
as a milestone toward maturity and beyond Friday night's passion
play.
</P>
<P>
   The second bout with Chavez was loaded with potentially
dangerous emotions. De La Hoya was angry at the old man, who did
not acknowledge him as an equal after a victory in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After the rematch, it was clear Chavez's only chance was a
mistake committed by a young man blinded by emotion.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen, perhaps because Chavez no longer can withstand
punishment long enough to capitalize on the momentary, late lapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat the old Chavez, the best Chavez anybody has seen in
the last five years,'' De La Hoya cornerman Gil Clancy said. ``He
did not beat a shill. He beat a great fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't knock him out. De La Hoya promised a KO. Perhaps,
an exhausted Chavez denied him that chance. Perhaps it wasn't a cut
at his lower lip, but the fear of an imminent KO that led to
Chavez's failure to answer the bell for the ninth round.
</P>
<P>
   For De La Hoya, the result will be questions about his punching
power. Chavez raised doubts by saying he ``was not a true knockout
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but Chavez had no doubt about one thing: He wasn't
talking about the Golden Boy anymore. Today, De La Hoya's old
nickname is just a bunch of kid stuff. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
