<SLUG> BC-ADD-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic stories have been added for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Sept. 20. If you
have any questions, please contact the Republic News Desk at (602)
271-8108.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OSHA _ It's not easy to place a value on human life. Juries have
set its worth in the millions. In Arizona, however, a worker's life
is worth a little less _ about $3,000. That's the median fine paid
by Arizona companies for safety violations that contributed to the
death of a worker, according to a computer analysis of Occupational
Safety and Health Administration records by The Arizona Republic.
By BILL MULLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OSHA-POWELL _ One button could have saved Cory Powell's life.
But it didn't work. Powell, a 35-year-old trash collector from
Mesa, was decapitated in 1994 while working in the bed of a garbage
truck. He left behind a wife and two daughters. OSHA investigators
said Powell might have survived to take care of his family if his
employer had bothered to maintain its trucks or train its workers.
The OSHA penalty: $7,500. By BILL MULLER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
OSHA-REDDEN _ Painters Robert Redden and Greg Gauthier were
probably in a hurry on that Christmas Eve in 1992. Their foreman
was on his way to the bank to get their paychecks, and they had
last-minute shopping to do. Both had big plans. Redden, 22, was
getting married in a week. Gauthier, 19, was studying to get his
general equivalency diploma. They were finishing up, taking down a
40-foot aluminum ladder. Suddenly, it began to topple, falling
toward a 7,200-volt power line. ``Somehow that ladder got away from
them,'' recalled Lorne Williams, former owner of Allied Painting.
``They grabbed the ladder and tried to catch it. It was aluminum,
and it hit them wires and cooked them.'' Both men were killed. By
BILL MULLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OSHA-GARCIA _ Macario Garcia feared the one thing that killed
him. Last year, after climbing an 8-foot ladder to install
fluorescent lights in a renovated office building, an electric
shock hurled Garcia to the concrete floor. He died 16 hours later
from head injuries. He was 40. ``He once told my younger brother
that it gave him chills to get up there,'' said Marilyn Chavez,
Garcia's sister. ``I wish I had known that before.'' OSHA
inspectors cited Garcia's employer, Keystone Electric, $6,500 for
unsafe working conditions and inadequate training. Keystone
appealed and eventually paid $2,625. By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RISKS (Washington) _ Fit, trim and tan at age 77, John Glenn just
grins and gives a thumbs up when asked whether he's worried about
the health consequences of being the oldest astronaut ever. But
some scientists and aging experts admit they are ``holding their
breath'' about the Oct. 29 flight's risks, which they say could
include a heart attack or stroke _ even for a superathlete such as
Glenn. Many worry because there are no data on whether anyone
Glenn's age can withstand some of the challenges of this ride in
space. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
