<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CALL PADRES PARTY-POOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres players were not nearly as wrapped up in
the moment as their fans and franchise after  &UR; Sammy Sosa slammed
his 63rd home run early last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most Padres players were, to put it mildly, steamed after
watching how their organization saluted Sosa after he cracked a
grand slam in the eighth inning that broke the tie at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to a man, Padres players said they felt betrayed by their
fans and the club, which shot off fireworks and flashed a huge
``San Diego Salutes Sammy Sosa!'' on the scoreboard after the
Padres, who recently clinched their second National League West
Division title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Sosa's a good friend of mine, and he's had a great
year,'' Padres left fielder  &UR; Greg Vaughn said. ``But what the
(expletive) is going on? We're trying to do something for this
city, and the fans are rooting for this guy to beat us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring a championship to San Diego, and they're
pulling for him to hit a grand slam. Everyone in this clubhouse
feels like we have our road uniforms on. Are we the enemy? No one
here understands. We're confused. With us or against us?
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Tony ( &UR; Gwynn) lines out to Sammy and they applaud. There are
a lot of (steamed) players in here. ( &UR; Kevin) &UR; Brown is.
( &UR; Trevor) &UR; Hoffman is. This is supposed to be our city . . . our
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Sterling Hitchcock was lustfully booed the night before
when he threw several pitches out of the strike zone against Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's garbage,'' Hitchcock said. ``And the biggest bunch of
crap is the fireworks our organization set off after he homered.
It's a joke. . . . a flat-out joke. We're playing for something.
And the fans turn on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said  &UR; Gwynn: ``I don't need to add anything else. A lot of guys
are very upset. They feel that us as an organization and the fans
went overboard out of respect. It's not a happy place. Everyone
understands the significance. But it went way overboard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres simply should have let the fans pay homage to Sosa,
not get involved themselves. Now they have alienated their players,
and that's just plain dumb, especially with the playoffs starting
next week. &QL; 
Arizona Belle-weather? &QL; 
 &UR; Albert Belle has returned to the top of the leader board in just
about every power category in the American League. Now the big
question is where he will wind up next season.
</P>
<P>
   With three players averaging more than his $10 million annual
salary, the White Sox left fielder can escape the remaining three
years on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes Chicago,'' Belle's brother and confidant  &UR; Terry Belle
said. ``People don't really bother him much. He wants to retire
with the White Sox and play until he's 40.''
</P>
<P>
   While that sounds promising for the White Sox, the man himself
spoke last week when Chicago was in Cleveland. Remaining in Chicago
doesn't seem like a lock.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, I'm not going anywhere,'' said Belle, who
last week became the fourth player since 1950 with at least 400
total bases. ``But you never know what will happen at the end of
the season. Certain payrolls could take on big-money guys.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Belle lives in Tucson in the off-season. And the
Diamondbacks strongly considered courting him when he was a free
agent two years ago _ yes, a year before they before they took the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does opportunity knock twice, right,  &UR; Jerry Colangelo? &QL; 
The cat's hat &QL; 
 &UR; Mark McGwire had an autographed cap sitting in his locker the past
several months, one he rarely noticed. The cap was given to McGwire
by St. Louis broadcaster and former Cardinals player  &UR; Mike Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   It was signed by none other than  &UR; Roger Maris, but McGwire
didn't learn of the special significance until a few days after he
broke Maris' single-season home run record. Maris died of cancer in
1985 but gave the cap to former teammate and then-Cardinals Manager
 &UR; Whitey
 &UR; Herzog in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger told Whitey, `Give this to the guy who breaks my
record,' '' said Shannon, who like Herzog was one of Maris' closest
friends.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire learned of the cap's significance after a reporter
filled in the All-Star first baseman two nights after McGwire broke
the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that until you told me just now,'' McGwire said.
``I knew it was something special, because not many people got
those hats, from what I understood. So I knew it was special. But I
didn't know it was that special.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said the cap is white and shows Maris' name with the
number ``61'' twice, signifying the record 61 homers that Maris hit
for the Yankees in 1961. &QL; 
Pepe Le Pew strikes back &QL; 
San Diego reliever  &UR; Roberto Ramirez thought it was a pretty good
idea at the time. Boy, was he wrong. Ramirez saw the skunk who
lives in the bowels of Qualcomm Stadium the other night, poking his
head out near the Padres bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez fired a baseball at the skunk but missed. The skunk came
back with a fastball of his own, spraying toward the bullpen. The
relievers immediately scattered as the smell permeated the left
field corner of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dumb things done and said in the bullpen should remain in
the bullpen,'' Padres reliever  &UR; Randy Myers said. &QL; 
Thin-skinned? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Veteran umpire  &UR; Ed Montague was so enraged at what he believed
was a slap in the face of one of his fellow umpires on his crew in
Philadelphia last week that he stopped the game and stormed into
the dugout to call the press box and order the song ``Double
Vision'' be taken off the stadium's loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   It seems  &UR; Brian Gibbons might have missed a close call at first
base and the old hit from Foreigner blared over the speakers.
Montague was told the music was for the Phillies' next batter,
 &UR; Alex Arias, who had three doubles in three at-bats that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a  &UR; Sinatra fan,'' said Montague, who admitted he'd never
heard of the group. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A true measure of greatness: Chicago's  &UR; Sammy Sosa has hit 50
home runs since  &UR; Roger Clemens last lost a game, which occurred May
29, when Sosa had 13 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No wonder their payroll is less than $10 million: Florida has
used 17 rookies in its rotation this season and 27 rookies overall,
which, according to the Elias Sports Bureau, is the most used in
the expansion era (since 1961). The previous record was 25 by the
1969 San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Ron Kittle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A case of the rich getting richer: The Atlanta Braves have
three players ( &UR; Andres Galarraga,  &UR; Chipper Jones and  &UR; Javier
 &UR; Lopez) with at least 100 RBIs for the first time since 1970 when
 &UR; Hank
 &UR; Aaron,  &UR; Orlando Cepeda and  &UR; Rico Carty all reached the century
mark.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here's someone we'd love to see managing in the
 &UR; majors some day: Scottsdale resident  &UR; Mike Gallego just might wind
up in the Boston Red Sox organization next spring as a minor league
coach or manager. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
 &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. became the fourth youngest player to reach 1,000
RBIs Tuesday. The three ahead of him place Griffey in high company.
 &UR; Mel Ott (27 years, 94 days),  &UR; Jimmie Foxx (27, 236) and  &UR; Lou
 &UR; Gehrig (28, 287). Griffey was 28 years, 297 days old when he
reached the plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's  &UR; Bret Boone, a probable Gold Glove winner, joined
 &UR; Joe Morgan as the only second basemen in the Reds' storied history
to hit 20 home runs in one season. Morgan hit at least 20 home runs
four times during his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City scored at least one run in each inning while
trouncing Oakland, 16-6, last Monday. The last time an American
League club managed that feat was May 11, 1949 when the Chicago
White Sox beat Boston. St. Louis did it Sept. 13, 1964 against the
Cubs, the last time a National League club managed the feat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terry Mulholland, who has replaced rookie sensation
 &UR; Kerry Wood in the Cubs' rotation, has a 2.51 ERA in four starts.
``I've always known what I can do physically,'' said Mulholland,
who very well could be in someone's rotation next season.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffman joined  &UR; Bobby Thigpen (57 in
'90),  &UR; Randy Myers (53 in '97) and  &UR; Dennis Eckersley (51 in '92) as
the only players to have at least 50 saves in one major league
season.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia catcher  &UR; Bobby Estalella thought he was going back
to south Florida to hang out for the winter. He was wrong. The
Phillies want him to go to the instructional league to improve
throwing out base stealers (he's 4 for 30). They also want him to
play winter ball in Puerto Rico. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
With General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone on board with the Dodgers, the
club's attention turns to finding a manager for next season. The
list of early candidates (in no particular order): Montreal's
 &UR; Felipe &UR; Alou, former Baltimore Manager  &UR; Davey Johnson and former
Texas and Boston Manager  &UR; Kevin Kennedy, who just may be the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Manager  &UR; Jim Leyland, who probably will not return to
the Marlins, is also a candidate to land the Dodgers job, but only
if he is willing to move to the West Coast, which seems unlikely.
Leyland could, however, be in line for the Detroit or Colorado job,
both of which will probably open.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with a Dodgers theme, it's become fairly well known
inside baseball circles that Los Angeles is desperately trying to
peddle Gold Glove catcher  &UR; Charles Johnson, who is arbitration
eligible and likely will land a 1999 contract worth at least $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati GM  &UR; Jim Bowden, who was passed over for the Dodgers'
GM post, is attempting to take over in Baltimore, where
 &UR; Pat Gillick is not expected to return. Bowden received his club's
permission to interview for the Orioles' job. Others in line are
Cleveland assistant  &UR; Dan O'Dowd and Florida assistant  &UR; Frank Wren.
</P>
<P>
   If Montreal GM  &UR; Jim Beattie decides to leave (he already has
turned down a contract extension), then scouting director
 &UR; Fred Ferreira likely take over. If Ferreira does not become general
manager, he could wind up taking over as Seattle's GM if  &UR; Woody
 &UR; Woodward is let go.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati has offered a minor league supervisory job to fired
Detroit Manager  &UR; Buddy Bell, who is expected to accept. Bell still
lives in the Cincinnati area. It would not be impossible think Bell
could one day manage the Reds. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
