<HEADER>
A4636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK20     09-19 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux fighting uneasiness
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix _ Bobby Cox thinks he threw well. Eddie Perez, his
catcher, thought he pitched better than he had in weeks. Even plate
umpire Ed Vanover felt he pitched well enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greg Maddux awoke to the same uncertain feeling Saturday
morning. He hasn't won in five starts, his last victory coming Aug.
23. In losing 5-0 to Arizona Friday night, he yielded 10 hits for
the third time in six games. Before Saturday's game, he even
wondered where he would fit into the postseason rotation, a
stunning thought from the pitcher who still leads the majors in ERA
(2.24).
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at where the balls are being hit,'' said Cox. ``His
velocity is up. He's still quick. He's had some bad luck. But he's
striking out more people than he ever has. He's just been hurt on a
few certain pitches or some ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux went over the 200-strikeout mark for the first time
Friday night, when he fanned nine, but it was little solace. He has
no explanation for his current plight, and it should be remembered
he had pitched 12 scoreless innings before the Diamondbacks scored
five times between the third and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some balls were hit hard,'' Maddux said. ``Some weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he made some great pitches,'' said Perez. ``I don't
think he's been making those pitches the last two or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has just one tune-up start, probably three to five
innings Friday against New York, before heading into the
postseason. And where that takes him is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez returns
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez made his first start at catcher in four games after
receiving a cortisone injection for a case of tendinitis in his
left elbow. He still has difficulty fully extending his arm but
that discomfort is expected to dissipate as the soreness from the
injection, made on the underside of the forearm, wears off over the
weekend. Lopez said he began experiencing the pain after ``a bad
swing.''Line-up matters
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Danny Bautista made his first start since Aug. 24 and
will wear a lightweight brace on his right knee (slight tear,
medial collateral ligament) the rest of the season. Right-handed
set-up man Rudy Seanez is expected to pitch today, if not Tuesday,
after throwing at nearly 100 percent in two bullpen sessions. Cox
is continuing to tinker with his rotation for the Florida series.
Cox has tentatively scheduled Kevin Millwood to pitch Tuesday in
Florida instead of John Smoltz, followed by Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
