<SLUG> BC-BRADLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albatross for Vols is a Gator
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. -- When last Tennessee beat Florida, Phillip
Fulmer was but an interim coach, a career assistant kicked
momentarily (or so it was thought) upstairs until Johnny Majors
returned from heart surgery. When last Tennessee beat Florida, on a
stormy day in 1992, it marked the end of Majors' reign and the
beginning of Fulmer's. Six years later, the opponent over whose
back Fulmer clambered to the top stands as the reason his
stewardship remains unsatisfying.
</P>
<P>
   As head coach Fulmer has beaten everyone save Florida. Almost
half his losses _ he has only 11 _ have been to the Gators. Yes, he
has won the SEC title, and yes, he has made Tennessee a fixture in
the Top 10, but he cannot be said to have succeeded until he whips
Florida on something other than an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the inability to beat Alabama drove Bill Battle out of
town, just as a similar failing undid Battle's successor, the
once-sainted Majors, Fulmer has found himself a nemesis. His
winning percentage (.833) is nearly as splendid as Steve Spurrier's
(.838) is at Florida, but where it counts, Spurrier has owned
Fulmer.
</P>
<P>
   Five in a row, none all that close, the worst being in 1995 when
Tennessee led 30-14 and lost 63-37. Peyton Manning came and went,
infamously going 0-for-Florida. On Sept. 21, 1996, what seemed the
Vols' best shot fizzled on the launch pad, Florida taking a 28-0
lead before 107,608, then an NCAA record crowd. Were hype a
measurable quantity, the ballyhoo for that game might also have set
a standard.
</P>
<P>
   Having aimed so high and missed so often, the Big Orange seemed
to approach this year's Florida assignment with something
approaching moderation. If a game between the Nos. 2 and 6 teams in
the land can be understated, this was. Yes, CBS had it in prime
time, but somehow the sporting day didn't seem to revolve around
Neyland Stadium. Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa were playing 90 miles
apart in the Central Time Zone. Evander Holyfield was fighting in
Atlanta. And don't the Gators always win this game anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was fairly light by big-game standards. The lead story
on 1-A of the Knoxville News-Sentinel had to do not with Saturday's
game but with Monday's videotape release in Washington. Maybe the
low-key approach aided the home side. Tennessee took an early lead
simply because the Gators kept messing up.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, sloppy as ever, made three turnovers and were called
for seven penalties in the first half. The Vols took a 10-3 lead on
the strength of one long run _ fullback Shawn Bryson went 57 yards
against an overshifted defense _ and a mini-drive to a field goal.
With 5:06 left before halftime, the Vols took the ball at their 26
with a chance to throw a hammerlock on the halting game. They went
nowhere, punted to Florida and saw the Gators tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing had been decided. Indeed, the impression left by this
first half was that neither team was as strong as in previous
seasons. But another half remained, time enough to make a stronger
impression, perhaps even time enough for Phillip Fulmer to break
through against the bane of his existence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
