<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Error-prone LSU holds off Auburn
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ The tone was set immediately. On the first play
from scrimmage, Kevin Faulk sped for 7 yards and the LSU coaches'
headsets went dead. Just the first of many Cajun faux pas on an
evening when LSU was often the bungle Tigers. And still won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a finished product,'' Gerry Dinardo, said in an
understatement after his No. 7 Tigers overcame their mistakes and
Auburn 31-19 Saturday night. ``There were times we did not look
very good out there. But you come on the road in the SEC, I guess
looking good is winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in your SEC opener and in Jordan-Hare Stadium, where
a capacity crowd of 85,214 saw LSU's Herb Tyler pass for three
touchdowns and run for a fourth. Especially on a night when you
have two extra points blocked and one returned for a 2-point
conversion. When two quarterback sneaks don't gain an inch but give
Auburn hope. When you lose a fumble at the Auburn 7 and, very
nearly, your quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite all that calamity, LSU finally prevailed in a game
it dominated and should have won handily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had times when we could've been a little bit better
offensively, but we just didn't knock 'em out,'' said Dinardo, his
team now 2-0, 1-0 in the SEC and clearly the early season best in
the SEC West.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spot them 14 and lose by 12, that's about as close as
you're going to come,'' said Auburn coach Terry Bowden, whose
Tigers (1-2, 1-1) have now lost four of their last five home games.
Bowden got 285 yards passing and two TDs from Ben Leard
(21-for-38). But Leard, the beneficiary of several blown coverages
by LSU in the first half, was intercepted three times and had 127
yards passing in the second quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked them apart in the first half,'' said Leard, who
threw a 54-yard TD pass to fullback Heath Evans (later lost for the
year with a broken ankle) and a 22-yarder to Karsten Bailey that
drew Auburn within 19-14 at halftime. ``I was able to sit back in
the pocket and throw. But they mixed it up in the second half and
put a lot of pressure on us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clarence LeBlanc intercepted Leard on Auburn's first play
and returned it 21 yards for a touchdown, Thomas Dunson recovered
Michael Burks' fumble on Auburn's next play at the Auburn 26. That
led to Tyler's third-down, 5-yard quarterback draw for a TD. But a
blocked extra-point attempt kept it 13-0 and Leard-to-Evans cut it
to 13-7. Tyler hit tailback Kevin Faulk (88 yards on 21 carries) on
a 19-yard TD pass, but Leard's 10-yard scoring pass to Karsten
Bailey made it 19-14.
</P>
<P>
   LSU dominated the third quarter but turned it over at the Auburn
18 when two Tyler sneaks got nothing. He later fumbled at the
Auburn 7. Even after Tyler hit Larry Foster on a 29-yard TD pass,
the PAT was blocked and returned by Auburn's Brad Ware to make it
25-19.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
