</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia jumps on Tigers early, then holds on
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ In a matter of seconds, what would have
been Tommy West's finest victory as head coach at Clemson turned
into his most bitter defeat as the Tigers dropped a 20-18
heartbreaker to No. 10 Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers snatched the game away early, gave it back late
and then took it back in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't fault our effort,'' West said. ``We made way too many
mistakes to go on the road and play a top 10 team.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes, without a doubt, cost Clemson (1-2) the game.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia (3-0) jumped on top 17-3 in the first quarter as
quarterback Aaron Brooks had his way with the Tigers defense.
Thomas Jones scored on a 31-yard run after a fumble recovery and
Brooks threw a 20-yard scoring pass to Kevin Coffey. The Cavaliers
looked headed for an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia was unable to score again in the half and that gave
Clemson new life after intermission.
</P>
<P>
   After trapping Jones in the end zone for a safety, the Tigers
caused Virginia fullback Tyree Foreman to fumble. Clemson safety
Antway Edwards picked it up and didn't put it down again until he
reached the Cavaliers' end zone 93 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, still leading 17-11, then allowed Clemson to open the
final period by moving 87 yards in six plays, with Tigers
quarterback Brandon Streeter hitting Brian Wofford with a 54-yard
scoring strike to give the Tigers an 18-17 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if that might be enough, but with 3:55 left,
Virginia began a drive on its own 34. On a third-and-8, the Tigers
were called for holding, and then on a third-and-10 from the 46,
Edwards was whistled for a pass-interference penalty on Virginia's
Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers moved to the 10, and Todd Braverman kicked the
game-winner with 49 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was picture perfect,'' Edwards said of his
defense against Coffey. ``I got my hands on the ball. I couldn't
play it any better.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was doubly bitter because the Tigers were pummeled
37-0 last week by Virginia Tech at home and could have redeemed
themselves here.
</P>
<P>
   ``After being beaten like we were last week, the worst thing we
could have done was to fall behind 17-3,'' West said. ``Instead of
throwing in the towel and saying we'd had enough, we tried to find
a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   West said the two-point loss was probably worse than the
37-point defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we lost is much more emotional,'' he said, ``it rips
your gut out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They got off to a great start early,'' Edwards said, ``but we
never lost our composure, and I thought we played a great second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never happy or satisfied with a loss, but the guys and
the determination and the fight ... I don't know if I've ever been
prouder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
