<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gamecocks thunderstruck by Marshall loss
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Marshall reached a milestone in its two-year
history as a I-A school Saturday night with a 24-21 victory over
South Carolina, not the best SEC school, but an SEC school
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   And in the process, the Thundering Herd could have trampled
embattled coach Brad Scott's hopes of keeping his job after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied and the Gamecocks on the move, Marshall's
Daninelle Derricott picked off his second Anthony Wright pass at
the 50 and returned it 30-yards to put the Herd on the 20. Three
plays later and after calling time out with two seconds left, Billy
Malashevich kicked a 37-yard field goal for the victory and
Marshall (3-0) players thundered onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecocks (1-2, 0-1 SEC) were hurt in the first half by the
loss of two fumbles inside the Marshall 10 and a chip-shot field
goal attempt that hit a goalpost. An interception to begin the
second half was just as damaging in the first meeting between the
schools, as Marshall then covered 23 yards for a 14-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, led by junior quarterback Chad Pennington who is
already being touted as a Heisman Trophy candidate, took its first
win over an SEC school in 11 tries before 78,717 at Williams-Brice
Stadium, the largest crowd to ever see Marshall play. Marshall has
now won 35 of its last 39 games, as Pennington has found plenty of
other receivers since Randy Moss left for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   A trick play by the Thundering Herd led to a 21-10 lead.
Pennington took the snap, pretended that the play was an
end-around, but really put the ball on the ground. Chapman picked
it up and ran untouched around left end for the 7-yard score with
6:25 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gamecocks had a trick up their sleeves, too. They faked
a field goal on fourth-and-1, and ultimately scored on an 8-yard
pass from Anthony Wright to Kerry Hood. The Gamecocks made a
2-point conversion on a Wright pass to Hambrick for a 21-18 margin.
The two receivers redeemed themselves after being the two players
who fumbled in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was short on a 46-yard field goal attempt with about
seven minutes left, then the Gamecocks made a 36-yarder to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, which called timeout on its first play from scrimmage,
wasted no time figuring out what to do against the Gamecock
defense. On the drive, Pennington was 5-for-5 for 46 yards,
including a 17-yarder to freshman Gregg Kellett on third-and-11
from the South Carolina 30. He followed that with a 13-yard
touchdown pass to Lanier Washington for a 7-0 lead with 11:04 left
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On South Carolina's first possession, the Gamecocks were on
track to post an answering score when Wright passed to Hood at the
Marshall 9. A thundering hit delivered by Derricott caused him to
fumble the ball, which was recovered by a member of the Herd.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, South Carolina lost its second fumble
inside the 10, this time when Troy Hambrick was stripped of the
ball at the 5.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
