<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's success on 3rd-down plays has been backbreaker for
Volunteers
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knoxville, Tenn. _ Tennessee knew it would have to win several
battles in order to emerge victorious Saturday night in the war
against No. 2 Florida, but none would be bigger than battles that
took place on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's success on third down against Tennessee has more or
less defined the last five meetings of the two teams, all won by
Florida. During the winning streak, Florida has converted 34 of 74
third downs. If you include the four fourth-down conversions in the
1996 game, the Gators converted nearly 50 percent of the time
against the Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the kicker: Over the last five games with Tennessee,
Florida has converted third and 7 or longer 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't put a finger on (why Florida has been so
successful),'' said Steve Johnson, Tennessee's senior cornerback.
``Some of it is coverage breakdowns. Sometimes it's the pass rush
that doesn't get there at the right time. Sometimes they just make
great plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's 33-20 victory, all three of Florida's offensive
touchdowns came on third down. Playing well on third down was a
point of emphasis for Tennessee's defense in the off season, but
the Vols struggled against Syracuse and Donovan McNabb in their
opener. Syracuse converted eight of 16 third-down situations,
including a third-and-23.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely close
</P>
<P>
   Over 107,000 fans packed Tennessee's Neyland Stadium, hoping for
a close game, which has been rare lately against Florida. The
Gators' margin of victory against Tennessee in the past five games
has been 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we've been able to get an early turnover or two and
get on top of them,'' said Florida coach Steve Spurrier. ``But I've
got a feeling that this one is going to go down to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosey speaks
</P>
<P>
   The trash talking from both teams was kept to a minimum this
week, but Tennessee guard Cosey Coleman did take a little shot at
the Gators. Coleman, the former high school All-American from
Southwest DeKalb, said he went on an official visit to Florida
while he was being recruited but decided to pass on the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little too cocky down there for me,'' he said.
``They were bragging about how good they were, and how they were
the cream of the crop of the SEC, and how they planned to stay that
way. I knew they were a good team, but it just wasn't right for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing powers
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee linebacker Eric Westmoreland suffered an ankle injury
Wednesday but after some serious rehabilitation Thursday was
cleared to play against Florida. Westmoreland spent the entire
night Thursday at the Neyland-Thompson Sports Center getting
treatment for the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Phillip Fulmer said he could never recall a Tennessee
football player spending the night getting rehab. But in 1997,
Tennessee women's basketball player Kellie Jolly was able to play
in an NCAA Tournament game 48 hours after a severe ankle injury.
She, too, spent an entire night in the complex getting treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
