<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4642 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-MILLER-AZR &LR;      09-19 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER IS EAGER TO LEAD  
 EARLY MISTAKES HELP LINEBACKER MATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Tony McCombs needs a few pointers about his new
position, right outside linebacker, and Jamir Miller is there for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth needs to adjust where he is
lining up, and Miller gets him in the right spot.
</P>
<P>
   Practice is a few beats below performance level, and Miller
pipes up, although not loudly enough, he would say after the
Cardinals suffered a season-opening rout at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Team leader and Jamir Miller: Not an image that came immediately
to mind when, as a wild 20-year-old who had left UCLA a year early,
Miller finally arrived at his first training camp _ 15 days late _
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Or when he was suspended by the NFL for four games in his second
season after violating the league's substance abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   Miller reflected what too many youngsters with too much money
are about. Misguided. Unaccountable. Rebellious. Underachieving.
Arrogant. Self-centered. A good party was far more important than a
good game against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   With the grace of one of his rangy strides, Miller has covered a
lot of ground since those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in people, so it doesn't surprise me at all,'' said
teammate Aeneas Williams, a four-time Pro Bowl cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was as optimistic as Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Jamir at the scouting combine when he was coming
out, and it amazes me that this is the same guy,'' Cardinals
defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said. ``He came out as a young
kid. Now he's a professional. He's not just a guy getting paid to
play football, he's a professional football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Ryan and his staff berated Miller, trying to coax the
talent out of him that they knew he had when they made him a
first-round draft pick. Miller blew them off.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran linebacker Seth Joyner got to him, though, taking Miller
under his wing and showing him how to be a professional. Some of it
sunk in.
</P>
<P>
   And then, more and more did.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Vince Tobin and his staff came in for the 1996
season, Miller was getting the hang of what it took, on and off the
field. Ironically, Miller became so dependable that the club was
confident cutting Joyner in 1997 and moving Miller from the right
linebacker spot into Joyner's left side position.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Miller is filling Joyner's shoes in more ways than one as a
respected veteran who leads by example, filling a void on a unit
crying out for a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``My assessment of what makes a good leader is one who leads by
example, yet when needed gives that push to bring everyone else
along,'' Miller said. ``Now when I say something, people do listen.
You have to pay your dues in order to be in that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a rah-rah type of guy, never have been, never will be.
But the thing is, people respond better when you perform on the
field. That's what they respect. Then they listen to what you're
saying because they figure what you're doing has to be right. It's
not about trying, it's about doing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a maturation, a transformation that perhaps only the likes
of Williams could have anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamir has taken a quantum leap in terms of understanding the
game,'' Williams said. ``He was fortunate to have a guy like Seth
Joyner here in his younger years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Jamir has taken on his own personality and maximized his
productivity. There's no doubt he has gained the respect of the
team, not just the defense, and not just the linebackers. He is the
veteran of our linebacking corps now. Roles are reversed now. Jamir
is doing the same thing, tutoring our young guys, that was done for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said there is more to his maturation than the passage of
a few football seasons, or even having a friend and mentor such as
Joyner. Miller's marriage to his wife, Racquel, and the birth two
years ago of their daughter, Ashlynn, really caused the lights to
go on for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed me a lot,'' Miller said. ``That showed me there
is more to life than just me.''
</P>
<P>
   His coaches could see the change in Miller immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all of us who have a family, he grew up,'' McGinnis said.
``We all come to a crossroads in our lives. You can go this way, or
you can go that way. He realized `that way' might not be a real
good way to go. He went the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Miller more often than not went the right way,
accounting for a career-high 139{ tackles and causing foes to run
away from him. He made 5{ quarterback sacks. At 6 feet 5 and 266
pounds, Miller is as big as most defensive ends, making him ideally
suited for the left side _ the one most teams attack for the tough
yards. He's also as fast as many safeties. As a high school
sprinter, he broke 11 seconds in the 100-meter dash.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he came out of college early, to cash in as quickly
as possible as a pro. And that's why two coaching staffs have done
everything they could to get him to reach that potential. Finally,
Miller has responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear this cliche a lot, but he's playing the game with
passion,'' said Cardinals linebackers coach Glenn Pires. ``He's
getting after people. With Jamir, the sky is the limit. He has all
the good qualities you'd want in a linebacker. He has improved
tremendously, but he has a long way to go. He can be as good as he
wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two games this season, Miller has 17 tackles, a sack and
a fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a guy with talent, you bend over backward to
try to get him into your system and get him to play,'' Tobin said.
``Players all have different buttons you have to push to get them
to perform. In Jamir's case, the buttons were first having patience
and then being demanding in getting him to do things in a certain
way, our way. There were some tense moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see him today, it's really a tribute to Jamir. He is the
one who decided that he needed to change both on and off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Ashlynn has Miller focused squarely. On the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one that lives in the past,'' Miller said. ``The
things that happened helped me grow. I'm thankful that some of them
happened. If they hadn't, I probably wouldn't be in the position
I'm in now. They showed me basically how to be a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask if I marvel at how far I've come. Not really. I
look more toward the future to see what that may hold for me. I
marvel at that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
