<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-BREWERS-MCG     09-19 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-BREWERS-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE IS NOW CHASING NORMALITY, AS CARDS BEAT BREWERS, 7-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Mark McGwire loves it and hates it. He loves that
tens of thousands of fans drive hours just to see him swing his
bat, that fans in opponents' stadiums stand and cheer every time he
moves toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire is bothered that his successful assault on
baseball's single-season home run record has led people to see him
as otherworldly, as someone who, for now, is larger than the game
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has hit more home runs in one season than anyone in
history, the St. Louis Cardinals' first baseman wants to be viewed
as normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around you change,'' McGwire, who hit his 64th homer
here Friday night against the Brewers, said before Saturday night's
game. ``They want to touch you; they want to shake your hand; they
want to say that they said hi to you. Just the other day, I was in
Houston, going out of the dugout after the game, and people were
touching me, and the comment I heard was: `Mom! Dad! I touched him!
I touched him!' It's weird that because of something you do, people
look at you differently.''
</P>
<P>
   It was definitely true a few hours later. The 54,132 fans in a
sold-out County Stadium stood and cheered. It was the third inning,
and everything was pointing toward another history-making home run.
</P>
<P>
   Both team's pitchers were struggling and two of McGwire's
teammates, Brian Jordan and Fernando Tatis, had already homered off
the Brewers rookie Steve Woodard. And the diminutive St. Louis
shortstop Luis Ordaz had hit the ball off the left-center-field
wall on one bounce in the Cardinals' three-run second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the drama were the powerful bats the Brewers were
wielding. Ripping the offerings of the St. Louis rookie Jose
Jimenez, Milwaukee also scored three runs in the second, one of
which was knocked in by Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   But while the rest of the Cardinals' lineup took batting
practice against Woodard, McGwire stumbled. To the dismay of the
Brewers' largest crowd this year, the home team's right-handed
finesse pitcher struck McGwire out on a called third strike that
nipped the outside corner of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Through eight innings, McGwire had struck out three times and
failed to add any distance between himself and Chicago's Sammy
Sosa, who had 63 homers after going 0 for 4 Saturday in a loss to
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday night's game, McGwire would have seven games
left, including one here Sunday, to add to his record-breaking
total. His son Matthew, 10, has given him a number to shoot for,
but McGwire will not reveal the figure. ``I'm pretty close,'' he
said. ``I'll tell you when I get there.'' Sosa has six games
remaining but could get another game's worth of at-bats if the Cubs
and Mets faced each other in a wild-card playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hasn't enjoyed facing the Brewers' staff. When he hit
his 64th homer an estimated 417 feet Friday night off the rookie
Rafael Roque, McGwire got his first homer this season at County
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In McGwire's first at-bat Saturday night, Woodard, who allowed
seven runs and nine hits in five and two-thirds innings, did
something few pitchers have done this year against McGwire. Moments
after Jordan hit his 24th home run an estimated 430 feet, Woodard
drilled McGwire in the back. It was only the sixth time this season
that McGwire was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people try to pitch him outside rather than inside,''
Milwaukee Manager Phil Garner had said, explaining why McGwire is
rarely hit. ``Some pitchers are afraid of it now. We're in a
kinder, gentler society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
