<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-NEXT-COX     09-19 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-NEXT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I feel like Norman Bates'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- If Mike Tyson wants to earn millions in a boxing
ring, he will have to go to Europe. At least for the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not convinced of Tyson's mental stability, the Nevada Athletic
Commission declined Saturday to reissue a boxing license to the
fallen former heavyweight champion. The commission listened to
testimony for six hours in Las Vegas, then decided to postpone its
decision until at least Oct. 3 after Tyson has been evaluated by an
independent psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they say he's normal and can fight again, then we have the
responsibility to maybe, probably, license him to fight again,''
said commission chairman Elias Ghanem, who will give Tyson a choice
of three psychiatric institutions from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) at this time we just don't feel like we have enough
information. I must say that if it had come to a vote today (on the
license), I would have voted no.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who has been out of boxing for 15 months since being
disqualified for twice biting Evander Holyfield's ears, is expected
to comply with the commission's request. If he fails to get
relicensed, or merely believes future attempts are futile, he will
almost certainly fight overseas. Other countries are not required
to comply with disciplinary measures by U.S. commissions. There
already has been talk of Tyson fighting Axel Shultz in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada commissioners also are ``uncomfortable'' _ a word used by
officials James Nave and Luther Mack _ with the two assault cases
pending against Tyson, stemming from a recent auto accident in
Maryland. Tyson's attorney, Dale Kinsella, asked that his client
not answer questions about the accident because of pending
litigation. Coincidentally, a preliminary hearing on the accident
is scheduled for Oct. 2, the day before the hearing's resumption,
possibly giving Tyson time to reach settlements with his accusers.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner James Nave said, ``For me to vote yes on this
license, I have to have more information'' on the accident and a
psychological evaluation. Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney, said,
``Evander has said on numerous occasions that Mike deserves to be
relicensed. There's no reason to believe his view has changed on
that... . It seems to me, the commission wants some evidence that
Mike Tyson is not a threat to others and to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who arrived at Cashman Center on a motorcycle dressed in
jeans and a polo shirt, had his head buried in his hands when the
commissioners announced their decision.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the hearing, Tyson appeared worn down after hearing
extensive exchanges about his mental stability. He finally cracked,
``For some reason, I feel like Norman Bates up here with all these
doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson continued to blame others for his mistakes. When asked
why he continually gets into trouble, he said he's ``an easy
target,'' and added, ``I'm belligerent sometimes when I'm provoked.
I'm tired of people trying to take advantage of me, trying to bully
me around and antagonize me. It's been pervasive for so many years
that I'm a bad seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's attorneys have portrayed the boxer as financially broke.
Kinsella presented a chart showing Tyson received only $5.2 million
of his $30 million purse for the second Holyfield fight.
</P>
<P>
   However, at one point, Tyson said money didn't matter: ``I'm
more of a socialist than anything. I help people. I help
charities.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
