<HEADER>
A4647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDSER-SIDE-COX     09-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDSER-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champ's sparring partner gets Bell rung by Pendergrass
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Not so long ago the word from the Evander Holyfield
camp was that the champion's sparring partner, Gary Bell, held the
potential to one day acquire a belt of his own. That may still turn
out to be the case, but Bell got his bell rung plenty in losing on
his boss' undercard Saturday night at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Against Artis Pendergrass _ who came in from Ft. Lauderdale with
an uninspiring 12-10 record _ Bell lost a slugfest when he was
knocked out midway through the sixth round. Pendergrass, an
unimposing sort with a protuding belly, floored Bell twice in the
round.
</P>
<P>
   Pendergrass followed three straight left hooks in the middle of
the ring with a right and a left that dropped Bell. He made it to
his feet by the count of eight, but was quickly decked for good by
a series of Pendergrass punches that sent him to the canvas hard on
his back.
</P>
<P>
   For Pendergrass, it was a victory that inspired hope after a
less than ordinary career start. For Bell, the WBA's No. 5-ranked
contender whose words on his trunks read: ``Bring The Pain,'' it is
a setback that could test his mettle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on him,'' said Don Turner, who trains Holyfield and
Bell. ``He's a game guy.''
</P>
<P>
   His boxing game, however, was way off Saturday night. Instead of
pressing forward after jabs as he did in working with Holyfield,
Bell backed away. And that signaled his demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary fought in a way that we've never seen before,'' said Jim
Thomas, co-manager along with Holyfield. ``He looked tired in the
second round. That's incomprehensible because he's in great shape.
Then he started backing up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He went forward in sparring,'' Turner said. ``Yes, I'm
surprised. When you jab and move back, you open yourself up to be
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bell was hit plenty. The two men exchanged heavy blows
throughout the fight. Pendergrass banged at Bell's head in a
neutral corner in the fourth, stunning Bell. But Bell recovered to
make a round-closing assault that got the crowd into it.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, however, Pendergrass controlled matters, getting
off first with shots to the head as Bell's lack of mobility hurt
him. The next round, Pendergrass turned out Bell's lights with the
series of unanswered bombs.
</P>
<P>
   That battle was not the only interesting match on an undercard
that provided a potpourri of excitement:
</P>
<P>
   Christy Martin, the best-known women's boxer, scored a
fifth-round technical knockout over Christine Robinson. Martin, of
Orlando, staggered Robinson at the end of the first round, but the
Sylva, N.C., challenger recovered to give Martin a good fight the
next three rounds. The fight was stopped with 47 seconds left in
the fifth round. Martin improved to 36-1-2; Robinson fell to 16-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``King'' Lawrence Chapman of College Park raised his record to
14-0 by battering Earl Monroe (10-3-4) for eight rounds. Monroe
provided more of a test of conditioning for Chapman, who chased the
Demopolis, Ala., native much of the fight. Johnny Ruiz (33-3) won
the North American Heavyweight Championship with a fourth-round
knockout of Jerry Ballard (19-2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Eliecher Julio won the WBO Bantamweight Championship with
an 12-round decision over Adonis Cruz (29-3-1) of Nicaragua. Julio
was not happy afterward, however. ``I want to fight the best, and
right now I'm being denied that,'' he said. ``I'm tired of fighting
people with no names. I want Johnny Tapia.''
</P>
<P>
   In a kick-boxing championship bout, Jerome ``Geronimo'' LeBanner
(23-6-1) retained his WKN Thai World Heavyweight title by knocking
out Espedito ``Black Panther'' Da Silva (25-4) after 52 seconds of
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   LeBanner, of Paris, nailed Brazil's Da Silva with a left kick to
the jaw that knocked him down and out for the count.
</P>
<P>
   Jade (The Jewel) Scott (25-2) of Brooklyn knocked out Derek Amos
(12-7) with a solid right counter in the first round. Amos, who did
not land a punch, shook his head ``no'' as he was counted out.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina prospect Juan Pablo Chacon ran his record to 25-0 with
an eight-round unanimous decision over Mario Diaz, who fights out
of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The undercard began typically. That is, there was a bit of a
controversy. The opening bout between Luis Perez of Puerto Rico and
Atlanta's Eugene Johnson was judged a draw after eight rounds.
Perez' record sustained its first blemish at 10-0-1, while
Johnson's moved to 5-5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
