r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFE     09-19 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC EAST TURNING INTO BOTTOM FEEDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their 32-year history, the Seattle Seahawks never have
started a season 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   They've also never started with three games against NFC East
teams.
</P>
<P>
   How bad is the division?
</P>
<P>
   Combined, it is 2-8 after two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are 0-6 against teams outside the division.
</P>
<P>
   They are 0-6 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, NFC East teams were 0-5 and outscored, 157-76.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy, really strange,'' said San Francisco 49ers
linebacker
 &UR; Ken Norton Jr., who played for the Dallas Cowboys of the East.
``When I played there, the NFC East was the best. The Cowboys,
Giants and Redskins _ they set the standard. But I guess it goes in
cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants, tied with Dallas for the division lead at
1-1, are 8-0-1 under second-year Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel against East
teams. They are 3-6 outside the division, 1-4 against AFC clubs.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 31 years since the East was this bad _ 1967 when the
Cowboys were division champions with a 9-5 record and the rest of
the teams were under .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no real secret,'' longtime Washington Redskins cornerback
 &UR; Darrell Green said. ``The game has changed with free agency.
Players leave, coaches leave. It's not the same game.''
</P>
<P>
   The only two coaches in the East who aren't under pressure are
Fassel and first-year Coach  &UR; Chan Gailey of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a miracle for Philadelphia Eagles Coach  &UR; Ray Rhodes
to save his job. Washington's  &UR; Norv Turner is a goner if the team
is sold. The Cardinals'  &UR; Vince Tobin probably needs seven wins to
be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than the quarterbacks who will start for East
teams this weekend to see why the division has declined.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trent Green will start for Washington at Seattle.  &UR; Jason
Garrett replaces injured  &UR; Troy Aikman against the Giants'  &UR; Danny
Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   In Sun Devil Stadium today, the Cardinals'  &UR; Jake Plummer, who
has 11 career starts, goes against inexperienced  &UR; Bobby Hoying of
the Eagles. They have combined to throw one touchdown pass and four
interceptions and have been sacked 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to playing the Cardinals and Eagles, Seattle's  &UR; Mike
Sinclair,
 &UR; Darrin Smith and  &UR; Phillip Daniels have combined for 10{ sacks.
</P>
<P>
   But the fun is over for the Seahawks (2-0). They don't play
another East opponent until Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division is in disarray,'' Rhodes said. ``It's open. All
we have to do is get on track, and we can be a player in this
division.'' &QL; 
Fat chance &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giants running back  &UR; Tyrone Wheatley, a 1995 first-round draft
pick, has been inactive the first two weeks because of being
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a bad bone in my body for that young man,''
Fassel said. `` I want him to play. We need him to play. But we
only need him to play if he's going to be functionally ready for us
to go in and do, and I can count on him. If you want to call it
tough love, then call it tough love. But he's going to do it based
on the standards I set, and I'm not yielding anything different
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel wants Wheatley to weigh less than 233 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he is overweight, Wheatley said, ``I don't know, man.
Same reason you wonder why  &UR; Bill ( &UR; Clinton) did it. I'm wondering
the same thing.'' &QL; 
Heads up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how much Oakland Raiders owner  &UR; Al Davis and Denver
Broncos Coach  &UR; Mike Shanahan hate each other: In the ``Monday Night
Football'' opener in 1994, Shanahan, then offensive coordinator of
the 49ers, suggested that backup quarterback  &UR; Elvis Grbac throw at
Davis' head during pre-game warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he said was, `Let's run the go route,' which we ran every
time in warm-ups,'' said Grbac, now with the Kansas City Chiefs.
``He said something like, `Al Davis is over there.' But he never
told me to throw the ball at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember throwing over Al Davis' head. He moved out of the
way and kind of looked at Shanahan, but that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   No it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis looked back and saw what Shanahan had done, he raised
his middle finger at his former coach.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to confirm Grbac's story, Shanahan, whose team plays in
Oakland today, said, smiling, ``He must be confusing me with
another coach. Would I do something like that?'' &QL; 
Expensive proposition &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any team that wants to hire Green Bay's  &UR; Mike Holmgren as
general manager/coach at the end of the season apparently will owe
the Packers a second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Ron Wolf wouldn't confirm that, but in his new
book, ``The Packer Way,'' Wolf wrote that the club would receive
compensation if Holmgren left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes perfect sense to me,'' Wolf wrote. ``We're
recognizing the sanctity of a contract, but we're also
acknowledging Mike's professional goals. We want him happy, and we
want the organization happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a second-round pick would be cheap compared to what
the New York Jets had to pay New England to hire  &UR; Bill Parcells
before last season. The Patriots received third- and fourth-round
picks in 1997 and a No. 2 choice in '98. Next year, they'll get a
first-round pick. &QL; 
Memorabilia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In July, Miami Dolphins quarterback  &UR; Dan Marino gave his son,
 &UR; Joey, a bat signed by St. Louis Cardinals first baseman  &UR; Mark
McGwire. It was a present for Joey's ninth birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to get him, then I realized that he was a
big Mark McGwire fan,'' Marino said. ``So I tracked down Mark down
in San Francisco and got him to sign a bat. Mark (shipped) the bat
for me, and Joey was excited when I gave him it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if Marino could just get the same reaction out of Coach
 &UR; Jimmy
 &UR; Johnson when they throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks Marino deserves much of the blame for the
Dolphins having the league's 28th-ranked passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had receivers open,'' Johnson said of last week's victory
over Buffalo. ``We've just got to hit them. We've got to throw to
the ones that are open, not the ones that are covered.'' &QL; 
Quick kick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers win 23 of their next 30 games, they will finish the
1990s with a .767 winning percentage, the best of any franchise in
any decade. They are 99-31 in the '90s. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
