<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-EAGLES-AZR &LR;      09-19 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-EAGLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS KNOW VICTORY OVER EAGLES IS CRUCIAL  
 RECORD-LOW CROWD FOR HOME OPENER EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The Cardinals and Eagles. Some are wont to call
them birds of a feather, or two 0-2 football teams desperately in
need of a victory.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a pair of foul fowls.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently this _ and the record heat _ hasn't been lost on the
public, which will stay away in record numbers tonight when the two
NFC East foes ruffle their feathers at Sun Devil Stadium. As of
Thursday afternoon, only 36,850 tickets had been sold, a startling
figure considering the Cardinals' season ticket base is 31,000 and
change. Team officials are expecting a crowd near 40,000 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a shocking walk-up sale, it could mark the smallest
crowd for a Cardinals home opener since the team moved to the
Valley in 1988 and a huge drop-off from last year's opener, when
70,060 saw the Cardinals upset the Dallas Cowboys, 25-22, in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the company they're keeping. If today's crowd is as
small as anticipated, Philadelphia will represent three of the top
four poorly attended openers (42,533 in 1992, and 45,004 in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   For the record, last year's Dallas win marks the Cardinals' only
victory in a home opener since they nested in the Valley. At least
now they can view their record in home openers as a modest winning
streak instead of being 1-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very important football game for us,'' Cardinals
Coach Vince Tobin said. ``It's a division opponent, and we're both
0-2 and need to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important we win for two reasons: One, we need to control
our division, and you do that by beating division opponents. And
two, it's important that we control our home turf.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, if the franchise ever hopes to sway the voting
public into subsidizing a new stadium, it must avoid the indignity
the public would foist on it with the type of season that an 0-3
start could trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals fully understand why they will be playing to a
half-empty house in the nationally televised (ESPN) game that _ as
usual _ will be blacked out in Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see more people, but you can't depend on
something like that to get yourself ready to play,'' All-Pro
cornerback Aeneas Williams said. ``We'd like to see the type of
crowds that are here for the Dallas games, but until we start
winning, we won't get that consistent fan support.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a half-filled home stadium will feel like heaven
after opening the season in noise pits called Dallas and Seattle,
quarterback Jake Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing at your place, before your fans, and it feels
better,'' Plummer said. ``It doesn't mean we'll be better. You
still have to play well to win. But I feel more comfortable in Sun
Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I even think back and picture everybody in an old
Arizona State jerseys and me playing where I just went out and made
plays. Sometimes it helps make me feel more comfortable and helps
me relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is not a stranger to sparse crowds between the buttes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the luxury of 70,000 die-hard season ticket
holders that some teams have,'' he said. ``But if that's a goal of
everyone on this team, we have to win and we'll eventually get
there. I worked my way through weak crowds at Arizona State, but we
eventually got there.''
</P>
<P>
   From a football aspect, the home field advantage this weekend
will be welcomed in the form of silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest advantage the home field represents, other than
having the fans behind you, is it gives you freedom to call
audibles at the line of scrimmage,'' Tobin said. ``A lot of time on
the road, the noise level is so high you can't hear the
quarterback's cadence, and you have to go on a silent count, which
can cause mistakes and affect how you come off the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As they always do in the battle against dehydration, the
Cardinals will have free water stations throughout the stadium for
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, the team also will introduce its new Spirit Flag Line.
Hopefully, they can pick up the blitz or won't wave white flags. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
