<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-NCSTATE-HN     09-19 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-NCSTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Big-play Baylor 
rises to occasion
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bears stun No. 20 N.C. State 33-30
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ After almost blowing a 26-point lead, the Baylor defense
stiffened in the fourth quarter against 20th-ranked North Carolina
State on a sweltering Saturday at Floyd Casey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bears needed to come up with one more big play if they
hoped to avoid going to overtime against the Wolfpack. North
Carolina State needed to make a 39-yard field goal with 13 seconds
left to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everybody in the huddle I was going to block it,''
Baylor cornerback Gary Baxter said. ``I wanted it more than
anybody. We had worked too hard to they them do that to us at the
end. I pulled all my goodies out of the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Baxter was true to his word, slipping through from the left side
and blocking the attempt by Wolfpack kicker Kent Passingham to
preserve a 33-30 upset victory for the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled for our team,'' Baylor coach Dave Roberts said.
``This is a win that we can build on. We hung in there and won
against a very good football team. We had a lot of guys make some
big plays today. We had our ups and downs and we still made a lot
of mistakes, but the guys came up big at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State (2-1) was coming off one of the biggest
wins in school history _ a surprising 24-7 upset victory over
then-No. 2 Florida State last week. But Baylor (1-1) shocked the
Wolfpack and built a 26-0 lead at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baylor may be better than we thought they were,'' North
Carolina State head coach Mike O'Cain said. ``They have great
running backs and an outstanding quarterback. They played harder
and wanted it more than we did, especially in the first half. But
I'm proud of the fight we put up in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack charged back by scoring 23 points in the third
quarter to make it 26-23 with one quarter to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little too content as a defense after the
first half, and we didn't have the same intensity,'' said Baylor
linebacker Kenyada Parker, who returned a fumble 82 yards for a
touchdown in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really tired out there and people were cramping up,
but we sucked it up in the fourth quarter and got it done. We told
ourselves we weren't going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The man doing most of the damage for North Carolina State was
senior receiver Torry Holt, who had 11 receptions for 255 yards.
But Holt did not have a catch in the final 14 minutes of the game
when Baxter was covering him man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches told me to stay on him and I said, `That's
fine,''' Baxter said. ``He's just another man. I wanted to show
that I could stop an All-American.''
</P>
<P>
   What really stopped the Wolfpack was a woeful kicking game.
Passingham missed two field-goal attempts before the block, and
Scott Earwood, who normally handles the kicking chores but was
nursing shin splints, dropped a punt snap in the end zone that gave
Baylor a safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears led 5-0 and kept the momentum up, thanks to a power
run by fullback Derek Lagway that Earl Campbell couldn't have done
better.
</P>
<P>
   On second-and-five at the North Carolina State 27, Lagway (82
yards on nine carries) took a handoff up the middle and appeared to
be stopped at the 25. But he broke through six potential tacklers
and scored to give Baylor 12-0 lead late in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack threatened to reach the end zone in the second
quarter when they had third-and-goal at the Baylor four, but the
biggest play of the half for the Bears transformed a potential
North Carolina State score into a touchdown for the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfpack quarterback Jamie Barnette (24-of-55, 469 yards, three
touchdowns) rolled to his left before he was blasted from behind by
Baylor weakside linebacker Jason Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The ball popped out, and Parker scooped it up at the 18 and
rambled down the sideline for an 82-yard TD to give the Bears a
19-0 lead with 6:01 to go in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blitzing from the left side,'' Parker said. ``Just as I
looked up, Jason was popping their quarterback right in the mouth.
The ball bounced right to me. It was the longest run of my life,
but I knew I was going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the rout was on with Baylor's next offensive
possession when Elijah Burkins ran in for a two-yard TD to make it
26-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wolfpack looked like a different team in the second
half. Two TD passes from Barnette to Holt and one to tight end
Devon Smith, plus a pair of two-point conversions, made it 26-23
with 1:56 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor offense finally stopped the bleeding when quarterback
Odell James scored on a four-yard bootleg early in the fourth
quarter to give the Bears a 33-23 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But North Carolina State scored again on a big play. Tailback
Ray Robinson took a pitch to the right, cut upfield and ran
untouched for a 34-yard TD, making it 33-30 with 12:13 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack had a chance to tie the game on a 45-yard
field-attempt by Passingham, but the kick was slightly off to the
right with 4:50 to go. Passingham would get one last chance, but
Baxter would made sure the ball didn't reach the goal posts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
