<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-S.MISS-H     09-19 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-S.MISS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A&AMP;M bottles up Southern Mississippi 24-6
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aggies' defense, kicking game &QL; 
help make up for lost ground
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Maybe Texas A&AMP;M eventually will have a good
game offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' 171 total yards against Southern Mississippi was
well under its 221-yards-per-game average, which ranked 102nd
nationally coming into Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Aggies, offense is but a third of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a dominant performance from its defense and a flawless
effort by its kickers, 17th-ranked Texas A&AMP;M easily handled
Southern Mississippi 24-6 before a sellout crowd of 33,233 at
Roberts Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The third-largest crowd in Southern Mississippi school history,
which had hoped to see the Eagles pull off one of their biggest
wins ever, instead saw them almost shut out for the first time in
22 years and fall to 0-2 for the first time since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming into their stadium it was going to be a hard
game, and if we take their crowd out (of the game), we take them
out,'' said Texas A&AMP;M linebacker Warrick Holdman, who keyed the
Aggies' blitz. ``I'm very proud of this defense. We were just
attacking. Every time we blitzed it was successful, and we blitzed
the whole game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team, and we know if we're not doing good, the offense
is going to help us. We just felt that if we don't let them score,
our offense would get rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies' offense never really got untracked.
</P>
<P>
   With starting running back Tiki Hardeman serving an an
indefinite suspension and Dante Hall limited because of a strained
muscle just below his right hamstring, the Aggies (2-1) struggled
to move the ball for much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   After holding the Eagles to five first downs and 58 yards in the
first half, the Aggies picked off three passes in the second half
and did not allow a score until 53 seconds remained to play. In
all, the A&AMP;M defense forced five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies won the battle of special teams as well. Kicker
Russell Bynum was 3-for-3 on field-goal attempts, and Shane Lechler
took advantage of a good workout with nine punts for a 50.1-yard
average.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive game, the A&AMP;M secondary shut down a
potent receiver. Sherrod Gideon, who had 13 catches for 176 yards
in the Eagles' season opener, managed only three catches for 25
yards against Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our main focus, shut the top guy out and play to our
capability,'' said Texas A&AMP;M free safety Brandon Jennings, who had
an interception. ``We're going back to our old tradition of
blitzing. That makes the secondary play a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us to hustle, and that's what we did to get those
interceptions _ they didn't come to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies batted away at least five of quarterback Lee Roberts'
attempts, and two of A&AMP;M's interceptions were the result of chasing
down tipped balls.
</P>
<P>
   Hall provided the Aggies' only offensive highlights. Although
questionable for the game because of a muscle pull suffered in
practice Thursday, Hall entered with the just over five minutes
remaining in the first half and the Aggies ahead 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a minute later, the fleet-footed junior was making his
way into the end zone , breaking four tackles on a beautiful
44-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   More accurately, it was three near-tackles and one whiff. The
fourth Golden Eagles player, who had the angle on Hall inside the
10-yard line, never got a hand on him as Hall pulled out a
stop-and-go move before crossing the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Sirr Parker took a toss around right end for the two-point
conversion to put the Aggies up 14-0 with 4:14 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who had 76 yards on eight carries, sat out the Aggies'
first two possessions of the second half and then re-entered in
pretty much the same fashion as he had earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings returned his interception 30 yards to set up the Aggies
at the Southern Mississippi 25 with 5:13 left. This time, Hall took
just 44 seconds off the clock to find the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   A carry over the right side netted nine yards. It was followed
by a nice hesitation and sprint down the right side as the Aggies
took a 21-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great cut that got me one-on-one with the defender,
and I just tried to get it on in there,'' Hall said. ``I just
wanted to get in there and help the team. Sirr had told me how they
were playing defensively, and I knew if I waited I could get the
blocks and then try to beat those who weren't blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius Anthony recovered a fumble to set up a Bynum 27-yard
field goal, and Gideon finally got free from an afternoon of
harassment by Texas A&AMP;M cornerback Jay Brooks for a six-yard
touchdown catch in the final minute to complete the scoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-19 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-KANSTATE-HN     09-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-KANSTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kansas St. waylays Texas 48-7, holds Williams to 43 yards
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MANHATTAN, Kan. _ The bright side somehow is getting hard to find.
Either that, or Texas is beginning to tire of the search.
</P>
<P>
   After Kansas State pounded Ricky Williams and punished the
Longhorns 48-7 on Saturday, refusing to quit began to lose its
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Texas did have second-half moments to equal many from its
save-face rally at UCLA last week. But against Kansas State, the
Longhorns saw Williams, their weekly saving grace, pounded. They
saw their line embarrassed, their tacklers undressed in the open
field.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs of possibilities, including a solid first
showing by freshman quarterback Major Applewhite. But this time,
after falling behind 35-0 by halftime _ in a score too similar to
last week's 35-3 for comfort _ the Longhorns found no joy in a few
meaningless moments.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State celebrated at their expense until the logical
question remained whether the No. 5 Wildcats have yet played a
competitive Division I-A team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone feels miserable,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``We
just feel so bad. It's not fun to be down so bad at halftime. I
told the team, `You don't like it, your coaches don't like it, but
you're playing a great football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our medicine handed to us, and we have to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State so thoroughly outmanned UT that the Wildcats had
more dominant Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jeff Kelly of La Grange had 11 tackles, forced two
fumbles and returned an interception 17 yards for a touchdown.
Quarterback Michael Bishop of Willis threw for 182 yards and two
touchdowns, and rushed for 41 yards and a score. Even punter James
Garcia of Victoria averaged 60.3 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kansas State defense was so in control that Williams
struggled to get even 43 yards, his fewest since he was held to 36
against UCLA last season and the fourth-worst total of his career.
On 25 carries, Williams lost yardage on five and made it only back
to the line on three others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit him so much, I just started helping him up,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kept coming and coming,'' Williams said. ``Every
play, there seemed like eight or nine guys up there. I didn't think
it was that physical; they were just everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas offense was so completely beaten that Applewhite was
far from the Longhorns' biggest problem. Forced by starter Richard
Walton's broken hand to play with just 18 career snaps of
experience, Applewhite completed 16 of 37 passes for 239 yards and
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But two passes were intercepted when Applewhite tried to throw
while being hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable playing, but I'm upset about the two
interceptions,'' Applewhite said. ``Any time you throw two
interceptions with a fumble, you're not going to do well as a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the Texas offense became mistake-prone without a
running game to at least lower the risk, the UT defense found new
ways to struggle in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   KSU running back Eric Hickson, who had 124 yards rushing on just
16 carries, was often surging past the Texas linebackers and into
the secondary before encountering any contact or a defender to
juke. He easily made J.J. Kelly and Aaron Babino miss 2:17 into the
game on a 44-yard touchdown run to begin the rout.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' defenders were almost turned into moving turnstiles when
with Kansas State leading 14-0, David Allen made Jay Humphrey,
De'Andre Lewis and Derek Lewis all miss on a 93-yard punt return
for a score, his third return for a touchdown in as many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And, like UCLA a week ago, the Wildcats added two touchdowns
before the half to make the game a rout, no matter what sort of
turnaround the Longhorns could muster in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half was a great, complete game,'' Kansas State
coach Bill Snyder said. ``In the second half, we couldn't move the
ball and had a few miscues on defense, and we gave up the
touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Texas again improved in the second half, another
opponent complained about its second-half letdown while the
Longhorns searched for signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds stupid when you come off the field 48-7,'' Brown
said. ``But we looked better on defense. The goal-line stand. We
forced some turnovers. We covered some people. In the first half
against UCLA, we weren't close enough to see who was in on the
play. At least today we could tell who was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely a better football team than we were two weeks
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``better'' remained far from good enough to play at the
level of Kansas State or UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, that was too obvious to argue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-19-98 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980919.0247 </DOCNO>
