<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-ARKANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS, QB STOERNER LEAVE SMU IN DARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Considering the stress the Arkansas
Razorbacks have suffered these past three autumns, they can
probably be forgiven for trying to turn the lights out on SMU a tad
early last night.
</P>
<P>
   But even a 29-minute shutdown that cast an eerie gloom over War
Memorial Stadium in the third quarter could not slow the Hogs'
march toward their objective _ ending SMU's three-year win streak
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   This time, in front of the seventh-largest crowd (55,544) in the
stadium's history, they obliterated it, 44-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have been better off,'' Mustangs coach Mike Cavan
said, ``if they'd just never turned the lights on again.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Razorbacks (2-0) were sitting on a 10-point
lead and the Mustangs (0-3) figured they still had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide had already turned, and the Arkansas attack _
fueled by Clint Stoerner (17-of-33, 262 yards, three touchdowns)
and Chrys Chukwuma (17 carries, 142 yards) _ was on its way to a
470-yard evening.
</P>
<P>
   SMU, meanwhile, was struggling on all fronts (209 total yards,
three turnovers), and two quick giveaways after the lights came on
gave Arkansas an insurmountable 34-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   There was elation among the hosts, as first-year coach Houston
Nutt thanked the fans and said he was happy ``that our seniors
finally got this thing off their back. They've heard a lot about it
from a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mustangs, Cavan said, ``it always looks darkest
before a comeback ... and right now it looks pretty dark.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first play after the opening kickoff, Stoerner flipped a
quick hitch pass to wide receiver Anthony Lucas, who juked two
defenders and fled 87 yards. With 26 seconds elapsed, the
Razorbacks had a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They increased it momentarily, with a helping hand from the
guests. After a penalty, freshman quarterback Josh McCown was
sacked at his 14 and coughed up the ball, with Jamel Harris
recovering for Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Hogs came away with a 47-yard Todd Latourette
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 10-0, the Mustangs revived themselves with a drive
into Arkansas territory, and when it stalled, Colin Vadheim dropped
a punt dead on the 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks punted out from the 2, and the Mustangs got a
35-yard Roy Rios field goal out of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the quarter, Arkansas' Chris Akin fumbled a snap on a
punt, and SMU took over at the Hogs' 28. On the first play of the
second quarter, McCown hit Albert Johnson with a 23-yard scoring
pass to tie it at 10.
</P>
<P>
   Akin later dropped a punt dead at the SMU 5, and Arkansas fared
better on the exchange, getting a 29-yard scoring pass from
Stoerner to Eric Branch for a 17-10 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Latourette added another field goal in the third quarter, and
after the teams' sojourn in the dark, the Razorbacks used two
breaks to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The first was an interception by Zac Painter that set Arkansas
up at the SMU 29 and launched a drive that Stoerner finished with a
1-yard sneak.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jacoby Rhinehart fumbled a punt at his 13, and Arkansas'
Madre Hill got the TD yardage in one play for a 34-10 lead. The
Hogs scored 10 more in the fourth, and SMU got a score on a
touchdown pass from Chris Sanders, brought in late to spell McCown.
</P>
<P>
   Cavan said he thought the crowd affected the Mustangs, and that
``we were a little nervous at first.'' McCown agreed, saying, ``I
was real nervous at the start, and I guess it was obvious by the
way I played. I just wasn't used to playing in front of a crowd
this big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
