u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HARVARD-COLUMBIA-     09-19 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARVARD-COLUMBIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUT, AS EXPECTED, BUT IVY CHAMPS ARE LOSERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to refine)   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most people figured Saturday's Ivy League football
opener between Columbia and Harvard would be one-sided. After all,
Harvard overran the Lions, 45-7, in last year's opener and went on
to a 9-1 record and the Ivy championship. The Crimson had won seven
straight games, and quarterback Rich Linden and tailback Chris
Menick, the big guns, were back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Columbia was trying to shed memories of a 4-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the game was clearly one-sided, but not as
expected. This time, Columbia embarrassed Harvard. It dominated the
line of scrimmage offensively and defensively. On a muggy Saturday
afternoon, it kept running the ball and wore down the opposition.
Columbia won, 24-0, and everyone knew why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, we really dominated the game,'' Columbia Coach Ray
Tellier said. ``I can't remember the last time we did that on both
sides of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tim Murphy of Harvard fully agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man for man, they're not a better team than us, but they
outplayed us,'' he said. ``They were bigger, stronger and more
physical. We got beat up in the trenches. They never gave us a
chance to get into the game. At least nobody got killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics told the story. Columbia, led by the freshman
Johnathan Reese (72 yards) and Norman Hayes (58), rushed for 196
yards. Harvard, which averaged more than 200 yards rushing and 200
yards passing a game last year, was held to 169 yards in total
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia introduced a 4-4 defense, the same that Harvard used,
and held Linden to 60 yards passing and Menick to 37 yards rushing.
Harvard suffered three sacks and two interceptions and two lost
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's deepest penetration, to the Columbia 41-yard line,
came in the final minute of the game. As Linden said: ``We couldn't
put it together. We never had 11 guys on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   The Homecoming Day crowd of 6,000 at Wien Stadium watched
Columbia dominate from the start. In the first quarter, Jason
Bivens ran a yard for a touchdown. In the second quarter, Neal
Kravitz kicked a 36-yard field goal. In the third quarter, Paris
Childress connected on a 25-yard touchdown pass to Mark Cannan, and
27 seconds later, after linebacker Paul Roland's 35-yard
interception return, Hayes crashed a yard for the final touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Bivens had double duty for Columbia, but not at his old tailback
position. On defense, he took half the snaps at strong safety,
usually in passing situations. On offense, he got in for 11 plays
at quarterback, always out of a resurrected wishbone rather than
Columbia's standard pro set. On one of those plays, a naked
reverse, he gained 11 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a limited package,'' Bivens said. ``I played quarterback
in high school, so it's not like I never took a snap before.''
</P>
<P>
   As well as Columbia played, Tellier said he had no illusions.
When someone asked whether this victory made the Lions the Ivy
favorites, their coach would have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played one game,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
