<HEADER>
A4668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OFFICE-REAL-2TAKES     09-19 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICE-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: NEW YORK SPACE IS TIGHT, OFFICE MARKETS ROBUST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With vacancy rates declining, rents rising and some
tenants opting to move either to the suburbs or to parts of
Manhattan that were once avoided, the fundamentals of the
commercial real estate market in the New York area have been robust
in the first nine months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary third quarter figures compiled by the
Julien J. Studley company, the overall vacancy rate for office
space in Manhattan fell to 5.8 percent, from 6.8 percent in the
second quarter, while average rents rose to $31.29 a square foot
annually, from $28.97 a foot.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in these averages is the fact that in some parts of
midtown, such as the area near Grand Central Terminal, space in the
newest and best buildings is all but unavailable, and asking rents
of $70 a square foot have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   The vitality of the office market has also been reflected in the
retail sector, with some stretches of Madison and Fifth avenues
commanding annual rents of $300 to $500 a square foot. Hotels are
filled nearly to practical capacity, with room-rate increases
fattening owners' profits.
</P>
<P>
   But the gyrations of the stock market are having an impact on
sales of property, with the decline in the price of real estate
investment trust stocks removing them, at least temporarily, from
the acquisition scene and forcing other financing sources to
reevaluate their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentiment is different,'' said Peter Hauspurg, the
chairman of Eastern Consolidated Properties, which specializes in
building sales, ``and we're trying to sort out what it means.'' He
said financing sources were now requiring developers to supply a
higher proportion of funding for deals. ``Wall Street and the hedge
funds pulled back from financing in the 80 to 90 percent range,''
Hauspurg said.
</P>
<P>
   Hauspurg said the new reluctance of investment firms to
aggressively finance purchases was likely to slow the pace of
transactions as buyers and sellers are forced to negotiate new
terms. ``This is not great for the sales business,'' he said.
``When the price changes, the volume drops 80 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean F. Hennessey, director of the New York hospitality practice
for PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting and consulting firm,
said, ``There were a number of players who were going to put
properties on the market who have pulled back due to the impact of
the stock market. The buyers have gotten fewer and pickier. They
are looking for better deals than two months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The real estate investment trusts, the tax-sheltered acquisition
and ownership vehicles that made such a splash in the metropolitan
area over the last few years, have grown quiet, the victim of their
falling share prices and their own structure.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid paying taxes on income, the REIT's must pay out 95
percent of their income to shareholders as dividends. This means
they do not have much in the way of retained earnings. And with a
depressed price, they are not inclined either to return to public
markets for additional financing or to use their stock to acquire
properties, in order to avoid diluting the value of existing
shares.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Vornado Realty Trust, which acquired Bernard
Mendik's portfolio of midtown buildings in 1997 and went on to buy
most of the property along Seventh Avenue between 34th and 31st
Streets, has not announced any new acquisitions recently. That is
probably because its shares, which reached $50 early in the year,
have recently been trading below $30.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it is difficult for REIT's to raise capital and
they don't want to use their own stock as scrip to make
acquisitions,'' said Michael Cohen, president of Williams Real
Estate. ``REIT stock is not cash anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some market watchers say the decline of the REIT's represents a
return to reality. ``The market got frothy,'' said Dennis Yeskey,
the regional manager for real estate services at Deloitte &AMP; Touche,
an accounting and consulting firm. ``REIT's were out of whack in
1996 and 1997, trading at 20 times earnings, when they should be at
eight times.''
</P>
<P>
   REIT's will find a way to stay active players in the real estate
market, but will be forced to change their tactics, others argue.
``REIT's were the No. 1 bidder for every property coming on the
market seven or eight months ago,'' said Kevin Haggarty, executive
managing director of the Insignia/ESG Capital Advisers group. ``Now
they are No. 2 or No. 3, but they will continue to make
acquisitions in categories where they are dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to sell stock or debt securities based on the
overall corporation, REIT's seeking capital in the current climate
are likely to place mortgages on individual properties, Haggarty
said, although there is little evidence they have done so yet.
</P>
<P>
   But if the investment market is being roiled by the stock
market, the leasing market remains strong, so strong that some
tenants' brokers are recommending that their clients not make any
long-term commitments at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd advise people to extend their lease short-term and stay
where they are,'' said James Meiskin, president of Plymouth
Partners, a tenants' broker. ``This is no time to make long-term
decisions. The market may well be at its apex.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Colp-Haber, a partner in Wharton Property Advisors, which
also represents tenants, said that because of the tight market
``landlords are making demands at the last minute, upping rents and
taking away space.'' High rentals and the shortage of space
``represent a significant impediment to small business growth in
New York City,'' Ms. Colp-Haber added. ``This is the downside of an
otherwise vibrant economy and booming real estate market. In sum:
things are so good, they're bad.''
</P>
<P>
   According to market analysts, the demand for space is being
driven by rising employment and the fact that virtually no new
office buildings have been added to the city's inventory for almost
10 years. ``There have been 180,000 jobs added in New York and
those people need space to work,'' said Raymond O'Keefe, president
of Grubb &AMP; Ellis New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look out the window, there are no building cranes,'' said
Thomas Falus, president of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield of New York,
speaking of most of the city. ``The only building that's going on
is where there are already leases. The supply/demand equation looks
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the glut of empty space coming on to a declining market
that characterized the late 1980s, many real estate executives
expect rent levels to hold, with companies priced out of the
Manhattan market heading for the other boroughs or suburbs. ``I
don't think we are going to see a big increase in rents, which is
good,'' O'Keefe said. ``They will probably stay on this plateau for
awhile.'' He said the reason for this moderation is that demand for
space and the available supply are in rough equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Class A space, which is in the newest and most technically
advanced buildings, is all but unavailable in midtown, with CB
Richard Ellis calculating the vacancy rate at 2.2 percent. This has
produced some movement of tenants to downtown, but for many
companies a midtown location is essential to running their business
and they are paying to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of alternative markets, including North
Dakota,'' observed David Levinson, an executive managing director
of Insignia/ESG, a real estate services company. ``The critical
questions are where are a company's clients and can they get the
employee skills they need. It's these operational issues that are
critical, not saving a couple of dollars a square foot on real
estate. Real estate only controls the relocation decision if
everything else is neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid an unending upward spiral some companies are seeking to
break out of the traditional tenant-landlord model. For instance,
the news and financial information company Reuters has formed a
joint venture with the Rudin family to build an 855,000-square-foot
building on Seventh Avenue from 42nd to 43rd streets that will
serve as Reuters headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters officials have said they see the joint venture as a
means of controlling costs in a rising market and being able to
tailor the building so it projects the image of a high-technology
company.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bear Stearns will control its own 1.1
million-square-foot building at 383 Madison Avenue between 46th and
47th streets, where demolition of the old structure on the site is
currently under way. The financial services company has a 99-year
lease on the underlying land.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority has a 49-year lease on
all 1,595,000 square feet of space at 2 Broadway under which it
controls the building and pays all the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major tenants don't want the traditional tenant-landlord
relationship,'' said Peter Riguardi, an executive vice president of
Colliers ABR, who helped negotiate the MTA deal this summer. ``They
want to control their environment and have their own security. They
don't want to have to look at the lease every time they want to do
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Reuters and Bear Stearns projects under way, the 1.6
million-square-foot building under construction by the Durst
Organization on Broadway between 42nd and 43rd streets loses it
distinction as the only major new office project in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives said they expect other available building
sites to be utilized quickly. These include the two remaining Times
Square sites south of 42nd Street, which are controlled by Mortimer
Zuckerman and George Klein, and the half block on Seventh Avenue
between 49th and 50th streets that is usually referred to as ``Rock
West'' because it is owned by The Rockefeller Group. At Rock West,
the financial services company Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has
reached an agreement with the Rockefeller Group to build a
million-square-foot building on what is now a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Since sites where new construction can proceed are very few in
Manhattan, older buildings will have to be upgraded if they are to
be competitive. A market report prepared by CB Richard Ellis noted
that while the vacancy rate in midtown buildings built since 1980
is 2.3 percent, it is 6.3 percent for those built before that.
``Building renovations will accelerate as the office market
tightens and tenants demand Internet-ready infrastructure,'' the
report predicts. ``As Grand Central station finishes its
renovation, look for the entire submarket to respond with building
upgrades.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago the prospects for real estate in the downtown
market were so bleak that the city mounted a special incentive
program that gave tax breaks to commercial tenants who would locate
there and incentives to owners who would convert old office
buildings to apartments and condominiums. Now downtown is becoming
an outlet for tenants being squeezed by midtown's rising rates.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA's decision to lease the entire 1,595,000 square feet at
2 Broadway, between Stone and Beaver streets on the southern tip of
the island, was one of the biggest leasing transactions of recent
years, but not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   Guardian Life Insurance Co. is leaving its midtown south
location near Union Square to occupy 450,000 square feet of space
at 7 Hanover Square at the intersection of William and Water
streets. The company also has options to expand to 880,000 square
feet over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by Cushman &AMP; Wakefield the overall vacancy
rate downtown has dipped below 10 percent, with Class A vacancies
down to 5.9 percent at the end of the second quarter, compared to
12.2 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the average asking rent in the district reached $28 a
square foot annually, a 13 percent increase from $24.85 in the same
1997 quarter, with Class A space up to $36.48 from $30.11 a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the 1980s, Park Avenue South was developed as an
alternate to midtown,'' said Levinson of Insignia/ESG. ``Now it is
downtown that is the alternative. The office market is getting so
tight that some buildings that were scheduled for conversion to
residential may stay office.'' For example, the building at 10
Hanover Square was scheduled for conversion before the Goldman
Sachs financial services company leased 522,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown is much healthier than it was, due to the conversion
program,'' said O'Keefe of Grubb &AMP; Ellis. ``You have the
residential units, and the state has signed to develop the Hudson
River park. The area will have a life of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The squeeze in on in midtown, and for that reason the Jersey
shoreline will blossom,'' said Michael T. Cohen of Williams Real
Estate.
</P>
<P>
   With the waterfronts of Jersey City, Hoboken and Weehawken just
a few PATH tube stops from Manhattan, building has resumed in
Jersey City for the first time in almost a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Lefrak Organization is building a 561,000-square-foot office
building at its Newport complex, while Hartz Mountain Industries is
at work on a 419,000-square-foot tower at its Colgate site. Last
week, the fund-management company Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co. announced that
it would move next year from the General Motors Building on Fifth
Avenue to 150,000 square feet in Hartz Mountain's Colgate Center.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects are being planned, including a
1,150,000-square-foot office and retail complex in Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of activity in New Jersey,'' said Donald P.
Eisen, an executive managing director of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield who
specializes in suburban properties. ``Now we are seeing companies
compete for the same space. There is great interest in Newark from
telecommunications companies who want to be close to the main
telephone switches.''
</P>
<P>
   Rental rates for office space in the northern part of the state
increased $2.15 a square foot to an average of $27.35 a square
foot, Cushman &AMP; Wakefield reported, and several speculative office
buildings are under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The activity in New Jersey is not limited to office properties.
The number of movie screens in the state has increased to 828 from
550 over the last decade as shopping center developers increasingly
incorporate them in their designs to add entertainment to
consumption and try to increase the latter by keeping shoppers
around longer.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives say the office markets in Westchester and
Fairfield Counties have not revived to the extent New Jersey's has.
``There is still space available in Westchester, although there is
renewed interest in White Plains,'' Eisen said. He noted that
Zurich Insurance was continuing to build in Stamford, Conn., but
had decided to keep its headquarters in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, the office market continues to recover, with the
overall vacancy rate dropping 2.4 percentage points to 10.8
percent. At mid-year 1990 the rate was 17.6 percent, according to
Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. Despite the low vacancy rate, rents, averaging
$24.43 a square foot, have not risen enough to justify speculative
construction, many real estate executives say.
</P>
<P>
   SoHo is the hot shopping area, retail leasing specialists say,
with both domestic and foreign-based retailers taking the place of
the art galleries, whose inability to pay rising rents has driven
them to west Chelsea. ``It is as if a whole new shopping area is
being built there,'' said Alan Victor, an executive vice president
of Lansco Corp., retail leasing specialists. He said many of the
stores opening in the area are selling merchandise priced below
that in stores along Fifth and Madison Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is a jewelry store, it will sell fashion jewelry as
opposed to custom works of art on Fifth Avenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy, which has filled office buildings with
well-paid workers, and the additional housing that has been built
or converted is fueling demand for retail services, analysts say.
This has strengthened the hand of landlords, particularly in areas
of the city where certain retailers feel they must have a presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carriage trade retailers from all over the world need a
Madison or Fifth Avenue address to show they are contenders in the
world of platinum-card purchasers,'' a study by CB Richard Ellis
concluded. ``Entertainment and sports retailers are interested in
Times Square and Fifth Avenue locations in order to burnish their
images as players on a global stage.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, the higher retail rents, from $300 to
$500 a square foot a year, are charged on Madison Avenue between
58th and 72d Streets and on Fifth Avenue between 51st and 59th
Streets.
</P>
<P>
   New York's hotels remain filled to a high level of occupancy, as
tourism and business bring more visitors to a city that is seen as
safe and exciting. According to a survey of 70 hotels by
PricewaterhouseCoopers, occupancy rates were 83.2 percent in the
second quarter of this year, compared to 81.5 percent in the same
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Strong demand is allowing hotel operators to improve their
profit margins by boosting room rates. According to the same
survey, the average daily cost of a hotel room in Manhattan rose to
$198.70, a 16 percent increase over last year's second-quarter
average of $171.39.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer an occupancy story, because it can't get much
higher,'' Hennessey said. ``But it is giving hotel owners the
opportunity to push up room rates.''
</P>
<P>
   And that translates directly into profits, because most hotel
costs are fixed. Once the break-even point has been reached, much
of the additional revenue falls to the bottom line, Hennessey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
